U||THE PURLOINED LETTER
U||   Nil sapientiæ odiosius acumine nimio.—Seneca.
U||   At Paris, just after dark one gusty evening in the autumn of 18-, I was
U||   enjoying the twofold luxury of meditation and a meerschaum, in company
U||   with my friend C. Auguste Dupin, in his little back library, or
U||   book-closet, au troisième, No. 33, Rue Dunôt, Faubourg St. Germain. For
U||   one hour at least we had maintained a profound silence; while each, to
U||   any casual observer, might have seemed intently and exclusively
U||   occupied with the curling eddies of smoke that oppressed the atmosphere
U||   of the chamber. For myself, however, I was mentally discussing certain
U||   topics which had formed matter for conversation between us at an
U||   earlier period of the evening; I mean the affair of the Rue Morgue, and
U||   the mystery attending the murder of Marie Rogêt. I looked upon it,
U||   therefore, as something of a coincidence, when the door of our
U||   apartment was thrown open and admitted our old acquaintance, Monsieur
U||   G——, the Prefect of the Parisian police.
U||   We gave him a hearty welcome; for there was nearly half as much of the
U||   entertaining as of the contemptible about the man, and we had not seen
U||   him for several years. We had been sitting in the dark, and Dupin now
U||   arose for the purpose of lighting a lamp, but sat down again, without
U||   doing so, upon G.‘s saying that he had called to consult us, or rather
U||   to ask the opinion of my friend, about some official business which had
U||   occasioned a great deal of trouble.
U||   “If it is any point requiring reflection,” observed Dupin, as he
U||   forebore to enkindle the wick, “we shall examine it to better purpose
U||   in the dark.”
U||   “That is another of your odd notions,” said the Prefect, who had a
U||   fashion of calling every thing “odd” that was beyond his comprehension,
U||   and thus lived amid an absolute legion of “oddities.”
U||   “Very true,” said Dupin, as he supplied his visitor with a pipe, and
U||   rolled towards him a comfortable chair.
U||   “And what is the difficulty now?” I asked. “Nothing more in the
U||   assassination way, I hope?”
U||   “Oh no; nothing of that nature. The fact is, the business is very
U||   simple indeed, and I make no doubt that we can manage it sufficiently
U||   well ourselves; but then I thought Dupin would like to hear the details
U||   of it, because it is so excessively odd.”
U||   “Simple and odd,” said Dupin.
U||   “Why, yes; and not exactly that, either. The fact is, we have all been
U||   a good deal puzzled because the affair is so simple, and yet baffles us
U||   altogether.”
U||   “Perhaps it is the very simplicity of the thing which puts you at
U||   fault,” said my friend.
U||   “What nonsense you do talk!” replied the Prefect, laughing heartily.
U||   “Perhaps the mystery is a little too plain,” said Dupin.
U||   “Oh, good heavens! who ever heard of such an idea?”
U||   “A little too self-evident.”
U||   “Ha! ha! ha—ha! ha! ha!—ho! ho! ho!” roared our visitor, profoundly
U||   amused, “oh, Dupin, you will be the death of me yet!”
U||   “And what, after all, is the matter on hand?” I asked.
U||   “Why, I will tell you,” replied the Prefect, as he gave a long, steady
U||   and contemplative puff, and settled himself in his chair. “I will tell
U||   you in a few words; but, before I begin, let me caution you that this
U||   is an affair demanding the greatest secrecy, and that I should most
U||   probably lose the position I now hold, were it known that I confided it
U||   to any one.”
U||   “Proceed,” said I.
U||   “Or not,” said Dupin.
U||   “Well, then; I have received personal information, from a very high
U||   quarter, that a certain document of the last importance has been
U||   purloined from the royal apartments. The individual who purloined it is
U||   known; this beyond a doubt; he was seen to take it. It is known, also,
U||   that it still remains in his possession.”
U||   “How is this known?” asked Dupin.
U||   “It is clearly inferred,” replied the Prefect, “from the nature of the
U||   document, and from the non-appearance of certain results which would at
U||   once arise from its passing out of the robber’s possession; that is to
U||   say, from his employing it as he must design in the end to employ it.”
U||   “Be a little more explicit,” I said.
U||   “Well, I may venture so far as to say that the paper gives its holder a
U||   certain power in a certain quarter where such power is immensely
U||   valuable.” The Prefect was fond of the cant of diplomacy.
U||   “Still I do not quite understand,” said Dupin.
U||   “No? Well; the disclosure of the document to a third person, who shall
U||   be nameless, would bring in question the honor of a personage of most
U||   exalted station; and this fact gives the holder of the document an
U||   ascendancy over the illustrious personage whose honor and peace are so
U||   jeopardized.”
U||   “But this ascendancy,” I interposed, “would depend upon the robber’s
U||   knowledge of the loser’s knowledge of the robber. Who would dare—”
U||   “The thief,” said G., “is the Minister D——, who dares all things, those
U||   unbecoming as well as those becoming a man. The method of the theft was
U||   not less ingenious than bold. The document in question—a letter, to be
U||   frank—had been received by the personage robbed while alone in the
U||   royal boudoir. During its perusal she was suddenly interrupted by the
U||   entrance of the other exalted personage from whom especially it was her
U||   wish to conceal it. After a hurried and vain endeavor to thrust it in a
U||   drawer, she was forced to place it, open as it was, upon a table. The
U||   address, however, was uppermost, and, the contents thus unexposed, the
U||   letter escaped notice. At this juncture enters the Minister D——. His
U||   lynx eye immediately perceives the paper, recognises the handwriting of
U||   the address, observes the confusion of the personage addressed, and
U||   fathoms her secret. After some business transactions, hurried through
U||   in his ordinary manner, he produces a letter somewhat similar to the
U||   one in question, opens it, pretends to read it, and then places it in
U||   close juxtaposition to the other. Again he converses, for some fifteen
U||   minutes, upon the public affairs. At length, in taking leave, he takes
U||   also from the table the letter to which he had no claim. Its rightful
U||   owner saw, but, of course, dared not call attention to the act, in the
U||   presence of the third personage who stood at her elbow. The minister
U||   decamped; leaving his own letter—one of no importance—upon the table.”
U||   “Here, then,” said Dupin to me, “you have precisely what you demand to
U||   make the ascendancy complete—the robber’s knowledge of the loser’s
U||   knowledge of the robber.”
U||   “Yes,” replied the Prefect; “and the power thus attained has, for some
U||   months past, been wielded, for political purposes, to a very dangerous
U||   extent. The personage robbed is more thoroughly convinced, every day,
U||   of the necessity of reclaiming her letter. But this, of course, cannot
U||   be done openly. In fine, driven to despair, she has committed the
U||   matter to me.”
U||   “Than whom,” said Dupin, amid a perfect whirlwind of smoke, “no more
U||   sagacious agent could, I suppose, be desired, or even imagined.”
U||   “You flatter me,” replied the Prefect; “but it is possible that some
U||   such opinion may have been entertained.”
U||   “It is clear,” said I, “as you observe, that the letter is still in
U||   possession of the minister; since it is this possession, and not any
U||   employment of the letter, which bestows the power. With the employment
U||   the power departs.”
U||   “True,” said G.; “and upon this conviction I proceeded. My first care
U||   was to make thorough search of the minister’s hotel; and here my chief
U||   embarrassment lay in the necessity of searching without his knowledge.
U||   Beyond all things, I have been warned of the danger which would result
U||   from giving him reason to suspect our design.”
U||   “But,” said I, “you are quite au fait in these investigations. The
U||   Parisian police have done this thing often before.”
U||   “Oh, yes; and for this reason I did not despair. The habits of the
U||   minister gave me, too, a great advantage. He is frequently absent from
U||   home all night. His servants are by no means numerous. They sleep at a
U||   distance from their master’s apartment, and, being chiefly Neapolitans,
U||   are readily made drunk. I have keys, as you know, with which I can open
U||   any chamber or cabinet in Paris. For three months a night has not
U||   passed, during the greater part of which I have not been engaged,
U||   personally, in ransacking the D—— Hotel. My honor is interested, and,
U||   to mention a great secret, the reward is enormous. So I did not abandon
U||   the search until I had become fully satisfied that the thief is a more
U||   astute man than myself. I fancy that I have investigated every nook and
U||   corner of the premises in which it is possible that the paper can be
U||   concealed.”
U||   “But is it not possible,” I suggested, “that although the letter may be
U||   in possession of the minister, as it unquestionably is, he may have
U||   concealed it elsewhere than upon his own premises?”
U||   “This is barely possible,” said Dupin. “The present peculiar condition
U||   of affairs at court, and especially of those intrigues in which D—— is
U||   known to be involved, would render the instant availability of the
U||   document—its susceptibility of being produced at a moment’s notice—a
U||   point of nearly equal importance with its possession.”
U||   “Its susceptibility of being produced?” said I.
U||   “That is to say, of being destroyed,” said Dupin.
U||   “True,” I observed; “the paper is clearly then upon the premises. As
U||   for its being upon the person of the minister, we may consider that as
U||   out of the question.”
U||   “Entirely,” said the Prefect. “He has been twice waylaid, as if by
U||   footpads, and his person rigorously searched under my own inspection.”
U||   “You might have spared yourself this trouble,” said Dupin. “D——, I
U||   presume, is not altogether a fool, and, if not, must have anticipated
U||   these waylayings, as a matter of course.”
U||   “Not altogether a fool,” said G., “but then he’s a poet, which I take
U||   to be only one remove from a fool.”
U||   “True,” said Dupin, after a long and thoughtful whiff from his
U||   meerschaum, “although I have been guilty of certain doggrel myself.”
U||   “Suppose you detail,” said I, “the particulars of your search.”
U||   “Why the fact is, we took our time, and we searched everywhere. I have
U||   had long experience in these affairs. I took the entire building, room
U||   by room; devoting the nights of a whole week to each. We examined,
U||   first, the furniture of each apartment. We opened every possible
U||   drawer; and I presume you know that, to a properly trained police
U||   agent, such a thing as a secret drawer is impossible. Any man is a dolt
U||   who permits a ‘secret’ drawer to escape him in a search of this kind.
U||   The thing is so plain. There is a certain amount of bulk—of space—to be
U||   accounted for in every cabinet. Then we have accurate rules. The
U||   fiftieth part of a line could not escape us. After the cabinets we took
U||   the chairs. The cushions we probed with the fine long needles you have
U||   seen me employ. From the tables we removed the tops.”
U||   “Why so?”
U||   “Sometimes the top of a table, or other similarly arranged piece of
U||   furniture, is removed by the person wishing to conceal an article; then
U||   the leg is excavated, the article deposited within the cavity, and the
U||   top replaced. The bottoms and tops of bedposts are employed in the same
U||   way.”
U||   “But could not the cavity be detected by sounding?” I asked.
U||   “By no means, if, when the article is deposited, a sufficient wadding
U||   of cotton be placed around it. Besides, in our case, we were obliged to
U||   proceed without noise.”
U||   “But you could not have removed—you could not have taken to pieces all
U||   articles of furniture in which it would have been possible to make a
U||   deposit in the manner you mention. A letter may be compressed into a
U||   thin spiral roll, not differing much in shape or bulk from a large
U||   knitting-needle, and in this form it might be inserted into the rung of
U||   a chair, for example. You did not take to pieces all the chairs?”
U||   “Certainly not; but we did better—we examined the rungs of every chair
U||   in the hotel, and, indeed the jointings of every description of
U||   furniture, by the aid of a most powerful microscope. Had there been any
U||   traces of recent disturbance we should not have failed to detect it
U||   instantly. A single grain of gimlet-dust, for example, would have been
U||   as obvious as an apple. Any disorder in the glueing—any unusual gaping
U||   in the joints—would have sufficed to insure detection.”
U||   “I presume you looked to the mirrors, between the boards and the
U||   plates, and you probed the beds and the bed-clothes, as well as the
U||   curtains and carpets.”
U||   “That of course; and when we had absolutely completed every particle of
U||   the furniture in this way, then we examined the house itself. We
U||   divided its entire surface into compartments, which we numbered, so
U||   that none might be missed; then we scrutinized each individual square
U||   inch throughout the premises, including the two houses immediately
U||   adjoining, with the microscope, as before.”
U||   “The two houses adjoining!” I exclaimed; “you must have had a great
U||   deal of trouble.”
U||   “We had; but the reward offered is prodigious!”
U||   “You include the grounds about the houses?”
U||   “All the grounds are paved with brick. They gave us comparatively
U||   little trouble. We examined the moss between the bricks, and found it
U||   undisturbed.”
U||   “You looked among D——‘s papers, of course, and into the books of the
U||   library?”
U||   “Certainly; we opened every package and parcel; we not only opened
U||   every book, but we turned over every leaf in each volume, not
U||   contenting ourselves with a mere shake, according to the fashion of
U||   some of our police officers. We also measured the thickness of every
U||   book-cover, with the most accurate admeasurement, and applied to each
U||   the most jealous scrutiny of the microscope. Had any of the bindings
U||   been recently meddled with, it would have been utterly impossible that
U||   the fact should have escaped observation. Some five or six volumes,
U||   just from the hands of the binder, we carefully probed, longitudinally,
U||   with the needles.”
U||   “You explored the floors beneath the carpets?”
U||   “Beyond doubt. We removed every carpet, and examined the boards with
U||   the microscope.”
U||   “And the paper on the walls?”
U||   “Yes.”
U||   “You looked into the cellars?”
U||   “We did.”
U||   “Then,” I said, “you have been making a miscalculation, and the letter
U||   is not upon the premises, as you suppose.”
U||   “I fear you are right there,” said the Prefect. “And now, Dupin, what
U||   would you advise me to do?”
U||   “To make a thorough re-search of the premises.”
U||   “That is absolutely needless,” replied G——. “I am not more sure that I
U||   breathe than I am that the letter is not at the Hotel.”
U||   “I have no better advice to give you,” said Dupin. “You have, of
U||   course, an accurate description of the letter?”
U||   “Oh yes!”—And here the Prefect, producing a memorandum-book, proceeded
U||   to read aloud a minute account of the internal, and especially of the
U||   external appearance of the missing document. Soon after finishing the
U||   perusal of this description, he took his departure, more entirely
U||   depressed in spirits than I had ever known the good gentleman before.
U||   In about a month afterwards he paid us another visit, and found us
U||   occupied very nearly as before. He took a pipe and a chair and entered
U||   into some ordinary conversation. At length I said,—
U||   “Well, but G——, what of the purloined letter? I presume you have at
U||   last made up your mind that there is no such thing as overreaching the
U||   Minister?”
U||   “Confound him, say I—yes; I made the re-examination, however, as Dupin
U||   suggested—but it was all labor lost, as I knew it would be.”
U||   “How much was the reward offered, did you say?” asked Dupin.
U||   “Why, a very great deal—a very liberal reward—I don’t like to say how
U||   much, precisely; but one thing I will say, that I wouldn’t mind giving
U||   my individual check for fifty thousand francs to any one who could
U||   obtain me that letter. The fact is, it is becoming of more and more
U||   importance every day; and the reward has been lately doubled. If it
U||   were trebled, however, I could do no more than I have done.”
U||   “Why, yes,” said Dupin, drawlingly, between the whiffs of his
U||   meerschaum, “I really—think, G——, you have not exerted yourself—to the
U||   utmost in this matter. You might—do a little more, I think, eh?”
U||   “How?—in what way?”
U||   “Why—puff, puff—you might—puff, puff—employ counsel in the matter,
U||   eh?—puff, puff, puff. Do you remember the story they tell of
U||   Abernethy?”
U||   “No; hang Abernethy!”
U||   “To be sure! hang him and welcome. But, once upon a time, a certain
U||   rich miser conceived the design of spunging upon this Abernethy for a
U||   medical opinion. Getting up, for this purpose, an ordinary conversation
U||   in a private company, he insinuated his case to the physician, as that
U||   of an imaginary individual.
U||   “‘We will suppose,’ said the miser, ‘that his symptoms are such and
U||   such; now, doctor, what would you have directed him to take?’
U||   “‘Take!’ said Abernethy, ‘why, take advice, to be sure.’”
U||   “But,” said the Prefect, a little discomposed, “I am perfectly willing
U||   to take advice, and to pay for it. I would really give fifty thousand
U||   francs to any one who would aid me in the matter.”
U||   “In that case,” replied Dupin, opening a drawer, and producing a
U||   check-book, “you may as well fill me up a check for the amount
U||   mentioned. When you have signed it, I will hand you the letter.”
U||   I was astounded. The Prefect appeared absolutely thunder-stricken. For
U||   some minutes he remained speechless and motionless, looking
U||   incredulously at my friend with open mouth, and eyes that seemed
U||   starting from their sockets; then, apparently recovering himself in
U||   some measure, he seized a pen, and after several pauses and vacant
U||   stares, finally filled up and signed a check for fifty thousand francs,
U||   and handed it across the table to Dupin. The latter examined it
U||   carefully and deposited it in his pocket-book; then, unlocking an
U||   escritoire, took thence a letter and gave it to the Prefect. This
U||   functionary grasped it in a perfect agony of joy, opened it with a
U||   trembling hand, cast a rapid glance at its contents, and then,
U||   scrambling and struggling to the door, rushed at length unceremoniously
U||   from the room and from the house, without having uttered a syllable
U||   since Dupin had requested him to fill up the check.
U||   When he had gone, my friend entered into some explanations.
U||   “The Parisian police,” he said, “are exceedingly able in their way.
U||   They are persevering, ingenious, cunning, and thoroughly versed in the
U||   knowledge which their duties seem chiefly to demand. Thus, when G——
U||   detailed to us his mode of searching the premises at the Hotel D——, I
U||   felt entire confidence in his having made a satisfactory
U||   investigation—so far as his labors extended.”
U||   “So far as his labors extended?” said I.
U||   “Yes,” said Dupin. “The measures adopted were not only the best of
U||   their kind, but carried out to absolute perfection. Had the letter been
U||   deposited within the range of their search, these fellows would, beyond
U||   a question, have found it.”
U||   I merely laughed—but he seemed quite serious in all that he said.
U||   “The measures, then,” he continued, “were good in their kind, and well
U||   executed; their defect lay in their being inapplicable to the case, and
U||   to the man. A certain set of highly ingenious resources are, with the
U||   Prefect, a sort of Procrustean bed, to which he forcibly adapts his
U||   designs. But he perpetually errs by being too deep or too shallow for
U||   the matter in hand; and many a schoolboy is a better reasoner than he.
U||   I knew one about eight years of age, whose success at guessing in the
U||   game of ‘even and odd’ attracted universal admiration. This game is
U||   simple, and is played with marbles. One player holds in his hand a
U||   number of these toys, and demands of another whether that number is
U||   even or odd. If the guess is right, the guesser wins one; if wrong, he
U||   loses one. The boy to whom I allude won all the marbles of the school.
U||   Of course he had some principle of guessing; and this lay in mere
U||   observation and admeasurement of the astuteness of his opponents. For
U||   example, an arrant simpleton is his opponent, and, holding up his
U||   closed hand, asks, ‘are they even or odd?’ Our schoolboy replies,
U||   ‘odd,’ and loses; but upon the second trial he wins, for he then says
U||   to himself, ‘the simpleton had them even upon the first trial, and his
U||   amount of cunning is just sufficient to make him have them odd upon the
U||   second; I will therefore guess odd;’—he guesses odd, and wins. Now,
U||   with a simpleton a degree above the first, he would have reasoned thus:
U||   ‘This fellow finds that in the first instance I guessed odd, and, in
U||   the second, he will propose to himself, upon the first impulse, a
U||   simple variation from even to odd, as did the first simpleton; but then
U||   a second thought will suggest that this is too simple a variation, and
U||   finally he will decide upon putting it even as before. I will therefore
U||   guess even;’—he guesses even, and wins. Now this mode of reasoning in
U||   the schoolboy, whom his fellows termed ‘lucky,’—what, in its last
U||   analysis, is it?”
U||   “It is merely,” I said, “an identification of the reasoner’s intellect
U||   with that of his opponent.”
U||   “It is,” said Dupin; “and, upon inquiring of the boy by what means he
U||   effected the thorough identification in which his success consisted, I
U||   received answer as follows: ‘When I wish to find out how wise, or how
U||   stupid, or how good, or how wicked is any one, or what are his thoughts
U||   at the moment, I fashion the expression of my face, as accurately as
U||   possible, in accordance with the expression of his, and then wait to
U||   see what thoughts or sentiments arise in my mind or heart, as if to
U||   match or correspond with the expression.’ This response of the
U||   schoolboy lies at the bottom of all the spurious profundity which has
U||   been attributed to Rochefoucault, to La Bougive, to Machiavelli, and to
U||   Campanella.”
U||   “And the identification,” I said, “of the reasoner’s intellect with
U||   that of his opponent, depends, if I understand you aright, upon the
U||   accuracy with which the opponent’s intellect is admeasured.”
U||   “For its practical value it depends upon this,” replied Dupin; “and the
U||   Prefect and his cohort fail so frequently, first, by default of this
U||   identification, and, secondly, by ill-admeasurement, or rather through
U||   non-admeasurement, of the intellect with which they are engaged. They
U||   consider only their own ideas of ingenuity; and, in searching for
U||   anything hidden, advert only to the modes in which they would have
U||   hidden it. They are right in this much—that their own ingenuity is a
U||   faithful representative of that of the mass; but when the cunning of
U||   the individual felon is diverse in character from their own, the felon
U||   foils them, of course. This always happens when it is above their own,
U||   and very usually when it is below. They have no variation of principle
U||   in their investigations; at best, when urged by some unusual
U||   emergency—by some extraordinary reward—they extend or exaggerate their
U||   old modes of practice, without touching their principles. What, for
U||   example, in this case of D——, has been done to vary the principle of
U||   action? What is all this boring, and probing, and sounding, and
U||   scrutinizing with the microscope and dividing the surface of the
U||   building into registered square inches—what is it all but an
U||   exaggeration of the application of the one principle or set of
U||   principles of search, which are based upon the one set of notions
U||   regarding human ingenuity, to which the Prefect, in the long routine of
U||   his duty, has been accustomed? Do you not see he has taken it for
U||   granted that all men proceed to conceal a letter,—not exactly in a
U||   gimlet hole bored in a chair-leg—but, at least, in some out-of-the-way
U||   hole or corner suggested by the same tenor of thought which would urge
U||   a man to secrete a letter in a gimlet-hole bored in a chair-leg? And do
U||   you not see also, that such recherchés nooks for concealment are
U||   adapted only for ordinary occasions, and would be adopted only by
U||   ordinary intellects; for, in all cases of concealment, a disposal of
U||   the article concealed—a disposal of it in this recherché manner,—is, in
U||   the very first instance, presumable and presumed; and thus its
U||   discovery depends, not at all upon the acumen, but altogether upon the
U||   mere care, patience, and determination of the seekers; and where the
U||   case is of importance—or, what amounts to the same thing in the
U||   political eyes, when the reward is of magnitude,—the qualities in
U||   question have never been known to fail. You will now understand what I
U||   meant in suggesting that, had the purloined letter been hidden any
U||   where within the limits of the Prefect’s examination—in other words,
U||   had the principle of its concealment been comprehended within the
U||   principles of the Prefect—its discovery would have been a matter
U||   altogether beyond question. This functionary, however, has been
U||   thoroughly mystified; and the remote source of his defeat lies in the
U||   supposition that the Minister is a fool, because he has acquired renown
U||   as a poet. All fools are poets; this the Prefect feels; and he is
U||   merely guilty of a non distributio medii in thence inferring that all
U||   poets are fools.”
U||   “But is this really the poet?” I asked. “There are two brothers, I
U||   know; and both have attained reputation in letters. The Minister I
U||   believe has written learnedly on the Differential Calculus. He is a
U||   mathematician, and no poet.”
U||   “You are mistaken; I know him well; he is both. As poet and
U||   mathematician, he would reason well; as mere mathematician, he could
U||   not have reasoned at all, and thus would have been at the mercy of the
U||   Prefect.”
U||   “You surprise me,” I said, “by these opinions, which have been
U||   contradicted by the voice of the world. You do not mean to set at
U||   naught the well-digested idea of centuries. The mathematical reason has
U||   long been regarded as the reason par excellence.”
U||   “‘Il y a à parièr,’” replied Dupin, quoting from Chamfort, “‘que toute
U||   idée publique, toute convention reçue est une sottise, car elle a
U||   convenue au plus grand nombre.’ The mathematicians, I grant you, have
U||   done their best to promulgate the popular error to which you allude,
U||   and which is none the less an error for its promulgation as truth. With
U||   an art worthy a better cause, for example, they have insinuated the
U||   term ‘analysis’ into application to algebra. The French are the
U||   originators of this particular deception; but if a term is of any
U||   importance—if words derive any value from applicability—then ‘analysis’
U||   conveys ‘algebra’ about as much as, in Latin, ‘ambitus’ implies
U||   ‘ambition,’ ‘religio’ ‘religion,’ or ‘homines honesti’ a set of
U||   honorable men.”
U||   “You have a quarrel on hand, I see,” said I, “with some of the
U||   algebraists of Paris; but proceed.”
U||   “I dispute the availability, and thus the value, of that reason which
U||   is cultivated in any especial form other than the abstractly logical. I
U||   dispute, in particular, the reason educed by mathematical study. The
U||   mathematics are the science of form and quantity; mathematical
U||   reasoning is merely logic applied to observation upon form and
U||   quantity. The great error lies in supposing that even the truths of
U||   what is called pure algebra, are abstract or general truths. And this
U||   error is so egregious that I am confounded at the universality with
U||   which it has been received. Mathematical axioms are not axioms of
U||   general truth. What is true of relation—of form and quantity—is often
U||   grossly false in regard to morals, for example. In this latter science
U||   it is very usually untrue that the aggregated parts are equal to the
U||   whole. In chemistry also the axiom fails. In the consideration of
U||   motive it fails; for two motives, each of a given value, have not,
U||   necessarily, a value when united, equal to the sum of their values
U||   apart. There are numerous other mathematical truths which are only
U||   truths within the limits of relation. But the mathematician argues,
U||   from his finite truths, through habit, as if they were of an absolutely
U||   general applicability—as the world indeed imagines them to be. Bryant,
U||   in his very learned ‘Mythology,’ mentions an analogous source of error,
U||   when he says that ‘although the Pagan fables are not believed, yet we
U||   forget ourselves continually, and make inferences from them as existing
U||   realities.’ With the algebraists, however, who are Pagans themselves,
U||   the ‘Pagan fables’ are believed, and the inferences are made, not so
U||   much through lapse of memory, as through an unaccountable addling of
U||   the brains. In short, I never yet encountered the mere mathematician
U||   who could be trusted out of equal roots, or one who did not
U||   clandestinely hold it as a point of his faith that x^2+px was
U||   absolutely and unconditionally equal to q. Say to one of these
U||   gentlemen, by way of experiment, if you please, that you believe
U||   occasions may occur where x^2+px is not altogether equal to q, and,
U||   having made him understand what you mean, get out of his reach as
U||   speedily as convenient, for, beyond doubt, he will endeavor to knock
U||   you down.
U||   “I mean to say,” continued Dupin, while I merely laughed at his last
U||   observations, “that if the Minister had been no more than a
U||   mathematician, the Prefect would have been under no necessity of giving
U||   me this check. I know him, however, as both mathematician and poet, and
U||   my measures were adapted to his capacity, with reference to the
U||   circumstances by which he was surrounded. I knew him as a courtier,
U||   too, and as a bold intriguant. Such a man, I considered, could not fail
U||   to be aware of the ordinary policial modes of action. He could not have
U||   failed to anticipate—and events have proved that he did not fail to
U||   anticipate—the waylayings to which he was subjected. He must have
U||   foreseen, I reflected, the secret investigations of his premises. His
U||   frequent absences from home at night, which were hailed by the Prefect
U||   as certain aids to his success, I regarded only as ruses, to afford
U||   opportunity for thorough search to the police, and thus the sooner to
U||   impress them with the conviction to which G——, in fact, did finally
U||   arrive—the conviction that the letter was not upon the premises. I
U||   felt, also, that the whole train of thought, which I was at some pains
U||   in detailing to you just now, concerning the invariable principle of
U||   policial action in searches for articles concealed—I felt that this
U||   whole train of thought would necessarily pass through the mind of the
U||   Minister. It would imperatively lead him to despise all the ordinary
U||   nooks of concealment. He could not, I reflected, be so weak as not to
U||   see that the most intricate and remote recess of his hotel would be as
U||   open as his commonest closets to the eyes, to the probes, to the
U||   gimlets, and to the microscopes of the Prefect. I saw, in fine, that he
U||   would be driven, as a matter of course, to simplicity, if not
U||   deliberately induced to it as a matter of choice. You will remember,
U||   perhaps, how desperately the Prefect laughed when I suggested, upon our
U||   first interview, that it was just possible this mystery troubled him so
U||   much on account of its being so very self-evident.”
U||   “Yes,” said I, “I remember his merriment well. I really thought he
U||   would have fallen into convulsions.”
U||   “The material world,” continued Dupin, “abounds with very strict
U||   analogies to the immaterial; and thus some color of truth has been
U||   given to the rhetorical dogma, that metaphor, or simile, may be made to
U||   strengthen an argument, as well as to embellish a description. The
U||   principle of the vis inertiæ, for example, seems to be identical in
U||   physics and metaphysics. It is not more true in the former, that a
U||   large body is with more difficulty set in motion than a smaller one,
U||   and that its subsequent momentum is commensurate with this difficulty,
U||   than it is, in the latter, that intellects of the vaster capacity,
U||   while more forcible, more constant, and more eventful in their
U||   movements than those of inferior grade, are yet the less readily moved,
U||   and more embarrassed and full of hesitation in the first few steps of
U||   their progress. Again: have you ever noticed which of the street signs,
U||   over the shop-doors, are the most attractive of attention?”
U||   “I have never given the matter a thought,” I said.
U||   “There is a game of puzzles,” he resumed, “which is played upon a map.
U||   One party playing requires another to find a given word—the name of
U||   town, river, state or empire—any word, in short, upon the motley and
U||   perplexed surface of the chart. A novice in the game generally seeks to
U||   embarrass his opponents by giving them the most minutely lettered
U||   names; but the adept selects such words as stretch, in large
U||   characters, from one end of the chart to the other. These, like the
U||   over-largely lettered signs and placards of the street, escape
U||   observation by dint of being excessively obvious; and here the physical
U||   oversight is precisely analogous with the moral inapprehension by which
U||   the intellect suffers to pass unnoticed those considerations which are
U||   too obtrusively and too palpably self-evident. But this is a point, it
U||   appears, somewhat above or beneath the understanding of the Prefect. He
U||   never once thought it probable, or possible, that the Minister had
U||   deposited the letter immediately beneath the nose of the whole world,
U||   by way of best preventing any portion of that world from perceiving it.
U||   “But the more I reflected upon the daring, dashing, and discriminating
U||   ingenuity of D——; upon the fact that the document must always have been
U||   at hand, if he intended to use it to good purpose; and upon the
U||   decisive evidence, obtained by the Prefect, that it was not hidden
U||   within the limits of that dignitary’s ordinary search—the more
U||   satisfied I became that, to conceal this letter, the Minister had
U||   resorted to the comprehensive and sagacious expedient of not attempting
U||   to conceal it at all.
U||   “Full of these ideas, I prepared myself with a pair of green
U||   spectacles, and called one fine morning, quite by accident, at the
U||   Ministerial hotel. I found D—— at home, yawning, lounging, and
U||   dawdling, as usual, and pretending to be in the last extremity of
U||   ennui. He is, perhaps, the most really energetic human being now
U||   alive—but that is only when nobody sees him.
U||   “To be even with him, I complained of my weak eyes, and lamented the
U||   necessity of the spectacles, under cover of which I cautiously and
U||   thoroughly surveyed the whole apartment, while seemingly intent only
U||   upon the conversation of my host.
U||   “I paid especial attention to a large writing-table near which he sat,
U||   and upon which lay confusedly, some miscellaneous letters and other
U||   papers, with one or two musical instruments and a few books. Here,
U||   however, after a long and very deliberate scrutiny, I saw nothing to
U||   excite particular suspicion.
U||   “At length my eyes, in going the circuit of the room, fell upon a
U||   trumpery fillagree card-rack of pasteboard, that hung dangling by a
U||   dirty blue ribbon, from a little brass knob just beneath the middle of
U||   the mantel-piece. In this rack, which had three or four compartments,
U||   were five or six visiting cards and a solitary letter. This last was
U||   much soiled and crumpled. It was torn nearly in two, across the
U||   middle—as if a design, in the first instance, to tear it entirely up as
U||   worthless, had been altered, or stayed, in the second. It had a large
U||   black seal, bearing the D—— cipher very conspicuously, and was
U||   addressed, in a diminutive female hand, to D——, the minister, himself.
U||   It was thrust carelessly, and even, as it seemed, contemptuously, into
U||   one of the uppermost divisions of the rack.
U||   “No sooner had I glanced at this letter, than I concluded it to be that
U||   of which I was in search. To be sure, it was, to all appearance,
U||   radically different from the one of which the Prefect had read us so
U||   minute a description. Here the seal was large and black, with the D——
U||   cipher; there it was small and red, with the ducal arms of the S——
U||   family. Here, the address, to the Minister, diminutive and feminine;
U||   there the superscription, to a certain royal personage, was markedly
U||   bold and decided; the size alone formed a point of correspondence. But,
U||   then, the radicalness of these differences, which was excessive; the
U||   dirt; the soiled and torn condition of the paper, so inconsistent with
U||   the true methodical habits of D——, and so suggestive of a design to
U||   delude the beholder into an idea of the worthlessness of the
U||   document—these things, together with the hyper-obtrusive situation of
U||   this document, full in the view of every visitor, and thus exactly in
U||   accordance with the conclusions to which I had previously arrived;
U||   these things, I say, were strongly corroborative of suspicion, in one
U||   who came with the intention to suspect.
U||   “I protracted my visit as long as possible, and, while I maintained a
U||   most animated discussion with the Minister upon a topic which I knew
U||   well had never failed to interest and excite him, I kept my attention
U||   really riveted upon the letter. In this examination, I committed to
U||   memory its external appearance and arrangement in the rack; and also
U||   fell, at length, upon a discovery which set at rest whatever trivial
U||   doubt I might have entertained. In scrutinizing the edges of the paper,
U||   I observed them to be more chafed than seemed necessary. They presented
U||   the broken appearance which is manifested when a stiff paper, having
U||   been once folded and pressed with a folder, is refolded in a reversed
U||   direction, in the same creases or edges which had formed the original
U||   fold. This discovery was sufficient. It was clear to me that the letter
U||   had been turned, as a glove, inside out, re-directed, and re-sealed. I
U||   bade the Minister good morning, and took my departure at once, leaving
U||   a gold snuff-box upon the table.
U||   “The next morning I called for the snuff-box, when we resumed, quite
U||   eagerly, the conversation of the preceding day. While thus engaged,
U||   however, a loud report, as if of a pistol, was heard immediately
U||   beneath the windows of the hotel, and was succeeded by a series of
U||   fearful screams, and the shoutings of a terrified mob. D—— rushed to a
U||   casement, threw it open, and looked out. In the meantime, I stepped to
U||   the card-rack, took the letter, put it in my pocket, and replaced it by
U||   a fac-simile, (so far as regards externals,) which I had carefully
U||   prepared at my lodgings—imitating the D—— cipher, very readily, by
U||   means of a seal formed of bread.
U||   “The disturbance in the street had been occasioned by the frantic
U||   behavior of a man with a musket. He had fired it among a crowd of women
U||   and children. It proved, however, to have been without ball, and the
U||   fellow was suffered to go his way as a lunatic or a drunkard. When he
U||   had gone, D—— came from the window, whither I had followed him
U||   immediately upon securing the object in view. Soon afterwards I bade
U||   him farewell. The pretended lunatic was a man in my own pay.”
U||   “But what purpose had you,” I asked, “in replacing the letter by a
U||   fac-simile? Would it not have been better, at the first visit, to have
U||   seized it openly, and departed?”
U||   “D——,” replied Dupin, “is a desperate man, and a man of nerve. His
U||   hotel, too, is not without attendants devoted to his interests. Had I
U||   made the wild attempt you suggest, I might never have left the
U||   Ministerial presence alive. The good people of Paris might have heard
U||   of me no more. But I had an object apart from these considerations. You
U||   know my political prepossessions. In this matter, I act as a partisan
U||   of the lady concerned. For eighteen months the Minister has had her in
U||   his power. She has now him in hers—since, being unaware that the letter
U||   is not in his possession, he will proceed with his exactions as if it
U||   was. Thus will he inevitably commit himself, at once, to his political
U||   destruction. His downfall, too, will not be more precipitate than
U||   awkward. It is all very well to talk about the facilis descensus
U||   Averni; but in all kinds of climbing, as Catalani said of singing, it
U||   is far more easy to get up than to come down. In the present instance I
U||   have no sympathy—at least no pity—for him who descends. He is that
U||   monstrum horrendum, an unprincipled man of genius. I confess, however,
U||   that I should like very well to know the precise character of his
U||   thoughts, when, being defied by her whom the Prefect terms ‘a certain
U||   personage’ he is reduced to opening the letter which I left for him in
U||   the card-rack.”
U||   “How? did you put any thing particular in it?”
U||   “Why—it did not seem altogether right to leave the interior blank—that
U||   would have been insulting. D——, at Vienna once, did me an evil turn,
U||   which I told him, quite good-humoredly, that I should remember. So, as
U||   I knew he would feel some curiosity in regard to the identity of the
U||   person who had outwitted him, I thought it a pity not to give him a
U||   clue. He is well acquainted with my MS., and I just copied into the
U||   middle of the blank sheet the words—
U||   “‘— — Un dessein si funeste,
U||   S’il n’est digne d’Atrée, est digne de Thyeste.
U||   They are to be found in Crébillon’s ‘Atrée.’”
U||THE THOUSAND-AND-SECOND TALE OF SCHEHERAZADE
U||   Truth is stranger than fiction.—Old Saying
U||   Having had occasion, lately, in the course of some Oriental
U||   investigations, to consult the Tellmenow Isitsöornot, a work which
U||   (like the Zohar of Simeon Jochaides) is scarcely known at all, even in
U||   Europe; and which has never been quoted, to my knowledge, by any
U||   American—if we except, perhaps, the author of the “Curiosities of
U||   American Literature”;—having had occasion, I say, to turn over some
U||   pages of the first-mentioned very remarkable work, I was not a little
U||   astonished to discover that the literary world has hitherto been
U||   strangely in error respecting the fate of the vizier’s daughter,
U||   Scheherazade, as that fate is depicted in the “Arabian Nights”; and
U||   that the dénouement there given, if not altogether inaccurate, as far
U||   as it goes, is at least to blame in not having gone very much farther.
U||   For full information on this interesting topic, I must refer the
U||   inquisitive reader to the “Isitsöornot” itself; but in the meantime, I
U||   shall be pardoned for giving a summary of what I there discovered.
U||   It will be remembered, that, in the usual version of the tales, a
U||   certain monarch having good cause to be jealous of his queen, not only
U||   puts her to death, but makes a vow, by his beard and the prophet, to
U||   espouse each night the most beautiful maiden in his dominions, and the
U||   next morning to deliver her up to the executioner.
U||   Having fulfilled this vow for many years to the letter, and with a
U||   religious punctuality and method that conferred great credit upon him
U||   as a man of devout feeling and excellent sense, he was interrupted one
U||   afternoon (no doubt at his prayers) by a visit from his grand vizier,
U||   to whose daughter, it appears, there had occurred an idea.
U||   Her name was Scheherazade, and her idea was, that she would either
U||   redeem the land from the depopulating tax upon its beauty, or perish,
U||   after the approved fashion of all heroines, in the attempt.
U||   Accordingly, and although we do not find it to be leap-year (which
U||   makes the sacrifice more meritorious), she deputes her father, the
U||   grand vizier, to make an offer to the king of her hand. This hand the
U||   king eagerly accepts—(he had intended to take it at all events, and had
U||   put off the matter from day to day, only through fear of the
U||   vizier),—but, in accepting it now, he gives all parties very distinctly
U||   to understand, that, grand vizier or no grand vizier, he has not the
U||   slightest design of giving up one iota of his vow or of his privileges.
U||   When, therefore, the fair Scheherazade insisted upon marrying the king,
U||   and did actually marry him despite her father’s excellent advice not to
U||   do any thing of the kind—when she would and did marry him, I say, will
U||   I, nill I, it was with her beautiful black eyes as thoroughly open as
U||   the nature of the case would allow.
U||   It seems, however, that this politic damsel (who had been reading
U||   Machiavelli, beyond doubt), had a very ingenious little plot in her
U||   mind. On the night of the wedding, she contrived, upon I forget what
U||   specious pretence, to have her sister occupy a couch sufficiently near
U||   that of the royal pair to admit of easy conversation from bed to bed;
U||   and, a little before cock-crowing, she took care to awaken the good
U||   monarch, her husband (who bore her none the worse will because he
U||   intended to wring her neck on the morrow),—she managed to awaken him, I
U||   say, (although on account of a capital conscience and an easy
U||   digestion, he slept well) by the profound interest of a story (about a
U||   rat and a black cat, I think) which she was narrating (all in an
U||   undertone, of course) to her sister. When the day broke, it so happened
U||   that this history was not altogether finished, and that Scheherazade,
U||   in the nature of things could not finish it just then, since it was
U||   high time for her to get up and be bowstrung—a thing very little more
U||   pleasant than hanging, only a trifle more genteel!
U||   The king’s curiosity, however, prevailing, I am sorry to say, even over
U||   his sound religious principles, induced him for this once to postpone
U||   the fulfilment of his vow until next morning, for the purpose and with
U||   the hope of hearing that night how it fared in the end with the black
U||   cat (a black cat, I think it was) and the rat.
U||   The night having arrived, however, the lady Scheherazade not only put
U||   the finishing stroke to the black cat and the rat (the rat was blue)
U||   but before she well knew what she was about, found herself deep in the
U||   intricacies of a narration, having reference (if I am not altogether
U||   mistaken) to a pink horse (with green wings) that went, in a violent
U||   manner, by clockwork, and was wound up with an indigo key. With this
U||   history the king was even more profoundly interested than with the
U||   other—and, as the day broke before its conclusion (notwithstanding all
U||   the queen’s endeavors to get through with it in time for the
U||   bowstringing), there was again no resource but to postpone that
U||   ceremony as before, for twenty-four hours. The next night there
U||   happened a similar accident with a similar result; and then the
U||   next—and then again the next; so that, in the end, the good monarch,
U||   having been unavoidably deprived of all opportunity to keep his vow
U||   during a period of no less than one thousand and one nights, either
U||   forgets it altogether by the expiration of this time, or gets himself
U||   absolved of it in the regular way, or (what is more probable) breaks it
U||   outright, as well as the head of his father confessor. At all events,
U||   Scheherazade, who, being lineally descended from Eve, fell heir,
U||   perhaps, to the whole seven baskets of talk, which the latter lady, we
U||   all know, picked up from under the trees in the garden of Eden;
U||   Scheherazade, I say, finally triumphed, and the tariff upon beauty was
U||   repealed.
U||   Now, this conclusion (which is that of the story as we have it upon
U||   record) is, no doubt, excessively proper and pleasant—but alas! like a
U||   great many pleasant things, is more pleasant than true, and I am
U||   indebted altogether to the “Isitsöornot” for the means of correcting
U||   the error. “Le mieux,” says a French proverb, “est l’ennemi du bien,”
U||   and, in mentioning that Scheherazade had inherited the seven baskets of
U||   talk, I should have added that she put them out at compound interest
U||   until they amounted to seventy-seven.
U||   “My dear sister,” said she, on the thousand-and-second night, (I quote
U||   the language of the “Isitsöornot” at this point, verbatim) “my dear
U||   sister,” said she, “now that all this little difficulty about the
U||   bowstring has blown over, and that this odious tax is so happily
U||   repealed, I feel that I have been guilty of great indiscretion in
U||   withholding from you and the king (who I am sorry to say, snores—a
U||   thing no gentleman would do) the full conclusion of Sinbad the sailor.
U||   This person went through numerous other and more interesting adventures
U||   than those which I related; but the truth is, I felt sleepy on the
U||   particular night of their narration, and so was seduced into cutting
U||   them short—a grievous piece of misconduct, for which I only trust that
U||   Allah will forgive me. But even yet it is not too late to remedy my
U||   great neglect—and as soon as I have given the king a pinch or two in
U||   order to wake him up so far that he may stop making that horrible
U||   noise, I will forthwith entertain you (and him if he pleases) with the
U||   sequel of this very remarkable story.”
U||   Hereupon the sister of Scheherazade, as I have it from the
U||   “Isitsöornot,” expressed no very particular intensity of gratification;
U||   but the king, having been sufficiently pinched, at length ceased
U||   snoring, and finally said, “Hum!” and then “Hoo!” when the queen,
U||   understanding these words (which are no doubt Arabic) to signify that
U||   he was all attention, and would do his best not to snore any more—the
U||   queen, I say, having arranged these matters to her satisfaction,
U||   re-entered thus, at once, into the history of Sinbad the sailor:
U||   “‘At length, in my old age,’ [these are the words of Sinbad himself, as
U||   retailed by Scheherazade]—‘at length, in my old age, and after enjoying
U||   many years of tranquillity at home, I became once more possessed of a
U||   desire of visiting foreign countries; and one day, without acquainting
U||   any of my family with my design, I packed up some bundles of such
U||   merchandise as was most precious and least bulky, and, engaging a
U||   porter to carry them, went with him down to the sea-shore, to await the
U||   arrival of any chance vessel that might convey me out of the kingdom
U||   into some region which I had not as yet explored.
U||   “‘Having deposited the packages upon the sands, we sat down beneath
U||   some trees, and looked out into the ocean in the hope of perceiving a
U||   ship, but during several hours we saw none whatever. At length I
U||   fancied that I could hear a singular buzzing or humming sound; and the
U||   porter, after listening awhile, declared that he also could distinguish
U||   it. Presently it grew louder, and then still louder, so that we could
U||   have no doubt that the object which caused it was approaching us. At
U||   length, on the edge of the horizon, we discovered a black speck, which
U||   rapidly increased in size until we made it out to be a vast monster,
U||   swimming with a great part of its body above the surface of the sea. It
U||   came toward us with inconceivable swiftness, throwing up huge waves of
U||   foam around its breast, and illuminating all that part of the sea
U||   through which it passed, with a long line of fire that extended far off
U||   into the distance.
U||   “‘As the thing drew near we saw it very distinctly. Its length was
U||   equal to that of three of the loftiest trees that grow, and it was as
U||   wide as the great hall of audience in your palace, O most sublime and
U||   munificent of the Caliphs. Its body, which was unlike that of ordinary
U||   fishes, was as solid as a rock, and of a jetty blackness throughout all
U||   that portion of it which floated above the water, with the exception of
U||   a narrow blood-red streak that completely begirdled it. The belly,
U||   which floated beneath the surface, and of which we could get only a
U||   glimpse now and then as the monster rose and fell with the billows, was
U||   entirely covered with metallic scales, of a color like that of the moon
U||   in misty weather. The back was flat and nearly white, and from it there
U||   extended upwards of six spines, about half the length of the whole
U||   body.
U||   “‘This horrible creature had no mouth that we could perceive; but, as
U||   if to make up for this deficiency, it was provided with at least four
U||   score of eyes, that protruded from their sockets like those of the
U||   green dragon-fly, and were arranged all around the body in two rows,
U||   one above the other, and parallel to the blood-red streak, which seemed
U||   to answer the purpose of an eyebrow. Two or three of these dreadful
U||   eyes were much larger than the others, and had the appearance of solid
U||   gold.
U||   “‘Although this beast approached us, as I have before said, with the
U||   greatest rapidity, it must have been moved altogether by necromancy—for
U||   it had neither fins like a fish nor web-feet like a duck, nor wings
U||   like the seashell which is blown along in the manner of a vessel; nor
U||   yet did it writhe itself forward as do the eels. Its head and its tail
U||   were shaped precisely alike, only, not far from the latter, were two
U||   small holes that served for nostrils, and through which the monster
U||   puffed out its thick breath with prodigious violence, and with a
U||   shrieking, disagreeable noise.
U||   “‘Our terror at beholding this hideous thing was very great, but it was
U||   even surpassed by our astonishment, when upon getting a nearer look, we
U||   perceived upon the creature’s back a vast number of animals about the
U||   size and shape of men, and altogether much resembling them, except that
U||   they wore no garments (as men do), being supplied (by nature, no doubt)
U||   with an ugly uncomfortable covering, a good deal like cloth, but
U||   fitting so tight to the skin, as to render the poor wretches laughably
U||   awkward, and put them apparently to severe pain. On the very tips of
U||   their heads were certain square-looking boxes, which, at first sight, I
U||   thought might have been intended to answer as turbans, but I soon
U||   discovered that they were excessively heavy and solid, and I therefore
U||   concluded they were contrivances designed, by their great weight, to
U||   keep the heads of the animals steady and safe upon their shoulders.
U||   Around the necks of the creatures were fastened black collars, (badges
U||   of servitude, no doubt,) such as we keep on our dogs, only much wider
U||   and infinitely stiffer, so that it was quite impossible for these poor
U||   victims to move their heads in any direction without moving the body at
U||   the same time; and thus they were doomed to perpetual contemplation of
U||   their noses—a view puggish and snubby in a wonderful, if not positively
U||   in an awful degree.
U||   “‘When the monster had nearly reached the shore where we stood, it
U||   suddenly pushed out one of its eyes to a great extent, and emitted from
U||   it a terrible flash of fire, accompanied by a dense cloud of smoke, and
U||   a noise that I can compare to nothing but thunder. As the smoke cleared
U||   away, we saw one of the odd man-animals standing near the head of the
U||   large beast with a trumpet in his hand, through which (putting it to
U||   his mouth) he presently addressed us in loud, harsh, and disagreeable
U||   accents, that, perhaps, we should have mistaken for language, had they
U||   not come altogether through the nose.
U||   “‘Being thus evidently spoken to, I was at a loss how to reply, as I
U||   could in no manner understand what was said; and in this difficulty I
U||   turned to the porter, who was near swooning through affright, and
U||   demanded of him his opinion as to what species of monster it was, what
U||   it wanted, and what kind of creatures those were that so swarmed upon
U||   its back. To this the porter replied, as well as he could for
U||   trepidation, that he had once before heard of this sea-beast; that it
U||   was a cruel demon, with bowels of sulphur and blood of fire, created by
U||   evil genii as the means of inflicting misery upon mankind; that the
U||   things upon its back were vermin, such as sometimes infest cats and
U||   dogs, only a little larger and more savage; and that these vermin had
U||   their uses, however evil—for, through the torture they caused the beast
U||   by their nibbling and stingings, it was goaded into that degree of
U||   wrath which was requisite to make it roar and commit ill, and so fulfil
U||   the vengeful and malicious designs of the wicked genii.
U||   “This account determined me to take to my heels, and, without once even
U||   looking behind me, I ran at full speed up into the hills, while the
U||   porter ran equally fast, although nearly in an opposite direction, so
U||   that, by these means, he finally made his escape with my bundles, of
U||   which I have no doubt he took excellent care—although this is a point I
U||   cannot determine, as I do not remember that I ever beheld him again.
U||   “‘For myself, I was so hotly pursued by a swarm of the men-vermin (who
U||   had come to the shore in boats) that I was very soon overtaken, bound
U||   hand and foot, and conveyed to the beast, which immediately swam out
U||   again into the middle of the sea.
U||   “‘I now bitterly repented my folly in quitting a comfortable home to
U||   peril my life in such adventures as this; but regret being useless, I
U||   made the best of my condition, and exerted myself to secure the
U||   goodwill of the man-animal that owned the trumpet, and who appeared to
U||   exercise authority over his fellows. I succeeded so well in this
U||   endeavor that, in a few days, the creature bestowed upon me various
U||   tokens of his favor, and in the end even went to the trouble of
U||   teaching me the rudiments of what it was vain enough to denominate its
U||   language; so that, at length, I was enabled to converse with it
U||   readily, and came to make it comprehend the ardent desire I had of
U||   seeing the world.
U||   “‘Washish squashish squeak, Sinbad, hey-diddle diddle, grunt unt
U||   grumble, hiss, fiss, whiss,’ said he to me, one day after dinner—but I
U||   beg a thousand pardons, I had forgotten that your majesty is not
U||   conversant with the dialect of the Cock-neighs (so the man-animals were
U||   called; I presume because their language formed the connecting link
U||   between that of the horse and that of the rooster). With your
U||   permission, I will translate. ‘Washish squashish,’ and so forth:—that
U||   is to say, ‘I am happy to find, my dear Sinbad, that you are really a
U||   very excellent fellow; we are now about doing a thing which is called
U||   circumnavigating the globe; and since you are so desirous of seeing the
U||   world, I will strain a point and give you a free passage upon back of
U||   the beast.’”
U||   When the Lady Scheherazade had proceeded thus far, relates the
U||   “Isitsöornot,” the king turned over from his left side to his right,
U||   and said:
U||   “It is, in fact, very surprising, my dear queen, that you omitted,
U||   hitherto, these latter adventures of Sinbad. Do you know I think them
U||   exceedingly entertaining and strange?”
U||   The king having thus expressed himself, we are told, the fair
U||   Scheherazade resumed her history in the following words:
U||   “Sinbad went on in this manner with his narrative—‘I thanked the
U||   man-animal for its kindness, and soon found myself very much at home on
U||   the beast, which swam at a prodigious rate through the ocean; although
U||   the surface of the latter is, in that part of the world, by no means
U||   flat, but round like a pomegranate, so that we went—so to say—either up
U||   hill or down hill all the time.’
U||   “That I think, was very singular,” interrupted the king.
U||   “Nevertheless, it is quite true,” replied Scheherazade.
U||   “I have my doubts,” rejoined the king; “but, pray, be so good as to go
U||   on with the story.”
U||   “I will,” said the queen. “‘The beast,’ continued Sinbad to the caliph,
U||   ‘swam, as I have related, up hill and down hill until, at length, we
U||   arrived at an island, many hundreds of miles in circumference, but
U||   which, nevertheless, had been built in the middle of the sea by a
U||   colony of little things like caterpillars.’” (*1)
U||   “Hum!” said the king.
U||   “‘Leaving this island,’ said Sinbad—(for Scheherazade, it must be
U||   understood, took no notice of her husband’s ill-mannered ejaculation)
U||   ‘leaving this island, we came to another where the forests were of
U||   solid stone, and so hard that they shivered to pieces the
U||   finest-tempered axes with which we endeavoured to cut them down.’” (*2)
U||   “Hum!” said the king, again; but Scheherazade, paying him no attention,
U||   continued in the language of Sinbad.
U||   “‘Passing beyond this last island, we reached a country where there was
U||   a cave that ran to the distance of thirty or forty miles within the
U||   bowels of the earth, and that contained a greater number of far more
U||   spacious and more magnificent palaces than are to be found in all
U||   Damascus and Bagdad. From the roofs of these palaces there hung myriads
U||   of gems, like diamonds, but larger than men; and in among the streets
U||   of towers and pyramids and temples, there flowed immense rivers as
U||   black as ebony, and swarming with fish that had no eyes.’” (*3)
U||   “Hum!” said the king.
U||   “‘We then swam into a region of the sea where we found a lofty
U||   mountain, down whose sides there streamed torrents of melted metal,
U||   some of which were twelve miles wide and sixty miles long (*4); while
U||   from an abyss on the summit, issued so vast a quantity of ashes that
U||   the sun was entirely blotted out from the heavens, and it became darker
U||   than the darkest midnight; so that when we were even at the distance of
U||   a hundred and fifty miles from the mountain, it was impossible to see
U||   the whitest object, however close we held it to our eyes.’” (*5)
U||   “Hum!” said the king.
U||   “‘After quitting this coast, the beast continued his voyage until we
U||   met with a land in which the nature of things seemed reversed—for we
U||   here saw a great lake, at the bottom of which, more than a hundred feet
U||   beneath the surface of the water, there flourished in full leaf a
U||   forest of tall and luxuriant trees.’” (*6)
U||   “Hoo!” said the king.
U||   “Some hundred miles farther on brought us to a climate where the
U||   atmosphere was so dense as to sustain iron or steel, just as our own
U||   does feather.’” (*7)
U||   “Fiddle de dee,” said the king.
U||   “Proceeding still in the same direction, we presently arrived at the
U||   most magnificent region in the whole world. Through it there meandered
U||   a glorious river for several thousands of miles. This river was of
U||   unspeakable depth, and of a transparency richer than that of amber. It
U||   was from three to six miles in width; and its banks which arose on
U||   either side to twelve hundred feet in perpendicular height, were
U||   crowned with ever-blossoming trees and perpetual sweet-scented flowers,
U||   that made the whole territory one gorgeous garden; but the name of this
U||   luxuriant land was the Kingdom of Horror, and to enter it was
U||   inevitable death.’” (*8)
U||   “Humph!” said the king.
U||   “‘We left this kingdom in great haste, and, after some days, came to
U||   another, where we were astonished to perceive myriads of monstrous
U||   animals with horns resembling scythes upon their heads. These hideous
U||   beasts dig for themselves vast caverns in the soil, of a funnel shape,
U||   and line the sides of them with rocks, so disposed one upon the other
U||   that they fall instantly, when trodden upon by other animals, thus
U||   precipitating them into the monster’s dens, where their blood is
U||   immediately sucked, and their carcasses afterwards hurled
U||   contemptuously out to an immense distance from “the caverns of
U||   death."’” (*9)
U||   “Pooh!” said the king.
U||   “‘Continuing our progress, we perceived a district with vegetables that
U||   grew not upon any soil but in the air. (*10) There were others that
U||   sprang from the substance of other vegetables; (*11) others that
U||   derived their substance from the bodies of living animals; (*12) and
U||   then again, there were others that glowed all over with intense fire;
U||   (*13) others that moved from place to place at pleasure, (*14) and what
U||   was still more wonderful, we discovered flowers that lived and breathed
U||   and moved their limbs at will and had, moreover, the detestable passion
U||   of mankind for enslaving other creatures, and confining them in horrid
U||   and solitary prisons until the fulfillment of appointed tasks.’” (*15)
U||   “Pshaw!” said the king.
U||   “‘Quitting this land, we soon arrived at another in which the bees and
U||   the birds are mathematicians of such genius and erudition, that they
U||   give daily instructions in the science of geometry to the wise men of
U||   the empire. The king of the place having offered a reward for the
U||   solution of two very difficult problems, they were solved upon the
U||   spot—the one by the bees, and the other by the birds; but the king
U||   keeping their solution a secret, it was only after the most profound
U||   researches and labor, and the writing of an infinity of big books,
U||   during a long series of years, that the men-mathematicians at length
U||   arrived at the identical solutions which had been given upon the spot
U||   by the bees and by the birds.’” (*16)
U||   “Oh my!” said the king.
U||   “‘We had scarcely lost sight of this empire when we found ourselves
U||   close upon another, from whose shores there flew over our heads a flock
U||   of fowls a mile in breadth, and two hundred and forty miles long; so
U||   that, although they flew a mile during every minute, it required no
U||   less than four hours for the whole flock to pass over us—in which there
U||   were several millions of millions of fowl.’” (*17)
U||   “Oh fy!” said the king.
U||   “‘No sooner had we got rid of these birds, which occasioned us great
U||   annoyance, than we were terrified by the appearance of a fowl of
U||   another kind, and infinitely larger than even the rocs which I met in
U||   my former voyages; for it was bigger than the biggest of the domes on
U||   your seraglio, oh, most Munificent of Caliphs. This terrible fowl had
U||   no head that we could perceive, but was fashioned entirely of belly,
U||   which was of a prodigious fatness and roundness, of a soft-looking
U||   substance, smooth, shining and striped with various colors. In its
U||   talons, the monster was bearing away to his eyrie in the heavens, a
U||   house from which it had knocked off the roof, and in the interior of
U||   which we distinctly saw human beings, who, beyond doubt, were in a
U||   state of frightful despair at the horrible fate which awaited them. We
U||   shouted with all our might, in the hope of frightening the bird into
U||   letting go of its prey, but it merely gave a snort or puff, as if of
U||   rage and then let fall upon our heads a heavy sack which proved to be
U||   filled with sand!’”
U||   “Stuff!” said the king.
U||   “‘It was just after this adventure that we encountered a continent of
U||   immense extent and prodigious solidity, but which, nevertheless, was
U||   supported entirely upon the back of a sky-blue cow that had no fewer
U||   than four hundred horns.’” (*18)
U||   “That, now, I believe,” said the king, “because I have read something
U||   of the kind before, in a book.”
U||   “‘We passed immediately beneath this continent, (swimming in between
U||   the legs of the cow), and, after some hours, found ourselves in a
U||   wonderful country indeed, which, I was informed by the man-animal, was
U||   his own native land, inhabited by things of his own species. This
U||   elevated the man-animal very much in my esteem, and in fact, I now
U||   began to feel ashamed of the contemptuous familiarity with which I had
U||   treated him; for I found that the man-animals in general were a nation
U||   of the most powerful magicians, who lived with worms in their brain,
U||   (*19) which, no doubt, served to stimulate them by their painful
U||   writhings and wrigglings to the most miraculous efforts of
U||   imagination!’”
U||   “Nonsense!” said the king.
U||   “‘Among the magicians, were domesticated several animals of very
U||   singular kinds; for example, there was a huge horse whose bones were
U||   iron and whose blood was boiling water. In place of corn, he had black
U||   stones for his usual food; and yet, in spite of so hard a diet, he was
U||   so strong and swift that he would drag a load more weighty than the
U||   grandest temple in this city, at a rate surpassing that of the flight
U||   of most birds.’” (*20)
U||   “Twattle!” said the king.
U||   “‘I saw, also, among these people a hen without feathers, but bigger
U||   than a camel; instead of flesh and bone she had iron and brick; her
U||   blood, like that of the horse, (to whom, in fact, she was nearly
U||   related,) was boiling water; and like him she ate nothing but wood or
U||   black stones. This hen brought forth very frequently, a hundred
U||   chickens in the day; and, after birth, they took up their residence for
U||   several weeks within the stomach of their mother.’” (*21)
U||   “Fal lal!” said the king.
U||   “‘One of this nation of mighty conjurors created a man out of brass and
U||   wood, and leather, and endowed him with such ingenuity that he would
U||   have beaten at chess, all the race of mankind with the exception of the
U||   great Caliph, Haroun Alraschid. (*22) Another of these magi constructed
U||   (of like material) a creature that put to shame even the genius of him
U||   who made it; for so great were its reasoning powers that, in a second,
U||   it performed calculations of so vast an extent that they would have
U||   required the united labor of fifty thousand fleshy men for a year.
U||   (*23) But a still more wonderful conjuror fashioned for himself a
U||   mighty thing that was neither man nor beast, but which had brains of
U||   lead, intermixed with a black matter like pitch, and fingers that it
U||   employed with such incredible speed and dexterity that it would have
U||   had no trouble in writing out twenty thousand copies of the Koran in an
U||   hour, and this with so exquisite a precision, that in all the copies
U||   there should not be found one to vary from another by the breadth of
U||   the finest hair. This thing was of prodigious strength, so that it
U||   erected or overthrew the mightiest empires at a breath; but its powers
U||   were exercised equally for evil and for good.’”
U||   “Ridiculous!” said the king.
U||   “‘Among this nation of necromancers there was also one who had in his
U||   veins the blood of the salamanders; for he made no scruple of sitting
U||   down to smoke his chibouc in a red-hot oven until his dinner was
U||   thoroughly roasted upon its floor. (*24) Another had the faculty of
U||   converting the common metals into gold, without even looking at them
U||   during the process. (*25) Another had such a delicacy of touch that he
U||   made a wire so fine as to be invisible. (*26) Another had such
U||   quickness of perception that he counted all the separate motions of an
U||   elastic body, while it was springing backward and forward at the rate
U||   of nine hundred millions of times in a second.’” (*27)
U||   “Absurd!” said the king.
U||   “‘Another of these magicians, by means of a fluid that nobody ever yet
U||   saw, could make the corpses of his friends brandish their arms, kick
U||   out their legs, fight, or even get up and dance at his will. (*28)
U||   Another had cultivated his voice to so great an extent that he could
U||   have made himself heard from one end of the world to the other. (*29)
U||   Another had so long an arm that he could sit down in Damascus and
U||   indite a letter at Bagdad—or indeed at any distance whatsoever. (*30)
U||   Another commanded the lightning to come down to him out of the heavens,
U||   and it came at his call; and served him for a plaything when it came.
U||   Another took two loud sounds and out of them made a silence. Another
U||   constructed a deep darkness out of two brilliant lights. (*31) Another
U||   made ice in a red-hot furnace. (*32) Another directed the sun to paint
