U||   their commonest cats and dogs have any difficulty in seeing objects
U||   that do not exist at all, or that for twenty millions of years before
U||   the birth of the nation itself had been blotted out from the face of
U||   creation.’” (*34)
U||   “Preposterous!” said the king.
U||   “‘The wives and daughters of these incomparably great and wise magi,’”
U||   continued Scheherazade, without being in any manner disturbed by these
U||   frequent and most ungentlemanly interruptions on the part of her
U||   husband—“‘the wives and daughters of these eminent conjurers are every
U||   thing that is accomplished and refined; and would be every thing that
U||   is interesting and beautiful, but for an unhappy fatality that besets
U||   them, and from which not even the miraculous powers of their husbands
