U||   in certain shapes, and some in others—but this of which I speak has
U||   come in the shape of a crotchet.’”
U||   “A what?” said the king.
U||   “‘A crotchet’” said Scheherazade. “‘One of the evil genii, who are
U||   perpetually upon the watch to inflict ill, has put it into the heads of
U||   these accomplished ladies that the thing which we describe as personal
U||   beauty consists altogether in the protuberance of the region which lies
U||   not very far below the small of the back. Perfection of loveliness,
U||   they say, is in the direct ratio of the extent of this lump. Having
U||   been long possessed of this idea, and bolsters being cheap in that
U||   country, the days have long gone by since it was possible to
U||   distinguish a woman from a dromedary—’”
U||   “Stop!” said the king—“I can’t stand that, and I won’t. You have
U||   already given me a dreadful headache with your lies. The day, too, I
U||   perceive, is beginning to break. How long have we been married?—my
U||   conscience is getting to be troublesome again. And then that dromedary
U||   touch—do you take me for a fool? Upon the whole, you might as well get
U||   up and be throttled.”
U||   These words, as I learn from the “Isitsöornot,” both grieved and
U||   astonished Scheherazade; but, as she knew the king to be a man of
U||   scrupulous integrity, and quite unlikely to forfeit his word, she
U||   submitted to her fate with a good grace. She derived, however, great
U||   consolation, (during the tightening of the bowstring,) from the
U||   reflection that much of the history remained still untold, and that the
U||   petulance of her brute of a husband had reaped for him a most righteous
U||   reward, in depriving him of many inconceivable adventures.
U||A DESCENT INTO THE MAELSTROM.
U||   The ways of God in Nature, as in Providence, are not as our ways; nor
U||   are the models that we frame any way commensurate to the vastness,
U||   profundity, and unsearchableness of His works, which have a depth in
U||   them greater than the well of Democritus.
U||   —Joseph Glanville.
U||   We had now reached the summit of the loftiest crag. For some minutes
U||   the old man seemed too much exhausted to speak.
U||   “Not long ago,” said he at length, “and I could have guided you on this
U||   route as well as the youngest of my sons; but, about three years past,
U||   there happened to me an event such as never happened to mortal man—or
U||   at least such as no man ever survived to tell of—and the six hours of
U||   deadly terror which I then endured have broken me up body and soul. You
U||   suppose me a very old man—but I am not. It took less than a single day
U||   to change these hairs from a jetty black to white, to weaken my limbs,
U||   and to unstring my nerves, so that I tremble at the least exertion, and
U||   am frightened at a shadow. Do you know I can scarcely look over this
U||   little cliff without getting giddy?”
U||   The “little cliff,” upon whose edge he had so carelessly thrown himself
U||   down to rest that the weightier portion of his body hung over it, while
U||   he was only kept from falling by the tenure of his elbow on its extreme
U||   and slippery edge—this “little cliff” arose, a sheer unobstructed
U||   precipice of black shining rock, some fifteen or sixteen hundred feet
U||   from the world of crags beneath us. Nothing would have tempted me to
U||   within half a dozen yards of its brink. In truth so deeply was I
U||   excited by the perilous position of my companion, that I fell at full
U||   length upon the ground, clung to the shrubs around me, and dared not
U||   even glance upward at the sky—while I struggled in vain to divest
U||   myself of the idea that the very foundations of the mountain were in
U||   danger from the fury of the winds. It was long before I could reason
U||   myself into sufficient courage to sit up and look out into the
U||   distance.
U||   “You must get over these fancies,” said the guide, “for I have brought
U||   you here that you might have the best possible view of the scene of
U||   that event I mentioned—and to tell you the whole story with the spot
U||   just under your eye.”
U||   “We are now,” he continued, in that particularizing manner which
U||   distinguished him—“we are now close upon the Norwegian coast—in the
U||   sixty-eighth degree of latitude—in the great province of Nordland—and
U||   in the dreary district of Lofoden. The mountain upon whose top we sit
U||   is Helseggen, the Cloudy. Now raise yourself up a little higher—hold on
U||   to the grass if you feel giddy—so—and look out, beyond the belt of
U||   vapor beneath us, into the sea.”
U||   I looked dizzily, and beheld a wide expanse of ocean, whose waters wore
U||   so inky a hue as to bring at once to my mind the Nubian geographer’s
U||   account of the Mare Tenebrarum. A panorama more deplorably desolate no
U||   human imagination can conceive. To the right and left, as far as the
U||   eye could reach, there lay outstretched, like ramparts of the world,
U||   lines of horridly black and beetling cliff, whose character of gloom
U||   was but the more forcibly illustrated by the surf which reared high up
U||   against its white and ghastly crest, howling and shrieking forever.
U||   Just opposite the promontory upon whose apex we were placed, and at a
U||   distance of some five or six miles out at sea, there was visible a
U||   small, bleak-looking island; or, more properly, its position was
U||   discernible through the wilderness of surge in which it was enveloped.
U||   About two miles nearer the land, arose another of smaller size,
U||   hideously craggy and barren, and encompassed at various intervals by a
U||   cluster of dark rocks.
U||   The appearance of the ocean, in the space between the more distant
U||   island and the shore, had something very unusual about it. Although, at
U||   the time, so strong a gale was blowing landward that a brig in the
U||   remote offing lay to under a double-reefed trysail, and constantly
U||   plunged her whole hull out of sight, still there was here nothing like
U||   a regular swell, but only a short, quick, angry cross dashing of water
U||   in every direction—as well in the teeth of the wind as otherwise. Of
U||   foam there was little except in the immediate vicinity of the rocks.
U||   “The island in the distance,” resumed the old man, “is called by the
U||   Norwegians Vurrgh. The one midway is Moskoe. That a mile to the
U||   northward is Ambaaren. Yonder are Islesen, Hotholm, Keildhelm, Suarven,
U||   and Buckholm. Farther off—between Moskoe and Vurrgh—are Otterholm,
U||   Flimen, Sandflesen, and Stockholm. These are the true names of the
U||   places—but why it has been thought necessary to name them at all, is
U||   more than either you or I can understand. Do you hear anything? Do you
U||   see any change in the water?”
U||   We had now been about ten minutes upon the top of Helseggen, to which
U||   we had ascended from the interior of Lofoden, so that we had caught no
U||   glimpse of the sea until it had burst upon us from the summit. As the
U||   old man spoke, I became aware of a loud and gradually increasing sound,
U||   like the moaning of a vast herd of buffaloes upon an American prairie;
U||   and at the same moment I perceived that what seamen term the chopping
U||   character of the ocean beneath us, was rapidly changing into a current
U||   which set to the eastward. Even while I gazed, this current acquired a
U||   monstrous velocity. Each moment added to its speed—to its headlong
U||   impetuosity. In five minutes the whole sea, as far as Vurrgh, was
U||   lashed into ungovernable fury; but it was between Moskoe and the coast
U||   that the main uproar held its sway. Here the vast bed of the waters,
U||   seamed and scarred into a thousand conflicting channels, burst suddenly
U||   into phrensied convulsion—heaving, boiling, hissing—gyrating in
U||   gigantic and innumerable vortices, and all whirling and plunging on to
U||   the eastward with a rapidity which water never elsewhere assumes except
U||   in precipitous descents.
U||   In a few minutes more, there came over the scene another radical
U||   alteration. The general surface grew somewhat more smooth, and the
U||   whirlpools, one by one, disappeared, while prodigious streaks of foam
U||   became apparent where none had been seen before. These streaks, at
U||   length, spreading out to a great distance, and entering into
U||   combination, took unto themselves the gyratory motion of the subsided
U||   vortices, and seemed to form the germ of another more vast.
U||   Suddenly—very suddenly—this assumed a distinct and definite existence,
U||   in a circle of more than a mile in diameter. The edge of the whirl was
U||   represented by a broad belt of gleaming spray; but no particle of this
U||   slipped into the mouth of the terrific funnel, whose interior, as far
U||   as the eye could fathom it, was a smooth, shining, and jet-black wall
U||   of water, inclined to the horizon at an angle of some forty-five
U||   degrees, speeding dizzily round and round with a swaying and sweltering
U||   motion, and sending forth to the winds an appalling voice, half shriek,
U||   half roar, such as not even the mighty cataract of Niagara ever lifts
U||   up in its agony to Heaven.
U||   The mountain trembled to its very base, and the rock rocked. I threw
U||   myself upon my face, and clung to the scant herbage in an excess of
U||   nervous agitation.
U||   “This,” said I at length, to the old man—“this can be nothing else than
U||   the great whirlpool of the Maelström.”
U||   “So it is sometimes termed,” said he. “We Norwegians call it the
U||   Moskoe-ström, from the island of Moskoe in the midway.”
U||   The ordinary accounts of this vortex had by no means prepared me for
U||   what I saw. That of Jonas Ramus, which is perhaps the most
U||   circumstantial of any, cannot impart the faintest conception either of
U||   the magnificence, or of the horror of the scene—or of the wild
U||   bewildering sense of the novel which confounds the beholder. I am not
U||   sure from what point of view the writer in question surveyed it, nor at
U||   what time; but it could neither have been from the summit of Helseggen,
U||   nor during a storm. There are some passages of his description,
U||   nevertheless, which may be quoted for their details, although their
U||   effect is exceedingly feeble in conveying an impression of the
U||   spectacle.
U||   “Between Lofoden and Moskoe,” he says, “the depth of the water is
U||   between thirty-six and forty fathoms; but on the other side, toward Ver
U||   (Vurrgh) this depth decreases so as not to afford a convenient passage
U||   for a vessel, without the risk of splitting on the rocks, which happens
U||   even in the calmest weather. When it is flood, the stream runs up the
U||   country between Lofoden and Moskoe with a boisterous rapidity; but the
U||   roar of its impetuous ebb to the sea is scarce equalled by the loudest
U||   and most dreadful cataracts; the noise being heard several leagues off,
U||   and the vortices or pits are of such an extent and depth, that if a
U||   ship comes within its attraction, it is inevitably absorbed and carried
U||   down to the bottom, and there beat to pieces against the rocks; and
U||   when the water relaxes, the fragments thereof are thrown up again. But
U||   these intervals of tranquility are only at the turn of the ebb and
U||   flood, and in calm weather, and last but a quarter of an hour, its
U||   violence gradually returning. When the stream is most boisterous, and
U||   its fury heightened by a storm, it is dangerous to come within a Norway
U||   mile of it. Boats, yachts, and ships have been carried away by not
U||   guarding against it before they were within its reach. It likewise
U||   happens frequently, that whales come too near the stream, and are
U||   overpowered by its violence; and then it is impossible to describe
U||   their howlings and bellowings in their fruitless struggles to disengage
U||   themselves. A bear once, attempting to swim from Lofoden to Moskoe, was
U||   caught by the stream and borne down, while he roared terribly, so as to
U||   be heard on shore. Large stocks of firs and pine trees, after being
U||   absorbed by the current, rise again broken and torn to such a degree as
U||   if bristles grew upon them. This plainly shows the bottom to consist of
U||   craggy rocks, among which they are whirled to and fro. This stream is
U||   regulated by the flux and reflux of the sea—it being constantly high
U||   and low water every six hours. In the year 1645, early in the morning
U||   of Sexagesima Sunday, it raged with such noise and impetuosity that the
U||   very stones of the houses on the coast fell to the ground.”
U||   In regard to the depth of the water, I could not see how this could
U||   have been ascertained at all in the immediate vicinity of the vortex.
U||   The “forty fathoms” must have reference only to portions of the channel
U||   close upon the shore either of Moskoe or Lofoden. The depth in the
U||   centre of the Moskoe-ström must be immeasurably greater; and no better
U||   proof of this fact is necessary than can be obtained from even the
U||   sidelong glance into the abyss of the whirl which may be had from the
U||   highest crag of Helseggen. Looking down from this pinnacle upon the
U||   howling Phlegethon below, I could not help smiling at the simplicity
U||   with which the honest Jonas Ramus records, as a matter difficult of
U||   belief, the anecdotes of the whales and the bears; for it appeared to
U||   me, in fact, a self-evident thing, that the largest ship of the line in
U||   existence, coming within the influence of that deadly attraction, could
U||   resist it as little as a feather the hurricane, and must disappear
U||   bodily and at once.
U||   The attempts to account for the phenomenon—some of which, I remember,
U||   seemed to me sufficiently plausible in perusal—now wore a very
U||   different and unsatisfactory aspect. The idea generally received is
U||   that this, as well as three smaller vortices among the Ferroe islands,
U||   “have no other cause than the collision of waves rising and falling, at
U||   flux and reflux, against a ridge of rocks and shelves, which confines
U||   the water so that it precipitates itself like a cataract; and thus the
U||   higher the flood rises, the deeper must the fall be, and the natural
U||   result of all is a whirlpool or vortex, the prodigious suction of which
U||   is sufficiently known by lesser experiments.”—These are the words of
U||   the Encyclopædia Britannica. Kircher and others imagine that in the
U||   centre of the channel of the Maelström is an abyss penetrating the
U||   globe, and issuing in some very remote part—the Gulf of Bothnia being
U||   somewhat decidedly named in one instance. This opinion, idle in itself,
U||   was the one to which, as I gazed, my imagination most readily assented;
U||   and, mentioning it to the guide, I was rather surprised to hear him say
U||   that, although it was the view almost universally entertained of the
U||   subject by the Norwegians, it nevertheless was not his own. As to the
U||   former notion he confessed his inability to comprehend it; and here I
U||   agreed with him—for, however conclusive on paper, it becomes altogether
U||   unintelligible, and even absurd, amid the thunder of the abyss.
U||   “You have had a good look at the whirl now,” said the old man, “and if
U||   you will creep round this crag, so as to get in its lee, and deaden the
U||   roar of the water, I will tell you a story that will convince you I
U||   ought to know something of the Moskoe-ström.”
U||   I placed myself as desired, and he proceeded.
U||   “Myself and my two brothers once owned a schooner-rigged smack of about
U||   seventy tons burthen, with which we were in the habit of fishing among
U||   the islands beyond Moskoe, nearly to Vurrgh. In all violent eddies at
U||   sea there is good fishing, at proper opportunities, if one has only the
U||   courage to attempt it; but among the whole of the Lofoden coastmen, we
U||   three were the only ones who made a regular business of going out to
U||   the islands, as I tell you. The usual grounds are a great way lower
U||   down to the southward. There fish can be got at all hours, without much
U||   risk, and therefore these places are preferred. The choice spots over
U||   here among the rocks, however, not only yield the finest variety, but
U||   in far greater abundance; so that we often got in a single day, what
U||   the more timid of the craft could not scrape together in a week. In
U||   fact, we made it a matter of desperate speculation—the risk of life
U||   standing instead of labor, and courage answering for capital.
U||   “We kept the smack in a cove about five miles higher up the coast than
U||   this; and it was our practice, in fine weather, to take advantage of
U||   the fifteen minutes’ slack to push across the main channel of the
U||   Moskoe-ström, far above the pool, and then drop down upon anchorage
U||   somewhere near Otterholm, or Sandflesen, where the eddies are not so
U||   violent as elsewhere. Here we used to remain until nearly time for
U||   slack-water again, when we weighed and made for home. We never set out
U||   upon this expedition without a steady side wind for going and
U||   coming—one that we felt sure would not fail us before our return—and we
U||   seldom made a mis-calculation upon this point. Twice, during six years,
U||   we were forced to stay all night at anchor on account of a dead calm,
U||   which is a rare thing indeed just about here; and once we had to remain
U||   on the grounds nearly a week, starving to death, owing to a gale which
U||   blew up shortly after our arrival, and made the channel too boisterous
U||   to be thought of. Upon this occasion we should have been driven out to
U||   sea in spite of everything, (for the whirlpools threw us round and
U||   round so violently, that, at length, we fouled our anchor and dragged
U||   it) if it had not been that we drifted into one of the innumerable
U||   cross currents—here to-day and gone to-morrow—which drove us under the
U||   lee of Flimen, where, by good luck, we brought up.
U||   “I could not tell you the twentieth part of the difficulties we
U||   encountered ‘on the grounds’—it is a bad spot to be in, even in good
U||   weather—but we made shift always to run the gauntlet of the
U||   Moskoe-ström itself without accident; although at times my heart has
U||   been in my mouth when we happened to be a minute or so behind or before
U||   the slack. The wind sometimes was not as strong as we thought it at
U||   starting, and then we made rather less way than we could wish, while
U||   the current rendered the smack unmanageable. My eldest brother had a
U||   son eighteen years old, and I had two stout boys of my own. These would
U||   have been of great assistance at such times, in using the sweeps, as
U||   well as afterward in fishing—but, somehow, although we ran the risk
U||   ourselves, we had not the heart to let the young ones get into the
U||   danger—for, after all is said and done, it was a horrible danger, and
U||   that is the truth.
U||   “It is now within a few days of three years since what I am going to
U||   tell you occurred. It was on the tenth day of July, 18—, a day which
U||   the people of this part of the world will never forget—for it was one
U||   in which blew the most terrible hurricane that ever came out of the
U||   heavens. And yet all the morning, and indeed until late in the
U||   afternoon, there was a gentle and steady breeze from the south-west,
U||   while the sun shone brightly, so that the oldest seaman among us could
U||   not have foreseen what was to follow.
U||   “The three of us—my two brothers and myself—had crossed over to the
U||   islands about two o’clock P. M., and had soon nearly loaded the smack
U||   with fine fish, which, we all remarked, were more plenty that day than
U||   we had ever known them. It was just seven, by my watch, when we weighed
U||   and started for home, so as to make the worst of the Ström at slack
U||   water, which we knew would be at eight.
U||   “We set out with a fresh wind on our starboard quarter, and for some
U||   time spanked along at a great rate, never dreaming of danger, for
U||   indeed we saw not the slightest reason to apprehend it. All at once we
U||   were taken aback by a breeze from over Helseggen. This was most
U||   unusual—something that had never happened to us before—and I began to
U||   feel a little uneasy, without exactly knowing why. We put the boat on
U||   the wind, but could make no headway at all for the eddies, and I was
U||   upon the point of proposing to return to the anchorage, when, looking
U||   astern, we saw the whole horizon covered with a singular copper-colored
U||   cloud that rose with the most amazing velocity.
U||   “In the meantime the breeze that had headed us off fell away, and we
U||   were dead becalmed, drifting about in every direction. This state of
U||   things, however, did not last long enough to give us time to think
U||   about it. In less than a minute the storm was upon us—in less than two
U||   the sky was entirely overcast—and what with this and the driving spray,
U||   it became suddenly so dark that we could not see each other in the
U||   smack.
U||   “Such a hurricane as then blew it is folly to attempt describing. The
U||   oldest seaman in Norway never experienced any thing like it. We had let
U||   our sails go by the run before it cleverly took us; but, at the first
U||   puff, both our masts went by the board as if they had been sawed
U||   off—the mainmast taking with it my youngest brother, who had lashed
U||   himself to it for safety.
U||   “Our boat was the lightest feather of a thing that ever sat upon water.
U||   It had a complete flush deck, with only a small hatch near the bow, and
U||   this hatch it had always been our custom to batten down when about to
U||   cross the Ström, by way of precaution against the chopping seas. But
U||   for this circumstance we should have foundered at once—for we lay
U||   entirely buried for some moments. How my elder brother escaped
U||   destruction I cannot say, for I never had an opportunity of
U||   ascertaining. For my part, as soon as I had let the foresail run, I
U||   threw myself flat on deck, with my feet against the narrow gunwale of
U||   the bow, and with my hands grasping a ring-bolt near the foot of the
U||   fore-mast. It was mere instinct that prompted me to do this—which was
U||   undoubtedly the very best thing I could have done—for I was too much
U||   flurried to think.
U||   “For some moments we were completely deluged, as I say, and all this
U||   time I held my breath, and clung to the bolt. When I could stand it no
U||   longer I raised myself upon my knees, still keeping hold with my hands,
U||   and thus got my head clear. Presently our little boat gave herself a
U||   shake, just as a dog does in coming out of the water, and thus rid
U||   herself, in some measure, of the seas. I was now trying to get the
U||   better of the stupor that had come over me, and to collect my senses so
U||   as to see what was to be done, when I felt somebody grasp my arm. It
U||   was my elder brother, and my heart leaped for joy, for I had made sure
U||   that he was overboard—but the next moment all this joy was turned into
U||   horror—for he put his mouth close to my ear, and screamed out the word
U||   ‘Moskoe-ström!’
U||   “No one ever will know what my feelings were at that moment. I shook
U||   from head to foot as if I had had the most violent fit of the ague. I
U||   knew what he meant by that one word well enough—I knew what he wished
U||   to make me understand. With the wind that now drove us on, we were
U||   bound for the whirl of the Ström, and nothing could save us!
U||   “You perceive that in crossing the Ström channel, we always went a long
U||   way up above the whirl, even in the calmest weather, and then had to
U||   wait and watch carefully for the slack—but now we were driving right
U||   upon the pool itself, and in such a hurricane as this! ‘To be sure,’ I
U||   thought, ‘we shall get there just about the slack—there is some little
U||   hope in that’—but in the next moment I cursed myself for being so great
U||   a fool as to dream of hope at all. I knew very well that we were
U||   doomed, had we been ten times a ninety-gun ship.
U||   “By this time the first fury of the tempest had spent itself, or
U||   perhaps we did not feel it so much, as we scudded before it, but at all
U||   events the seas, which at first had been kept down by the wind, and lay
U||   flat and frothing, now got up into absolute mountains. A singular
U||   change, too, had come over the heavens. Around in every direction it
U||   was still as black as pitch, but nearly overhead there burst out, all
U||   at once, a circular rift of clear sky—as clear as I ever saw—and of a
U||   deep bright blue—and through it there blazed forth the full moon with a
U||   lustre that I never before knew her to wear. She lit up every thing
U||   about us with the greatest distinctness—but, oh God, what a scene it
U||   was to light up!
U||   “I now made one or two attempts to speak to my brother—but, in some
U||   manner which I could not understand, the din had so increased that I
U||   could not make him hear a single word, although I screamed at the top
U||   of my voice in his ear. Presently he shook his head, looking as pale as
U||   death, and held up one of his fingers, as if to say ‘listen! ‘
U||   “At first I could not make out what he meant—but soon a hideous thought
U||   flashed upon me. I dragged my watch from its fob. It was not going. I
U||   glanced at its face by the moonlight, and then burst into tears as I
U||   flung it far away into the ocean. It had run down at seven o’clock! We
U||   were behind the time of the slack, and the whirl of the Ström was in
U||   full fury!
U||   “When a boat is well built, properly trimmed, and not deep laden, the
U||   waves in a strong gale, when she is going large, seem always to slip
U||   from beneath her—which appears very strange to a landsman—and this is
U||   what is called riding, in sea phrase.
U||   “Well, so far we had ridden the swells very cleverly; but presently a
U||   gigantic sea happened to take us right under the counter, and bore us
U||   with it as it rose—up—up—as if into the sky. I would not have believed
U||   that any wave could rise so high. And then down we came with a sweep, a
U||   slide, and a plunge, that made me feel sick and dizzy, as if I was
U||   falling from some lofty mountain-top in a dream. But while we were up I
U||   had thrown a quick glance around—and that one glance was all
U||   sufficient. I saw our exact position in an instant. The Moskoe-Ström
U||   whirlpool was about a quarter of a mile dead ahead—but no more like the
U||   every-day Moskoe-Ström than the whirl as you now see it, is like a
U||   mill-race. If I had not known where we were, and what we had to expect,
U||   I should not have recognised the place at all. As it was, I
U||   involuntarily closed my eyes in horror. The lids clenched themselves
U||   together as if in a spasm.
U||   “It could not have been more than two minutes afterward until we
U||   suddenly felt the waves subside, and were enveloped in foam. The boat
U||   made a sharp half turn to larboard, and then shot off in its new
U||   direction like a thunderbolt. At the same moment the roaring noise of
U||   the water was completely drowned in a kind of shrill shriek—such a
U||   sound as you might imagine given out by the waste-pipes of many
U||   thousand steam-vessels, letting off their steam all together. We were
U||   now in the belt of surf that always surrounds the whirl; and I thought,
U||   of course, that another moment would plunge us into the abyss, down
U||   which we could only see indistinctly on account of the amazing velocity
U||   with which we wore borne along. The boat did not seem to sink into the
U||   water at all, but to skim like an air-bubble upon the surface of the
U||   surge. Her starboard side was next the whirl, and on the larboard arose
U||   the world of ocean we had left. It stood like a huge writhing wall
U||   between us and the horizon.
U||   “It may appear strange, but now, when we were in the very jaws of the
U||   gulf, I felt more composed than when we were only approaching it.
U||   Having made up my mind to hope no more, I got rid of a great deal of
U||   that terror which unmanned me at first. I suppose it was despair that
U||   strung my nerves.
U||   “It may look like boasting—but what I tell you is truth—I began to
U||   reflect how magnificent a thing it was to die in such a manner, and how
U||   foolish it was in me to think of so paltry a consideration as my own
U||   individual life, in view of so wonderful a manifestation of God’s
U||   power. I do believe that I blushed with shame when this idea crossed my
U||   mind. After a little while I became possessed with the keenest
U||   curiosity about the whirl itself. I positively felt a wish to explore
U||   its depths, even at the sacrifice I was going to make; and my principal
U||   grief was that I should never be able to tell my old companions on
U||   shore about the mysteries I should see. These, no doubt, were singular
U||   fancies to occupy a man’s mind in such extremity—and I have often
U||   thought since, that the revolutions of the boat around the pool might
U||   have rendered me a little light-headed.
U||   “There was another circumstance which tended to restore my
U||   self-possession; and this was the cessation of the wind, which could
U||   not reach us in our present situation—for, as you saw yourself, the
U||   belt of surf is considerably lower than the general bed of the ocean,
U||   and this latter now towered above us, a high, black, mountainous ridge.
U||   If you have never been at sea in a heavy gale, you can form no idea of
U||   the confusion of mind occasioned by the wind and spray together. They
U||   blind, deafen, and strangle you, and take away all power of action or
U||   reflection. But we were now, in a great measure, rid of these
U||   annoyances—just as death-condemned felons in prison are allowed petty
U||   indulgences, forbidden them while their doom is yet uncertain.
U||   “How often we made the circuit of the belt it is impossible to say. We
U||   careered round and round for perhaps an hour, flying rather than
U||   floating, getting gradually more and more into the middle of the surge,
U||   and then nearer and nearer to its horrible inner edge. All this time I
U||   had never let go of the ring-bolt. My brother was at the stern, holding
U||   on to a small empty water-cask which had been securely lashed under the
U||   coop of the counter, and was the only thing on deck that had not been
U||   swept overboard when the gale first took us. As we approached the brink
U||   of the pit he let go his hold upon this, and made for the ring, from
U||   which, in the agony of his terror, he endeavored to force my hands, as
U||   it was not large enough to afford us both a secure grasp. I never felt
U||   deeper grief than when I saw him attempt this act—although I knew he
U||   was a madman when he did it—a raving maniac through sheer fright. I did
U||   not care, however, to contest the point with him. I knew it could make
U||   no difference whether either of us held on at all; so I let him have
U||   the bolt, and went astern to the cask. This there was no great
U||   difficulty in doing; for the smack flew round steadily enough, and upon
U||   an even keel—only swaying to and fro, with the immense sweeps and
U||   swelters of the whirl. Scarcely had I secured myself in my new
U||   position, when we gave a wild lurch to starboard, and rushed headlong
U||   into the abyss. I muttered a hurried prayer to God, and thought all was
U||   over.
U||   “As I felt the sickening sweep of the descent, I had instinctively
U||   tightened my hold upon the barrel, and closed my eyes. For some seconds
U||   I dared not open them—while I expected instant destruction, and
U||   wondered that I was not already in my death-struggles with the water.
U||   But moment after moment elapsed. I still lived. The sense of falling
U||   had ceased; and the motion of the vessel seemed much as it had been
U||   before, while in the belt of foam, with the exception that she now lay
U||   more along. I took courage, and looked once again upon the scene.
U||   “Never shall I forget the sensations of awe, horror, and admiration
U||   with which I gazed about me. The boat appeared to be hanging, as if by
U||   magic, midway down, upon the interior surface of a funnel vast in
U||   circumference, prodigious in depth, and whose perfectly smooth sides
U||   might have been mistaken for ebony, but for the bewildering rapidity
U||   with which they spun around, and for the gleaming and ghastly radiance
U||   they shot forth, as the rays of the full moon, from that circular rift
U||   amid the clouds which I have already described, streamed in a flood of
U||   golden glory along the black walls, and far away down into the inmost
U||   recesses of the abyss.
U||   “At first I was too much confused to observe anything accurately. The
U||   general burst of terrific grandeur was all that I beheld. When I
U||   recovered myself a little, however, my gaze fell instinctively
U||   downward. In this direction I was able to obtain an unobstructed view,
U||   from the manner in which the smack hung on the inclined surface of the
U||   pool. She was quite upon an even keel—that is to say, her deck lay in a
U||   plane parallel with that of the water—but this latter sloped at an
U||   angle of more than forty-five degrees, so that we seemed to be lying
U||   upon our beam-ends. I could not help observing, nevertheless, that I
U||   had scarcely more difficulty in maintaining my hold and footing in this
U||   situation, than if we had been upon a dead level; and this, I suppose,
U||   was owing to the speed at which we revolved.
U||   “The rays of the moon seemed to search the very bottom of the profound
U||   gulf; but still I could make out nothing distinctly, on account of a
U||   thick mist in which everything there was enveloped, and over which
U||   there hung a magnificent rainbow, like that narrow and tottering bridge
U||   which Mussulmen say is the only pathway between Time and Eternity. This
U||   mist, or spray, was no doubt occasioned by the clashing of the great
U||   walls of the funnel, as they all met together at the bottom—but the
U||   yell that went up to the Heavens from out of that mist, I dare not
U||   attempt to describe.
U||   “Our first slide into the abyss itself, from the belt of foam above,
U||   had carried us a great distance down the slope; but our farther descent
U||   was by no means proportionate. Round and round we swept—not with any
U||   uniform movement—but in dizzying swings and jerks, that sent us
U||   sometimes only a few hundred yards—sometimes nearly the complete
U||   circuit of the whirl. Our progress downward, at each revolution, was
U||   slow, but very perceptible.
U||   “Looking about me upon the wide waste of liquid ebony on which we were
U||   thus borne, I perceived that our boat was not the only object in the
U||   embrace of the whirl. Both above and below us were visible fragments of
U||   vessels, large masses of building timber and trunks of trees, with many
U||   smaller articles, such as pieces of house furniture, broken boxes,
U||   barrels and staves. I have already described the unnatural curiosity
U||   which had taken the place of my original terrors. It appeared to grow
U||   upon me as I drew nearer and nearer to my dreadful doom. I now began to
U||   watch, with a strange interest, the numerous things that floated in our
U||   company. I must have been delirious, for I even sought amusement in
U||   speculating upon the relative velocities of their several descents
U||   toward the foam below. ‘This fir tree,’ I found myself at one time
U||   saying, ‘will certainly be the next thing that takes the awful plunge
U||   and disappears,’—and then I was disappointed to find that the wreck of
U||   a Dutch merchant ship overtook it and went down before. At length,
U||   after making several guesses of this nature, and being deceived in
U||   all—this fact—the fact of my invariable miscalculation, set me upon a
U||   train of reflection that made my limbs again tremble, and my heart beat
U||   heavily once more.
U||   “It was not a new terror that thus affected me, but the dawn of a more
U||   exciting hope. This hope arose partly from memory, and partly from
U||   present observation. I called to mind the great variety of buoyant
U||   matter that strewed the coast of Lofoden, having been absorbed and then
U||   thrown forth by the Moskoe-ström. By far the greater number of the
U||   articles were shattered in the most extraordinary way—so chafed and
U||   roughened as to have the appearance of being stuck full of
U||   splinters—but then I distinctly recollected that there were some of
U||   them which were not disfigured at all. Now I could not account for this
U||   difference except by supposing that the roughened fragments were the
U||   only ones which had been completely absorbed—that the others had
U||   entered the whirl at so late a period of the tide, or, for some reason,
U||   had descended so slowly after entering, that they did not reach the
U||   bottom before the turn of the flood came, or of the ebb, as the case
U||   might be. I conceived it possible, in either instance, that they might
U||   thus be whirled up again to the level of the ocean, without undergoing
U||   the fate of those which had been drawn in more early, or absorbed more
U||   rapidly. I made, also, three important observations. The first was,
U||   that, as a general rule, the larger the bodies were, the more rapid
U||   their descent—the second, that, between two masses of equal extent, the
U||   one spherical, and the other of any other shape, the superiority in
U||   speed of descent was with the sphere—the third, that, between two
U||   masses of equal size, the one cylindrical, and the other of any other
U||   shape, the cylinder was absorbed the more slowly. Since my escape, I
U||   have had several conversations on this subject with an old
U||   school-master of the district; and it was from him that I learned the
U||   use of the words ‘cylinder’ and ‘sphere.’ He explained to me—although I
U||   have forgotten the explanation—how what I observed was, in fact, the
U||   natural consequence of the forms of the floating fragments—and showed
U||   me how it happened that a cylinder, swimming in a vortex, offered more
U||   resistance to its suction, and was drawn in with greater difficulty
U||   than an equally bulky body, of any form whatever. (*1)
U||   “There was one startling circumstance which went a great way in
U||   enforcing these observations, and rendering me anxious to turn them to
U||   account, and this was that, at every revolution, we passed something
U||   like a barrel, or else the yard or the mast of a vessel, while many of
U||   these things, which had been on our level when I first opened my eyes
U||   upon the wonders of the whirlpool, were now high up above us, and
U||   seemed to have moved but little from their original station.
U||   “I no longer hesitated what to do. I resolved to lash myself securely
U||   to the water cask upon which I now held, to cut it loose from the
U||   counter, and to throw myself with it into the water. I attracted my
U||   brother’s attention by signs, pointed to the floating barrels that came
U||   near us, and did everything in my power to make him understand what I
U||   was about to do. I thought at length that he comprehended my
U||   design—but, whether this was the case or not, he shook his head
U||   despairingly, and refused to move from his station by the ring-bolt. It
U||   was impossible to reach him; the emergency admitted of no delay; and
U||   so, with a bitter struggle, I resigned him to his fate, fastened myself
U||   to the cask by means of the lashings which secured it to the counter,
U||   and precipitated myself with it into the sea, without another moment’s
U||   hesitation.
U||   “The result was precisely what I had hoped it might be. As it is myself
U||   who now tell you this tale—as you see that I did escape—and as you are
U||   already in possession of the mode in which this escape was effected,
U||   and must therefore anticipate all that I have farther to say—I will
U||   bring my story quickly to conclusion. It might have been an hour, or
U||   thereabout, after my quitting the smack, when, having descended to a
U||   vast distance beneath me, it made three or four wild gyrations in rapid
U||   succession, and, bearing my loved brother with it, plunged headlong, at
U||   once and forever, into the chaos of foam below. The barrel to which I
U||   was attached sunk very little farther than half the distance between
U||   the bottom of the gulf and the spot at which I leaped overboard, before
U||   a great change took place in the character of the whirlpool. The slope
U||   of the sides of the vast funnel became momently less and less steep.
U||   The gyrations of the whirl grew, gradually, less and less violent. By
U||   degrees, the froth and the rainbow disappeared, and the bottom of the
U||   gulf seemed slowly to uprise. The sky was clear, the winds had gone
U||   down, and the full moon was setting radiantly in the west, when I found
U||   myself on the surface of the ocean, in full view of the shores of
U||   Lofoden, and above the spot where the pool of the Moskoe-ström had
U||   been. It was the hour of the slack—but the sea still heaved in
U||   mountainous waves from the effects of the hurricane. I was borne
U||   violently into the channel of the Ström, and in a few minutes was
U||   hurried down the coast into the ‘grounds’ of the fishermen. A boat
U||   picked me up—exhausted from fatigue—and (now that the danger was
U||   removed) speechless from the memory of its horror. Those who drew me on
U||   board were my old mates and daily companions—but they knew me no more
U||   than they would have known a traveller from the spirit-land. My hair
U||   which had been raven-black the day before, was as white as you see it
U||   now. They say too that the whole expression of my countenance had
U||   changed. I told them my story—they did not believe it. I now tell it to
U||   you—and I can scarcely expect you to put more faith in it than did the
U||   merry fishermen of Lofoden.”
U||VON KEMPELEN AND HIS DISCOVERY
U||   After the very minute and elaborate paper by Arago, to say nothing of
U||   the summary in ‘Silliman’s Journal,’ with the detailed statement just
U||   published by Lieutenant Maury, it will not be supposed, of course, that
U||   in offering a few hurried remarks in reference to Von Kempelen’s
U||   discovery, I have any design to look at the subject in a scientific
U||   point of view. My object is simply, in the first place, to say a few
U||   words of Von Kempelen himself (with whom, some years ago, I had the
U||   honor of a slight personal acquaintance), since every thing which
U||   concerns him must necessarily, at this moment, be of interest; and, in
U||   the second place, to look in a general way, and speculatively, at the
U||   results of the discovery.
U||   It may be as well, however, to premise the cursory observations which I
U||   have to offer, by denying, very decidedly, what seems to be a general
U||   impression (gleaned, as usual in a case of this kind, from the
U||   newspapers), viz.: that this discovery, astounding as it unquestionably
U||   is, is unanticipated.
U||   By reference to the ‘Diary of Sir Humphrey Davy’ (Cottle and Munroe,
U||   London, pp. 150), it will be seen at pp. 53 and 82, that this
U||   illustrious chemist had not only conceived the idea now in question,
U||   but had actually made no inconsiderable progress, experimentally, in
U||   the very identical analysis now so triumphantly brought to an issue by
U||   Von Kempelen, who although he makes not the slightest allusion to it,
U||   is, without doubt (I say it unhesitatingly, and can prove it, if
U||   required), indebted to the ‘Diary’ for at least the first hint of his
U||   own undertaking.
U||   The paragraph from the ‘Courier and Enquirer,’ which is now going the
U||   rounds of the press, and which purports to claim the invention for a
U||   Mr. Kissam, of Brunswick, Maine, appears to me, I confess, a little
U||   apocryphal, for several reasons; although there is nothing either
U||   impossible or very improbable in the statement made. I need not go into
U||   details. My opinion of the paragraph is founded principally upon its
U||   manner. It does not look true. Persons who are narrating facts, are
U||   seldom so particular as Mr. Kissam seems to be, about day and date and
U||   precise location. Besides, if Mr. Kissam actually did come upon the
U||   discovery he says he did, at the period designated—nearly eight years
U||   ago—how happens it that he took no steps, on the instant, to reap the
U||   immense benefits which the merest bumpkin must have known would have
U||   resulted to him individually, if not to the world at large, from the
U||   discovery? It seems to me quite incredible that any man of common
U||   understanding could have discovered what Mr. Kissam says he did, and
U||   yet have subsequently acted so like a baby—so like an owl—as Mr. Kissam
U||   admits that he did. By-the-way, who is Mr. Kissam? and is not the whole
U||   paragraph in the ‘Courier and Enquirer’ a fabrication got up to ‘make a
U||   talk’? It must be confessed that it has an amazingly moon-hoaxy-air.
U||   Very little dependence is to be placed upon it, in my humble opinion;
U||   and if I were not well aware, from experience, how very easily men of
U||   science are mystified, on points out of their usual range of inquiry, I
U||   should be profoundly astonished at finding so eminent a chemist as
U||   Professor Draper, discussing Mr. Kissam’s (or is it Mr. Quizzem’s?)
U||   pretensions to the discovery, in so serious a tone.
U||   But to return to the ‘Diary’ of Sir Humphrey Davy. This pamphlet was
U||   not designed for the public eye, even upon the decease of the writer,
U||   as any person at all conversant with authorship may satisfy himself at
U||   once by the slightest inspection of the style. At page 13, for example,
U||   near the middle, we read, in reference to his researches about the
U||   protoxide of azote: ‘In less than half a minute the respiration being
U||   continued, diminished gradually and were succeeded by analogous to
U||   gentle pressure on all the muscles.’ That the respiration was not
U||   ‘diminished,’ is not only clear by the subsequent context, but by the
U||   use of the plural, ‘were.’ The sentence, no doubt, was thus intended:
U||   ‘In less than half a minute, the respiration [being continued, these
U||   feelings] diminished gradually, and were succeeded by [a sensation]
U||   analogous to gentle pressure on all the muscles.’ A hundred similar
U||   instances go to show that the MS. so inconsiderately published, was
U||   merely a rough note-book, meant only for the writer’s own eye, but an
U||   inspection of the pamphlet will convince almost any thinking person of
U||   the truth of my suggestion. The fact is, Sir Humphrey Davy was about
U||   the last man in the world to commit himself on scientific topics. Not
U||   only had he a more than ordinary dislike to quackery, but he was
U||   morbidly afraid of appearing empirical; so that, however fully he might
U||   have been convinced that he was on the right track in the matter now in
U||   question, he would never have spoken out, until he had every thing
U||   ready for the most practical demonstration. I verily believe that his
U||   last moments would have been rendered wretched, could he have suspected
U||   that his wishes in regard to burning this ‘Diary’ (full of crude
U||   speculations) would have been unattended to; as, it seems, they were. I
U||   say ‘his wishes,’ for that he meant to include this note-book among the
U||   miscellaneous papers directed ‘to be burnt,’ I think there can be no
U||   manner of doubt. Whether it escaped the flames by good fortune or by
U||   bad, yet remains to be seen. That the passages quoted above, with the
U||   other similar ones referred to, gave Von Kempelen the hint, I do not in
U||   the slightest degree question; but I repeat, it yet remains to be seen
U||   whether this momentous discovery itself (momentous under any
U||   circumstances) will be of service or disservice to mankind at large.
U||   That Von Kempelen and his immediate friends will reap a rich harvest,
U||   it would be folly to doubt for a moment. They will scarcely be so weak
U||   as not to ‘realize,’ in time, by large purchases of houses and land,
U||   with other property of intrinsic value.
U||   In the brief account of Von Kempelen which appeared in the ‘Home
U||   Journal,’ and has since been extensively copied, several
U||   misapprehensions of the German original seem to have been made by the
U||   translator, who professes to have taken the passage from a late number
U||   of the Presburg ‘Schnellpost.’ ‘Viele’ has evidently been misconceived
U||   (as it often is), and what the translator renders by ‘sorrows,’ is
U||   probably ‘lieden,’ which, in its true version, ‘sufferings,’ would give
U||   a totally different complexion to the whole account; but, of course,
U||   much of this is merely guess, on my part.
U||   Von Kempelen, however, is by no means ‘a misanthrope,’ in appearance,
U||   at least, whatever he may be in fact. My acquaintance with him was
U||   casual altogether; and I am scarcely warranted in saying that I know
U||   him at all; but to have seen and conversed with a man of so prodigious
U||   a notoriety as he has attained, or will attain in a few days, is not a
U||   small matter, as times go.
U||   “The Literary World” speaks of him, confidently, as a native of
U||   Presburg (misled, perhaps, by the account in “The Home Journal”) but I
U||   am pleased in being able to state positively, since I have it from his
U||   own lips, that he was born in Utica, in the State of New York, although
U||   both his parents, I believe, are of Presburg descent. The family is
U||   connected, in some way, with Mäelzel, of Automaton-chess-player memory.
U||   In person, he is short and stout, with large, fat, blue eyes, sandy
U||   hair and whiskers, a wide but pleasing mouth, fine teeth, and I think a
U||   Roman nose. There is some defect in one of his feet. His address is
U||   frank, and his whole manner noticeable for bonhomie. Altogether, he
U||   looks, speaks, and acts as little like ‘a misanthrope’ as any man I
U||   ever saw. We were fellow-sojourners for a week about six years ago, at
U||   Earl’s Hotel, in Providence, Rhode Island; and I presume that I
U||   conversed with him, at various times, for some three or four hours
U||   altogether. His principal topics were those of the day; and nothing
U||   that fell from him led me to suspect his scientific attainments. He
U||   left the hotel before me, intending to go to New York, and thence to
U||   Bremen; it was in the latter city that his great discovery was first
U||   made public; or, rather, it was there that he was first suspected of
U||   having made it. This is about all that I personally know of the now
U||   immortal Von Kempelen; but I have thought that even these few details
U||   would have interest for the public.
U||   There can be little question that most of the marvellous rumors afloat
U||   about this affair are pure inventions, entitled to about as much credit
U||   as the story of Aladdin’s lamp; and yet, in a case of this kind, as in
U||   the case of the discoveries in California, it is clear that the truth
U||   may be stranger than fiction. The following anecdote, at least, is so
U||   well authenticated, that we may receive it implicitly.
U||   Von Kempelen had never been even tolerably well off during his
U||   residence at Bremen; and often, it was well known, he had been put to
U||   extreme shifts in order to raise trifling sums. When the great
U||   excitement occurred about the forgery on the house of Gutsmuth & Co.,
U||   suspicion was directed toward Von Kempelen, on account of his having
U||   purchased a considerable property in Gasperitch Lane, and his refusing,
U||   when questioned, to explain how he became possessed of the purchase
U||   money. He was at length arrested, but nothing decisive appearing
U||   against him, was in the end set at liberty. The police, however, kept a
U||   strict watch upon his movements, and thus discovered that he left home
U||   frequently, taking always the same road, and invariably giving his
U||   watchers the slip in the neighborhood of that labyrinth of narrow and
U||   crooked passages known by the flash name of the ‘Dondergat.’ Finally,
U||   by dint of great perseverance, they traced him to a garret in an old
U||   house of seven stories, in an alley called Flatzplatz,—and, coming upon
U||   him suddenly, found him, as they imagined, in the midst of his
U||   counterfeiting operations. His agitation is represented as so excessive
U||   that the officers had not the slightest doubt of his guilt. After
U||   hand-cuffing him, they searched his room, or rather rooms, for it
U||   appears he occupied all the mansarde.
U||   Opening into the garret where they caught him, was a closet, ten feet
U||   by eight, fitted up with some chemical apparatus, of which the object
U||   has not yet been ascertained. In one corner of the closet was a very
U||   small furnace, with a glowing fire in it, and on the fire a kind of
U||   duplicate crucible—two crucibles connected by a tube. One of these
U||   crucibles was nearly full of lead in a state of fusion, but not
U||   reaching up to the aperture of the tube, which was close to the brim.
U||   The other crucible had some liquid in it, which, as the officers
U||   entered, seemed to be furiously dissipating in vapor. They relate that,
U||   on finding himself taken, Kempelen seized the crucibles with both hands
U||   (which were encased in gloves that afterwards turned out to be
U||   asbestic), and threw the contents on the tiled floor. It was now that
U||   they hand-cuffed him; and before proceeding to ransack the premises
U||   they searched his person, but nothing unusual was found about him,
U||   excepting a paper parcel, in his coat-pocket, containing what was
U||   afterward ascertained to be a mixture of antimony and some unknown
U||   substance, in nearly, but not quite, equal proportions. All attempts at
U||   analyzing the unknown substance have, so far, failed, but that it will
U||   ultimately be analyzed, is not to be doubted.
U||   Passing out of the closet with their prisoner, the officers went
U||   through a sort of ante-chamber, in which nothing material was found, to
U||   the chemist’s sleeping-room. They here rummaged some drawers and boxes,
U||   but discovered only a few papers, of no importance, and some good coin,
U||   silver and gold. At length, looking under the bed, they saw a large,
U||   common hair trunk, without hinges, hasp, or lock, and with the top
U||   lying carelessly across the bottom portion. Upon attempting to draw
U||   this trunk out from under the bed, they found that, with their united
U||   strength (there were three of them, all powerful men), they ‘could not
U||   stir it one inch.’ Much astonished at this, one of them crawled under
U||   the bed, and looking into the trunk, said:
U||   ‘No wonder we couldn’t move it—why it’s full to the brim of old bits of
U||   brass!’
U||   Putting his feet, now, against the wall so as to get a good purchase,
U||   and pushing with all his force, while his companions pulled with all
U||   theirs, the trunk, with much difficulty, was slid out from under the
U||   bed, and its contents examined. The supposed brass with which it was
U||   filled was all in small, smooth pieces, varying from the size of a pea
U||   to that of a dollar; but the pieces were irregular in shape, although
U||   more or less flat-looking, upon the whole, “very much as lead looks
U||   when thrown upon the ground in a molten state, and there suffered to
U||   grow cool.” Now, not one of these officers for a moment suspected this
U||   metal to be anything but brass. The idea of its being gold never
U||   entered their brains, of course; how could such a wild fancy have
U||   entered it? And their astonishment may be well conceived, when the next
U||   day it became known, all over Bremen, that the “lot of brass” which
U||   they had carted so contemptuously to the police office, without putting
U||   themselves to the trouble of pocketing the smallest scrap, was not only
U||   gold—real gold—but gold far finer than any employed in coinage—gold, in
U||   fact, absolutely pure, virgin, without the slightest appreciable alloy.
U||   I need not go over the details of Von Kempelen’s confession (as far as
U||   it went) and release, for these are familiar to the public. That he has
U||   actually realized, in spirit and in effect, if not to the letter, the
U||   old chimaera of the philosopher’s stone, no sane person is at liberty
U||   to doubt. The opinions of Arago are, of course, entitled to the
U||   greatest consideration; but he is by no means infallible; and what he
U||   says of bismuth, in his report to the Academy, must be taken cum grano
U||   salis. The simple truth is, that up to this period all analysis has
U||   failed; and until Von Kempelen chooses to let us have the key to his
U||   own published enigma, it is more than probable that the matter will
U||   remain, for years, in statu quo. All that as yet can fairly be said to
U||   be known is, that ‘Pure gold can be made at will, and very readily from
U||   lead in connection with certain other substances, in kind and in
U||   proportions, unknown.’
U||   Speculation, of course, is busy as to the immediate and ultimate
U||   results of this discovery—a discovery which few thinking persons will
U||   hesitate in referring to an increased interest in the matter of gold
U||   generally, by the late developments in California; and this reflection
U||   brings us inevitably to another—the exceeding inopportuneness of Von
U||   Kempelen’s analysis. If many were prevented from adventuring to
U||   California, by the mere apprehension that gold would so materially
U||   diminish in value, on account of its plentifulness in the mines there,
U||   as to render the speculation of going so far in search of it a doubtful
U||   one—what impression will be wrought now, upon the minds of those about
U||   to emigrate, and especially upon the minds of those actually in the
U||   mineral region, by the announcement of this astounding discovery of Von
U||   Kempelen? a discovery which declares, in so many words, that beyond its
U||   intrinsic worth for manufacturing purposes (whatever that worth may
U||   be), gold now is, or at least soon will be (for it cannot be supposed
U||   that Von Kempelen can long retain his secret), of no greater value than
U||   lead, and of far inferior value to silver. It is, indeed, exceedingly
U||   difficult to speculate prospectively upon the consequences of the
U||   discovery, but one thing may be positively maintained—that the
U||   announcement of the discovery six months ago would have had material
U||   influence in regard to the settlement of California.
U||   In Europe, as yet, the most noticeable results have been a rise of two
U||   hundred per cent. in the price of lead, and nearly twenty-five per
U||   cent. that of silver.
U||MESMERIC REVELATION
U||   Whatever doubt may still envelop the rationale of mesmerism, its
U||   startling facts are now almost universally admitted. Of these latter,
U||   those who doubt, are your mere doubters by profession—an unprofitable
U||   and disreputable tribe. There can be no more absolute waste of time
U||   than the attempt to prove, at the present day, that man, by mere
U||   exercise of will, can so impress his fellow, as to cast him into an
U||   abnormal condition, of which the phenomena resemble very closely those
U||   of death, or at least resemble them more nearly than they do the
U||   phenomena of any other normal condition within our cognizance; that,
U||   while in this state, the person so impressed employs only with effort,
U||   and then feebly, the external organs of sense, yet perceives, with
U||   keenly refined perception, and through channels supposed unknown,
U||   matters beyond the scope of the physical organs; that, moreover, his
U||   intellectual faculties are wonderfully exalted and invigorated; that
U||   his sympathies with the person so impressing him are profound; and,
U||   finally, that his susceptibility to the impression increases with its
U||   frequency, while, in the same proportion, the peculiar phenomena
U||   elicited are more extended and more pronounced.
U||   I say that these—which are the laws of mesmerism in its general
U||   features—it would be supererogation to demonstrate; nor shall I inflict
U||   upon my readers so needless a demonstration; to-day. My purpose at
U||   present is a very different one indeed. I am impelled, even in the
U||   teeth of a world of prejudice, to detail without comment the very
U||   remarkable substance of a colloquy, occurring between a sleep-waker and
U||   myself.
U||   I had been long in the habit of mesmerizing the person in question (Mr.
U||   Vankirk), and the usual acute susceptibility and exaltation of the
U||   mesmeric perception had supervened. For many months he had been
U||   laboring under confirmed phthisis, the more distressing effects of
U||   which had been relieved by my manipulations; and on the night of
U||   Wednesday, the fifteenth instant, I was summoned to his bedside.
U||   The invalid was suffering with acute pain in the region of the heart,
U||   and breathed with great difficulty, having all the ordinary symptoms of
U||   asthma. In spasms such as these he had usually found relief from the
U||   application of mustard to the nervous centres, but to-night this had
U||   been attempted in vain.
U||   As I entered his room he greeted me with a cheerful smile, and although
U||   evidently in much bodily pain, appeared to be, mentally, quite at ease.
U||   “I sent for you to-night,” he said, “not so much to administer to my
U||   bodily ailment, as to satisfy me concerning certain psychal impressions
U||   which, of late, have occasioned me much anxiety and surprise. I need
U||   not tell you how sceptical I have hitherto been on the topic of the
U||   soul’s immortality. I cannot deny that there has always existed, as if
U||   in that very soul which I have been denying, a vague half-sentiment of
U||   its own existence. But this half-sentiment at no time amounted to
U||   conviction. With it my reason had nothing to do. All attempts at
U||   logical inquiry resulted, indeed, in leaving me more sceptical than
U||   before. I had been advised to study Cousin. I studied him in his own
U||   works as well as in those of his European and American echoes. The
U||   ‘Charles Elwood’ of Mr. Brownson, for example, was placed in my hands.
U||   I read it with profound attention. Throughout I found it logical, but
U||   the portions which were not merely logical were unhappily the initial
U||   arguments of the disbelieving hero of the book. In his summing up it
U||   seemed evident to me that the reasoner had not even succeeded in
U||   convincing himself. His end had plainly forgotten his beginning, like
U||   the government of Trinculo. In short, I was not long in perceiving that
U||   if man is to be intellectually convinced of his own immortality, he
U||   will never be so convinced by the mere abstractions which have been so
U||   long the fashion of the moralists of England, of France, and of
U||   Germany. Abstractions may amuse and exercise, but take no hold on the
U||   mind. Here upon earth, at least, philosophy, I am persuaded, will
U||   always in vain call upon us to look upon qualities as things. The will
U||   may assent—the soul—the intellect, never.
U||   “I repeat, then, that I only half felt, and never intellectually
U||   believed. But latterly there has been a certain deepening of the
U||   feeling, until it has come so nearly to resemble the acquiescence of
U||   reason, that I find it difficult to distinguish between the two. I am
U||   enabled, too, plainly to trace this effect to the mesmeric influence. I
U||   cannot better explain my meaning than by the hypothesis that the
U||   mesmeric exaltation enables me to perceive a train of ratiocination
U||   which, in my abnormal existence, convinces, but which, in full
U||   accordance with the mesmeric phenomena, does not extend, except through
U||   its effect, into my normal condition. In sleep-waking, the reasoning
U||   and its conclusion—the cause and its effect—are present together. In my
U||   natural state, the cause vanishing, the effect only, and perhaps only
U||   partially, remains.
U||   “These considerations have led me to think that some good results might
U||   ensue from a series of well-directed questions propounded to me while
U||   mesmerized. You have often observed the profound self-cognizance
U||   evinced by the sleep-waker—the extensive knowledge he displays upon all
U||   points relating to the mesmeric condition itself; and from this
U||   self-cognizance may be deduced hints for the proper conduct of a
U||   catechism.”
U||   I consented of course to make this experiment. A few passes threw Mr.
U||   Vankirk into the mesmeric sleep. His breathing became immediately more
U||   easy, and he seemed to suffer no physical uneasiness. The following
U||   conversation then ensued:—V. in the dialogue representing the patient,
U||   and P. myself.
U||   P. Are you asleep?
U||   V. Yes—no; I would rather sleep more soundly.
U||   P. [After a few more passes.] Do you sleep now?
U||   V. Yes.
U||   P. How do you think your present illness will result?
U||   V. [After a long hesitation and speaking as if with effort.] I must
U||   die.
U||   P. Does the idea of death afflict you?
U||   V. [Very quickly.] No—no!
U||   P. Are you pleased with the prospect?
U||   V. If I were awake I should like to die, but now it is no matter. The
U||   mesmeric condition is so near death as to content me.
U||   P. I wish you would explain yourself, Mr. Vankirk.
U||   V. I am willing to do so, but it requires more effort than I feel able
U||   to make. You do not question me properly.
U||   P. What then shall I ask?
U||   V. You must begin at the beginning.
U||   P. The beginning! But where is the beginning?
U||   V. You know that the beginning is GOD. [This was said in a low,
U||   fluctuating tone, and with every sign of the most profound veneration.]
U||   P. What then, is God?
U||   V. [Hesitating for many minutes.] I cannot tell.
U||   P. Is not God spirit?
U||   V. While I was awake I knew what you meant by “spirit,” but now it
U||   seems only a word—such, for instance, as truth, beauty—a quality, I
U||   mean.
U||   P. Is not God immaterial?
U||   V. There is no immateriality—it is a mere word. That which is not
U||   matter, is not at all—unless qualities are things.
U||   P. Is God, then, material?
U||   V. No. [This reply startled me very much.]
U||   P. What, then, is he?
U||   V. [After a long pause, and mutteringly.] I see—but it is a thing
U||   difficult to tell. [Another long pause.] He is not spirit, for he
U||   exists. Nor is he matter, as you understand it. But there are
U||   gradations of matter of which man knows nothing; the grosser impelling
U||   the finer, the finer pervading the grosser. The atmosphere, for
U||   example, impels the electric principle, while the electric principle
U||   permeates the atmosphere. These gradations of matter increase in rarity
U||   or fineness, until we arrive at a matter unparticled—without
U||   particles—indivisible—one; and here the law of impulsion and permeation
U||   is modified. The ultimate, or unparticled matter, not only permeates
U||   all things but impels all things; and thus is all things within itself.
U||   This matter is God. What men attempt to embody in the word “thought,”
U||   is this matter in motion.
U||   P. The metaphysicians maintain that all action is reducible to motion
U||   and thinking, and that the latter is the origin of the former.
U||   V. Yes; and I now see the confusion of idea. Motion is the action of
U||   mind, not of thinking. The unparticled matter, or God, in quiescence,
U||   is (as nearly as we can conceive it) what men call mind. And the power
U||   of self-movement (equivalent in effect to human volition) is, in the
U||   unparticled matter, the result of its unity and omniprevalence; how I
U||   know not, and now clearly see that I shall never know. But the
U||   unparticled matter, set in motion by a law, or quality, existing within
U||   itself, is thinking.
U||   P. Can you give me no more precise idea of what you term the
U||   unparticled matter?
U||   V. The matters of which man is cognizant escape the senses in
U||   gradation. We have, for example, a metal, a piece of wood, a drop of
U||   water, the atmosphere, a gas, caloric, electricity, the luminiferous
U||   ether. Now we call all these things matter, and embrace all matter in
U||   one general definition; but in spite of this, there can be no two ideas
U||   more essentially distinct than that which we attach to a metal, and
U||   that which we attach to the luminiferous ether. When we reach the
U||   latter, we feel an almost irresistible inclination to class it with
U||   spirit, or with nihility. The only consideration which restrains us is
U||   our conception of its atomic constitution; and here, even, we have to
U||   seek aid from our notion of an atom, as something possessing in
U||   infinite minuteness, solidity, palpability, weight. Destroy the idea of
U||   the atomic constitution and we should no longer be able to regard the
U||   ether as an entity, or at least as matter. For want of a better word we
U||   might term it spirit. Take, now, a step beyond the luminiferous
U||   ether—conceive a matter as much more rare than the ether, as this ether
U||   is more rare than the metal, and we arrive at once (in spite of all the
U||   school dogmas) at a unique mass—an unparticled matter. For although we
U||   may admit infinite littleness in the atoms themselves, the infinitude
U||   of littleness in the spaces between them is an absurdity. There will be
U||   a point—there will be a degree of rarity, at which, if the atoms are
U||   sufficiently numerous, the interspaces must vanish, and the mass
U||   absolutely coalesce. But the consideration of the atomic constitution
U||   being now taken away, the nature of the mass inevitably glides into
U||   what we conceive of spirit. It is clear, however, that it is as fully
U||   matter as before. The truth is, it is impossible to conceive spirit,
U||   since it is impossible to imagine what is not. When we flatter
U||   ourselves that we have formed its conception, we have merely deceived
U||   our understanding by the consideration of infinitely rarified matter.
U||   P. There seems to me an insurmountable objection to the idea of
U||   absolute coalescence;—and that is the very slight resistance
U||   experienced by the heavenly bodies in their revolutions through space—a
U||   resistance now ascertained, it is true, to exist in some degree, but
U||   which is, nevertheless, so slight as to have been quite overlooked by
U||   the sagacity even of Newton. We know that the resistance of bodies is,
U||   chiefly, in proportion to their density. Absolute coalescence is
U||   absolute density. Where there are no interspaces, there can be no
U||   yielding. An ether, absolutely dense, would put an infinitely more
U||   effectual stop to the progress of a star than would an ether of adamant
U||   or of iron.
U||   V. Your objection is answered with an ease which is nearly in the ratio
U||   of its apparent unanswerability.—As regards the progress of the star,
U||   it can make no difference whether the star passes through the ether or
U||   the ether through it. There is no astronomical error more unaccountable
U||   than that which reconciles the known retardation of the comets with the
U||   idea of their passage through an ether: for, however rare this ether be
U||   supposed, it would put a stop to all sidereal revolution in a very far
U||   briefer period than has been admitted by those astronomers who have
U||   endeavored to slur over a point which they found it impossible to
U||   comprehend. The retardation actually experienced is, on the other hand,
U||   about that which might be expected from the friction of the ether in
U||   the instantaneous passage through the orb. In the one case, the
U||   retarding force is momentary and complete within itself—in the other it
U||   is endlessly accumulative.
U||   P. But in all this—in this identification of mere matter with God—is
U||   there nothing of irreverence? [I was forced to repeat this question
U||   before the sleep-waker fully comprehended my meaning.]
U||   V. Can you say why matter should be less reverenced than mind? But you
U||   forget that the matter of which I speak is, in all respects, the very
U||   “mind” or “spirit” of the schools, so far as regards its high
U||   capacities, and is, moreover, the “matter” of these schools at the same
U||   time. God, with all the powers attributed to spirit, is but the
U||   perfection of matter.
U||   P. You assert, then, that the unparticled matter, in motion, is
U||   thought?
U||   V. In general, this motion is the universal thought of the universal
U||   mind. This thought creates. All created things are but the thoughts of
U||   God.
U||   P. You say, “in general.”
U||   V. Yes. The universal mind is God. For new individualities, matter is
U||   necessary.
U||   P. But you now speak of “mind” and “matter” as do the metaphysicians.
U||   V. Yes—to avoid confusion. When I say “mind,” I mean the unparticled or
U||   ultimate matter; by “matter,” I intend all else.
U||   P. You were saying that “for new individualities matter is necessary.”
U||   V. Yes; for mind, existing unincorporate, is merely God. To create
U||   individual, thinking beings, it was necessary to incarnate portions of
U||   the divine mind. Thus man is individualized. Divested of corporate
U||   investiture, he were God. Now, the particular motion of the incarnated
U||   portions of the unparticled matter is the thought of man; as the motion
U||   of the whole is that of God.
U||   P. You say that divested of the body man will be God?
U||   V. [After much hesitation.] I could not have said this; it is an
U||   absurdity.
U||   P. [Referring to my notes.] You did say that “divested of corporate
U||   investiture man were God.”
U||   V. And this is true. Man thus divested would be God—would be
U||   unindividualized. But he can never be thus divested—at least never will
U||   be—else we must imagine an action of God returning upon itself—a
U||   purposeless and futile action. Man is a creature. Creatures are
U||   thoughts of God. It is the nature of thought to be irrevocable.
U||   P. I do not comprehend. You say that man will never put off the body?
U||   V. I say that he will never be bodiless.
U||   P. Explain.
U||   V. There are two bodies—the rudimental and the complete; corresponding
U||   with the two conditions of the worm and the butterfly. What we call
U||   “death,” is but the painful metamorphosis. Our present incarnation is
U||   progressive, preparatory, temporary. Our future is perfected, ultimate,
U||   immortal. The ultimate life is the full design.
U||   P. But of the worm’s metamorphosis we are palpably cognizant.
U||   V. We, certainly—but not the worm. The matter of which our rudimental
U||   body is composed, is within the ken of the organs of that body; or,
U||   more distinctly, our rudimental organs are adapted to the matter of
U||   which is formed the rudimental body; but not to that of which the
U||   ultimate is composed. The ultimate body thus escapes our rudimental
U||   senses, and we perceive only the shell which falls, in decaying, from
U||   the inner form; not that inner form itself; but this inner form, as
U||   well as the shell, is appreciable by those who have already acquired
U||   the ultimate life.
U||   P. You have often said that the mesmeric state very nearly resembles
U||   death. How is this?
U||   V. When I say that it resembles death, I mean that it resembles the
U||   ultimate life; for when I am entranced the senses of my rudimental life
