U||   organs, through a medium which I shall employ in the ultimate,
U||   unorganized life.
U||   P. Unorganized?
U||   V. Yes; organs are contrivances by which the individual is brought into
U||   sensible relation with particular classes and forms of matter, to the
U||   exclusion of other classes and forms. The organs of man are adapted to
U||   his rudimental condition, and to that only; his ultimate condition,
U||   being unorganized, is of unlimited comprehension in all points but
U||   one—the nature of the volition of God—that is to say, the motion of the
U||   unparticled matter. You will have a distinct idea of the ultimate body
U||   by conceiving it to be entire brain. This it is not; but a conception
U||   of this nature will bring you near a comprehension of what it is. A
U||   luminous body imparts vibration to the luminiferous ether. The
U||   vibrations generate similar ones within the retina; these again
U||   communicate similar ones to the optic nerve. The nerve conveys similar
U||   ones to the brain; the brain, also, similar ones to the unparticled
U||   matter which permeates it. The motion of this latter is thought, of
U||   which perception is the first undulation. This is the mode by which the
U||   mind of the rudimental life communicates with the external world; and
U||   this external world is, to the rudimental life, limited, through the
U||   idiosyncrasy of its organs. But in the ultimate, unorganized life, the
