U||THE FACTS IN THE CASE OF M. VALDEMAR
U||   Of course I shall not pretend to consider it any matter for wonder,
U||   that the extraordinary case of M. Valdemar has excited discussion. It
U||   would have been a miracle had it not—especially under the
U||   circumstances. Through the desire of all parties concerned, to keep the
U||   affair from the public, at least for the present, or until we had
U||   farther opportunities for investigation—through our endeavors to effect
U||   this—a garbled or exaggerated account made its way into society, and
U||   became the source of many unpleasant misrepresentations; and, very
U||   naturally, of a great deal of disbelief.
U||   It is now rendered necessary that I give the facts—as far as I
U||   comprehend them myself. They are, succinctly, these:
U||   My attention, for the last three years, had been repeatedly drawn to
U||   the subject of Mesmerism; and, about nine months ago it occurred to me,
U||   quite suddenly, that in the series of experiments made hitherto, there
U||   had been a very remarkable and most unaccountable omission:—no person
U||   had as yet been mesmerized in articulo mortis. It remained to be seen,
U||   first, whether, in such condition, there existed in the patient any
U||   susceptibility to the magnetic influence; secondly, whether, if any
U||   existed, it was impaired or increased by the condition; thirdly, to
U||   what extent, or for how long a period, the encroachments of Death might
U||   be arrested by the process. There were other points to be ascertained,
U||   but these most excited my curiosity—the last in especial, from the
U||   immensely important character of its consequences.
U||   In looking around me for some subject by whose means I might test these
U||   particulars, I was brought to think of my friend, M. Ernest Valdemar,
U||   the well-known compiler of the “Bibliotheca Forensica,” and author
U||   (under the nom de plume of Issachar Marx) of the Polish versions of
U||   “Wallenstein” and “Gargantua.” M. Valdemar, who has resided principally
U||   at Harlem, N.Y., since the year 1839, is (or was) particularly
U||   noticeable for the extreme spareness of his person—his lower limbs much
U||   resembling those of John Randolph; and, also, for the whiteness of his
U||   whiskers, in violent contrast to the blackness of his hair—the latter,
U||   in consequence, being very generally mistaken for a wig. His
U||   temperament was markedly nervous, and rendered him a good subject for
U||   mesmeric experiment. On two or three occasions I had put him to sleep
U||   with little difficulty, but was disappointed in other results which his
U||   peculiar constitution had naturally led me to anticipate. His will was
U||   at no period positively, or thoroughly, under my control, and in regard
U||   to clairvoyance, I could accomplish with him nothing to be relied upon.
U||   I always attributed my failure at these points to the disordered state
U||   of his health. For some months previous to my becoming acquainted with
U||   him, his physicians had declared him in a confirmed phthisis. It was
U||   his custom, indeed, to speak calmly of his approaching dissolution, as
U||   of a matter neither to be avoided nor regretted.
U||   When the ideas to which I have alluded first occurred to me, it was of
U||   course very natural that I should think of M. Valdemar. I knew the
U||   steady philosophy of the man too well to apprehend any scruples from
U||   him; and he had no relatives in America who would be likely to
U||   interfere. I spoke to him frankly upon the subject; and, to my
U||   surprise, his interest seemed vividly excited. I say to my surprise,
U||   for, although he had always yielded his person freely to my
U||   experiments, he had never before given me any tokens of sympathy with
U||   what I did. His disease was of that character which would admit of
U||   exact calculation in respect to the epoch of its termination in death;
U||   and it was finally arranged between us that he would send for me about
U||   twenty-four hours before the period announced by his physicians as that
U||   of his decease.
U||   It is now rather more than seven months since I received, from M.
U||   Valdemar himself, the subjoined note:
U||   MY DEAR P——,
U||   You may as well come now. D—— and F—— are agreed that I cannot hold out
U||   beyond to-morrow midnight; and I think they have hit the time very
U||   nearly.
U||   VALDEMAR
U||   I received this note within half an hour after it was written, and in
U||   fifteen minutes more I was in the dying man’s chamber. I had not seen
U||   him for ten days, and was appalled by the fearful alteration which the
U||   brief interval had wrought in him. His face wore a leaden hue; the eyes
U||   were utterly lustreless; and the emaciation was so extreme that the
U||   skin had been broken through by the cheek-bones. His expectoration was
U||   excessive. The pulse was barely perceptible. He retained, nevertheless,
U||   in a very remarkable manner, both his mental power and a certain degree
U||   of physical strength. He spoke with distinctness—took some palliative
U||   medicines without aid—and, when I entered the room, was occupied in
U||   penciling memoranda in a pocket-book. He was propped up in the bed by
U||   pillows. Doctors D—— and F—— were in attendance.
U||   After pressing Valdemar’s hand, I took these gentlemen aside, and
U||   obtained from them a minute account of the patient’s condition. The
U||   left lung had been for eighteen months in a semi-osseous or
U||   cartilaginous state, and was, of course, entirely useless for all
U||   purposes of vitality. The right, in its upper portion, was also
U||   partially, if not thoroughly, ossified, while the lower region was
U||   merely a mass of purulent tubercles, running one into another. Several
U||   extensive perforations existed; and, at one point, permanent adhesion
U||   to the ribs had taken place. These appearances in the right lobe were
U||   of comparatively recent date. The ossification had proceeded with very
U||   unusual rapidity; no sign of it had been discovered a month before, and
U||   the adhesion had only been observed during the three previous days.
U||   Independently of the phthisis, the patient was suspected of aneurism of
U||   the aorta; but on this point the osseous symptoms rendered an exact
U||   diagnosis impossible. It was the opinion of both physicians that M.
U||   Valdemar would die about midnight on the morrow (Sunday). It was then
U||   seven o’clock on Saturday evening.
U||   On quitting the invalid’s bed-side to hold conversation with myself,
U||   Doctors D—— and F—— had bidden him a final farewell. It had not been
U||   their intention to return; but, at my request, they agreed to look in
U||   upon the patient about ten the next night.
U||   When they had gone, I spoke freely with M. Valdemar on the subject of
U||   his approaching dissolution, as well as, more particularly, of the
U||   experiment proposed. He still professed himself quite willing and even
U||   anxious to have it made, and urged me to commence it at once. A male
U||   and a female nurse were in attendance; but I did not feel myself
U||   altogether at liberty to engage in a task of this character with no
U||   more reliable witnesses than these people, in case of sudden accident,
U||   might prove. I therefore postponed operations until about eight the
U||   next night, when the arrival of a medical student with whom I had some
U||   acquaintance, (Mr. Theodore L—l,) relieved me from farther
U||   embarrassment. It had been my design, originally, to wait for the
U||   physicians; but I was induced to proceed, first, by the urgent
U||   entreaties of M. Valdemar, and secondly, by my conviction that I had
U||   not a moment to lose, as he was evidently sinking fast.
U||   Mr. L—l was so kind as to accede to my desire that he would take notes
U||   of all that occurred, and it is from his memoranda that what I now have
U||   to relate is, for the most part, either condensed or copied verbatim.
U||   It wanted about five minutes of eight when, taking the patient’s hand,
U||   I begged him to state, as distinctly as he could, to Mr. L—l, whether
U||   he (M. Valdemar) was entirely willing that I should make the experiment
U||   of mesmerizing him in his then condition.
U||   He replied feebly, yet quite audibly, “Yes, I wish to be. I fear you
U||   have mesmerized”—adding immediately afterwards: “I fear you have
U||   deferred it too long.”
U||   While he spoke thus, I commenced the passes which I had already found
U||   most effectual in subduing him. He was evidently influenced with the
U||   first lateral stroke of my hand across his forehead; but although I
U||   exerted all my powers, no further perceptible effect was induced until
U||   some minutes after ten o’clock, when Doctors D—— and F—— called,
U||   according to appointment. I explained to them, in a few words, what I
U||   designed, and as they opposed no objection, saying that the patient was
U||   already in the death agony, I proceeded without hesitation—exchanging,
U||   however, the lateral passes for downward ones, and directing my gaze
U||   entirely into the right eye of the sufferer.
U||   By this time his pulse was imperceptible and his breathing was
U||   stertorous, and at intervals of half a minute.
U||   This condition was nearly unaltered for a quarter of an hour. At the
U||   expiration of this period, however, a natural although a very deep sigh
U||   escaped the bosom of the dying man, and the stertorous breathing
U||   ceased—that is to say, its stertorousness was no longer apparent; the
U||   intervals were undiminished. The patient’s extremities were of an icy
U||   coldness.
U||   At five minutes before eleven I perceived unequivocal signs of the
U||   mesmeric influence. The glassy roll of the eye was changed for that
U||   expression of uneasy inward examination which is never seen except in
U||   cases of sleep-waking, and which it is quite impossible to mistake.
U||   With a few rapid lateral passes I made the lids quiver, as in incipient
U||   sleep, and with a few more I closed them altogether. I was not
U||   satisfied, however, with this, but continued the manipulations
U||   vigorously, and with the fullest exertion of the will, until I had
U||   completely stiffened the limbs of the slumberer, after placing them in
U||   a seemingly easy position. The legs were at full length; the arms were
U||   nearly so, and reposed on the bed at a moderate distance from the loin.
U||   The head was very slightly elevated.
U||   When I had accomplished this, it was fully midnight, and I requested
U||   the gentlemen present to examine M. Valdemar’s condition. After a few
U||   experiments, they admitted him to be an unusually perfect state of
U||   mesmeric trance. The curiosity of both the physicians was greatly
U||   excited. Dr. D—— resolved at once to remain with the patient all night,
U||   while Dr. F—— took leave with a promise to return at daybreak. Mr. L—l
U||   and the nurses remained.
U||   We left M. Valdemar entirely undisturbed until about three o’clock in
U||   the morning, when I approached him and found him in precisely the same
U||   condition as when Dr. F—— went away—that is to say, he lay in the same
U||   position; the pulse was imperceptible; the breathing was gentle
U||   (scarcely noticeable, unless through the application of a mirror to the
U||   lips); the eyes were closed naturally; and the limbs were as rigid and
U||   as cold as marble. Still, the general appearance was certainly not that
U||   of death.
U||   As I approached M. Valdemar I made a kind of half effort to influence
U||   his right arm into pursuit of my own, as I passed the latter gently to
U||   and fro above his person. In such experiments with this patient, I had
U||   never perfectly succeeded before, and assuredly I had little thought of
U||   succeeding now; but to my astonishment, his arm very readily, although
U||   feebly, followed every direction I assigned it with mine. I determined
U||   to hazard a few words of conversation.
U||   “M. Valdemar,” I said, “are you asleep?” He made no answer, but I
U||   perceived a tremor about the lips, and was thus induced to repeat the
U||   question, again and again. At its third repetition, his whole frame was
U||   agitated by a very slight shivering; the eyelids unclosed themselves so
U||   far as to display a white line of the ball; the lips moved sluggishly,
U||   and from between them, in a barely audible whisper, issued the words:
U||   “Yes;—asleep now. Do not wake me!—let me die so!”
U||   I here felt the limbs and found them as rigid as ever. The right arm,
U||   as before, obeyed the direction of my hand. I questioned the
U||   sleep-waker again:
U||   “Do you still feel pain in the breast, M. Valdemar?”
U||   The answer now was immediate, but even less audible than before:
U||   “No pain—I am dying.”
U||   I did not think it advisable to disturb him farther just then, and
U||   nothing more was said or done until the arrival of Dr. F——, who came a
U||   little before sunrise, and expressed unbounded astonishment at finding
U||   the patient still alive. After feeling the pulse and applying a mirror
U||   to the lips, he requested me to speak to the sleep-waker again. I did
U||   so, saying:
U||   “M. Valdemar, do you still sleep?”
U||   As before, some minutes elapsed ere a reply was made; and during the
U||   interval the dying man seemed to be collecting his energies to speak.
U||   At my fourth repetition of the question, he said very faintly, almost
U||   inaudibly:
U||   “Yes; still asleep—dying.”
U||   It was now the opinion, or rather the wish, of the physicians, that M.
U||   Valdemar should be suffered to remain undisturbed in his present
U||   apparently tranquil condition, until death should supervene—and this,
U||   it was generally agreed, must now take place within a few minutes. I
U||   concluded, however, to speak to him once more, and merely repeated my
U||   previous question.
U||   While I spoke, there came a marked change over the countenance of the
U||   sleep-waker. The eyes rolled themselves slowly open, the pupils
U||   disappearing upwardly; the skin generally assumed a cadaverous hue,
U||   resembling not so much parchment as white paper; and the circular
U||   hectic spots which, hitherto, had been strongly defined in the centre
U||   of each cheek, went out at once. I use this expression, because the
U||   suddenness of their departure put me in mind of nothing so much as the
U||   extinguishment of a candle by a puff of the breath. The upper lip, at
U||   the same time, writhed itself away from the teeth, which it had
U||   previously covered completely; while the lower jaw fell with an audible
U||   jerk, leaving the mouth widely extended, and disclosing in full view
U||   the swollen and blackened tongue. I presume that no member of the party
U||   then present had been unaccustomed to death-bed horrors; but so hideous
U||   beyond conception was the appearance of M. Valdemar at this moment,
U||   that there was a general shrinking back from the region of the bed.
U||   I now feel that I have reached a point of this narrative at which every
U||   reader will be startled into positive disbelief. It is my business,
U||   however, simply to proceed.
U||   There was no longer the faintest sign of vitality in M. Valdemar; and
U||   concluding him to be dead, we were consigning him to the charge of the
U||   nurses, when a strong vibratory motion was observable in the tongue.
U||   This continued for perhaps a minute. At the expiration of this period,
U||   there issued from the distended and motionless jaws a voice—such as it
U||   would be madness in me to attempt describing. There are, indeed, two or
U||   three epithets which might be considered as applicable to it in part; I
U||   might say, for example, that the sound was harsh, and broken and
U||   hollow; but the hideous whole is indescribable, for the simple reason
U||   that no similar sounds have ever jarred upon the ear of humanity. There
U||   were two particulars, nevertheless, which I thought then, and still
U||   think, might fairly be stated as characteristic of the intonation—as
U||   well adapted to convey some idea of its unearthly peculiarity. In the
U||   first place, the voice seemed to reach our ears—at least mine—from a
U||   vast distance, or from some deep cavern within the earth. In the second
U||   place, it impressed me (I fear, indeed, that it will be impossible to
U||   make myself comprehended) as gelatinous or glutinous matters impress
U||   the sense of touch.
U||   I have spoken both of “sound” and of “voice.” I mean to say that the
U||   sound was one of distinct—of even wonderfully, thrillingly
U||   distinct—syllabification. M. Valdemar spoke—obviously in reply to the
U||   question I had propounded to him a few minutes before. I had asked him,
U||   it will be remembered, if he still slept. He now said:
U||   “Yes;—no;—I have been sleeping—and now—now—I am dead.”
U||   No person present even affected to deny, or attempted to repress, the
U||   unutterable, shuddering horror which these few words, thus uttered,
U||   were so well calculated to convey. Mr. L—l (the student) swooned. The
U||   nurses immediately left the chamber, and could not be induced to
U||   return. My own impressions I would not pretend to render intelligible
U||   to the reader. For nearly an hour, we busied ourselves,
U||   silently—without the utterance of a word—in endeavors to revive Mr.
U||   L—l. When he came to himself, we addressed ourselves again to an
U||   investigation of M. Valdemar’s condition.
U||   It remained in all respects as I have last described it, with the
U||   exception that the mirror no longer afforded evidence of respiration.
U||   An attempt to draw blood from the arm failed. I should mention, too,
U||   that this limb was no farther subject to my will. I endeavored in vain
U||   to make it follow the direction of my hand. The only real indication,
U||   indeed, of the mesmeric influence, was now found in the vibratory
U||   movement of the tongue, whenever I addressed M. Valdemar a question. He
U||   seemed to be making an effort to reply, but had no longer sufficient
U||   volition. To queries put to him by any other person than myself he
U||   seemed utterly insensible—although I endeavored to place each member of
U||   the company in mesmeric rapport with him. I believe that I have now
U||   related all that is necessary to an understanding of the sleep-waker’s
U||   state at this epoch. Other nurses were procured; and at ten o’clock I
U||   left the house in company with the two physicians and Mr. L—l.
U||   In the afternoon we all called again to see the patient. His condition
U||   remained precisely the same. We had now some discussion as to the
U||   propriety and feasibility of awakening him; but we had little
U||   difficulty in agreeing that no good purpose would be served by so
U||   doing. It was evident that, so far, death (or what is usually termed
U||   death) had been arrested by the mesmeric process. It seemed clear to us
U||   all that to awaken M. Valdemar would be merely to insure his instant,
U||   or at least his speedy, dissolution.
U||   From this period until the close of last week—an interval of nearly
U||   seven months—we continued to make daily calls at M. Valdemar’s house,
U||   accompanied, now and then, by medical and other friends. All this time
U||   the sleeper-waker remained exactly as I have last described him. The
U||   nurses’ attentions were continual.
U||   It was on Friday last that we finally resolved to make the experiment
U||   of awakening, or attempting to awaken him; and it is the (perhaps)
U||   unfortunate result of this latter experiment which has given rise to so
U||   much discussion in private circles—to so much of what I cannot help
U||   thinking unwarranted popular feeling.
U||   For the purpose of relieving M. Valdemar from the mesmeric trance, I
U||   made use of the customary passes. These, for a time, were unsuccessful.
U||   The first indication of revival was afforded by a partial descent of
U||   the iris. It was observed, as especially remarkable, that this lowering
U||   of the pupil was accompanied by the profuse out-flowing of a yellowish
U||   ichor (from beneath the lids) of a pungent and highly offensive odor.
U||   It was now suggested that I should attempt to influence the patient’s
U||   arm, as heretofore. I made the attempt and failed. Dr. F—— then
U||   intimated a desire to have me put a question. I did so, as follows:
U||   “M. Valdemar, can you explain to us what are your feelings or wishes
U||   now?”
U||   There was an instant return of the hectic circles on the cheeks; the
U||   tongue quivered, or rather rolled violently in the mouth (although the
U||   jaws and lips remained rigid as before), and at length the same hideous
U||   voice which I have already described, broke forth:
U||   “For God’s sake!—quick!—quick!—put me to sleep—or, quick!—waken
U||   me!—quick!—I say to you that I am dead!”
U||   I was thoroughly unnerved, and for an instant remained undecided what
U||   to do. At first I made an endeavor to recompose the patient; but,
U||   failing in this through total abeyance of the will, I retraced my steps
U||   and as earnestly struggled to awaken him. In this attempt I soon saw
U||   that I should be successful—or at least I soon fancied that my success
U||   would be complete—and I am sure that all in the room were prepared to
U||   see the patient awaken.
U||   For what really occurred, however, it is quite impossible that any
U||   human being could have been prepared.
U||   As I rapidly made the mesmeric passes, amid ejaculations of “dead!
U||   dead!” absolutely bursting from the tongue and not from the lips of the
U||   sufferer, his whole frame at once—within the space of a single minute,
U||   or even less, shrunk—crumbled—absolutely rotted away beneath my hands.
U||   Upon the bed, before that whole company, there lay a nearly liquid mass
U||   of loathsome—of detestable putrescence.
U||THE BLACK CAT.
U||   For the most wild, yet most homely narrative which I am about to pen, I
U||   neither expect nor solicit belief. Mad indeed would I be to expect it,
U||   in a case where my very senses reject their own evidence. Yet, mad am I
U||   not—and very surely do I not dream. But to-morrow I die, and to-day I
U||   would unburthen my soul. My immediate purpose is to place before the
U||   world, plainly, succinctly, and without comment, a series of mere
U||   household events. In their consequences, these events have
U||   terrified—have tortured—have destroyed me. Yet I will not attempt to
U||   expound them. To me, they have presented little but horror—to many they
U||   will seem less terrible than barroques. Hereafter, perhaps, some
U||   intellect may be found which will reduce my phantasm to the
U||   common-place—some intellect more calm, more logical, and far less
U||   excitable than my own, which will perceive, in the circumstances I
U||   detail with awe, nothing more than an ordinary succession of very
U||   natural causes and effects.
U||   From my infancy I was noted for the docility and humanity of my
U||   disposition. My tenderness of heart was even so conspicuous as to make
U||   me the jest of my companions. I was especially fond of animals, and was
U||   indulged by my parents with a great variety of pets. With these I spent
U||   most of my time, and never was so happy as when feeding and caressing
U||   them. This peculiarity of character grew with my growth, and in my
U||   manhood, I derived from it one of my principal sources of pleasure. To
U||   those who have cherished an affection for a faithful and sagacious dog,
U||   I need hardly be at the trouble of explaining the nature or the
U||   intensity of the gratification thus derivable. There is something in
U||   the unselfish and self-sacrificing love of a brute, which goes directly
U||   to the heart of him who has had frequent occasion to test the paltry
U||   friendship and gossamer fidelity of mere Man.
U||   I married early, and was happy to find in my wife a disposition not
U||   uncongenial with my own. Observing my partiality for domestic pets, she
U||   lost no opportunity of procuring those of the most agreeable kind. We
U||   had birds, gold-fish, a fine dog, rabbits, a small monkey, and a cat.
U||   This latter was a remarkably large and beautiful animal, entirely
U||   black, and sagacious to an astonishing degree. In speaking of his
U||   intelligence, my wife, who at heart was not a little tinctured with
U||   superstition, made frequent allusion to the ancient popular notion,
U||   which regarded all black cats as witches in disguise. Not that she was
U||   ever serious upon this point—and I mention the matter at all for no
U||   better reason than that it happens, just now, to be remembered.
U||   Pluto—this was the cat’s name—was my favorite pet and playmate. I alone
U||   fed him, and he attended me wherever I went about the house. It was
U||   even with difficulty that I could prevent him from following me through
U||   the streets.
U||   Our friendship lasted, in this manner, for several years, during which
U||   my general temperament and character—through the instrumentality of the
U||   Fiend Intemperance—had (I blush to confess it) experienced a radical
U||   alteration for the worse. I grew, day by day, more moody, more
U||   irritable, more regardless of the feelings of others. I suffered myself
U||   to use intemperate language to my wife. At length, I even offered her
U||   personal violence. My pets, of course, were made to feel the change in
U||   my disposition. I not only neglected, but ill-used them. For Pluto,
U||   however, I still retained sufficient regard to restrain me from
U||   maltreating him, as I made no scruple of maltreating the rabbits, the
U||   monkey, or even the dog, when by accident, or through affection, they
U||   came in my way. But my disease grew upon me—for what disease is like
U||   Alcohol!—and at length even Pluto, who was now becoming old, and
U||   consequently somewhat peevish—even Pluto began to experience the
U||   effects of my ill temper.
U||   One night, returning home, much intoxicated, from one of my haunts
U||   about town, I fancied that the cat avoided my presence. I seized him;
U||   when, in his fright at my violence, he inflicted a slight wound upon my
U||   hand with his teeth. The fury of a demon instantly possessed me. I knew
U||   myself no longer. My original soul seemed, at once, to take its flight
U||   from my body and a more than fiendish malevolence, gin-nurtured,
U||   thrilled every fibre of my frame. I took from my waistcoat-pocket a
U||   pen-knife, opened it, grasped the poor beast by the throat, and
U||   deliberately cut one of its eyes from the socket! I blush, I burn, I
U||   shudder, while I pen the damnable atrocity.
U||   When reason returned with the morning—when I had slept off the fumes of
U||   the night’s debauch—I experienced a sentiment half of horror, half of
U||   remorse, for the crime of which I had been guilty; but it was, at best,
U||   a feeble and equivocal feeling, and the soul remained untouched. I
U||   again plunged into excess, and soon drowned in wine all memory of the
U||   deed.
U||   In the meantime the cat slowly recovered. The socket of the lost eye
U||   presented, it is true, a frightful appearance, but he no longer
U||   appeared to suffer any pain. He went about the house as usual, but, as
U||   might be expected, fled in extreme terror at my approach. I had so much
U||   of my old heart left, as to be at first grieved by this evident dislike
U||   on the part of a creature which had once so loved me. But this feeling
U||   soon gave place to irritation. And then came, as if to my final and
U||   irrevocable overthrow, the spirit of PERVERSENESS. Of this spirit
U||   philosophy takes no account. Yet I am not more sure that my soul lives,
U||   than I am that perverseness is one of the primitive impulses of the
U||   human heart—one of the indivisible primary faculties, or sentiments,
U||   which give direction to the character of Man. Who has not, a hundred
U||   times, found himself committing a vile or a silly action, for no other
U||   reason than because he knows he should not? Have we not a perpetual
U||   inclination, in the teeth of our best judgment, to violate that which
U||   is Law, merely because we understand it to be such? This spirit of
U||   perverseness, I say, came to my final overthrow. It was this
U||   unfathomable longing of the soul to vex itself—to offer violence to its
U||   own nature—to do wrong for the wrong’s sake only—that urged me to
U||   continue and finally to consummate the injury I had inflicted upon the
U||   unoffending brute. One morning, in cool blood, I slipped a noose about
U||   its neck and hung it to the limb of a tree;—hung it with the tears
U||   streaming from my eyes, and with the bitterest remorse at my
U||   heart;—hung it because I knew that it had loved me, and because I felt
U||   it had given me no reason of offence;—hung it because I knew that in so
U||   doing I was committing a sin—a deadly sin that would so jeopardize my
U||   immortal soul as to place it—if such a thing wore possible—even beyond
U||   the reach of the infinite mercy of the Most Merciful and Most Terrible
U||   God.
U||   On the night of the day on which this cruel deed was done, I was
U||   aroused from sleep by the cry of fire. The curtains of my bed were in
U||   flames. The whole house was blazing. It was with great difficulty that
U||   my wife, a servant, and myself, made our escape from the conflagration.
U||   The destruction was complete. My entire worldly wealth was swallowed
U||   up, and I resigned myself thenceforward to despair.
U||   I am above the weakness of seeking to establish a sequence of cause and
U||   effect, between the disaster and the atrocity. But I am detailing a
U||   chain of facts—and wish not to leave even a possible link imperfect. On
U||   the day succeeding the fire, I visited the ruins. The walls, with one
U||   exception, had fallen in. This exception was found in a compartment
U||   wall, not very thick, which stood about the middle of the house, and
U||   against which had rested the head of my bed. The plastering had here,
U||   in great measure, resisted the action of the fire—a fact which I
U||   attributed to its having been recently spread. About this wall a dense
U||   crowd were collected, and many persons seemed to be examining a
U||   particular portion of it with very minute and eager attention. The
U||   words “strange!” “singular!” and other similar expressions, excited my
U||   curiosity. I approached and saw, as if graven in bas relief upon the
U||   white surface, the figure of a gigantic cat. The impression was given
U||   with an accuracy truly marvellous. There was a rope about the animal’s
U||   neck.
U||   When I first beheld this apparition—for I could scarcely regard it as
U||   less—my wonder and my terror were extreme. But at length reflection
U||   came to my aid. The cat, I remembered, had been hung in a garden
U||   adjacent to the house. Upon the alarm of fire, this garden had been
U||   immediately filled by the crowd—by some one of whom the animal must
U||   have been cut from the tree and thrown, through an open window, into my
U||   chamber. This had probably been done with the view of arousing me from
U||   sleep. The falling of other walls had compressed the victim of my
U||   cruelty into the substance of the freshly-spread plaster; the lime of
U||   which, with the flames, and the ammonia from the carcass, had then
U||   accomplished the portraiture as I saw it.
U||   Although I thus readily accounted to my reason, if not altogether to my
U||   conscience, for the startling fact just detailed, it did not the less
U||   fail to make a deep impression upon my fancy. For months I could not
U||   rid myself of the phantasm of the cat; and, during this period, there
U||   came back into my spirit a half-sentiment that seemed, but was not,
U||   remorse. I went so far as to regret the loss of the animal, and to look
U||   about me, among the vile haunts which I now habitually frequented, for
U||   another pet of the same species, and of somewhat similar appearance,
U||   with which to supply its place.
U||   One night as I sat, half stupefied, in a den of more than infamy, my
U||   attention was suddenly drawn to some black object, reposing upon the
U||   head of one of the immense hogsheads of gin, or of rum, which
U||   constituted the chief furniture of the apartment. I had been looking
U||   steadily at the top of this hogshead for some minutes, and what now
U||   caused me surprise was the fact that I had not sooner perceived the
U||   object thereupon. I approached it, and touched it with my hand. It was
U||   a black cat—a very large one—fully as large as Pluto, and closely
U||   resembling him in every respect but one. Pluto had not a white hair
U||   upon any portion of his body; but this cat had a large, although
U||   indefinite splotch of white, covering nearly the whole region of the
U||   breast. Upon my touching him, he immediately arose, purred loudly,
U||   rubbed against my hand, and appeared delighted with my notice. This,
U||   then, was the very creature of which I was in search. I at once offered
U||   to purchase it of the landlord; but this person made no claim to
U||   it—knew nothing of it—had never seen it before.
U||   I continued my caresses, and, when I prepared to go home, the animal
U||   evinced a disposition to accompany me. I permitted it to do so;
U||   occasionally stooping and patting it as I proceeded. When it reached
U||   the house it domesticated itself at once, and became immediately a
U||   great favorite with my wife.
U||   For my own part, I soon found a dislike to it arising within me. This
U||   was just the reverse of what I had anticipated; but—I know not how or
U||   why it was—its evident fondness for myself rather disgusted and
U||   annoyed. By slow degrees, these feelings of disgust and annoyance rose
U||   into the bitterness of hatred. I avoided the creature; a certain sense
U||   of shame, and the remembrance of my former deed of cruelty, preventing
U||   me from physically abusing it. I did not, for some weeks, strike, or
U||   otherwise violently ill use it; but gradually—very gradually—I came to
U||   look upon it with unutterable loathing, and to flee silently from its
U||   odious presence, as from the breath of a pestilence.
U||   What added, no doubt, to my hatred of the beast, was the discovery, on
U||   the morning after I brought it home, that, like Pluto, it also had been
U||   deprived of one of its eyes. This circumstance, however, only endeared
U||   it to my wife, who, as I have already said, possessed, in a high
U||   degree, that humanity of feeling which had once been my distinguishing
U||   trait, and the source of many of my simplest and purest pleasures.
U||   With my aversion to this cat, however, its partiality for myself seemed
U||   to increase. It followed my footsteps with a pertinacity which it would
U||   be difficult to make the reader comprehend. Whenever I sat, it would
U||   crouch beneath my chair, or spring upon my knees, covering me with its
U||   loathsome caresses. If I arose to walk it would get between my feet and
U||   thus nearly throw me down, or, fastening its long and sharp claws in my
U||   dress, clamber, in this manner, to my breast. At such times, although I
U||   longed to destroy it with a blow, I was yet withheld from so doing,
U||   partly by a memory of my former crime, but chiefly—let me confess it at
U||   once—by absolute dread of the beast.
U||   This dread was not exactly a dread of physical evil—and yet I should be
U||   at a loss how otherwise to define it. I am almost ashamed to own—yes,
U||   even in this felon’s cell, I am almost ashamed to own—that the terror
U||   and horror with which the animal inspired me, had been heightened by
U||   one of the merest chimaeras it would be possible to conceive. My wife
U||   had called my attention, more than once, to the character of the mark
U||   of white hair, of which I have spoken, and which constituted the sole
U||   visible difference between the strange beast and the one I had
U||   destroyed. The reader will remember that this mark, although large, had
U||   been originally very indefinite; but, by slow degrees—degrees nearly
U||   imperceptible, and which for a long time my reason struggled to reject
U||   as fanciful—it had, at length, assumed a rigorous distinctness of
U||   outline. It was now the representation of an object that I shudder to
U||   name—and for this, above all, I loathed, and dreaded, and would have
U||   rid myself of the monster had I dared—it was now, I say, the image of a
U||   hideous—of a ghastly thing—of the GALLOWS!—oh, mournful and terrible
U||   engine of Horror and of Crime—of Agony and of Death!
U||   And now was I indeed wretched beyond the wretchedness of mere Humanity.
U||   And a brute beast —whose fellow I had contemptuously destroyed—a brute
U||   beast to work out for me—for me a man, fashioned in the image of the
U||   High God—so much of insufferable woe! Alas! neither by day nor by night
U||   knew I the blessing of rest any more! During the former the creature
U||   left me no moment alone, and in the latter I started hourly from dreams
U||   of unutterable fear to find the hot breath of the thing upon my face,
U||   and its vast weight—an incarnate nightmare that I had no power to shake
U||   off—incumbent eternally upon my heart!
U||   Beneath the pressure of torments such as these, the feeble remnant of
U||   the good within me succumbed. Evil thoughts became my sole
U||   intimates—the darkest and most evil of thoughts. The moodiness of my
U||   usual temper increased to hatred of all things and of all mankind;
U||   while, from the sudden, frequent, and ungovernable outbursts of a fury
U||   to which I now blindly abandoned myself, my uncomplaining wife, alas,
U||   was the most usual and the most patient of sufferers.
U||   One day she accompanied me, upon some household errand, into the cellar
U||   of the old building which our poverty compelled us to inhabit. The cat
U||   followed me down the steep stairs, and, nearly throwing me headlong,
U||   exasperated me to madness. Uplifting an axe, and forgetting, in my
U||   wrath, the childish dread which had hitherto stayed my hand, I aimed a
U||   blow at the animal which, of course, would have proved instantly fatal
U||   had it descended as I wished. But this blow was arrested by the hand of
U||   my wife. Goaded, by the interference, into a rage more than demoniacal,
U||   I withdrew my arm from her grasp and buried the axe in her brain. She
U||   fell dead upon the spot, without a groan.
U||   This hideous murder accomplished, I set myself forthwith, and with
U||   entire deliberation, to the task of concealing the body. I knew that I
U||   could not remove it from the house, either by day or by night, without
U||   the risk of being observed by the neighbors. Many projects entered my
U||   mind. At one period I thought of cutting the corpse into minute
U||   fragments, and destroying them by fire. At another, I resolved to dig a
U||   grave for it in the floor of the cellar. Again, I deliberated about
U||   casting it in the well in the yard—about packing it in a box, as if
U||   merchandise, with the usual arrangements, and so getting a porter to
U||   take it from the house. Finally I hit upon what I considered a far
U||   better expedient than either of these. I determined to wall it up in
U||   the cellar—as the monks of the middle ages are recorded to have walled
U||   up their victims.
U||   For a purpose such as this the cellar was well adapted. Its walls were
U||   loosely constructed, and had lately been plastered throughout with a
U||   rough plaster, which the dampness of the atmosphere had prevented from
U||   hardening. Moreover, in one of the walls was a projection, caused by a
U||   false chimney, or fireplace, that had been filled up, and made to
U||   resemble the red of the cellar. I made no doubt that I could readily
U||   displace the bricks at this point, insert the corpse, and wall the
U||   whole up as before, so that no eye could detect any thing suspicious.
U||   And in this calculation I was not deceived. By means of a crow-bar I
U||   easily dislodged the bricks, and, having carefully deposited the body
U||   against the inner wall, I propped it in that position, while, with
U||   little trouble, I re-laid the whole structure as it originally stood.
U||   Having procured mortar, sand, and hair, with every possible precaution,
U||   I prepared a plaster which could not be distinguished from the old, and
U||   with this I very carefully went over the new brickwork. When I had
U||   finished, I felt satisfied that all was right. The wall did not present
U||   the slightest appearance of having been disturbed. The rubbish on the
U||   floor was picked up with the minutest care. I looked around
U||   triumphantly, and said to myself: “Here at least, then, my labor has
U||   not been in vain.”
U||   My next step was to look for the beast which had been the cause of so
U||   much wretchedness; for I had, at length, firmly resolved to put it to
U||   death. Had I been able to meet with it, at the moment, there could have
U||   been no doubt of its fate; but it appeared that the crafty animal had
U||   been alarmed at the violence of my previous anger, and forebore to
U||   present itself in my present mood. It is impossible to describe, or to
U||   imagine, the deep, the blissful sense of relief which the absence of
U||   the detested creature occasioned in my bosom. It did not make its
U||   appearance during the night; and thus for one night at least, since its
U||   introduction into the house, I soundly and tranquilly slept; aye, slept
U||   even with the burden of murder upon my soul!
U||   The second and the third day passed, and still my tormentor came not.
U||   Once again I breathed as a freeman. The monster, in terror, had fled
U||   the premises forever! I should behold it no more! My happiness was
U||   supreme! The guilt of my dark deed disturbed me but little. Some few
U||   inquiries had been made, but these had been readily answered. Even a
U||   search had been instituted—but of course nothing was to be discovered.
U||   I looked upon my future felicity as secured.
U||   Upon the fourth day of the assassination, a party of the police came,
U||   very unexpectedly, into the house, and proceeded again to make rigorous
U||   investigation of the premises. Secure, however, in the inscrutability
U||   of my place of concealment, I felt no embarrassment whatever. The
U||   officers bade me accompany them in their search. They left no nook or
U||   corner unexplored. At length, for the third or fourth time, they
U||   descended into the cellar. I quivered not in a muscle. My heart beat
U||   calmly as that of one who slumbers in innocence. I walked the cellar
U||   from end to end. I folded my arms upon my bosom, and roamed easily to
U||   and fro. The police were thoroughly satisfied and prepared to depart.
U||   The glee at my heart was too strong to be restrained. I burned to say
U||   if but one word, by way of triumph, and to render doubly sure their
U||   assurance of my guiltlessness.
U||   “Gentlemen,” I said at last, as the party ascended the steps, “I
U||   delight to have allayed your suspicions. I wish you all health, and a
U||   little more courtesy. By the bye, gentlemen, this—this is a very
U||   well-constructed house.” (In the rabid desire to say something easily,
U||   I scarcely knew what I uttered at all.)—“I may say an excellently
U||   well-constructed house. These walls—are you going, gentlemen?—these
U||   walls are solidly put together;” and here, through the mere phrenzy of
U||   bravado, I rapped heavily, with a cane which I held in my hand, upon
U||   that very portion of the brick-work behind which stood the corpse of
U||   the wife of my bosom.
U||   But may God shield and deliver me from the fangs of the Arch-Fiend! No
U||   sooner had the reverberation of my blows sunk into silence, than I was
U||   answered by a voice from within the tomb!—by a cry, at first muffled
U||   and broken, like the sobbing of a child, and then quickly swelling into
U||   one long, loud, and continuous scream, utterly anomalous and inhuman—a
U||   howl—a wailing shriek, half of horror and half of triumph, such as
U||   might have arisen only out of hell, conjointly from the throats of the
U||   damned in their agony and of the demons that exult in the damnation.
U||   Of my own thoughts it is folly to speak. Swooning, I staggered to the
U||   opposite wall. For one instant the party upon the stairs remained
U||   motionless, through extremity of terror and of awe. In the next, a
U||   dozen stout arms were toiling at the wall. It fell bodily. The corpse,
U||   already greatly decayed and clotted with gore, stood erect before the
U||   eyes of the spectators. Upon its head, with red extended mouth and
U||   solitary eye of fire, sat the hideous beast whose craft had seduced me
U||   into murder, and whose informing voice had consigned me to the hangman.
U||   I had walled the monster up within the tomb!
U||THE FALL OF THE HOUSE OF USHER
U||   Son cœur est un luth suspendu;
U||   Sitôt qu’on le touche il résonne..
U||   —De Béranger.
U||   During the whole of a dull, dark, and soundless day in the autumn of
U||   the year, when the clouds hung oppressively low in the heavens, I had
U||   been passing alone, on horseback, through a singularly dreary tract of
U||   country; and at length found myself, as the shades of the evening drew
U||   on, within view of the melancholy House of Usher. I know not how it
U||   was—but, with the first glimpse of the building, a sense of
U||   insufferable gloom pervaded my spirit. I say insufferable; for the
U||   feeling was unrelieved by any of that half-pleasurable, because poetic,
U||   sentiment, with which the mind usually receives even the sternest
U||   natural images of the desolate or terrible. I looked upon the scene
U||   before me—upon the mere house, and the simple landscape features of the
U||   domain—upon the bleak walls—upon the vacant eye-like windows—upon a few
U||   rank sedges—and upon a few white trunks of decayed trees—with an utter
U||   depression of soul which I can compare to no earthly sensation more
U||   properly than to the after-dream of the reveller upon opium—the bitter
U||   lapse into everyday life—the hideous dropping off of the veil. There
U||   was an iciness, a sinking, a sickening of the heart—an unredeemed
U||   dreariness of thought which no goading of the imagination could torture
U||   into aught of the sublime. What was it—I paused to think—what was it
U||   that so unnerved me in the contemplation of the House of Usher? It was
U||   a mystery all insoluble; nor could I grapple with the shadowy fancies
U||   that crowded upon me as I pondered. I was forced to fall back upon the
U||   unsatisfactory conclusion, that while, beyond doubt, there are
U||   combinations of very simple natural objects which have the power of
U||   thus affecting us, still the analysis of this power lies among
U||   considerations beyond our depth. It was possible, I reflected, that a
U||   mere different arrangement of the particulars of the scene, of the
U||   details of the picture, would be sufficient to modify, or perhaps to
U||   annihilate its capacity for sorrowful impression; and, acting upon this
U||   idea, I reined my horse to the precipitous brink of a black and lurid
U||   tarn that lay in unruffled lustre by the dwelling, and gazed down—but
U||   with a shudder even more thrilling than before—upon the remodelled and
U||   inverted images of the gray sedge, and the ghastly tree-stems, and the
U||   vacant and eye-like windows.
U||   Nevertheless, in this mansion of gloom I now proposed to myself a
U||   sojourn of some weeks. Its proprietor, Roderick Usher, had been one of
U||   my boon companions in boyhood; but many years had elapsed since our
U||   last meeting. A letter, however, had lately reached me in a distant
U||   part of the country—a letter from him—which, in its wildly importunate
U||   nature, had admitted of no other than a personal reply. The MS. gave
U||   evidence of nervous agitation. The writer spoke of acute bodily
U||   illness—of a mental disorder which oppressed him—and of an earnest
U||   desire to see me, as his best, and indeed his only personal friend,
U||   with a view of attempting, by the cheerfulness of my society, some
U||   alleviation of his malady. It was the manner in which all this, and
U||   much more, was said—it was the apparent heart that went with his
U||   request—which allowed me no room for hesitation; and I accordingly
U||   obeyed forthwith what I still considered a very singular summons.
U||   Although, as boys, we had been even intimate associates, yet I really
U||   knew little of my friend. His reserve had been always excessive and
U||   habitual. I was aware, however, that his very ancient family had been
U||   noted, time out of mind, for a peculiar sensibility of temperament,
U||   displaying itself, through long ages, in many works of exalted art, and
U||   manifested, of late, in repeated deeds of munificent yet unobtrusive
U||   charity, as well as in a passionate devotion to the intricacies,
U||   perhaps even more than to the orthodox and easily recognisable
U||   beauties, of musical science. I had learned, too, the very remarkable
U||   fact, that the stem of the Usher race, all time-honored as it was, had
U||   put forth, at no period, any enduring branch; in other words, that the
U||   entire family lay in the direct line of descent, and had always, with
U||   very trifling and very temporary variation, so lain. It was this
U||   deficiency, I considered, while running over in thought the perfect
U||   keeping of the character of the premises with the accredited character
U||   of the people, and while speculating upon the possible influence which
U||   the one, in the long lapse of centuries, might have exercised upon the
U||   other—it was this deficiency, perhaps, of collateral issue, and the
U||   consequent undeviating transmission, from sire to son, of the patrimony
U||   with the name, which had, at length, so identified the two as to merge
U||   the original title of the estate in the quaint and equivocal
U||   appellation of the “House of Usher”—an appellation which seemed to
U||   include, in the minds of the peasantry who used it, both the family and
U||   the family mansion.
U||   I have said that the sole effect of my somewhat childish
U||   experiment—that of looking down within the tarn—had been to deepen the
U||   first singular impression. There can be no doubt that the consciousness
U||   of the rapid increase of my superstition—for why should I not so term
U||   it?—served mainly to accelerate the increase itself. Such, I have long
U||   known, is the paradoxical law of all sentiments having terror as a
U||   basis. And it might have been for this reason only, that, when I again
U||   uplifted my eyes to the house itself, from its image in the pool, there
U||   grew in my mind a strange fancy—a fancy so ridiculous, indeed, that I
U||   but mention it to show the vivid force of the sensations which
U||   oppressed me. I had so worked upon my imagination as really to believe
U||   that about the whole mansion and domain there hung an atmosphere
U||   peculiar to themselves and their immediate vicinity—an atmosphere which
U||   had no affinity with the air of heaven, but which had reeked up from
U||   the decayed trees, and the gray wall, and the silent tarn—a pestilent
U||   and mystic vapor, dull, sluggish, faintly discernible, and leaden-hued.
U||   Shaking off from my spirit what must have been a dream, I scanned more
U||   narrowly the real aspect of the building. Its principal feature seemed
U||   to be that of an excessive antiquity. The discoloration of ages had
U||   been great. Minute fungi overspread the whole exterior, hanging in a
U||   fine tangled web-work from the eaves. Yet all this was apart from any
U||   extraordinary dilapidation. No portion of the masonry had fallen; and
U||   there appeared to be a wild inconsistency between its still perfect
U||   adaptation of parts, and the crumbling condition of the individual
U||   stones. In this there was much that reminded me of the specious
U||   totality of old wood-work which has rotted for long years in some
U||   neglected vault, with no disturbance from the breath of the external
U||   air. Beyond this indication of extensive decay, however, the fabric
U||   gave little token of instability. Perhaps the eye of a scrutinizing
U||   observer might have discovered a barely perceptible fissure, which,
U||   extending from the roof of the building in front, made its way down the
U||   wall in a zigzag direction, until it became lost in the sullen waters
U||   of the tarn.
U||   Noticing these things, I rode over a short causeway to the house. A
U||   servant in waiting took my horse, and I entered the Gothic archway of
U||   the hall. A valet, of stealthy step, thence conducted me, in silence,
U||   through many dark and intricate passages in my progress to the studio
U||   of his master. Much that I encountered on the way contributed, I know
U||   not how, to heighten the vague sentiments of which I have already
U||   spoken. While the objects around me—while the carvings of the ceilings,
U||   the sombre tapestries of the walls, the ebon blackness of the floors,
U||   and the phantasmagoric armorial trophies which rattled as I strode,
U||   were but matters to which, or to such as which, I had been accustomed
U||   from my infancy—while I hesitated not to acknowledge how familiar was
U||   all this—I still wondered to find how unfamiliar were the fancies which
U||   ordinary images were stirring up. On one of the staircases, I met the
U||   physician of the family. His countenance, I thought, wore a mingled
U||   expression of low cunning and perplexity. He accosted me with
U||   trepidation and passed on. The valet now threw open a door and ushered
U||   me into the presence of his master.
U||   The room in which I found myself was very large and lofty. The windows
U||   were long, narrow, and pointed, and at so vast a distance from the
U||   black oaken floor as to be altogether inaccessible from within. Feeble
U||   gleams of encrimsoned light made their way through the trellissed
U||   panes, and served to render sufficiently distinct the more prominent
U||   objects around; the eye, however, struggled in vain to reach the
U||   remoter angles of the chamber, or the recesses of the vaulted and
U||   fretted ceiling. Dark draperies hung upon the walls. The general
U||   furniture was profuse, comfortless, antique, and tattered. Many books
U||   and musical instruments lay scattered about, but failed to give any
U||   vitality to the scene. I felt that I breathed an atmosphere of sorrow.
U||   An air of stern, deep, and irredeemable gloom hung over and pervaded
U||   all.
U||   Upon my entrance, Usher arose from a sofa on which he had been lying at
U||   full length, and greeted me with a vivacious warmth which had much in
U||   it, I at first thought, of an overdone cordiality—of the constrained
U||   effort of the ennuyé man of the world. A glance, however, at his
U||   countenance, convinced me of his perfect sincerity. We sat down; and
U||   for some moments, while he spoke not, I gazed upon him with a feeling
U||   half of pity, half of awe. Surely, man had never before so terribly
U||   altered, in so brief a period, as had Roderick Usher! It was with
U||   difficulty that I could bring myself to admit the identity of the wan
U||   being before me with the companion of my early boyhood. Yet the
U||   character of his face had been at all times remarkable. A
U||   cadaverousness of complexion; an eye large, liquid, and luminous beyond
U||   comparison; lips somewhat thin and very pallid, but of a surpassingly
U||   beautiful curve; a nose of a delicate Hebrew model, but with a breadth
U||   of nostril unusual in similar formations; a finely moulded chin,
U||   speaking, in its want of prominence, of a want of moral energy; hair of
U||   a more than web-like softness and tenuity; these features, with an
U||   inordinate expansion above the regions of the temple, made up
U||   altogether a countenance not easily to be forgotten. And now in the
U||   mere exaggeration of the prevailing character of these features, and of
U||   the expression they were wont to convey, lay so much of change that I
U||   doubted to whom I spoke. The now ghastly pallor of the skin, and the
U||   now miraculous lustre of the eye, above all things startled and even
U||   awed me. The silken hair, too, had been suffered to grow all unheeded,
U||   and as, in its wild gossamer texture, it floated rather than fell about
U||   the face, I could not, even with effort, connect its Arabesque
U||   expression with any idea of simple humanity.
U||   In the manner of my friend I was at once struck with an incoherence—an
U||   inconsistency; and I soon found this to arise from a series of feeble
U||   and futile struggles to overcome an habitual trepidancy—an excessive
U||   nervous agitation. For something of this nature I had indeed been
U||   prepared, no less by his letter, than by reminiscences of certain
U||   boyish traits, and by conclusions deduced from his peculiar physical
U||   conformation and temperament. His action was alternately vivacious and
U||   sullen. His voice varied rapidly from a tremulous indecision (when the
U||   animal spirits seemed utterly in abeyance) to that species of energetic
U||   concision—that abrupt, weighty, unhurried, and hollow-sounding
U||   enunciation—that leaden, self-balanced and perfectly modulated guttural
U||   utterance, which may be observed in the lost drunkard, or the
U||   irreclaimable eater of opium, during the periods of his most intense
U||   excitement.
U||   It was thus that he spoke of the object of my visit, of his earnest
U||   desire to see me, and of the solace he expected me to afford him. He
U||   entered, at some length, into what he conceived to be the nature of his
U||   malady. It was, he said, a constitutional and a family evil, and one
U||   for which he despaired to find a remedy—a mere nervous affection, he
U||   immediately added, which would undoubtedly soon pass off. It displayed
U||   itself in a host of unnatural sensations. Some of these, as he detailed
U||   them, interested and bewildered me; although, perhaps, the terms, and
U||   the general manner of the narration had their weight. He suffered much
U||   from a morbid acuteness of the senses; the most insipid food was alone
U||   endurable; he could wear only garments of certain texture; the odors of
U||   all flowers were oppressive; his eyes were tortured by even a faint
U||   light; and there were but peculiar sounds, and these from stringed
U||   instruments, which did not inspire him with horror.
U||   To an anomalous species of terror I found him a bounden slave. “I shall
U||   perish,” said he, “I must perish in this deplorable folly. Thus, thus,
U||   and not otherwise, shall I be lost. I dread the events of the future,
U||   not in themselves, but in their results. I shudder at the thought of
U||   any, even the most trivial, incident, which may operate upon this
U||   intolerable agitation of soul. I have, indeed, no abhorrence of danger,
U||   except in its absolute effect—in terror. In this unnerved—in this
U||   pitiable condition—I feel that the period will sooner or later arrive
U||   when I must abandon life and reason together, in some struggle with the
U||   grim phantasm, FEAR.”
U||   I learned, moreover, at intervals, and through broken and equivocal
U||   hints, another singular feature of his mental condition. He was
U||   enchained by certain superstitious impressions in regard to the
U||   dwelling which he tenanted, and whence, for many years, he had never
U||   ventured forth—in regard to an influence whose supposititious force was
U||   conveyed in terms too shadowy here to be re-stated—an influence which
U||   some peculiarities in the mere form and substance of his family
U||   mansion, had, by dint of long sufferance, he said, obtained over his
U||   spirit—an effect which the physique of the gray walls and turrets, and
U||   of the dim tarn into which they all looked down, had, at length,
U||   brought about upon the morale of his existence.
U||   He admitted, however, although with hesitation, that much of the
U||   peculiar gloom which thus afflicted him could be traced to a more
U||   natural and far more palpable origin—to the severe and long-continued
U||   illness—indeed to the evidently approaching dissolution—of a tenderly
U||   beloved sister—his sole companion for long years—his last and only
U||   relative on earth. “Her decease,” he said, with a bitterness which I
U||   can never forget, “would leave him (him the hopeless and the frail) the
U||   last of the ancient race of the Ushers.” While he spoke, the lady
U||   Madeline (for so was she called) passed slowly through a remote portion
U||   of the apartment, and, without having noticed my presence, disappeared.
U||   I regarded her with an utter astonishment not unmingled with dread—and
U||   yet I found it impossible to account for such feelings. A sensation of
U||   stupor oppressed me, as my eyes followed her retreating steps. When a
U||   door, at length, closed upon her, my glance sought instinctively and
U||   eagerly the countenance of the brother—but he had buried his face in
U||   his hands, and I could only perceive that a far more than ordinary
U||   wanness had overspread the emaciated fingers through which trickled
U||   many passionate tears.
U||   The disease of the lady Madeline had long baffled the skill of her
U||   physicians. A settled apathy, a gradual wasting away of the person, and
U||   frequent although transient affections of a partially cataleptical
U||   character, were the unusual diagnosis. Hitherto she had steadily borne
U||   up against the pressure of her malady, and had not betaken herself
U||   finally to bed; but, on the closing in of the evening of my arrival at
U||   the house, she succumbed (as her brother told me at night with
U||   inexpressible agitation) to the prostrating power of the destroyer; and
U||   I learned that the glimpse I had obtained of her person would thus
U||   probably be the last I should obtain—that the lady, at least while
U||   living, would be seen by me no more.
U||   For several days ensuing, her name was unmentioned by either Usher or
U||   myself; and during this period I was busied in earnest endeavors to
U||   alleviate the melancholy of my friend. We painted and read together; or
U||   I listened, as if in a dream, to the wild improvisations of his
U||   speaking guitar. And thus, as a closer and still closer intimacy
U||   admitted me more unreservedly into the recesses of his spirit, the more
U||   bitterly did I perceive the futility of all attempt at cheering a mind
U||   from which darkness, as if an inherent positive quality, poured forth
U||   upon all objects of the moral and physical universe, in one unceasing
U||   radiation of gloom.
U||   I shall ever bear about me a memory of the many solemn hours I thus
U||   spent alone with the master of the House of Usher. Yet I should fail in
U||   any attempt to convey an idea of the exact character of the studies, or
U||   of the occupations, in which he involved me, or led me the way. An
U||   excited and highly distempered ideality threw a sulphureous lustre over
U||   all. His long improvised dirges will ring forever in my ears. Among
U||   other things, I hold painfully in mind a certain singular perversion
U||   and amplification of the wild air of the last waltz of Von Weber. From
U||   the paintings over which his elaborate fancy brooded, and which grew,
U||   touch by touch, into vaguenesses at which I shuddered the more
U||   thrillingly, because I shuddered knowing not why—from these paintings
U||   (vivid as their images now are before me) I would in vain endeavor to
U||   educe more than a small portion which should lie within the compass of
U||   merely written words. By the utter simplicity, by the nakedness of his
U||   designs, he arrested and overawed attention. If ever mortal painted an
U||   idea, that mortal was Roderick Usher. For me at least—in the
U||   circumstances then surrounding me—there arose out of the pure
U||   abstractions which the hypochondriac contrived to throw upon his
U||   canvass, an intensity of intolerable awe, no shadow of which felt I
U||   ever yet in the contemplation of the certainly glowing yet too concrete
U||   reveries of Fuseli.
U||   One of the phantasmagoric conceptions of my friend, partaking not so
U||   rigidly of the spirit of abstraction, may be shadowed forth, although
U||   feebly, in words. A small picture presented the interior of an
U||   immensely long and rectangular vault or tunnel, with low walls, smooth,
U||   white, and without interruption or device. Certain accessory points of
U||   the design served well to convey the idea that this excavation lay at
U||   an exceeding depth below the surface of the earth. No outlet was
U||   observed in any portion of its vast extent, and no torch, or other
U||   artificial source of light was discernible; yet a flood of intense rays
