U||   Our books—the books which, for years, had formed no small portion of
U||   the mental existence of the invalid—were, as might be supposed, in
U||   strict keeping with this character of phantasm. We pored together over
U||   such works as the Ververt et Chartreuse of Gresset; the Belphegor of
U||   Machiavelli; the Heaven and Hell of Swedenborg; the Subterranean Voyage
U||   of Nicholas Klimm by Holberg; the Chiromancy of Robert Flud, of Jean
U||   D’Indaginé, and of De la Chambre; the Journey into the Blue Distance of
U||   Tieck; and the City of the Sun of Campanella. One favorite volume was a
U||   small octavo edition of the Directorium Inquisitorium, by the Dominican
U||   Eymeric de Gironne; and there were passages in Pomponius Mela, about
U||   the old African Satyrs and OEgipans, over which Usher would sit
U||   dreaming for hours. His chief delight, however, was found in the
U||   perusal of an exceedingly rare and curious book in quarto Gothic—the
U||   manual of a forgotten church—the Vigiliae Mortuorum secundum Chorum
U||   Ecclesiae Maguntinae.
U||   I could not help thinking of the wild ritual of this work, and of its
U||   probable influence upon the hypochondriac, when, one evening, having
U||   informed me abruptly that the lady Madeline was no more, he stated his
U||   intention of preserving her corpse for a fortnight, (previously to its
U||   final interment,) in one of the numerous vaults within the main walls
U||   of the building. The worldly reason, however, assigned for this
U||   singular proceeding, was one which I did not feel at liberty to
U||   dispute. The brother had been led to his resolution (so he told me) by
U||   consideration of the unusual character of the malady of the deceased,
U||   of certain obtrusive and eager inquiries on the part of her medical
U||   men, and of the remote and exposed situation of the burial-ground of
U||   the family. I will not deny that when I called to mind the sinister
U||   countenance of the person whom I met upon the staircase, on the day of
U||   my arrival at the house, I had no desire to oppose what I regarded as
U||   at best but a harmless, and by no means an unnatural, precaution.
U||   At the request of Usher, I personally aided him in the arrangements for
U||   the temporary entombment. The body having been encoffined, we two alone
U||   bore it to its rest. The vault in which we placed it (and which had
U||   been so long unopened that our torches, half smothered in its
U||   oppressive atmosphere, gave us little opportunity for investigation)
U||   was small, damp, and entirely without means of admission for light;
U||   lying, at great depth, immediately beneath that portion of the building
U||   in which was my own sleeping apartment. It had been used, apparently,
U||   in remote feudal times, for the worst purposes of a donjon-keep, and,
U||   in later days, as a place of deposit for powder, or some other highly
U||   combustible substance, as a portion of its floor, and the whole
U||   interior of a long archway through which we reached it, were carefully
U||   sheathed with copper. The door, of massive iron, had been, also,
U||   similarly protected. Its immense weight caused an unusually sharp
U||   grating sound, as it moved upon its hinges.
U||   Having deposited our mournful burden upon tressels within this region
U||   of horror, we partially turned aside the yet unscrewed lid of the
U||   coffin, and looked upon the face of the tenant. A striking similitude
U||   between the brother and sister now first arrested my attention; and
U||   Usher, divining, perhaps, my thoughts, murmured out some few words from
U||   which I learned that the deceased and himself had been twins, and that
U||   sympathies of a scarcely intelligible nature had always existed between
U||   them. Our glances, however, rested not long upon the dead—for we could
U||   not regard her unawed. The disease which had thus entombed the lady in
U||   the maturity of youth, had left, as usual in all maladies of a strictly
U||   cataleptical character, the mockery of a faint blush upon the bosom and
U||   the face, and that suspiciously lingering smile upon the lip which is
U||   so terrible in death. We replaced and screwed down the lid, and, having
U||   secured the door of iron, made our way, with toil, into the scarcely
U||   less gloomy apartments of the upper portion of the house.
U||   And now, some days of bitter grief having elapsed, an observable change
U||   came over the features of the mental disorder of my friend. His
U||   ordinary manner had vanished. His ordinary occupations were neglected
U||   or forgotten. He roamed from chamber to chamber with hurried, unequal,
U||   and objectless step. The pallor of his countenance had assumed, if
U||   possible, a more ghastly hue—but the luminousness of his eye had
U||   utterly gone out. The once occasional huskiness of his tone was heard
U||   no more; and a tremulous quaver, as if of extreme terror, habitually
U||   characterized his utterance. There were times, indeed, when I thought
U||   his unceasingly agitated mind was laboring with some oppressive secret,
U||   to divulge which he struggled for the necessary courage. At times,
U||   again, I was obliged to resolve all into the mere inexplicable vagaries
U||   of madness, for I beheld him gazing upon vacancy for long hours, in an
U||   attitude of the profoundest attention, as if listening to some
U||   imaginary sound. It was no wonder that his condition terrified—that it
U||   infected me. I felt creeping upon me, by slow yet certain degrees, the
U||   wild influences of his own fantastic yet impressive superstitions.
U||   It was, especially, upon retiring to bed late in the night of the
U||   seventh or eighth day after the placing of the lady Madeline within the
U||   donjon, that I experienced the full power of such feelings. Sleep came
U||   not near my couch—while the hours waned and waned away. I struggled to
U||   reason off the nervousness which had dominion over me. I endeavored to
U||   believe that much, if not all of what I felt, was due to the
U||   bewildering influence of the gloomy furniture of the room—of the dark
U||   and tattered draperies, which, tortured into motion by the breath of a
U||   rising tempest, swayed fitfully to and fro upon the walls, and rustled
U||   uneasily about the decorations of the bed. But my efforts were
U||   fruitless. An irrepressible tremor gradually pervaded my frame; and, at
U||   length, there sat upon my very heart an incubus of utterly causeless
U||   alarm. Shaking this off with a gasp and a struggle, I uplifted myself
U||   upon the pillows, and, peering earnestly within the intense darkness of
U||   the chamber, harkened—I know not why, except that an instinctive spirit
U||   prompted me—to certain low and indefinite sounds which came, through
U||   the pauses of the storm, at long intervals, I knew not whence.
U||   Overpowered by an intense sentiment of horror, unaccountable yet
U||   unendurable, I threw on my clothes with haste (for I felt that I should
U||   sleep no more during the night), and endeavored to arouse myself from
U||   the pitiable condition into which I had fallen, by pacing rapidly to
U||   and fro through the apartment.
U||   I had taken but few turns in this manner, when a light step on an
U||   adjoining staircase arrested my attention. I presently recognised it as
U||   that of Usher. In an instant afterward he rapped, with a gentle touch,
U||   at my door, and entered, bearing a lamp. His countenance was, as usual,
U||   cadaverously wan—but, moreover, there was a species of mad hilarity in
U||   his eyes—an evidently restrained hysteria in his whole demeanor. His
U||   air appalled me—but anything was preferable to the solitude which I had
U||   so long endured, and I even welcomed his presence as a relief.
U||   “And you have not seen it?” he said abruptly, after having stared about
U||   him for some moments in silence—“you have not then seen it?—but, stay!
U||   you shall.” Thus speaking, and having carefully shaded his lamp, he
U||   hurried to one of the casements, and threw it freely open to the storm.
U||   The impetuous fury of the entering gust nearly lifted us from our feet.
U||   It was, indeed, a tempestuous yet sternly beautiful night, and one
U||   wildly singular in its terror and its beauty. A whirlwind had
U||   apparently collected its force in our vicinity; for there were frequent
U||   and violent alterations in the direction of the wind; and the exceeding
U||   density of the clouds (which hung so low as to press upon the turrets
U||   of the house) did not prevent our perceiving the life-like velocity
U||   with which they flew careering from all points against each other,
U||   without passing away into the distance. I say that even their exceeding
U||   density did not prevent our perceiving this—yet we had no glimpse of
U||   the moon or stars—nor was there any flashing forth of the lightning.
U||   But the under surfaces of the huge masses of agitated vapor, as well as
U||   all terrestrial objects immediately around us, were glowing in the
U||   unnatural light of a faintly luminous and distinctly visible gaseous
U||   exhalation which hung about and enshrouded the mansion.
U||   “You must not—you shall not behold this!” said I, shudderingly, to
U||   Usher, as I led him, with a gentle violence, from the window to a seat.
U||   “These appearances, which bewilder you, are merely electrical phenomena
U||   not uncommon—or it may be that they have their ghastly origin in the
U||   rank miasma of the tarn. Let us close this casement;—the air is
U||   chilling and dangerous to your frame. Here is one of your favorite
U||   romances. I will read, and you shall listen;—and so we will pass away
U||   this terrible night together.”
U||   The antique volume which I had taken up was the “Mad Trist” of Sir
U||   Launcelot Canning; but I had called it a favorite of Usher’s more in
U||   sad jest than in earnest; for, in truth, there is little in its uncouth
U||   and unimaginative prolixity which could have had interest for the lofty
U||   and spiritual ideality of my friend. It was, however, the only book
U||   immediately at hand; and I indulged a vague hope that the excitement
U||   which now agitated the hypochondriac, might find relief (for the
U||   history of mental disorder is full of similar anomalies) even in the
U||   extremeness of the folly which I should read. Could I have judged,
U||   indeed, by the wild overstrained air of vivacity with which he
U||   harkened, or apparently harkened, to the words of the tale, I might
U||   well have congratulated myself upon the success of my design.
U||   I had arrived at that well-known portion of the story where Ethelred,
U||   the hero of the Trist, having sought in vain for peaceable admission
U||   into the dwelling of the hermit, proceeds to make good an entrance by
U||   force. Here, it will be remembered, the words of the narrative run
U||   thus:
U||   “And Ethelred, who was by nature of a doughty heart, and who was now
U||   mighty withal, on account of the powerfulness of the wine which he had
U||   drunken, waited no longer to hold parley with the hermit, who, in
U||   sooth, was of an obstinate and maliceful turn, but, feeling the rain
U||   upon his shoulders, and fearing the rising of the tempest, uplifted his
U||   mace outright, and, with blows, made quickly room in the plankings of
U||   the door for his gauntleted hand; and now pulling therewith sturdily,
U||   he so cracked, and ripped, and tore all asunder, that the noise of the
U||   dry and hollow-sounding wood alarummed and reverberated throughout the
U||   forest.”
U||   At the termination of this sentence I started, and for a moment,
U||   paused; for it appeared to me (although I at once concluded that my
U||   excited fancy had deceived me)—it appeared to me that, from some very
U||   remote portion of the mansion, there came, indistinctly, to my ears,
U||   what might have been, in its exact similarity of character, the echo
U||   (but a stifled and dull one certainly) of the very cracking and ripping
U||   sound which Sir Launcelot had so particularly described. It was, beyond
U||   doubt, the coincidence alone which had arrested my attention; for, amid
U||   the rattling of the sashes of the casements, and the ordinary
U||   commingled noises of the still increasing storm, the sound, in itself,
U||   had nothing, surely, which should have interested or disturbed me. I
U||   continued the story:
U||   “But the good champion Ethelred, now entering within the door, was sore
U||   enraged and amazed to perceive no signal of the maliceful hermit; but,
U||   in the stead thereof, a dragon of a scaly and prodigious demeanor, and
U||   of a fiery tongue, which sate in guard before a palace of gold, with a
U||   floor of silver; and upon the wall there hung a shield of shining brass
U||   with this legend enwritten—
U||   Who entereth herein, a conqueror hath bin;
U||   Who slayeth the dragon, the shield he shall win;
U||   And Ethelred uplifted his mace, and struck upon the head of the dragon,
U||   which fell before him, and gave up his pesty breath, with a shriek so
U||   horrid and harsh, and withal so piercing, that Ethelred had fain to
U||   close his ears with his hands against the dreadful noise of it, the
U||   like whereof was never before heard.”
U||   Here again I paused abruptly, and now with a feeling of wild
U||   amazement—for there could be no doubt whatever that, in this instance,
U||   I did actually hear (although from what direction it proceeded I found
U||   it impossible to say) a low and apparently distant, but harsh,
U||   protracted, and most unusual screaming or grating sound—the exact
U||   counterpart of what my fancy had already conjured up for the dragon’s
U||   unnatural shriek as described by the romancer.
U||   Oppressed, as I certainly was, upon the occurrence of this second and
U||   most extraordinary coincidence, by a thousand conflicting sensations,
U||   in which wonder and extreme terror were predominant, I still retained
U||   sufficient presence of mind to avoid exciting, by any observation, the
U||   sensitive nervousness of my companion. I was by no means certain that
U||   he had noticed the sounds in question; although, assuredly, a strange
U||   alteration had, during the last few minutes, taken place in his
U||   demeanor. From a position fronting my own, he had gradually brought
U||   round his chair, so as to sit with his face to the door of the chamber;
U||   and thus I could but partially perceive his features, although I saw
U||   that his lips trembled as if he were murmuring inaudibly. His head had
U||   dropped upon his breast—yet I knew that he was not asleep, from the
U||   wide and rigid opening of the eye as I caught a glance of it in
U||   profile. The motion of his body, too, was at variance with this
U||   idea—for he rocked from side to side with a gentle yet constant and
U||   uniform sway. Having rapidly taken notice of all this, I resumed the
U||   narrative of Sir Launcelot, which thus proceeded:
U||   “And now, the champion, having escaped from the terrible fury of the
U||   dragon, bethinking himself of the brazen shield, and of the breaking up
U||   of the enchantment which was upon it, removed the carcass from out of
U||   the way before him, and approached valorously over the silver pavement
U||   of the castle to where the shield was upon the wall; which in sooth
U||   tarried not for his full coming, but fell down at his feet upon the
U||   silver floor, with a mighty great and terrible ringing sound.”
U||   No sooner had these syllables passed my lips, than—as if a shield of
U||   brass had indeed, at the moment, fallen heavily upon a floor of
U||   silver—I became aware of a distinct, hollow, metallic, and clangorous,
U||   yet apparently muffled reverberation. Completely unnerved, I leaped to
U||   my feet; but the measured rocking movement of Usher was undisturbed. I
U||   rushed to the chair in which he sat. His eyes were bent fixedly before
U||   him, and throughout his whole countenance there reigned a stony
U||   rigidity. But, as I placed my hand upon his shoulder, there came a
U||   strong shudder over his whole person; a sickly smile quivered about his
U||   lips; and I saw that he spoke in a low, hurried, and gibbering murmur,
U||   as if unconscious of my presence. Bending closely over him, I at length
U||   drank in the hideous import of his words.
U||   “Not hear it?—yes, I hear it, and have heard it. Long—long—long—many
U||   minutes, many hours, many days, have I heard it—yet I dared not—oh,
U||   pity me, miserable wretch that I am!—I dared not—I dared not speak! We
U||   have put her living in the tomb! Said I not that my senses were acute?
U||   I now tell you that I heard her first feeble movements in the hollow
U||   coffin. I heard them—many, many days ago—yet I dared not—I dared not
U||   speak! And now—to-night—Ethelred—ha! ha!—the breaking of the hermit’s
U||   door, and the death-cry of the dragon, and the clangor of the
U||   shield!—say, rather, the rending of her coffin, and the grating of the
U||   iron hinges of her prison, and her struggles within the coppered
U||   archway of the vault! Oh whither shall I fly? Will she not be here
U||   anon? Is she not hurrying to upbraid me for my haste? Have I not heard
U||   her footstep on the stair? Do I not distinguish that heavy and horrible
U||   beating of her heart? Madman!”—here he sprang furiously to his feet,
U||   and shrieked out his syllables, as if in the effort he were giving up
U||   his soul—“Madman! I tell you that she now stands without the door!”
U||   As if in the superhuman energy of his utterance there had been found
U||   the potency of a spell—the huge antique pannels to which the speaker
U||   pointed, threw slowly back, upon the instant, their ponderous and ebony
U||   jaws. It was the work of the rushing gust—but then without those doors
U||   there did stand the lofty and enshrouded figure of the lady Madeline of
U||   Usher. There was blood upon her white robes, and the evidence of some
U||   bitter struggle upon every portion of her emaciated frame. For a moment
U||   she remained trembling and reeling to and fro upon the threshold—then,
U||   with a low moaning cry, fell heavily inward upon the person of her
U||   brother, and in her violent and now final death-agonies, bore him to
U||   the floor a corpse, and a victim to the terrors he had anticipated.
U||   From that chamber, and from that mansion, I fled aghast. The storm was
U||   still abroad in all its wrath as I found myself crossing the old
U||   causeway. Suddenly there shot along the path a wild light, and I turned
U||   to see whence a gleam so unusual could have issued; for the vast house
U||   and its shadows were alone behind me. The radiance was that of the
U||   full, setting, and blood-red moon, which now shone vividly through that
U||   once barely-discernible fissure, of which I have before spoken as
U||   extending from the roof of the building, in a zigzag direction, to the
U||   base. While I gazed, this fissure rapidly widened—there came a fierce
U||   breath of the whirlwind—the entire orb of the satellite burst at once
U||   upon my sight—my brain reeled as I saw the mighty walls rushing
U||   asunder—there was a long tumultuous shouting sound like the voice of a
U||   thousand waters—and the deep and dank tarn at my feet closed sullenly
U||   and silently over the fragments of the “House of Usher.”
U||SILENCE—A FABLE
U||   “The mountain pinnacles slumber; valleys, crags and caves are silent.”
U||   “Listen to me,” said the Demon as he placed his hand upon my head. “The
U||   region of which I speak is a dreary region in Libya, by the borders of
U||   the river Zaire. And there is no quiet there, nor silence.
U||   “The waters of the river have a saffron and sickly hue; and they flow
U||   not onwards to the sea, but palpitate forever and forever beneath the
U||   red eye of the sun with a tumultuous and convulsive motion. For many
U||   miles on either side of the river’s oozy bed is a pale desert of
U||   gigantic water-lilies. They sigh one unto the other in that solitude,
U||   and stretch towards the heaven their long and ghastly necks, and nod to
U||   and fro their everlasting heads. And there is an indistinct murmur
U||   which cometh out from among them like the rushing of subterrene water.
U||   And they sigh one unto the other.
U||   “But there is a boundary to their realm—the boundary of the dark,
U||   horrible, lofty forest. There, like the waves about the Hebrides, the
U||   low underwood is agitated continually. But there is no wind throughout
U||   the heaven. And the tall primeval trees rock eternally hither and
U||   thither with a crashing and mighty sound. And from their high summits,
U||   one by one, drop everlasting dews. And at the roots strange poisonous
U||   flowers lie writhing in perturbed slumber. And overhead, with a
U||   rustling and loud noise, the gray clouds rush westwardly forever, until
U||   they roll, a cataract, over the fiery wall of the horizon. But there is
U||   no wind throughout the heaven. And by the shores of the river Zaire
U||   there is neither quiet nor silence.
U||   “It was night, and the rain fell; and falling, it was rain, but, having
U||   fallen, it was blood. And I stood in the morass among the tall and the
U||   rain fell upon my head—and the lilies sighed one unto the other in the
U||   solemnity of their desolation.
U||   “And, all at once, the moon arose through the thin ghastly mist, and
U||   was crimson in color. And mine eyes fell upon a huge gray rock which
U||   stood by the shore of the river, and was lighted by the light of the
U||   moon. And the rock was gray, and ghastly, and tall,—and the rock was
U||   gray. Upon its front were characters engraven in the stone; and I
U||   walked through the morass of water-lilies, until I came close unto the
U||   shore, that I might read the characters upon the stone. But I could not
U||   decypher them. And I was going back into the morass, when the moon
