U||   Now there are fine tales in the volumes of the Magi—in the iron-bound,
U||   melancholy volumes of the Magi. Therein, I say, are glorious histories
U||   of the Heaven, and of the Earth, and of the mighty sea—and of the Genii
U||   that over-ruled the sea, and the earth, and the lofty heaven. There was
U||   much lore too in the sayings which were said by the Sybils; and holy,
U||   holy things were heard of old by the dim leaves that trembled around
U||   Dodona—but, as Allah liveth, that fable which the Demon told me as he
U||   sat by my side in the shadow of the tomb, I hold to be the most
U||   wonderful of all! And as the Demon made an end of his story, he fell
U||   back within the cavity of the tomb and laughed. And I could not laugh
U||   with the Demon, and he cursed me because I could not laugh. And the
U||   lynx which dwelleth forever in the tomb, came out therefrom, and lay
U||   down at the feet of the Demon, and looked at him steadily in the face.
U||THE MASQUE OF THE RED DEATH.
U||   The “Red Death” had long devastated the country. No pestilence had ever
U||   been so fatal, or so hideous. Blood was its Avatar and its seal—the
U||   redness and the horror of blood. There were sharp pains, and sudden
U||   dizziness, and then profuse bleeding at the pores, with dissolution.
U||   The scarlet stains upon the body and especially upon the face of the
U||   victim, were the pest ban which shut him out from the aid and from the
U||   sympathy of his fellow-men. And the whole seizure, progress and
U||   termination of the disease, were the incidents of half an hour.
U||   But the Prince Prospero was happy and dauntless and sagacious. When his
U||   dominions were half depopulated, he summoned to his presence a thousand
U||   hale and light-hearted friends from among the knights and dames of his
U||   court, and with these retired to the deep seclusion of one of his
U||   castellated abbeys. This was an extensive and magnificent structure,
U||   the creation of the prince’s own eccentric yet august taste. A strong
U||   and lofty wall girdled it in. This wall had gates of iron. The
U||   courtiers, having entered, brought furnaces and massy hammers and
U||   welded the bolts. They resolved to leave means neither of ingress or
U||   egress to the sudden impulses of despair or of frenzy from within. The
U||   abbey was amply provisioned. With such precautions the courtiers might
U||   bid defiance to contagion. The external world could take care of
U||   itself. In the meantime it was folly to grieve, or to think. The prince
U||   had provided all the appliances of pleasure. There were buffoons, there
U||   were improvisatori, there were ballet-dancers, there were musicians,
U||   there was Beauty, there was wine. All these and security were within.
U||   Without was the “Red Death.”
U||   It was toward the close of the fifth or sixth month of his seclusion,
U||   and while the pestilence raged most furiously abroad, that the Prince
U||   Prospero entertained his thousand friends at a masked ball of the most
U||   unusual magnificence.
U||   It was a voluptuous scene, that masquerade. But first let me tell of
U||   the rooms in which it was held. There were seven—an imperial suite. In
U||   many palaces, however, such suites form a long and straight vista,
U||   while the folding doors slide back nearly to the walls on either hand,
U||   so that the view of the whole extent is scarcely impeded. Here the case
U||   was very different; as might have been expected from the duke’s love of
U||   the bizarre. The apartments were so irregularly disposed that the
U||   vision embraced but little more than one at a time. There was a sharp
U||   turn at every twenty or thirty yards, and at each turn a novel effect.
U||   To the right and left, in the middle of each wall, a tall and narrow
U||   Gothic window looked out upon a closed corridor which pursued the
U||   windings of the suite. These windows were of stained glass whose color
U||   varied in accordance with the prevailing hue of the decorations of the
U||   chamber into which it opened. That at the eastern extremity was hung,
U||   for example, in blue—and vividly blue were its windows. The second
U||   chamber was purple in its ornaments and tapestries, and here the panes
U||   were purple. The third was green throughout, and so were the casements.
U||   The fourth was furnished and lighted with orange—the fifth with
U||   white—the sixth with violet. The seventh apartment was closely shrouded
U||   in black velvet tapestries that hung all over the ceiling and down the
U||   walls, falling in heavy folds upon a carpet of the same material and
U||   hue. But in this chamber only, the color of the windows failed to
U||   correspond with the decorations. The panes here were scarlet—a deep
U||   blood color. Now in no one of the seven apartments was there any lamp
U||   or candelabrum, amid the profusion of golden ornaments that lay
U||   scattered to and fro or depended from the roof. There was no light of
U||   any kind emanating from lamp or candle within the suite of chambers.
U||   But in the corridors that followed the suite, there stood, opposite to
U||   each window, a heavy tripod, bearing a brazier of fire that projected
U||   its rays through the tinted glass and so glaringly illumined the room.
U||   And thus were produced a multitude of gaudy and fantastic appearances.
U||   But in the western or black chamber the effect of the fire-light that
U||   streamed upon the dark hangings through the blood-tinted panes, was
U||   ghastly in the extreme, and produced so wild a look upon the
U||   countenances of those who entered, that there were few of the company
U||   bold enough to set foot within its precincts at all.
U||   It was in this apartment, also, that there stood against the western
U||   wall, a gigantic clock of ebony. Its pendulum swung to and fro with a
U||   dull, heavy, monotonous clang; and when the minute-hand made the
U||   circuit of the face, and the hour was to be stricken, there came from
U||   the brazen lungs of the clock a sound which was clear and loud and deep
U||   and exceedingly musical, but of so peculiar a note and emphasis that,
U||   at each lapse of an hour, the musicians of the orchestra were
U||   constrained to pause, momentarily, in their performance, to hearken to
U||   the sound; and thus the waltzers perforce ceased their evolutions; and
U||   there was a brief disconcert of the whole gay company; and, while the
U||   chimes of the clock yet rang, it was observed that the giddiest grew
U||   pale, and the more aged and sedate passed their hands over their brows
U||   as if in confused reverie or meditation. But when the echoes had fully
U||   ceased, a light laughter at once pervaded the assembly; the musicians
U||   looked at each other and smiled as if at their own nervousness and
U||   folly, and made whispering vows, each to the other, that the next
U||   chiming of the clock should produce in them no similar emotion; and
U||   then, after the lapse of sixty minutes (which embrace three thousand
U||   and six hundred seconds of the Time that flies), there came yet another
U||   chiming of the clock, and then were the same disconcert and
U||   tremulousness and meditation as before.
U||   But, in spite of these things, it was a gay and magnificent revel. The
U||   tastes of the duke were peculiar. He had a fine eye for colors and
U||   effects. He disregarded the decora of mere fashion. His plans were bold
U||   and fiery, and his conceptions glowed with barbaric lustre. There are
U||   some who would have thought him mad. His followers felt that he was
U||   not. It was necessary to hear and see and touch him to be sure that he
U||   was not.
U||   He had directed, in great part, the moveable embellishments of the
U||   seven chambers, upon occasion of this great fête; and it was his own
U||   guiding taste which had given character to the masqueraders. Be sure
U||   they were grotesque. There were much glare and glitter and piquancy and
U||   phantasm—much of what has been since seen in “Hernani.” There were
U||   arabesque figures with unsuited limbs and appointments. There were
U||   delirious fancies such as the madman fashions. There was much of the
U||   beautiful, much of the wanton, much of the bizarre, something of the
U||   terrible, and not a little of that which might have excited disgust. To
U||   and fro in the seven chambers there stalked, in fact, a multitude of
U||   dreams. And these—the dreams—writhed in and about, taking hue from the
U||   rooms, and causing the wild music of the orchestra to seem as the echo
U||   of their steps. And, anon, there strikes the ebony clock which stands
U||   in the hall of the velvet. And then, for a moment, all is still, and
U||   all is silent save the voice of the clock. The dreams are stiff-frozen
U||   as they stand. But the echoes of the chime die away—they have endured
U||   but an instant—and a light, half-subdued laughter floats after them as
U||   they depart. And now again the music swells, and the dreams live, and
U||   writhe to and fro more merrily than ever, taking hue from the
U||   many-tinted windows through which stream the rays from the tripods. But
U||   to the chamber which lies most westwardly of the seven, there are now
U||   none of the maskers who venture; for the night is waning away; and
U||   there flows a ruddier light through the blood-colored panes; and the
U||   blackness of the sable drapery appals; and to him whose foot falls upon
U||   the sable carpet, there comes from the near clock of ebony a muffled
U||   peal more solemnly emphatic than any which reaches their ears who
U||   indulge in the more remote gaieties of the other apartments.
U||   But these other apartments were densely crowded, and in them beat
U||   feverishly the heart of life. And the revel went whirlingly on, until
U||   at length there commenced the sounding of midnight upon the clock. And
U||   then the music ceased, as I have told; and the evolutions of the
U||   waltzers were quieted; and there was an uneasy cessation of all things
U||   as before. But now there were twelve strokes to be sounded by the bell
U||   of the clock; and thus it happened, perhaps, that more of thought
U||   crept, with more of time, into the meditations of the thoughtful among
U||   those who revelled. And thus, too, it happened, perhaps, that before
U||   the last echoes of the last chime had utterly sunk into silence, there
U||   were many individuals in the crowd who had found leisure to become
U||   aware of the presence of a masked figure which had arrested the
U||   attention of no single individual before. And the rumor of this new
U||   presence having spread itself whisperingly around, there arose at
U||   length from the whole company a buzz, or murmur, expressive of
U||   disapprobation and surprise—then, finally, of terror, of horror, and of
U||   disgust.
U||   In an assembly of phantasms such as I have painted, it may well be
U||   supposed that no ordinary appearance could have excited such sensation.
U||   In truth the masquerade license of the night was nearly unlimited; but
U||   the figure in question had out-Heroded Herod, and gone beyond the
U||   bounds of even the prince’s indefinite decorum. There are chords in the
U||   hearts of the most reckless which cannot be touched without emotion.
U||   Even with the utterly lost, to whom life and death are equally jests,
U||   there are matters of which no jest can be made. The whole company,
U||   indeed, seemed now deeply to feel that in the costume and bearing of
U||   the stranger neither wit nor propriety existed. The figure was tall and
U||   gaunt, and shrouded from head to foot in the habiliments of the grave.
U||   The mask which concealed the visage was made so nearly to resemble the
U||   countenance of a stiffened corpse that the closest scrutiny must have
U||   had difficulty in detecting the cheat. And yet all this might have been
U||   endured, if not approved, by the mad revellers around. But the mummer
U||   had gone so far as to assume the type of the Red Death. His vesture was
U||   dabbled in blood—and his broad brow, with all the features of the face,
U||   was besprinkled with the scarlet horror.
U||   When the eyes of Prince Prospero fell upon this spectral image (which
U||   with a slow and solemn movement, as if more fully to sustain its role,
U||   stalked to and fro among the waltzers) he was seen to be convulsed, in
U||   the first moment with a strong shudder either of terror or distaste;
U||   but, in the next, his brow reddened with rage.
U||   “Who dares?” he demanded hoarsely of the courtiers who stood near
U||   him—“who dares insult us with this blasphemous mockery? Seize him and
U||   unmask him—that we may know whom we have to hang at sunrise, from the
U||   battlements!”
U||   It was in the eastern or blue chamber in which stood the Prince
U||   Prospero as he uttered these words. They rang throughout the seven
U||   rooms loudly and clearly—for the prince was a bold and robust man, and
U||   the music had become hushed at the waving of his hand.
U||   It was in the blue room where stood the prince, with a group of pale
U||   courtiers by his side. At first, as he spoke, there was a slight
U||   rushing movement of this group in the direction of the intruder, who at
U||   the moment was also near at hand, and now, with deliberate and stately
U||   step, made closer approach to the speaker. But from a certain nameless
U||   awe with which the mad assumptions of the mummer had inspired the whole
U||   party, there were found none who put forth hand to seize him; so that,
U||   unimpeded, he passed within a yard of the prince’s person; and, while
U||   the vast assembly, as if with one impulse, shrank from the centres of
U||   the rooms to the walls, he made his way uninterruptedly, but with the
U||   same solemn and measured step which had distinguished him from the
U||   first, through the blue chamber to the purple—through the purple to the
U||   green—through the green to the orange—through this again to the
U||   white—and even thence to the violet, ere a decided movement had been
U||   made to arrest him. It was then, however, that the Prince Prospero,
U||   maddening with rage and the shame of his own momentary cowardice,
U||   rushed hurriedly through the six chambers, while none followed him on
U||   account of a deadly terror that had seized upon all. He bore aloft a
U||   drawn dagger, and had approached, in rapid impetuosity, to within three
U||   or four feet of the retreating figure, when the latter, having attained
U||   the extremity of the velvet apartment, turned suddenly and confronted
U||   his pursuer. There was a sharp cry—and the dagger dropped gleaming upon
U||   the sable carpet, upon which, instantly afterwards, fell prostrate in
U||   death the Prince Prospero. Then, summoning the wild courage of despair,
U||   a throng of the revellers at once threw themselves into the black
U||   apartment, and, seizing the mummer, whose tall figure stood erect and
U||   motionless within the shadow of the ebony clock, gasped in unutterable
U||   horror at finding the grave-cerements and corpse-like mask which they
U||   handled with so violent a rudeness, untenanted by any tangible form.
U||   And now was acknowledged the presence of the Red Death. He had come
U||   like a thief in the night. And one by one dropped the revellers in the
U||   blood-bedewed halls of their revel, and died each in the despairing
U||   posture of his fall. And the life of the ebony clock went out with that
U||   of the last of the gay. And the flames of the tripods expired. And
U||   Darkness and Decay and the Red Death held illimitable dominion over
U||   all.
U||THE CASK OF AMONTILLADO.
U||   The thousand injuries of Fortunato I had borne as I best could; but
U||   when he ventured upon insult, I vowed revenge. You, who so well know
U||   the nature of my soul, will not suppose, however, that I gave utterance
U||   to a threat. At length I would be avenged; this was a point
U||   definitively settled—but the very definitiveness with which it was
U||   resolved, precluded the idea of risk. I must not only punish, but
U||   punish with impunity. A wrong is unredressed when retribution overtakes
U||   its redresser. It is equally unredressed when the avenger fails to make
U||   himself felt as such to him who has done the wrong.
U||   It must be understood, that neither by word nor deed had I given
U||   Fortunato cause to doubt my good will. I continued, as was my wont, to
U||   smile in his face, and he did not perceive that my smile now was at the
U||   thought of his immolation.
U||   He had a weak point—this Fortunato—although in other regards he was a
U||   man to be respected and even feared. He prided himself on his
U||   connoisseurship in wine. Few Italians have the true virtuoso spirit.
U||   For the most part their enthusiasm is adopted to suit the time and
U||   opportunity—to practise imposture upon the British and Austrian
U||   millionaires. In painting and gemmary, Fortunato, like his countrymen,
U||   was a quack—but in the matter of old wines he was sincere. In this
U||   respect I did not differ from him materially: I was skilful in the
U||   Italian vintages myself, and bought largely whenever I could.
U||   It was about dusk, one evening during the supreme madness of the
U||   carnival season, that I encountered my friend. He accosted me with
U||   excessive warmth, for he had been drinking much. The man wore motley.
U||   He had on a tight-fitting parti-striped dress, and his head was
U||   surmounted by the conical cap and bells. I was so pleased to see him,
U||   that I thought I should never have done wringing his hand.
U||   I said to him: “My dear Fortunato, you are luckily met. How remarkably
U||   well you are looking to-day! But I have received a pipe of what passes
U||   for Amontillado, and I have my doubts.”
U||   “How?” said he. “Amontillado? A pipe? Impossible! And in the middle of
U||   the carnival!”
U||   “I have my doubts,” I replied; “and I was silly enough to pay the full
U||   Amontillado price without consulting you in the matter. You were not to
U||   be found, and I was fearful of losing a bargain.”
U||   “Amontillado!”
U||   “I have my doubts.”
U||   “Amontillado!”
U||   “And I must satisfy them.”
U||   “Amontillado!”
U||   “As you are engaged, I am on my way to Luchesi. If any one has a
U||   critical turn, it is he. He will tell me—”
U||   “Luchesi cannot tell Amontillado from Sherry.”
U||   “And yet some fools will have it that his taste is a match for your
U||   own.”
U||   “Come, let us go.”
U||   “Whither?”
U||   “To your vaults.”
U||   “My friend, no; I will not impose upon your good nature. I perceive you
U||   have an engagement. Luchesi—”
U||   “I have no engagement;—come.”
U||   “My friend, no. It is not the engagement, but the severe cold with
U||   which I perceive you are afflicted. The vaults are insufferably damp.
U||   They are encrusted with nitre.”
U||   “Let us go, nevertheless. The cold is merely nothing. Amontillado! You
U||   have been imposed upon. And as for Luchesi, he cannot distinguish
U||   Sherry from Amontillado.”
U||   Thus speaking, Fortunato possessed himself of my arm. Putting on a mask
U||   of black silk, and drawing a roquelaire closely about my person, I
U||   suffered him to hurry me to my palazzo.
U||   There were no attendants at home; they had absconded to make merry in
U||   honor of the time. I had told them that I should not return until the
U||   morning, and had given them explicit orders not to stir from the house.
U||   These orders were sufficient, I well knew, to insure their immediate
U||   disappearance, one and all, as soon as my back was turned.
U||   I took from their sconces two flambeaux, and giving one to Fortunato,
U||   bowed him through several suites of rooms to the archway that led into
U||   the vaults. I passed down a long and winding staircase, requesting him
U||   to be cautious as he followed. We came at length to the foot of the
U||   descent, and stood together on the damp ground of the catacombs of the
U||   Montresors.
U||   The gait of my friend was unsteady, and the bells upon his cap jingled
U||   as he strode.
U||   “The pipe,” said he.
U||   “It is farther on,” said I; “but observe the white web-work which
U||   gleams from these cavern walls.”
U||   He turned towards me, and looked into my eyes with two filmy orbs that
U||   distilled the rheum of intoxication.
U||   “Nitre?” he asked, at length.
U||   “Nitre,” I replied. “How long have you had that cough?”
U||   “Ugh! ugh! ugh!—ugh! ugh! ugh!—ugh! ugh! ugh!—ugh! ugh! ugh!—ugh! ugh!
U||   ugh!”
U||   My poor friend found it impossible to reply for many minutes.
U||   “It is nothing,” he said, at last.
U||   “Come,” I said, with decision, “we will go back; your health is
U||   precious. You are rich, respected, admired, beloved; you are happy, as
U||   once I was. You are a man to be missed. For me it is no matter. We will
U||   go back; you will be ill, and I cannot be responsible. Besides, there
U||   is Luchesi—”
U||   “Enough,” he said; “the cough is a mere nothing; it will not kill me. I
U||   shall not die of a cough.”
U||   “True—true,” I replied; “and, indeed, I had no intention of alarming
U||   you unnecessarily—but you should use all proper caution. A draught of
U||   this Medoc will defend us from the damps.”
U||   Here I knocked off the neck of a bottle which I drew from a long row of
U||   its fellows that lay upon the mould.
U||   “Drink,” I said, presenting him the wine.
U||   He raised it to his lips with a leer. He paused and nodded to me
U||   familiarly, while his bells jingled.
U||   “I drink,” he said, “to the buried that repose around us.”
U||   “And I to your long life.”
U||   He again took my arm, and we proceeded.
U||   “These vaults,” he said, “are extensive.”
U||   “The Montresors,” I replied, “were a great and numerous family.”
U||   “I forget your arms.”
U||   “A huge human foot d’or, in a field azure; the foot crushes a serpent
U||   rampant whose fangs are imbedded in the heel.”
U||   “And the motto?”
U||   “Nemo me impune lacessit.”
U||   “Good!” he said.
U||   The wine sparkled in his eyes and the bells jingled. My own fancy grew
U||   warm with the Medoc. We had passed through walls of piled bones, with
U||   casks and puncheons intermingling, into the inmost recesses of the
U||   catacombs. I paused again, and this time I made bold to seize Fortunato
U||   by an arm above the elbow.
U||   “The nitre!” I said: “see, it increases. It hangs like moss upon the
U||   vaults. We are below the river’s bed. The drops of moisture trickle
U||   among the bones. Come, we will go back ere it is too late. Your cough—”
U||   “It is nothing,” he said; “let us go on. But first, another draught of
U||   the Medoc.”
U||   I broke and reached him a flagon of De Grâve. He emptied it at a
U||   breath. His eyes flashed with a fierce light. He laughed and threw the
U||   bottle upwards with a gesticulation I did not understand.
U||   I looked at him in surprise. He repeated the movement—a grotesque one.
U||   “You do not comprehend?” he said.
U||   “Not I,” I replied.
U||   “Then you are not of the brotherhood.”
U||   “How?”
U||   “You are not of the masons.”
U||   “Yes, yes,” I said, “yes, yes.”
U||   “You? Impossible! A mason?”
U||   “A mason,” I replied.
U||   “A sign,” he said.
U||   “It is this,” I answered, producing a trowel from beneath the folds of
U||   my roquelaire.
U||   “You jest,” he exclaimed, recoiling a few paces. “But let us proceed to
U||   the Amontillado.”
U||   “Be it so,” I said, replacing the tool beneath the cloak, and again
U||   offering him my arm. He leaned upon it heavily. We continued our route
U||   in search of the Amontillado. We passed through a range of low arches,
U||   descended, passed on, and descending again, arrived at a deep crypt, in
U||   which the foulness of the air caused our flambeaux rather to glow than
U||   flame.
U||   At the most remote end of the crypt there appeared another less
U||   spacious. Its walls had been lined with human remains, piled to the
U||   vault overhead, in the fashion of the great catacombs of Paris. Three
U||   sides of this interior crypt were still ornamented in this manner. From
U||   the fourth the bones had been thrown down, and lay promiscuously upon
U||   the earth, forming at one point a mound of some size. Within the wall
U||   thus exposed by the displacing of the bones, we perceived a still
U||   interior recess, in depth about four feet, in width three, in height
U||   six or seven. It seemed to have been constructed for no especial use in
U||   itself, but formed merely the interval between two of the colossal
U||   supports of the roof of the catacombs, and was backed by one of their
U||   circumscribing walls of solid granite.
U||   It was in vain that Fortunato, uplifting his dull torch, endeavored to
U||   pry into the depths of the recess. Its termination the feeble light did
U||   not enable us to see.
U||   “Proceed,” I said; “herein is the Amontillado. As for Luchesi—”
U||   “He is an ignoramus,” interrupted my friend, as he stepped unsteadily
U||   forward, while I followed immediately at his heels. In an instant he
U||   had reached the extremity of the niche, and finding his progress
U||   arrested by the rock, stood stupidly bewildered. A moment more and I
U||   had fettered him to the granite. In its surface were two iron staples,
U||   distant from each other about two feet, horizontally. From one of these
U||   depended a short chain, from the other a padlock. Throwing the links
U||   about his waist, it was but the work of a few seconds to secure it. He
U||   was too much astounded to resist. Withdrawing the key I stepped back
U||   from the recess.
U||   “Pass your hand,” I said, “over the wall; you cannot help feeling the
U||   nitre. Indeed it is very damp. Once more let me implore you to return.
U||   No? Then I must positively leave you. But I must first render you all
U||   the little attentions in my power.”
U||   “The Amontillado!” ejaculated my friend, not yet recovered from his
U||   astonishment.
U||   “True,” I replied; “the Amontillado.”
U||   As I said these words I busied myself among the pile of bones of which
U||   I have before spoken. Throwing them aside, I soon uncovered a quantity
U||   of building stone and mortar. With these materials and with the aid of
U||   my trowel, I began vigorously to wall up the entrance of the niche.
U||   I had scarcely laid the first tier of my masonry when I discovered that
U||   the intoxication of Fortunato had in a great measure worn off. The
U||   earliest indication I had of this was a low moaning cry from the depth
U||   of the recess. It was not the cry of a drunken man. There was then a
U||   long and obstinate silence. I laid the second tier, and the third, and
U||   the fourth; and then I heard the furious vibrations of the chain. The
U||   noise lasted for several minutes, during which, that I might hearken to
U||   it with the more satisfaction, I ceased my labors and sat down upon the
U||   bones. When at last the clanking subsided, I resumed the trowel, and
U||   finished without interruption the fifth, the sixth, and the seventh
U||   tier. The wall was now nearly upon a level with my breast. I again
U||   paused, and holding the flambeaux over the mason-work, threw a few
U||   feeble rays upon the figure within.
U||   A succession of loud and shrill screams, bursting suddenly from the
U||   throat of the chained form, seemed to thrust me violently back. For a
U||   brief moment I hesitated—I trembled. Unsheathing my rapier, I began to
U||   grope with it about the recess; but the thought of an instant reassured
U||   me. I placed my hand upon the solid fabric of the catacombs, and felt
U||   satisfied. I reapproached the wall. I replied to the yells of him who
U||   clamored. I re-echoed—I aided—I surpassed them in volume and in
U||   strength. I did this, and the clamorer grew still.
U||   It was now midnight, and my task was drawing to a close. I had
U||   completed the eighth, the ninth, and the tenth tier. I had finished a
U||   portion of the last and the eleventh; there remained but a single stone
U||   to be fitted and plastered in. I struggled with its weight; I placed it
U||   partially in its destined position. But now there came from out the
U||   niche a low laugh that erected the hairs upon my head. It was succeeded
U||   by a sad voice, which I had difficulty in recognising as that of the
U||   noble Fortunato. The voice said—
U||   “Ha! ha! ha!—he! he!—a very good joke indeed—an excellent jest. We will
U||   have many a rich laugh about it at the palazzo—he! he! he!—over our
U||   wine—he! he! he!”
U||   “The Amontillado!” I said.
U||   “He! he! he!—he! he! he!—yes, the Amontillado. But is it not getting
U||   late? Will not they be awaiting us at the palazzo, the Lady Fortunato
U||   and the rest? Let us be gone.”
U||   “Yes,” I said, “let us be gone.”
U||   “For the love of God, Montressor!”
U||   “Yes,” I said, “for the love of God!”
U||   But to these words I hearkened in vain for a reply. I grew impatient. I
U||   called aloud—
U||   “Fortunato!”
U||   No answer. I called again—
U||   “Fortunato!”
U||   No answer still. I thrust a torch through the remaining aperture and
U||   let it fall within. There came forth in return only a jingling of the
U||   bells. My heart grew sick—on account of the dampness of the catacombs.
U||   I hastened to make an end of my labor. I forced the last stone into its
U||   position; I plastered it up. Against the new masonry I re-erected the
U||   old rampart of bones. For the half of a century no mortal has disturbed
U||   them. In pace requiescat!
U||THE IMP OF THE PERVERSE
U||   In the consideration of the faculties and impulses—of the prima mobilia
U||   of the human soul, the phrenologists have failed to make room for a
U||   propensity which, although obviously existing as a radical, primitive,
U||   irreducible sentiment, has been equally overlooked by all the moralists
U||   who have preceded them. In the pure arrogance of the reason, we have
U||   all overlooked it. We have suffered its existence to escape our senses,
U||   solely through want of belief—of faith;—whether it be faith in
U||   Revelation, or faith in the Kabbala. The idea of it has never occurred
U||   to us, simply because of its supererogation. We saw no need of the
U||   impulse—for the propensity. We could not perceive its necessity. We
U||   could not understand, that is to say, we could not have understood, had
U||   the notion of this primum mobile ever obtruded itself;—we could not
U||   have understood in what manner it might be made to further the objects
U||   of humanity, either temporal or eternal. It cannot be denied that
U||   phrenology and, in great measure, all metaphysicianism have been
U||   concocted a priori. The intellectual or logical man, rather than the
U||   understanding or observant man, set himself to imagine designs—to
U||   dictate purposes to God. Having thus fathomed, to his satisfaction, the
U||   intentions of Jehovah, out of these intentions he built his innumerable
U||   systems of mind. In the matter of phrenology, for example, we first
U||   determined, naturally enough, that it was the design of the Deity that
U||   man should eat. We then assigned to man an organ of alimentiveness, and
U||   this organ is the scourge with which the Deity compels man, will-I
U||   nill-I, into eating. Secondly, having settled it to be God’s will that
U||   man should continue his species, we discovered an organ of amativeness,
U||   forthwith. And so with combativeness, with ideality, with causality,
U||   with constructiveness,—so, in short, with every organ, whether
U||   representing a propensity, a moral sentiment, or a faculty of the pure
U||   intellect. And in these arrangements of the Principia of human action,
U||   the Spurzheimites, whether right or wrong, in part, or upon the whole,
U||   have but followed, in principle, the footsteps of their predecessors;
U||   deducing and establishing every thing from the preconceived destiny of
U||   man, and upon the ground of the objects of his Creator.
U||   It would have been wiser, it would have been safer, to classify (if
U||   classify we must) upon the basis of what man usually or occasionally
U||   did, and was always occasionally doing, rather than upon the basis of
U||   what we took it for granted the Deity intended him to do. If we cannot
U||   comprehend God in his visible works, how then in his inconceivable
U||   thoughts, that call the works into being? If we cannot understand him
U||   in his objective creatures, how then in his substantive moods and
U||   phases of creation?
U||   Induction, a posteriori, would have brought phrenology to admit, as an
U||   innate and primitive principle of human action, a paradoxical
U||   something, which we may call perverseness, for want of a more
U||   characteristic term. In the sense I intend, it is, in fact, a mobile
U||   without motive, a motive not motivirt. Through its promptings we act
U||   without comprehensible object; or, if this shall be understood as a
U||   contradiction in terms, we may so far modify the proposition as to say,
U||   that through its promptings we act, for the reason that we should not.
U||   In theory, no reason can be more unreasonable, but, in fact, there is
U||   none more strong. With certain minds, under certain conditions, it
U||   becomes absolutely irresistible. I am not more certain that I breathe,
U||   than that the assurance of the wrong or error of any action is often
U||   the one unconquerable force which impels us, and alone impels us to its
U||   prosecution. Nor will this overwhelming tendency to do wrong for the
U||   wrong’s sake, admit of analysis, or resolution into ulterior elements.
U||   It is a radical, a primitive impulse—elementary. It will be said, I am
U||   aware, that when we persist in acts because we feel we should not
U||   persist in them, our conduct is but a modification of that which
U||   ordinarily springs from the combativeness of phrenology. But a glance
U||   will show the fallacy of this idea. The phrenological combativeness has
U||   for its essence, the necessity of self-defence. It is our safeguard
U||   against injury. Its principle regards our well-being; and thus the
U||   desire to be well is excited simultaneously with its development. It
U||   follows, that the desire to be well must be excited simultaneously with
U||   any principle which shall be merely a modification of combativeness,
U||   but in the case of that something which I term perverseness, the desire
U||   to be well is not only not aroused, but a strongly antagonistical
U||   sentiment exists.
U||   An appeal to one’s own heart is, after all, the best reply to the
U||   sophistry just noticed. No one who trustingly consults and thoroughly
U||   questions his own soul, will be disposed to deny the entire radicalness
U||   of the propensity in question. It is not more incomprehensible than
U||   distinctive. There lives no man who at some period has not been
U||   tormented, for example, by an earnest desire to tantalize a listener by
U||   circumlocution. The speaker is aware that he displeases; he has every
U||   intention to please, he is usually curt, precise, and clear; the most
U||   laconic and luminous language is struggling for utterance upon his
U||   tongue; it is only with difficulty that he restrains himself from
U||   giving it flow; he dreads and deprecates the anger of him whom he
U||   addresses; yet, the thought strikes him, that by certain involutions
U||   and parentheses this anger may be engendered. That single thought is
U||   enough. The impulse increases to a wish, the wish to a desire, the
U||   desire to an uncontrollable longing, and the longing (to the deep
U||   regret and mortification of the speaker, and in defiance of all
U||   consequences) is indulged.
U||   We have a task before us which must be speedily performed. We know that
U||   it will be ruinous to make delay. The most important crisis of our life
U||   calls, trumpet-tongued, for immediate energy and action. We glow, we
U||   are consumed with eagerness to commence the work, with the anticipation
U||   of whose glorious result our whole souls are on fire. It must, it shall
U||   be undertaken to-day, and yet we put it off until to-morrow; and why?
U||   There is no answer, except that we feel perverse, using the word with
U||   no comprehension of the principle. To-morrow arrives, and with it a
U||   more impatient anxiety to do our duty, but with this very increase of
U||   anxiety arrives, also, a nameless, a positively fearful, because
U||   unfathomable, craving for delay. This craving gathers strength as the
U||   moments fly. The last hour for action is at hand. We tremble with the
U||   violence of the conflict within us,—of the definite with the
U||   indefinite—of the substance with the shadow. But, if the contest have
U||   proceeded thus far, it is the shadow which prevails,—we struggle in
U||   vain. The clock strikes, and is the knell of our welfare. At the same
U||   time, it is the chanticleer-note to the ghost that has so long overawed
U||   us. It flies—it disappears—we are free. The old energy returns. We will
U||   labor now. Alas, it is too late!
U||   We stand upon the brink of a precipice. We peer into the abyss—we grow
U||   sick and dizzy. Our first impulse is to shrink from the danger.
U||   Unaccountably we remain. By slow degrees our sickness and dizziness and
U||   horror become merged in a cloud of unnamable feeling. By gradations,
U||   still more imperceptible, this cloud assumes shape, as did the vapor
U||   from the bottle out of which arose the genius in the Arabian Nights.
U||   But out of this our cloud upon the precipice’s edge, there grows into
U||   palpability, a shape, far more terrible than any genius or any demon of
U||   a tale, and yet it is but a thought, although a fearful one, and one
U||   which chills the very marrow of our bones with the fierceness of the
U||   delight of its horror. It is merely the idea of what would be our
U||   sensations during the sweeping precipitancy of a fall from such a
U||   height. And this fall—this rushing annihilation—for the very reason
U||   that it involves that one most ghastly and loathsome of all the most
U||   ghastly and loathsome images of death and suffering which have ever
U||   presented themselves to our imagination—for this very cause do we now
U||   the most vividly desire it. And because our reason violently deters us
U||   from the brink, therefore do we the most impetuously approach it. There
U||   is no passion in nature so demoniacally impatient, as that of him who,
U||   shuddering upon the edge of a precipice, thus meditates a plunge. To
U||   indulge, for a moment, in any attempt at thought, is to be inevitably
U||   lost; for reflection but urges us to forbear, and therefore it is, I
U||   say, that we cannot. If there be no friendly arm to check us, or if we
U||   fail in a sudden effort to prostrate ourselves backward from the abyss,
U||   we plunge, and are destroyed.
U||   Examine these similar actions as we will, we shall find them resulting
U||   solely from the spirit of the Perverse. We perpetrate them because we
U||   feel that we should not. Beyond or behind this there is no intelligible
U||   principle; and we might, indeed, deem this perverseness a direct
U||   instigation of the Arch-Fiend, were it not occasionally known to
U||   operate in furtherance of good.
U||   I have said thus much, that in some measure I may answer your
U||   question—that I may explain to you why I am here—that I may assign to
U||   you something that shall have at least the faint aspect of a cause for
U||   my wearing these fetters, and for my tenanting this cell of the
U||   condemned. Had I not been thus prolix, you might either have
U||   misunderstood me altogether, or, with the rabble, have fancied me mad.
U||   As it is, you will easily perceive that I am one of the many uncounted
U||   victims of the Imp of the Perverse.
U||   It is impossible that any deed could have been wrought with a more
U||   thorough deliberation. For weeks, for months, I pondered upon the means
U||   of the murder. I rejected a thousand schemes, because their
U||   accomplishment involved a chance of detection. At length, in reading
U||   some French memoirs, I found an account of a nearly fatal illness that
U||   occurred to Madame Pilau, through the agency of a candle accidentally
U||   poisoned. The idea struck my fancy at once. I knew my victim’s habit of
U||   reading in bed. I knew, too, that his apartment was narrow and
U||   ill-ventilated. But I need not vex you with impertinent details. I need
U||   not describe the easy artifices by which I substituted, in his bed-room
U||   candle-stand, a wax-light of my own making for the one which I there
U||   found. The next morning he was discovered dead in his bed, and the
U||   coroner’s verdict was—“Death by the visitation of God.”
U||   Having inherited his estate, all went well with me for years. The idea
U||   of detection never once entered my brain. Of the remains of the fatal
U||   taper I had myself carefully disposed. I had left no shadow of a clew
U||   by which it would be possible to convict, or even to suspect me of the
U||   crime. It is inconceivable how rich a sentiment of satisfaction arose
U||   in my bosom as I reflected upon my absolute security. For a very long
U||   period of time I was accustomed to revel in this sentiment. It afforded
U||   me more real delight than all the mere worldly advantages accruing from
U||   my sin. But there arrived at length an epoch, from which the
U||   pleasurable feeling grew, by scarcely perceptible gradations, into a
U||   haunting and harassing thought. It harassed because it haunted. I could
U||   scarcely get rid of it for an instant. It is quite a common thing to be
U||   thus annoyed with the ringing in our ears, or rather in our memories,
U||   of the burthen of some ordinary song, or some unimpressive snatches
U||   from an opera. Nor will we be the less tormented if the song in itself
U||   be good, or the opera air meritorious. In this manner, at last, I would
U||   perpetually catch myself pondering upon my security, and repeating, in
U||   a low undertone, the phrase, “I am safe.”
U||   One day, whilst sauntering along the streets, I arrested myself in the
U||   act of murmuring, half aloud, these customary syllables. In a fit of
U||   petulance, I remodelled them thus: “I am safe—I am safe—yes—if I be not
U||   fool enough to make open confession!”
U||   No sooner had I spoken these words, than I felt an icy chill creep to
U||   my heart. I had had some experience in these fits of perversity (whose
U||   nature I have been at some trouble to explain), and I remembered well
U||   that in no instance I had successfully resisted their attacks. And now
U||   my own casual self-suggestion that I might possibly be fool enough to
U||   confess the murder of which I had been guilty, confronted me, as if the
U||   very ghost of him whom I had murdered—and beckoned me on to death.
U||   At first, I made an effort to shake off this nightmare of the soul. I
U||   walked vigorously—faster—still faster—at length I ran. I felt a
U||   maddening desire to shriek aloud. Every succeeding wave of thought
U||   overwhelmed me with new terror, for, alas! I well, too well understood
U||   that to think, in my situation, was to be lost. I still quickened my
U||   pace. I bounded like a madman through the crowded thoroughfares. At
U||   length, the populace took the alarm, and pursued me. I felt then the
U||   consummation of my fate. Could I have torn out my tongue, I would have
U||   done it, but a rough voice resounded in my ears—a rougher grasp seized
U||   me by the shoulder. I turned—I gasped for breath. For a moment I
U||   experienced all the pangs of suffocation; I became blind, and deaf, and
U||   giddy; and then some invisible fiend, I thought, struck me with his
U||   broad palm upon the back. The long imprisoned secret burst forth from
U||   my soul.
U||   They say that I spoke with a distinct enunciation, but with marked
U||   emphasis and passionate hurry, as if in dread of interruption before
U||   concluding the brief but pregnant sentences that consigned me to the
U||   hangman and to hell.
U||   Having related all that was necessary for the fullest judicial
U||   conviction, I fell prostrate in a swoon.
U||   But why shall I say more? To-day I wear these chains, and am here!
U||   To-morrow I shall be fetterless!—but where?
U||THE ISLAND OF THE FAY
U||   Nullus enim locus sine genio est.—Servius.
U||   “La musique,” says Marmontel, in those “Contes Moraux” (*1) which in
U||   all our translations, we have insisted upon calling “Moral Tales,” as
U||   if in mockery of their spirit—“la musique est le seul des talents qui
U||   jouissent de lui-même; tous les autres veulent des temoins.” He here
U||   confounds the pleasure derivable from sweet sounds with the capacity
U||   for creating them. No more than any other talent, is that for music
U||   susceptible of complete enjoyment, where there is no second party to
U||   appreciate its exercise. And it is only in common with other talents
U||   that it produces effects which may be fully enjoyed in solitude. The
U||   idea which the raconteur has either failed to entertain clearly, or has
U||   sacrificed in its expression to his national love of point, is,
U||   doubtless, the very tenable one that the higher order of music is the
U||   most thoroughly estimated when we are exclusively alone. The
U||   proposition, in this form, will be admitted at once by those who love
U||   the lyre for its own sake, and for its spiritual uses. But there is one
U||   pleasure still within the reach of fallen mortality and perhaps only
U||   one—which owes even more than does music to the accessory sentiment of
U||   seclusion. I mean the happiness experienced in the contemplation of
U||   natural scenery. In truth, the man who would behold aright the glory of
U||   God upon earth must in solitude behold that glory. To me, at least, the
U||   presence—not of human life only, but of life in any other form than
U||   that of the green things which grow upon the soil and are voiceless—is
U||   a stain upon the landscape—is at war with the genius of the scene. I
U||   love, indeed, to regard the dark valleys, and the gray rocks, and the
U||   waters that silently smile, and the forests that sigh in uneasy
U||   slumbers, and the proud watchful mountains that look down upon all,—I
U||   love to regard these as themselves but the colossal members of one vast
U||   animate and sentient whole—a whole whose form (that of the sphere) is
U||   the most perfect and most inclusive of all; whose path is among
U||   associate planets; whose meek handmaiden is the moon, whose mediate
U||   sovereign is the sun; whose life is eternity, whose thought is that of
U||   a God; whose enjoyment is knowledge; whose destinies are lost in
U||   immensity, whose cognizance of ourselves is akin with our own
U||   cognizance of the animalculae which infest the brain—a being which we,
U||   in consequence, regard as purely inanimate and material much in the
U||   same manner as these animalculae must thus regard us.
U||   Our telescopes and our mathematical investigations assure us on every
U||   hand—notwithstanding the cant of the more ignorant of the
U||   priesthood—that space, and therefore that bulk, is an important
U||   consideration in the eyes of the Almighty. The cycles in which the
U||   stars move are those best adapted for the evolution, without collision,
U||   of the greatest possible number of bodies. The forms of those bodies
U||   are accurately such as, within a given surface, to include the greatest
U||   possible amount of matter;—while the surfaces themselves are so
U||   disposed as to accommodate a denser population than could be
U||   accommodated on the same surfaces otherwise arranged. Nor is it any
U||   argument against bulk being an object with God, that space itself is
U||   infinite; for there may be an infinity of matter to fill it. And since
U||   we see clearly that the endowment of matter with vitality is a
U||   principle—indeed, as far as our judgments extend, the leading principle
U||   in the operations of Deity,—it is scarcely logical to imagine it
U||   confined to the regions of the minute, where we daily trace it, and not
U||   extending to those of the august. As we find cycle within cycle without
U||   end,—yet all revolving around one far-distant centre which is the
U||   God-head, may we not analogically suppose in the same manner, life
U||   within life, the less within the greater, and all within the Spirit
U||   Divine? In short, we are madly erring, through self-esteem, in
U||   believing man, in either his temporal or future destinies, to be of
U||   more moment in the universe than that vast “clod of the valley” which
U||   he tills and contemns, and to which he denies a soul for no more
U||   profound reason than that he does not behold it in operation. (*2)
U||   These fancies, and such as these, have always given to my meditations
U||   among the mountains and the forests, by the rivers and the ocean, a
U||   tinge of what the everyday world would not fail to term fantastic. My
U||   wanderings amid such scenes have been many, and far-searching, and
U||   often solitary; and the interest with which I have strayed through many
U||   a dim, deep valley, or gazed into the reflected Heaven of many a bright
U||   lake, has been an interest greatly deepened by the thought that I have
U||   strayed and gazed alone. What flippant Frenchman was it who said in
U||   allusion to the well-known work of Zimmerman, that, “la solitude est
U||   une belle chose; mais il faut quelqu’un pour vous dire que la solitude
U||   est une belle chose?” The epigram cannot be gainsayed; but the
U||   necessity is a thing that does not exist.
U||   It was during one of my lonely journeyings, amid a far distant region
U||   of mountain locked within mountain, and sad rivers and melancholy tarn
U||   writhing or sleeping within all—that I chanced upon a certain rivulet
U||   and island. I came upon them suddenly in the leafy June, and threw
U||   myself upon the turf, beneath the branches of an unknown odorous shrub,
U||   that I might doze as I contemplated the scene. I felt that thus only
U||   should I look upon it—such was the character of phantasm which it wore.
U||   On all sides—save to the west, where the sun was about sinking—arose
U||   the verdant walls of the forest. The little river which turned sharply
U||   in its course, and was thus immediately lost to sight, seemed to have
U||   no exit from its prison, but to be absorbed by the deep green foliage
U||   of the trees to the east—while in the opposite quarter (so it appeared
U||   to me as I lay at length and glanced upward) there poured down
U||   noiselessly and continuously into the valley, a rich golden and crimson
