U||THE ASSIGNATION
U||   Stay for me there! I will not fail.
U||   To meet thee in that hollow vale.
U||   (Exequy on the death of his wife, by Henry King, Bishop of Chichester.)
U||   Ill-fated and mysterious man!—bewildered in the brilliancy of thine own
U||   imagination, and fallen in the flames of thine own youth! Again in
U||   fancy I behold thee! Once more thy form hath risen before me!—not—oh!
U||   not as thou art—in the cold valley and shadow—but as thou shouldst
U||   be—squandering away a life of magnificent meditation in that city of
U||   dim visions, thine own Venice—which is a star-beloved Elysium of the
U||   sea, and the wide windows of whose Palladian palaces look down with a
U||   deep and bitter meaning upon the secrets of her silent waters. Yes! I
U||   repeat it—as thou shouldst be. There are surely other worlds than
U||   this—other thoughts than the thoughts of the multitude—other
U||   speculations than the speculations of the sophist. Who then shall call
U||   thy conduct into question? who blame thee for thy visionary hours, or
U||   denounce those occupations as a wasting away of life, which were but
U||   the overflowings of thine everlasting energies?
U||   It was at Venice, beneath the covered archway there called the Ponte di
U||   Sospiri, that I met for the third or fourth time the person of whom I
U||   speak. It is with a confused recollection that I bring to mind the
U||   circumstances of that meeting. Yet I remember—ah! how should I
U||   forget?—the deep midnight, the Bridge of Sighs, the beauty of woman,
U||   and the Genius of Romance that stalked up and down the narrow canal.
U||   It was a night of unusual gloom. The great clock of the Piazza had
U||   sounded the fifth hour of the Italian evening. The square of the
U||   Campanile lay silent and deserted, and the lights in the old Ducal
U||   Palace were dying fast away. I was returning home from the Piazetta, by
U||   way of the Grand Canal. But as my gondola arrived opposite the mouth of
U||   the canal San Marco, a female voice from its recesses broke suddenly
U||   upon the night, in one wild, hysterical, and long continued shriek.
U||   Startled at the sound, I sprang upon my feet: while the gondolier,
U||   letting slip his single oar, lost it in the pitchy darkness beyond a
