U||   The tumult had subsided, the lights had died away within the palace,
U||   and the stranger, whom I now recognized, stood alone upon the flags. He
U||   shook with inconceivable agitation, and his eye glanced around in
U||   search of a gondola. I could not do less than offer him the service of
U||   my own; and he accepted the civility. Having obtained an oar at the
U||   water-gate, we proceeded together to his residence, while he rapidly
U||   recovered his self-possession, and spoke of our former slight
U||   acquaintance in terms of great apparent cordiality.
U||   There are some subjects upon which I take pleasure in being minute. The
U||   person of the stranger—let me call him by this title, who to all the
U||   world was still a stranger—the person of the stranger is one of these
U||   subjects. In height he might have been below rather than above the
U||   medium size: although there were moments of intense passion when his
U||   frame actually expanded and belied the assertion. The light, almost
U||   slender symmetry of his figure, promised more of that ready activity
U||   which he evinced at the Bridge of Sighs, than of that Herculean
U||   strength which he has been known to wield without an effort, upon
U||   occasions of more dangerous emergency. With the mouth and chin of a
U||   deity—singular, wild, full, liquid eyes, whose shadows varied from pure
U||   hazel to intense and brilliant jet—and a profusion of curling, black
U||   hair, from which a forehead of unusual breadth gleamed forth at
U||   intervals all light and ivory—his were features than which I have seen
U||   none more classically regular, except, perhaps, the marble ones of the
U||   Emperor Commodus. Yet his countenance was, nevertheless, one of those
U||   which all men have seen at some period of their lives, and have never
U||   afterwards seen again. It had no peculiar, it had no settled
U||   predominant expression to be fastened upon the memory; a countenance
U||   seen and instantly forgotten, but forgotten with a vague and
U||   never-ceasing desire of recalling it to mind. Not that the spirit of
U||   each rapid passion failed, at any time, to throw its own distinct image
U||   upon the mirror of that face—but that the mirror, mirror-like, retained
U||   no vestige of the passion, when the passion had departed.
U||   Upon leaving him on the night of our adventure, he solicited me, in
U||   what I thought an urgent manner, to call upon him very early the next
U||   morning. Shortly after sunrise, I found myself accordingly at his
U||   Palazzo, one of those huge structures of gloomy, yet fantastic pomp,
U||   which tower above the waters of the Grand Canal in the vicinity of the
U||   Rialto. I was shown up a broad winding staircase of mosaics, into an
U||   apartment whose unparalleled splendor burst through the opening door
U||   with an actual glare, making me blind and dizzy with luxuriousness.
U||   I knew my acquaintance to be wealthy. Report had spoken of his
U||   possessions in terms which I had even ventured to call terms of
U||   ridiculous exaggeration. But as I gazed about me, I could not bring
U||   myself to believe that the wealth of any subject in Europe could have
U||   supplied the princely magnificence which burned and blazed around.
U||   Although, as I say, the sun had arisen, yet the room was still
U||   brilliantly lighted up. I judge from this circumstance, as well as from
U||   an air of exhaustion in the countenance of my friend, that he had not
U||   retired to bed during the whole of the preceding night. In the
U||   architecture and embellishments of the chamber, the evident design had
