U||   I had swooned; but still will not say that all of consciousness was
U||   lost. What of it there remained I will not attempt to define, or even
U||   to describe; yet all was not lost. In the deepest slumber—no! In
U||   delirium—no! In a swoon—no! In death—no! even in the grave all is not
U||   lost. Else there is no immortality for man. Arousing from the most
U||   profound of slumbers, we break the gossamer web of some dream. Yet in a
U||   second afterward, (so frail may that web have been) we remember not
U||   that we have dreamed. In the return to life from the swoon there are
U||   two stages; first, that of the sense of mental or spiritual; secondly,
U||   that of the sense of physical, existence. It seems probable that if,
U||   upon reaching the second stage, we could recall the impressions of the
U||   first, we should find these impressions eloquent in memories of the
U||   gulf beyond. And that gulf is—what? How at least shall we distinguish
U||   its shadows from those of the tomb? But if the impressions of what I
U||   have termed the first stage are not, at will, recalled, yet, after long
U||   interval, do they not come unbidden, while we marvel whence they come?
U||   He who has never swooned, is not he who finds strange palaces and
U||   wildly familiar faces in coals that glow; is not he who beholds
U||   floating in mid-air the sad visions that the many may not view; is not
U||   he who ponders over the perfume of some novel flower; is not he whose
U||   brain grows bewildered with the meaning of some musical cadence which
U||   has never before arrested his attention.
U||   Amid frequent and thoughtful endeavors to remember; amid earnest
U||   struggles to regather some token of the state of seeming nothingness
