U||   a later day and much earnestness of endeavor have enabled me vaguely to
U||   recall.
U||   So far, I had not opened my eyes. I felt that I lay upon my back,
U||   unbound. I reached out my hand, and it fell heavily upon something damp
U||   and hard. There I suffered it to remain for many minutes, while I
U||   strove to imagine where and what I could be. I longed, yet dared not to
U||   employ my vision. I dreaded the first glance at objects around me. It
U||   was not that I feared to look upon things horrible, but that I grew
U||   aghast lest there should be nothing to see. At length, with a wild
U||   desperation at heart, I quickly unclosed my eyes. My worst thoughts,
U||   then, were confirmed. The blackness of eternal night encompassed me. I
U||   struggled for breath. The intensity of the darkness seemed to oppress
U||   and stifle me. The atmosphere was intolerably close. I still lay
U||   quietly, and made effort to exercise my reason. I brought to mind the
U||   inquisitorial proceedings, and attempted from that point to deduce my
U||   real condition. The sentence had passed; and it appeared to me that a
U||   very long interval of time had since elapsed. Yet not for a moment did
U||   I suppose myself actually dead. Such a supposition, notwithstanding
U||   what we read in fiction, is altogether inconsistent with real
U||   existence;—but where and in what state was I? The condemned to death, I
U||   knew, perished usually at the autos-da-fe, and one of these had been
U||   held on the very night of the day of my trial. Had I been remanded to
U||   my dungeon, to await the next sacrifice, which would not take place for
U||   many months? This I at once saw could not be. Victims had been in
U||   immediate demand. Moreover, my dungeon, as well as all the condemned
U||   cells at Toledo, had stone floors, and light was not altogether
U||   excluded.
U||   A fearful idea now suddenly drove the blood in torrents upon my heart,
