U||   speedy descent. I grew frantically mad, and struggled to force myself
U||   upward against the sweep of the fearful scimitar. And then I fell
U||   suddenly calm, and lay smiling at the glittering death, as a child at
U||   some rare bauble.
U||   There was another interval of utter insensibility; it was brief; for,
U||   upon again lapsing into life there had been no perceptible descent in
U||   the pendulum. But it might have been long; for I knew there were demons
U||   who took note of my swoon, and who could have arrested the vibration at
U||   pleasure. Upon my recovery, too, I felt very—oh! inexpressibly—sick and
U||   weak, as if through long inanition. Even amid the agonies of that
U||   period, the human nature craved food. With painful effort I
U||   outstretched my left arm as far as my bonds permitted, and took
U||   possession of the small remnant which had been spared me by the rats.
U||   As I put a portion of it within my lips, there rushed to my mind a half
U||   formed thought of joy—of hope. Yet what business had I with hope? It
U||   was, as I say, a half formed thought—man has many such, which are never
U||   completed. I felt that it was of joy—of hope; but felt also that it had
U||   perished in its formation. In vain I struggled to perfect—to regain it.
U||   Long suffering had nearly annihilated all my ordinary powers of mind. I
U||   was an imbecile—an idiot.
U||   The vibration of the pendulum was at right angles to my length. I saw
U||   that the crescent was designed to cross the region of the heart. It
U||   would fray the serge of my robe—it would return and repeat its
U||   operations—again—and again. Notwithstanding its terrifically wide sweep
U||   (some thirty feet or more) and the hissing vigor of its descent,
U||   sufficient to sunder these very walls of iron, still the fraying of my
U||   robe would be all that, for several minutes, it would accomplish. And
U||   at this thought I paused. I dared not go farther than this reflection.
U||   I dwelt upon it with a pertinacity of attention—as if, in so dwelling,
U||   I could arrest here the descent of the steel. I forced myself to ponder
U||   upon the sound of the crescent as it should pass across the
U||   garment—upon the peculiar thrilling sensation which the friction of
U||   cloth produces on the nerves. I pondered upon all this frivolity until
U||   my teeth were on edge.
U||   Down—steadily down it crept. I took a frenzied pleasure in contrasting
U||   its downward with its lateral velocity. To the right—to the left—far
U||   and wide—with the shriek of a damned spirit! to my heart with the
U||   stealthy pace of the tiger! I alternately laughed and howled as the one
U||   or the other idea grew predominant.
U||   Down—certainly, relentlessly down! It vibrated within three inches of
U||   my bosom! I struggled violently, furiously, to free my left arm. This
U||   was free only from the elbow to the hand. I could reach the latter,
U||   from the platter beside me, to my mouth, with great effort, but no
U||   farther. Could I have broken the fastenings above the elbow, I would
U||   have seized and attempted to arrest the pendulum. I might as well have
U||   attempted to arrest an avalanche!
U||   Down—still unceasingly—still inevitably down! I gasped and struggled at
U||   each vibration. I shrunk convulsively at its every sweep. My eyes
U||   followed its outward or upward whirls with the eagerness of the most
U||   unmeaning despair; they closed themselves spasmodically at the descent,
U||   although death would have been a relief, oh, how unspeakable! Still I
U||   quivered in every nerve to think how slight a sinking of the machinery
U||   would precipitate that keen, glistening axe upon my bosom. It was hope
U||   that prompted the nerve to quiver—the frame to shrink. It was hope—the
U||   hope that triumphs on the rack—that whispers to the death-condemned
U||   even in the dungeons of the Inquisition.
U||   I saw that some ten or twelve vibrations would bring the steel in
U||   actual contact with my robe, and with this observation there suddenly
U||   came over my spirit all the keen, collected calmness of despair. For
U||   the first time during many hours—or perhaps days—I thought. It now
U||   occurred to me that the bandage, or surcingle, which enveloped me, was
U||   unique. I was tied by no separate cord. The first stroke of the
U||   razorlike crescent athwart any portion of the band, would so detach it
U||   that it might be unwound from my person by means of my left hand. But
U||   how fearful, in that case, the proximity of the steel! The result of
U||   the slightest struggle how deadly! Was it likely, moreover, that the
U||   minions of the torturer had not foreseen and provided for this
U||   possibility? Was it probable that the bandage crossed my bosom in the
U||   track of the pendulum? Dreading to find my faint, and, as it seemed, my
U||   last hope frustrated, I so far elevated my head as to obtain a distinct
U||   view of my breast. The surcingle enveloped my limbs and body close in
U||   all directions—save in the path of the destroying crescent.
U||   Scarcely had I dropped my head back into its original position, when
U||   there flashed upon my mind what I cannot better describe than as the
U||   unformed half of that idea of deliverance to which I have previously
U||   alluded, and of which a moiety only floated indeterminately through my
U||   brain when I raised food to my burning lips. The whole thought was now
U||   present—feeble, scarcely sane, scarcely definite,—but still entire. I
U||   proceeded at once, with the nervous energy of despair, to attempt its
U||   execution.
U||   For many hours the immediate vicinity of the low framework upon which I
U||   lay had been literally swarming with rats. They were wild, bold,
U||   ravenous—their red eyes glaring upon me as if they waited but for
U||   motionlessness on my part to make me their prey. “To what food,” I
U||   thought, “have they been accustomed in the well?”
U||   They had devoured, in spite of all my efforts to prevent them, all but
U||   a small remnant of the contents of the dish. I had fallen into an
U||   habitual see-saw, or wave of the hand about the platter; and, at
U||   length, the unconscious uniformity of the movement deprived it of
U||   effect. In their voracity the vermin frequently fastened their sharp
U||   fangs in my fingers. With the particles of the oily and spicy viand
U||   which now remained, I thoroughly rubbed the bandage wherever I could
U||   reach it; then, raising my hand from the floor, I lay breathlessly
U||   still.
U||   At first the ravenous animals were startled and terrified at the
U||   change—at the cessation of movement. They shrank alarmedly back; many
U||   sought the well. But this was only for a moment. I had not counted in
U||   vain upon their voracity. Observing that I remained without motion, one
U||   or two of the boldest leaped upon the frame-work, and smelt at the
U||   surcingle. This seemed the signal for a general rush. Forth from the
U||   well they hurried in fresh troops. They clung to the wood—they overran
U||   it, and leaped in hundreds upon my person. The measured movement of the
U||   pendulum disturbed them not at all. Avoiding its strokes they busied
U||   themselves with the anointed bandage. They pressed—they swarmed upon me
U||   in ever accumulating heaps. They writhed upon my throat; their cold
U||   lips sought my own; I was half stifled by their thronging pressure;
U||   disgust, for which the world has no name, swelled my bosom, and
U||   chilled, with a heavy clamminess, my heart. Yet one minute, and I felt
U||   that the struggle would be over. Plainly I perceived the loosening of
U||   the bandage. I knew that in more than one place it must be already
U||   severed. With a more than human resolution I lay still.
U||   Nor had I erred in my calculations—nor had I endured in vain. I at
U||   length felt that I was free. The surcingle hung in ribands from my
U||   body. But the stroke of the pendulum already pressed upon my bosom. It
U||   had divided the serge of the robe. It had cut through the linen
U||   beneath. Twice again it swung, and a sharp sense of pain shot through
U||   every nerve. But the moment of escape had arrived. At a wave of my hand
U||   my deliverers hurried tumultuously away. With a steady
U||   movement—cautious, sidelong, shrinking, and slow—I slid from the
U||   embrace of the bandage and beyond the reach of the scimitar. For the
U||   moment, at least, I was free.
U||   Free!—and in the grasp of the Inquisition! I had scarcely stepped from
U||   my wooden bed of horror upon the stone floor of the prison, when the
U||   motion of the hellish machine ceased and I beheld it drawn up, by some
U||   invisible force, through the ceiling. This was a lesson which I took
U||   desperately to heart. My every motion was undoubtedly watched. Free!—I
U||   had but escaped death in one form of agony, to be delivered unto worse
U||   than death in some other. With that thought I rolled my eves nervously
U||   around on the barriers of iron that hemmed me in. Something
U||   unusual—some change which, at first, I could not appreciate
U||   distinctly—it was obvious, had taken place in the apartment. For many
U||   minutes of a dreamy and trembling abstraction, I busied myself in vain,
U||   unconnected conjecture. During this period, I became aware, for the
U||   first time, of the origin of the sulphurous light which illumined the
U||   cell. It proceeded from a fissure, about half an inch in width,
U||   extending entirely around the prison at the base of the walls, which
U||   thus appeared, and were, completely separated from the floor. I
U||   endeavored, but of course in vain, to look through the aperture.
U||   As I arose from the attempt, the mystery of the alteration in the
U||   chamber broke at once upon my understanding. I have observed that,
U||   although the outlines of the figures upon the walls were sufficiently
U||   distinct, yet the colors seemed blurred and indefinite. These colors
U||   had now assumed, and were momentarily assuming, a startling and most
U||   intense brilliancy, that gave to the spectral and fiendish portraitures
U||   an aspect that might have thrilled even firmer nerves than my own.
U||   Demon eyes, of a wild and ghastly vivacity, glared upon me in a
U||   thousand directions, where none had been visible before, and gleamed
U||   with the lurid lustre of a fire that I could not force my imagination
U||   to regard as unreal.
U||   Unreal!—Even while I breathed there came to my nostrils the breath of
U||   the vapour of heated iron! A suffocating odour pervaded the prison! A
U||   deeper glow settled each moment in the eyes that glared at my agonies!
U||   A richer tint of crimson diffused itself over the pictured horrors of
U||   blood. I panted! I gasped for breath! There could be no doubt of the
U||   design of my tormentors—oh! most unrelenting! oh! most demoniac of men!
U||   I shrank from the glowing metal to the centre of the cell. Amid the
U||   thought of the fiery destruction that impended, the idea of the
U||   coolness of the well came over my soul like balm. I rushed to its
U||   deadly brink. I threw my straining vision below. The glare from the
U||   enkindled roof illumined its inmost recesses. Yet, for a wild moment,
U||   did my spirit refuse to comprehend the meaning of what I saw. At length
U||   it forced—it wrestled its way into my soul—it burned itself in upon my
U||   shuddering reason. Oh! for a voice to speak!—oh! horror!—oh! any horror
U||   but this! With a shriek, I rushed from the margin, and buried my face
U||   in my hands—weeping bitterly.
U||   The heat rapidly increased, and once again I looked up, shuddering as
U||   with a fit of the ague. There had been a second change in the cell—and
U||   now the change was obviously in the form. As before, it was in vain
U||   that I, at first, endeavoured to appreciate or understand what was
U||   taking place. But not long was I left in doubt. The Inquisitorial
U||   vengeance had been hurried by my two-fold escape, and there was to be
U||   no more dallying with the King of Terrors. The room had been square. I
U||   saw that two of its iron angles were now acute—two, consequently,
U||   obtuse. The fearful difference quickly increased with a low rumbling or
U||   moaning sound. In an instant the apartment had shifted its form into
U||   that of a lozenge. But the alteration stopped not here—I neither hoped
U||   nor desired it to stop. I could have clasped the red walls to my bosom
U||   as a garment of eternal peace. “Death,” I said, “any death but that of
U||   the pit!” Fool! might I have not known that into the pit it was the
U||   object of the burning iron to urge me? Could I resist its glow? or, if
U||   even that, could I withstand its pressure? And now, flatter and flatter
U||   grew the lozenge, with a rapidity that left me no time for
U||   contemplation. Its centre, and of course, its greatest width, came just
U||   over the yawning gulf. I shrank back—but the closing walls pressed me
U||   resistlessly onward. At length for my seared and writhing body there
U||   was no longer an inch of foothold on the firm floor of the prison. I
U||   struggled no more, but the agony of my soul found vent in one loud,
U||   long, and final scream of despair. I felt that I tottered upon the
U||   brink—I averted my eyes—
U||   There was a discordant hum of human voices! There was a loud blast as
U||   of many trumpets! There was a harsh grating as of a thousand thunders!
U||   The fiery walls rushed back! An outstretched arm caught my own as I
U||   fell, fainting, into the abyss. It was that of General Lasalle. The
U||   French army had entered Toledo. The Inquisition was in the hands of its
U||   enemies.
U||THE PREMATURE BURIAL
U||   There are certain themes of which the interest is all-absorbing, but
U||   which are too entirely horrible for the purposes of legitimate fiction.
U||   These the mere romanticist must eschew, if he do not wish to offend or
U||   to disgust. They are with propriety handled only when the severity and
U||   majesty of Truth sanctify and sustain them. We thrill, for example,
U||   with the most intense of “pleasurable pain” over the accounts of the
U||   Passage of the Beresina, of the Earthquake at Lisbon, of the Plague at
U||   London, of the Massacre of St. Bartholomew, or of the stifling of the
U||   hundred and twenty-three prisoners in the Black Hole at Calcutta. But
U||   in these accounts it is the fact——it is the reality——it is the history
U||   which excites. As inventions, we should regard them with simple
U||   abhorrence.
U||   I have mentioned some few of the more prominent and august calamities
U||   on record; but in these it is the extent, not less than the character
U||   of the calamity, which so vividly impresses the fancy. I need not
U||   remind the reader that, from the long and weird catalogue of human
U||   miseries, I might have selected many individual instances more replete
U||   with essential suffering than any of these vast generalities of
U||   disaster. The true wretchedness, indeed—the ultimate woe——is
U||   particular, not diffuse. That the ghastly extremes of agony are endured
U||   by man the unit, and never by man the mass——for this let us thank a
U||   merciful God!
U||   To be buried while alive is, beyond question, the most terrific of
U||   these extremes which has ever fallen to the lot of mere mortality. That
U||   it has frequently, very frequently, so fallen will scarcely be denied
U||   by those who think. The boundaries which divide Life from Death are at
U||   best shadowy and vague. Who shall say where the one ends, and where the
U||   other begins? We know that there are diseases in which occur total
U||   cessations of all the apparent functions of vitality, and yet in which
U||   these cessations are merely suspensions, properly so called. They are
U||   only temporary pauses in the incomprehensible mechanism. A certain
U||   period elapses, and some unseen mysterious principle again sets in
U||   motion the magic pinions and the wizard wheels. The silver cord was not
U||   for ever loosed, nor the golden bowl irreparably broken. But where,
U||   meantime, was the soul?
U||   Apart, however, from the inevitable conclusion, a priori that such
U||   causes must produce such effects——that the well-known occurrence of
U||   such cases of suspended animation must naturally give rise, now and
U||   then, to premature interments—apart from this consideration, we have
U||   the direct testimony of medical and ordinary experience to prove that a
U||   vast number of such interments have actually taken place. I might refer
U||   at once, if necessary, to a hundred well-authenticated instances. One
U||   of very remarkable character, and of which the circumstances may be
U||   fresh in the memory of some of my readers, occurred, not very long ago,
U||   in the neighboring city of Baltimore, where it occasioned a painful,
U||   intense, and widely-extended excitement. The wife of one of the most
U||   respectable citizens—a lawyer of eminence and a member of Congress—was
U||   seized with a sudden and unaccountable illness, which completely
U||   baffled the skill of her physicians. After much suffering she died, or
U||   was supposed to die. No one suspected, indeed, or had reason to
U||   suspect, that she was not actually dead. She presented all the ordinary
U||   appearances of death. The face assumed the usual pinched and sunken
U||   outline. The lips were of the usual marble pallor. The eyes were
U||   lustreless. There was no warmth. Pulsation had ceased. For three days
U||   the body was preserved unburied, during which it had acquired a stony
U||   rigidity. The funeral, in short, was hastened, on account of the rapid
U||   advance of what was supposed to be decomposition.
U||   The lady was deposited in her family vault, which, for three subsequent
U||   years, was undisturbed. At the expiration of this term it was opened
U||   for the reception of a sarcophagus; but, alas! how fearful a shock
U||   awaited the husband, who, personally, threw open the door! As its
U||   portals swung outwardly back, some white-apparelled object fell
U||   rattling within his arms. It was the skeleton of his wife in her yet
U||   unmoulded shroud.
U||   A careful investigation rendered it evident that she had revived within
U||   two days after her entombment; that her struggles within the coffin had
U||   caused it to fall from a ledge, or shelf to the floor, where it was so
U||   broken as to permit her escape. A lamp which had been accidentally
U||   left, full of oil, within the tomb, was found empty; it might have been
U||   exhausted, however, by evaporation. On the uttermost of the steps which
U||   led down into the dread chamber was a large fragment of the coffin,
U||   with which, it seemed, that she had endeavored to arrest attention by
U||   striking the iron door. While thus occupied, she probably swooned, or
U||   possibly died, through sheer terror; and, in failing, her shroud became
U||   entangled in some iron-work which projected interiorly. Thus she
U||   remained, and thus she rotted, erect.
U||   In the year 1810, a case of living inhumation happened in France,
U||   attended with circumstances which go far to warrant the assertion that
U||   truth is, indeed, stranger than fiction. The heroine of the story was a
U||   Mademoiselle Victorine Lafourcade, a young girl of illustrious family,
U||   of wealth, and of great personal beauty. Among her numerous suitors was
U||   Julien Bossuet, a poor litterateur, or journalist of Paris. His talents
U||   and general amiability had recommended him to the notice of the
U||   heiress, by whom he seems to have been truly beloved; but her pride of
U||   birth decided her, finally, to reject him, and to wed a Monsieur
U||   Renelle, a banker and a diplomatist of some eminence. After marriage,
U||   however, this gentleman neglected, and, perhaps, even more positively
U||   ill-treated her. Having passed with him some wretched years, she
U||   died—at least her condition so closely resembled death as to deceive
U||   every one who saw her. She was buried——not in a vault, but in an
U||   ordinary grave in the village of her nativity. Filled with despair, and
U||   still inflamed by the memory of a profound attachment, the lover
U||   journeys from the capital to the remote province in which the village
U||   lies, with the romantic purpose of disinterring the corpse, and
U||   possessing himself of its luxuriant tresses. He reaches the grave. At
U||   midnight he unearths the coffin, opens it, and is in the act of
U||   detaching the hair, when he is arrested by the unclosing of the beloved
U||   eyes. In fact, the lady had been buried alive. Vitality had not
U||   altogether departed, and she was aroused by the caresses of her lover
U||   from the lethargy which had been mistaken for death. He bore her
U||   frantically to his lodgings in the village. He employed certain
U||   powerful restoratives suggested by no little medical learning. In fine,
U||   she revived. She recognized her preserver. She remained with him until,
U||   by slow degrees, she fully recovered her original health. Her woman’s
U||   heart was not adamant, and this last lesson of love sufficed to soften
U||   it. She bestowed it upon Bossuet. She returned no more to her husband,
U||   but, concealing from him her resurrection, fled with her lover to
U||   America. Twenty years afterward, the two returned to France, in the
U||   persuasion that time had so greatly altered the lady’s appearance that
U||   her friends would be unable to recognize her. They were mistaken,
U||   however, for, at the first meeting, Monsieur Renelle did actually
U||   recognize and make claim to his wife. This claim she resisted, and a
U||   judicial tribunal sustained her in her resistance, deciding that the
U||   peculiar circumstances, with the long lapse of years, had extinguished,
U||   not only equitably, but legally, the authority of the husband.
U||   The “Chirurgical Journal” of Leipsic, a periodical of high authority
U||   and merit, which some American bookseller would do well to translate
U||   and republish, records in a late number a very distressing event of the
U||   character in question.
U||   An officer of artillery, a man of gigantic stature and of robust
U||   health, being thrown from an unmanageable horse, received a very severe
U||   contusion upon the head, which rendered him insensible at once; the
U||   skull was slightly fractured, but no immediate danger was apprehended.
U||   Trepanning was accomplished successfully. He was bled, and many other
U||   of the ordinary means of relief were adopted. Gradually, however, he
U||   fell into a more and more hopeless state of stupor, and, finally, it
U||   was thought that he died.
U||   The weather was warm, and he was buried with indecent haste in one of
U||   the public cemeteries. His funeral took place on Thursday. On the
U||   Sunday following, the grounds of the cemetery were, as usual, much
U||   thronged with visitors, and about noon an intense excitement was
U||   created by the declaration of a peasant that, while sitting upon the
U||   grave of the officer, he had distinctly felt a commotion of the earth,
U||   as if occasioned by some one struggling beneath. At first little
U||   attention was paid to the man’s asseveration; but his evident terror,
U||   and the dogged obstinacy with which he persisted in his story, had at
U||   length their natural effect upon the crowd. Spades were hurriedly
U||   procured, and the grave, which was shamefully shallow, was in a few
U||   minutes so far thrown open that the head of its occupant appeared. He
U||   was then seemingly dead; but he sat nearly erect within his coffin, the
U||   lid of which, in his furious struggles, he had partially uplifted.
U||   He was forthwith conveyed to the nearest hospital, and there pronounced
U||   to be still living, although in an asphytic condition. After some hours
U||   he revived, recognized individuals of his acquaintance, and, in broken
U||   sentences spoke of his agonies in the grave.
U||   From what he related, it was clear that he must have been conscious of
U||   life for more than an hour, while inhumed, before lapsing into
U||   insensibility. The grave was carelessly and loosely filled with an
U||   exceedingly porous soil; and thus some air was necessarily admitted. He
U||   heard the footsteps of the crowd overhead, and endeavored to make
U||   himself heard in turn. It was the tumult within the grounds of the
U||   cemetery, he said, which appeared to awaken him from a deep sleep, but
U||   no sooner was he awake than he became fully aware of the awful horrors
U||   of his position.
U||   This patient, it is recorded, was doing well and seemed to be in a fair
U||   way of ultimate recovery, but fell a victim to the quackeries of
U||   medical experiment. The galvanic battery was applied, and he suddenly
U||   expired in one of those ecstatic paroxysms which, occasionally, it
U||   superinduces.
U||   The mention of the galvanic battery, nevertheless, recalls to my memory
U||   a well known and very extraordinary case in point, where its action
U||   proved the means of restoring to animation a young attorney of London,
U||   who had been interred for two days. This occurred in 1831, and created,
U||   at the time, a very profound sensation wherever it was made the subject
U||   of converse.
U||   The patient, Mr. Edward Stapleton, had died, apparently of typhus
U||   fever, accompanied with some anomalous symptoms which had excited the
U||   curiosity of his medical attendants. Upon his seeming decease, his
U||   friends were requested to sanction a post-mortem examination, but
U||   declined to permit it. As often happens, when such refusals are made,
U||   the practitioners resolved to disinter the body and dissect it at
U||   leisure, in private. Arrangements were easily effected with some of the
U||   numerous corps of body-snatchers, with which London abounds; and, upon
U||   the third night after the funeral, the supposed corpse was unearthed
U||   from a grave eight feet deep, and deposited in the opening chamber of
U||   one of the private hospitals.
U||   An incision of some extent had been actually made in the abdomen, when
U||   the fresh and undecayed appearance of the subject suggested an
U||   application of the battery. One experiment succeeded another, and the
U||   customary effects supervened, with nothing to characterize them in any
U||   respect, except, upon one or two occasions, a more than ordinary degree
U||   of life-likeness in the convulsive action.
U||   It grew late. The day was about to dawn; and it was thought expedient,
U||   at length, to proceed at once to the dissection. A student, however,
U||   was especially desirous of testing a theory of his own, and insisted
U||   upon applying the battery to one of the pectoral muscles. A rough gash
U||   was made, and a wire hastily brought in contact, when the patient, with
U||   a hurried but quite unconvulsive movement, arose from the table,
U||   stepped into the middle of the floor, gazed about him uneasily for a
U||   few seconds, and then—spoke. What he said was unintelligible, but words
U||   were uttered; the syllabification was distinct. Having spoken, he fell
U||   heavily to the floor.
U||   For some moments all were paralyzed with awe—but the urgency of the
U||   case soon restored them their presence of mind. It was seen that Mr.
U||   Stapleton was alive, although in a swoon. Upon exhibition of ether he
U||   revived and was rapidly restored to health, and to the society of his
U||   friends—from whom, however, all knowledge of his resuscitation was
U||   withheld, until a relapse was no longer to be apprehended. Their
U||   wonder—their rapturous astonishment—may be conceived.
U||   The most thrilling peculiarity of this incident, nevertheless, is
U||   involved in what Mr. S. himself asserts. He declares that at no period
U||   was he altogether insensible—that, dully and confusedly, he was aware
U||   of everything which happened to him, from the moment in which he was
U||   pronounced dead by his physicians, to that in which he fell swooning to
U||   the floor of the hospital. “I am alive,” were the uncomprehended words
U||   which, upon recognizing the locality of the dissecting-room, he had
U||   endeavored, in his extremity, to utter.
U||   It were an easy matter to multiply such histories as these—but I
U||   forbear—for, indeed, we have no need of such to establish the fact that
U||   premature interments occur. When we reflect how very rarely, from the
U||   nature of the case, we have it in our power to detect them, we must
U||   admit that they may frequently occur without our cognizance. Scarcely,
U||   in truth, is a graveyard ever encroached upon, for any purpose, to any
U||   great extent, that skeletons are not found in postures which suggest
U||   the most fearful of suspicions.
U||   Fearful indeed the suspicion—but more fearful the doom! It may be
U||   asserted, without hesitation, that no event is so terribly well adapted
U||   to inspire the supremeness of bodily and of mental distress, as is
U||   burial before death. The unendurable oppression of the lungs—the
U||   stifling fumes from the damp earth—the clinging to the death
U||   garments—the rigid embrace of the narrow house—the blackness of the
U||   absolute Night—the silence like a sea that overwhelms—the unseen but
U||   palpable presence of the Conqueror Worm—these things, with the thoughts
U||   of the air and grass above, with memory of dear friends who would fly
U||   to save us if but informed of our fate, and with consciousness that of
U||   this fate they can never be informed—that our hopeless portion is that
U||   of the really dead—these considerations, I say, carry into the heart,
U||   which still palpitates, a degree of appalling and intolerable horror
U||   from which the most daring imagination must recoil. We know of nothing
U||   so agonizing upon Earth—we can dream of nothing half so hideous in the
U||   realms of the nethermost Hell. And thus all narratives upon this topic
U||   have an interest profound; an interest, nevertheless, which, through
U||   the sacred awe of the topic itself, very properly and very peculiarly
U||   depends upon our conviction of the truth of the matter narrated. What I
U||   have now to tell is of my own actual knowledge—of my own positive and
U||   personal experience.
U||   For several years I had been subject to attacks of the singular
U||   disorder which physicians have agreed to term catalepsy, in default of
U||   a more definitive title. Although both the immediate and the
U||   predisposing causes, and even the actual diagnosis, of this disease are
U||   still mysterious, its obvious and apparent character is sufficiently
U||   well understood. Its variations seem to be chiefly of degree. Sometimes
U||   the patient lies, for a day only, or even for a shorter period, in a
U||   species of exaggerated lethargy. He is senseless and externally
U||   motionless; but the pulsation of the heart is still faintly
U||   perceptible; some traces of warmth remain; a slight color lingers
U||   within the centre of the cheek; and, upon application of a mirror to
U||   the lips, we can detect a torpid, unequal, and vacillating action of
U||   the lungs. Then again the duration of the trance is for weeks—even for
U||   months; while the closest scrutiny, and the most rigorous medical
U||   tests, fail to establish any material distinction between the state of
U||   the sufferer and what we conceive of absolute death. Very usually he is
U||   saved from premature interment solely by the knowledge of his friends
U||   that he has been previously subject to catalepsy, by the consequent
U||   suspicion excited, and, above all, by the non-appearance of decay. The
U||   advances of the malady are, luckily, gradual. The first manifestations,
U||   although marked, are unequivocal. The fits grow successively more and
U||   more distinctive, and endure each for a longer term than the preceding.
U||   In this lies the principal security from inhumation. The unfortunate
U||   whose first attack should be of the extreme character which is
U||   occasionally seen, would almost inevitably be consigned alive to the
U||   tomb.
U||   My own case differed in no important particular from those mentioned in
U||   medical books. Sometimes, without any apparent cause, I sank, little by
U||   little, into a condition of semi-syncope, or half swoon; and, in this
U||   condition, without pain, without ability to stir, or, strictly
U||   speaking, to think, but with a dull lethargic consciousness of life and
U||   of the presence of those who surrounded my bed, I remained, until the
U||   crisis of the disease restored me, suddenly, to perfect sensation. At
U||   other times I was quickly and impetuously smitten. I grew sick, and
U||   numb, and chilly, and dizzy, and so fell prostrate at once. Then, for
U||   weeks, all was void, and black, and silent, and Nothing became the
U||   universe. Total annihilation could be no more. From these latter
U||   attacks I awoke, however, with a gradation slow in proportion to the
U||   suddenness of the seizure. Just as the day dawns to the friendless and
U||   houseless beggar who roams the streets throughout the long desolate
U||   winter night—just so tardily—just so wearily—just so cheerily came back
U||   the light of the Soul to me.
U||   Apart from the tendency to trance, however, my general health appeared
U||   to be good; nor could I perceive that it was at all affected by the one
U||   prevalent malady—unless, indeed, an idiosyncrasy in my ordinary sleep
U||   may be looked upon as superinduced. Upon awaking from slumber, I could
U||   never gain, at once, thorough possession of my senses, and always
U||   remained, for many minutes, in much bewilderment and perplexity—the
U||   mental faculties in general, but the memory in especial, being in a
U||   condition of absolute abeyance.
U||   In all that I endured there was no physical suffering but of moral
U||   distress an infinitude. My fancy grew charnel, I talked “of worms, of
U||   tombs, and epitaphs.” I was lost in reveries of death, and the idea of
U||   premature burial held continual possession of my brain. The ghastly
U||   Danger to which I was subjected haunted me day and night. In the
U||   former, the torture of meditation was excessive—in the latter, supreme.
U||   When the grim Darkness overspread the Earth, then, with every horror of
U||   thought, I shook—shook as the quivering plumes upon the hearse. When
U||   Nature could endure wakefulness no longer, it was with a struggle that
U||   I consented to sleep—for I shuddered to reflect that, upon awaking, I
U||   might find myself the tenant of a grave. And when, finally, I sank into
U||   slumber, it was only to rush at once into a world of phantasms, above
U||   which, with vast, sable, overshadowing wing, hovered, predominant, the
U||   one sepulchral Idea.
U||   From the innumerable images of gloom which thus oppressed me in dreams,
U||   I select for record but a solitary vision. Methought I was immersed in
U||   a cataleptic trance of more than usual duration and profundity.
U||   Suddenly there came an icy hand upon my forehead, and an impatient,
U||   gibbering voice whispered the word “Arise!” within my ear.
U||   I sat erect. The darkness was total. I could not see the figure of him
U||   who had aroused me. I could call to mind neither the period at which I
U||   had fallen into the trance, nor the locality in which I then lay. While
U||   I remained motionless, and busied in endeavors to collect my thought,
U||   the cold hand grasped me fiercely by the wrist, shaking it petulantly,
U||   while the gibbering voice said again:
U||   “Arise! did I not bid thee arise?”
U||   “And who,” I demanded, “art thou?”
U||   “I have no name in the regions which I inhabit,” replied the voice,
U||   mournfully; “I was mortal, but am fiend. I was merciless, but am
U||   pitiful. Thou dost feel that I shudder. My teeth chatter as I speak,
U||   yet it is not with the chilliness of the night—of the night without
U||   end. But this hideousness is insufferable. How canst thou tranquilly
U||   sleep? I cannot rest for the cry of these great agonies. These sights
U||   are more than I can bear. Get thee up! Come with me into the outer
U||   Night, and let me unfold to thee the graves. Is not this a spectacle of
U||   woe?—Behold!”
U||   I looked; and the unseen figure, which still grasped me by the wrist,
U||   had caused to be thrown open the graves of all mankind; and from each
U||   issued the faint phosphoric radiance of decay; so that I could see into
U||   the innermost recesses, and there view the shrouded bodies in their sad
U||   and solemn slumbers with the worm. But alas! the real sleepers were
U||   fewer, by many millions, than those who slumbered not at all; and there
U||   was a feeble struggling; and there was a general sad unrest; and from
U||   out the depths of the countless pits there came a melancholy rustling
U||   from the garments of the buried. And of those who seemed tranquilly to
U||   repose, I saw that a vast number had changed, in a greater or less
U||   degree, the rigid and uneasy position in which they had originally been
U||   entombed. And the voice again said to me as I gazed:
U||   “Is it not—oh! is it not a pitiful sight?” But, before I could find
U||   words to reply, the figure had ceased to grasp my wrist, the phosphoric
U||   lights expired, and the graves were closed with a sudden violence,
U||   while from out them arose a tumult of despairing cries, saying again:
U||   “Is it not—O, God, is it not a very pitiful sight?”
U||   Phantasies such as these, presenting themselves at night, extended
U||   their terrific influence far into my waking hours. My nerves became
U||   thoroughly unstrung, and I fell a prey to perpetual horror. I hesitated
U||   to ride, or to walk, or to indulge in any exercise that would carry me
U||   from home. In fact, I no longer dared trust myself out of the immediate
U||   presence of those who were aware of my proneness to catalepsy, lest,
U||   falling into one of my usual fits, I should be buried before my real
U||   condition could be ascertained. I doubted the care, the fidelity of my
U||   dearest friends. I dreaded that, in some trance of more than customary
U||   duration, they might be prevailed upon to regard me as irrecoverable. I
U||   even went so far as to fear that, as I occasioned much trouble, they
U||   might be glad to consider any very protracted attack as sufficient
U||   excuse for getting rid of me altogether. It was in vain they endeavored
U||   to reassure me by the most solemn promises. I exacted the most sacred
U||   oaths, that under no circumstances they would bury me until
U||   decomposition had so materially advanced as to render farther
U||   preservation impossible. And, even then, my mortal terrors would listen
U||   to no reason—would accept no consolation. I entered into a series of
U||   elaborate precautions. Among other things, I had the family vault so
U||   remodelled as to admit of being readily opened from within. The
U||   slightest pressure upon a long lever that extended far into the tomb
U||   would cause the iron portal to fly back. There were arrangements also
U||   for the free admission of air and light, and convenient receptacles for
U||   food and water, within immediate reach of the coffin intended for my
U||   reception. This coffin was warmly and softly padded, and was provided
U||   with a lid, fashioned upon the principle of the vault-door, with the
U||   addition of springs so contrived that the feeblest movement of the body
U||   would be sufficient to set it at liberty. Besides all this, there was
U||   suspended from the roof of the tomb, a large bell, the rope of which,
U||   it was designed, should extend through a hole in the coffin, and so be
U||   fastened to one of the hands of the corpse. But, alas? what avails the
U||   vigilance against the Destiny of man? Not even these well-contrived
U||   securities sufficed to save from the uttermost agonies of living
U||   inhumation, a wretch to these agonies foredoomed!
U||   There arrived an epoch—as often before there had arrived—in which I
U||   found myself emerging from total unconsciousness into the first feeble
U||   and indefinite sense of existence. Slowly—with a tortoise
U||   gradation—approached the faint gray dawn of the psychal day. A torpid
U||   uneasiness. An apathetic endurance of dull pain. No care—no hope—no
U||   effort. Then, after a long interval, a ringing in the ears; then, after
U||   a lapse still longer, a prickling or tingling sensation in the
U||   extremities; then a seemingly eternal period of pleasurable quiescence,
U||   during which the awakening feelings are struggling into thought; then a
U||   brief re-sinking into non-entity; then a sudden recovery. At length the
U||   slight quivering of an eyelid, and immediately thereupon, an electric
U||   shock of a terror, deadly and indefinite, which sends the blood in
U||   torrents from the temples to the heart. And now the first positive
U||   effort to think. And now the first endeavor to remember. And now a
U||   partial and evanescent success. And now the memory has so far regained
U||   its dominion, that, in some measure, I am cognizant of my state. I feel
U||   that I am not awaking from ordinary sleep. I recollect that I have been
U||   subject to catalepsy. And now, at last, as if by the rush of an ocean,
U||   my shuddering spirit is overwhelmed by the one grim Danger—by the one
U||   spectral and ever-prevalent idea.
U||   For some minutes after this fancy possessed me, I remained without
U||   motion. And why? I could not summon courage to move. I dared not make
U||   the effort which was to satisfy me of my fate—and yet there was
U||   something at my heart which whispered me it was sure. Despair—such as
U||   no other species of wretchedness ever calls into being—despair alone
U||   urged me, after long irresolution, to uplift the heavy lids of my eyes.
U||   I uplifted them. It was dark—all dark. I knew that the fit was over. I
U||   knew that the crisis of my disorder had long passed. I knew that I had
U||   now fully recovered the use of my visual faculties—and yet it was
U||   dark—all dark—the intense and utter raylessness of the Night that
U||   endureth for evermore.
U||   I endeavored to shriek; and my lips and my parched tongue moved
U||   convulsively together in the attempt—but no voice issued from the
U||   cavernous lungs, which oppressed as if by the weight of some incumbent
U||   mountain, gasped and palpitated, with the heart, at every elaborate and
U||   struggling inspiration.
U||   The movement of the jaws, in this effort to cry aloud, showed me that
U||   they were bound up, as is usual with the dead. I felt, too, that I lay
U||   upon some hard substance; and by something similar my sides were, also,
U||   closely compressed. So far, I had not ventured to stir any of my
U||   limbs—but now I violently threw up my arms, which had been lying at
U||   length, with the wrists crossed. They struck a solid wooden substance,
U||   which extended above my person at an elevation of not more than six
U||   inches from my face. I could no longer doubt that I reposed within a
U||   coffin at last.
U||   And now, amid all my infinite miseries, came sweetly the cherub
U||   Hope—for I thought of my precautions. I writhed, and made spasmodic
U||   exertions to force open the lid: it would not move. I felt my wrists
U||   for the bell-rope: it was not to be found. And now the Comforter fled
U||   for ever, and a still sterner Despair reigned triumphant; for I could
U||   not help perceiving the absence of the paddings which I had so
U||   carefully prepared—and then, too, there came suddenly to my nostrils
U||   the strong peculiar odor of moist earth. The conclusion was
U||   irresistible. I was not within the vault. I had fallen into a trance
U||   while absent from home—while among strangers—when, or how, I could not
U||   remember—and it was they who had buried me as a dog—nailed up in some
U||   common coffin—and thrust deep, deep, and for ever, into some ordinary
U||   and nameless grave.
U||   As this awful conviction forced itself, thus, into the innermost
U||   chambers of my soul, I once again struggled to cry aloud. And in this
U||   second endeavor I succeeded. A long, wild, and continuous shriek, or
U||   yell of agony, resounded through the realms of the subterranean Night.
U||   “Hillo! hillo, there!” said a gruff voice, in reply.
U||   “What the devil’s the matter now!” said a second.
U||   “Get out o’ that!” said a third.
U||   “What do you mean by yowling in that ere kind of style, like a
U||   cattymount?” said a fourth; and hereupon I was seized and shaken
U||   without ceremony, for several minutes, by a junto of very rough-looking
U||   individuals. They did not arouse me from my slumber—for I was wide
U||   awake when I screamed—but they restored me to the full possession of my
U||   memory.
U||   This adventure occurred near Richmond, in Virginia. Accompanied by a
U||   friend, I had proceeded, upon a gunning expedition, some miles down the
U||   banks of the James River. Night approached, and we were overtaken by a
U||   storm. The cabin of a small sloop lying at anchor in the stream, and
U||   laden with garden mould, afforded us the only available shelter. We
U||   made the best of it, and passed the night on board. I slept in one of
U||   the only two berths in the vessel—and the berths of a sloop of sixty or
U||   twenty tons need scarcely be described. That which I occupied had no
U||   bedding of any kind. Its extreme width was eighteen inches. The
U||   distance of its bottom from the deck overhead was precisely the same. I
U||   found it a matter of exceeding difficulty to squeeze myself in.
U||   Nevertheless, I slept soundly, and the whole of my vision—for it was no
U||   dream, and no nightmare—arose naturally from the circumstances of my
U||   position—from my ordinary bias of thought—and from the difficulty, to
U||   which I have alluded, of collecting my senses, and especially of
U||   regaining my memory, for a long time after awaking from slumber. The
U||   men who shook me were the crew of the sloop, and some laborers engaged
U||   to unload it. From the load itself came the earthly smell. The bandage
U||   about the jaws was a silk handkerchief in which I had bound up my head,
U||   in default of my customary nightcap.
U||   The tortures endured, however, were indubitably quite equal for the
U||   time, to those of actual sepulture. They were fearfully—they were
U||   inconceivably hideous; but out of Evil proceeded Good; for their very
U||   excess wrought in my spirit an inevitable revulsion. My soul acquired
U||   tone—acquired temper. I went abroad. I took vigorous exercise. I
U||   breathed the free air of Heaven. I thought upon other subjects than
U||   Death. I discarded my medical books. “Buchan” I burned. I read no
U||   “Night Thoughts”—no fustian about churchyards—no bugaboo tales—such as
U||   this. In short, I became a new man, and lived a man’s life. From that
U||   memorable night, I dismissed forever my charnel apprehensions, and with
U||   them vanished the cataleptic disorder, of which, perhaps, they had been
U||   less the consequence than the cause.
U||   There are moments when, even to the sober eye of Reason, the world of
U||   our sad Humanity may assume the semblance of a Hell—but the imagination
U||   of man is no Carathis, to explore with impunity its every cavern. Alas!
U||   the grim legion of sepulchral terrors cannot be regarded as altogether
U||   fanciful—but, like the Demons in whose company Afrasiab made his voyage
U||   down the Oxus, they must sleep, or they will devour us—they must be
U||   suffered to slumber, or we perish.
