U||   The garden like a lady fair was cut,
U||       That lay as if she slumbered in delight,
U||   And to the open skies her eyes did shut.
U||       The azure fields of Heaven were ’sembled right
U||       In a large round, set with the flowers of light.
U||   The flowers de luce, and the round sparks of dew
U||   That hung upon their azure leaves did shew
U||   Like twinkling stars that sparkle in the evening blue.
U||                       —Giles Fletcher.
U||   From his cradle to his grave a gale of prosperity bore my friend
U||   Ellison along. Nor do I use the word prosperity in its mere worldly
U||   sense. I mean it as synonymous with happiness. The person of whom I
U||   speak seemed born for the purpose of foreshadowing the doctrines of
U||   Turgot, Price, Priestley, and Condorcet—of exemplifying by individual
U||   instance what has been deemed the chimera of the perfectionists. In the
U||   brief existence of Ellison I fancy that I have seen refuted the dogma,
U||   that in man’s very nature lies some hidden principle, the antagonist of
U||   bliss. An anxious examination of his career has given me to understand
U||   that in general, from the violation of a few simple laws of humanity
U||   arises the wretchedness of mankind—that as a species we have in our
U||   possession the as yet unwrought elements of content—and that, even now,
U||   in the present darkness and madness of all thought on the great
U||   question of the social condition, it is not impossible that man, the
U||   individual, under certain unusual and highly fortuitous conditions, may
U||   be happy.
U||   With opinions such as these my young friend, too, was fully imbued, and
U||   thus it is worthy of observation that the uninterrupted enjoyment which
U||   distinguished his life was, in great measure, the result of preconcert.
U||   It is indeed evident that with less of the instinctive philosophy
U||   which, now and then, stands so well in the stead of experience, Mr.
U||   Ellison would have found himself precipitated, by the very
U||   extraordinary success of his life, into the common vortex of
U||   unhappiness which yawns for those of pre-eminent endowments. But it is
U||   by no means my object to pen an essay on happiness. The ideas of my
U||   friend may be summed up in a few words. He admitted but four elementary
U||   principles, or more strictly, conditions of bliss. That which he
U||   considered chief was (strange to say!) the simple and purely physical
U||   one of free exercise in the open air. “The health,” he said,
U||   “attainable by other means is scarcely worth the name.” He instanced
U||   the ecstasies of the fox-hunter, and pointed to the tillers of the
U||   earth, the only people who, as a class, can be fairly considered
U||   happier than others. His second condition was the love of woman. His
U||   third, and most difficult of realization, was the contempt of ambition.
U||   His fourth was an object of unceasing pursuit; and he held that, other
U||   things being equal, the extent of attainable happiness was in
U||   proportion to the spirituality of this object.
U||   Ellison was remarkable in the continuous profusion of good gifts
U||   lavished upon him by fortune. In personal grace and beauty he exceeded
U||   all men. His intellect was of that order to which the acquisition of
U||   knowledge is less a labor than an intuition and a necessity. His family
U||   was one of the most illustrious of the empire. His bride was the
U||   loveliest and most devoted of women. His possessions had been always
U||   ample; but on the attainment of his majority, it was discovered that
U||   one of those extraordinary freaks of fate had been played in his behalf
U||   which startle the whole social world amid which they occur, and seldom
U||   fail radically to alter the moral constitution of those who are their
U||   objects.
U||   It appears that about a hundred years before Mr. Ellison’s coming of
U||   age, there had died, in a remote province, one Mr. Seabright Ellison.
U||   This gentleman had amassed a princely fortune, and, having no immediate
U||   connections, conceived the whim of suffering his wealth to accumulate
U||   for a century after his decease. Minutely and sagaciously directing the
U||   various modes of investment, he bequeathed the aggregate amount to the
U||   nearest of blood, bearing the name of Ellison, who should be alive at
U||   the end of the hundred years. Many attempts had been made to set aside
U||   this singular bequest; their ex post facto character rendered them
U||   abortive; but the attention of a jealous government was aroused, and a
U||   legislative act finally obtained, forbidding all similar accumulations.
U||   This act, however, did not prevent young Ellison from entering into
U||   possession, on his twenty-first birthday, as the heir of his ancestor
U||   Seabright, of a fortune of four hundred and fifty millions of dollars.
U||   (*1)
U||   When it had become known that such was the enormous wealth inherited,
U||   there were, of course, many speculations as to the mode of its
U||   disposal. The magnitude and the immediate availability of the sum
U||   bewildered all who thought on the topic. The possessor of any
U||   appreciable amount of money might have been imagined to perform any one
U||   of a thousand things. With riches merely surpassing those of any
U||   citizen, it would have been easy to suppose him engaging to supreme
U||   excess in the fashionable extravagances of his time—or busying himself
U||   with political intrigue—or aiming at ministerial power—or purchasing
U||   increase of nobility—or collecting large museums of virtu—or playing
U||   the munificent patron of letters, of science, of art—or endowing, and
U||   bestowing his name upon extensive institutions of charity. But for the
U||   inconceivable wealth in the actual possession of the heir, these
U||   objects and all ordinary objects were felt to afford too limited a
U||   field. Recourse was had to figures, and these but sufficed to confound.
U||   It was seen that, even at three per cent., the annual income of the
U||   inheritance amounted to no less than thirteen millions and five hundred
U||   thousand dollars; which was one million and one hundred and twenty-five
U||   thousand per month; or thirty-six thousand nine hundred and eighty-six
U||   per day; or one thousand five hundred and forty-one per hour; or six
U||   and twenty dollars for every minute that flew. Thus the usual track of
U||   supposition was thoroughly broken up. Men knew not what to imagine.
U||   There were some who even conceived that Mr. Ellison would divest
U||   himself of at least one-half of his fortune, as of utterly superfluous
U||   opulence—enriching whole troops of his relatives by division of his
U||   superabundance. To the nearest of these he did, in fact, abandon the
U||   very unusual wealth which was his own before the inheritance.
U||   I was not surprised, however, to perceive that he had long made up his
U||   mind on a point which had occasioned so much discussion to his friends.
U||   Nor was I greatly astonished at the nature of his decision. In regard
U||   to individual charities he had satisfied his conscience. In the
U||   possibility of any improvement, properly so called, being effected by
U||   man himself in the general condition of man, he had (I am sorry to
U||   confess it) little faith. Upon the whole, whether happily or unhappily,
U||   he was thrown back, in very great measure, upon self.
U||   In the widest and noblest sense he was a poet. He comprehended,
U||   moreover, the true character, the august aims, the supreme majesty and
U||   dignity of the poetic sentiment. The fullest, if not the sole proper
U||   satisfaction of this sentiment he instinctively felt to lie in the
U||   creation of novel forms of beauty. Some peculiarities, either in his
U||   early education, or in the nature of his intellect, had tinged with
U||   what is termed materialism all his ethical speculations; and it was
U||   this bias, perhaps, which led him to believe that the most advantageous
U||   at least, if not the sole legitimate field for the poetic exercise,
U||   lies in the creation of novel moods of purely physical loveliness. Thus
U||   it happened he became neither musician nor poet—if we use this latter
U||   term in its every-day acceptation. Or it might have been that he
U||   neglected to become either, merely in pursuance of his idea that in
U||   contempt of ambition is to be found one of the essential principles of
U||   happiness on earth. Is it not indeed, possible that, while a high order
U||   of genius is necessarily ambitious, the highest is above that which is
U||   termed ambition? And may it not thus happen that many far greater than
U||   Milton have contentedly remained “mute and inglorious?” I believe that
U||   the world has never seen—and that, unless through some series of
U||   accidents goading the noblest order of mind into distasteful exertion,
U||   the world will never see—that full extent of triumphant execution, in
U||   the richer domains of art, of which the human nature is absolutely
U||   capable.
U||   Ellison became neither musician nor poet; although no man lived more
U||   profoundly enamored of music and poetry. Under other circumstances than
U||   those which invested him, it is not impossible that he would have
U||   become a painter. Sculpture, although in its nature rigorously poetical
U||   was too limited in its extent and consequences, to have occupied, at
U||   any time, much of his attention. And I have now mentioned all the
U||   provinces in which the common understanding of the poetic sentiment has
U||   declared it capable of expatiating. But Ellison maintained that the
U||   richest, the truest, and most natural, if not altogether the most
U||   extensive province, had been unaccountably neglected. No definition had
U||   spoken of the landscape-gardener as of the poet; yet it seemed to my
U||   friend that the creation of the landscape-garden offered to the proper
U||   Muse the most magnificent of opportunities. Here, indeed, was the
U||   fairest field for the display of imagination in the endless combining
U||   of forms of novel beauty; the elements to enter into combination being,
U||   by a vast superiority, the most glorious which the earth could afford.
U||   In the multiform and multicolor of the flowers and the trees, he
U||   recognised the most direct and energetic efforts of Nature at physical
U||   loveliness. And in the direction or concentration of this effort—or,
U||   more properly, in its adaptation to the eyes which were to behold it on
U||   earth—he perceived that he should be employing the best means—laboring
U||   to the greatest advantage—in the fulfilment, not only of his own
U||   destiny as poet, but of the august purposes for which the Deity had
U||   implanted the poetic sentiment in man.
U||   “Its adaptation to the eyes which were to behold it on earth.” In his
U||   explanation of this phraseology, Mr. Ellison did much toward solving
U||   what has always seemed to me an enigma:—I mean the fact (which none but
U||   the ignorant dispute) that no such combination of scenery exists in
U||   nature as the painter of genius may produce. No such paradises are to
U||   be found in reality as have glowed on the canvas of Claude. In the most
U||   enchanting of natural landscapes, there will always be found a defect
U||   or an excess—many excesses and defects. While the component parts may
U||   defy, individually, the highest skill of the artist, the arrangement of
U||   these parts will always be susceptible of improvement. In short, no
U||   position can be attained on the wide surface of the natural earth, from
U||   which an artistical eye, looking steadily, will not find matter of
U||   offence in what is termed the “composition” of the landscape. And yet
U||   how unintelligible is this! In all other matters we are justly
U||   instructed to regard nature as supreme. With her details we shrink from
U||   competition. Who shall presume to imitate the colors of the tulip, or
U||   to improve the proportions of the lily of the valley? The criticism
U||   which says, of sculpture or portraiture, that here nature is to be
U||   exalted or idealized rather than imitated, is in error. No pictorial or
U||   sculptural combinations of points of human liveliness do more than
U||   approach the living and breathing beauty. In landscape alone is the
U||   principle of the critic true; and, having felt its truth here, it is
U||   but the headlong spirit of generalization which has led him to
U||   pronounce it true throughout all the domains of art. Having, I say,
U||   felt its truth here; for the feeling is no affectation or chimera. The
U||   mathematics afford no more absolute demonstrations than the sentiments
U||   of his art yields the artist. He not only believes, but positively
U||   knows, that such and such apparently arbitrary arrangements of matter
U||   constitute and alone constitute the true beauty. His reasons, however,
U||   have not yet been matured into expression. It remains for a more
U||   profound analysis than the world has yet seen, fully to investigate and
U||   express them. Nevertheless he is confirmed in his instinctive opinions
U||   by the voice of all his brethren. Let a “composition” be defective; let
U||   an emendation be wrought in its mere arrangement of form; let this
U||   emendation be submitted to every artist in the world; by each will its
U||   necessity be admitted. And even far more than this; in remedy of the
U||   defective composition, each insulated member of the fraternity would
U||   have suggested the identical emendation.
U||   I repeat that in landscape arrangements alone is the physical nature
U||   susceptible of exaltation, and that, therefore, her susceptibility of
U||   improvement at this one point, was a mystery I had been unable to
U||   solve. My own thoughts on the subject had rested in the idea that the
U||   primitive intention of nature would have so arranged the earth’s
U||   surface as to have fulfilled at all points man’s sense of perfection in
U||   the beautiful, the sublime, or the picturesque; but that this primitive
U||   intention had been frustrated by the known geological
U||   disturbances—disturbances of form and color—grouping, in the correction
U||   or allaying of which lies the soul of art. The force of this idea was
U||   much weakened, however, by the necessity which it involved of
U||   considering the disturbances abnormal and unadapted to any purpose. It
U||   was Ellison who suggested that they were prognostic of death. He thus
U||   explained:—Admit the earthly immortality of man to have been the first
U||   intention. We have then the primitive arrangement of the earth’s
U||   surface adapted to his blissful estate, as not existent but designed.
U||   The disturbances were the preparations for his subsequently conceived
U||   deathful condition.
U||   “Now,” said my friend, “what we regard as exaltation of the landscape
U||   may be really such, as respects only the moral or human point of view.
U||   Each alteration of the natural scenery may possibly effect a blemish in
U||   the picture, if we can suppose this picture viewed at large—in
U||   mass—from some point distant from the earth’s surface, although not
U||   beyond the limits of its atmosphere. It is easily understood that what
U||   might improve a closely scrutinized detail, may at the same time injure
U||   a general or more distantly observed effect. There may be a class of
U||   beings, human once, but now invisible to humanity, to whom, from afar,
U||   our disorder may seem order—our unpicturesqueness picturesque; in a
U||   word, the earth-angels, for whose scrutiny more especially than our
U||   own, and for whose death-refined appreciation of the beautiful, may
U||   have been set in array by God the wide landscape-gardens of the
U||   hemispheres.”
U||   In the course of discussion, my friend quoted some passages from a
U||   writer on landscape-gardening who has been supposed to have well
U||   treated his theme:
U||   “There are properly but two styles of landscape-gardening, the natural
U||   and the artificial. One seeks to recall the original beauty of the
U||   country, by adapting its means to the surrounding scenery, cultivating
U||   trees in harmony with the hills or plain of the neighboring land;
U||   detecting and bringing into practice those nice relations of size,
U||   proportion, and color which, hid from the common observer, are revealed
U||   everywhere to the experienced student of nature. The result of the
U||   natural style of gardening, is seen rather in the absence of all
U||   defects and incongruities—in the prevalence of a healthy harmony and
U||   order—than in the creation of any special wonders or miracles. The
U||   artificial style has as many varieties as there are different tastes to
U||   gratify. It has a certain general relation to the various styles of
U||   building. There are the stately avenues and retirements of Versailles;
U||   Italian terraces; and a various mixed old English style, which bears
U||   some relation to the domestic Gothic or English Elizabethan
U||   architecture. Whatever may be said against the abuses of the artificial
U||   landscape-gardening, a mixture of pure art in a garden scene adds to it
U||   a great beauty. This is partly pleasing to the eye, by the show of
U||   order and design, and partly moral. A terrace, with an old moss-covered
U||   balustrade, calls up at once to the eye the fair forms that have passed
U||   there in other days. The slightest exhibition of art is an evidence of
U||   care and human interest.”
U||   “From what I have already observed,” said Ellison, “you will understand
U||   that I reject the idea, here expressed, of recalling the original
U||   beauty of the country. The original beauty is never so great as that
U||   which may be introduced. Of course, every thing depends on the
U||   selection of a spot with capabilities. What is said about detecting and
U||   bringing into practice nice relations of size, proportion, and color,
U||   is one of those mere vaguenesses of speech which serve to veil
U||   inaccuracy of thought. The phrase quoted may mean any thing, or
U||   nothing, and guides in no degree. That the true result of the natural
U||   style of gardening is seen rather in the absence of all defects and
U||   incongruities than in the creation of any special wonders or miracles,
U||   is a proposition better suited to the grovelling apprehension of the
U||   herd than to the fervid dreams of the man of genius. The negative merit
