U||   would elevate Addison into apotheosis. In truth, while that virtue
U||   which consists in the mere avoidance of vice appeals directly to the
U||   understanding, and can thus be circumscribed in rule, the loftier
U||   virtue, which flames in creation, can be apprehended in its results
U||   alone. Rule applies but to the merits of denial—to the excellencies
U||   which refrain. Beyond these, the critical art can but suggest. We may
U||   be instructed to build a “Cato,” but we are in vain told how to
U||   conceive a Parthenon or an “Inferno.” The thing done, however; the
U||   wonder accomplished; and the capacity for apprehension becomes
U||   universal. The sophists of the negative school who, through inability
U||   to create, have scoffed at creation, are now found the loudest in
U||   applause. What, in its chrysalis condition of principle, affronted
U||   their demure reason, never fails, in its maturity of accomplishment, to
U||   extort admiration from their instinct of beauty.
U||   “The author’s observations on the artificial style,” continued Ellison,
U||   “are less objectionable. A mixture of pure art in a garden scene adds
U||   to it a great beauty. This is just; as also is the reference to the
U||   sense of human interest. The principle expressed is
U||   incontrovertible—but there may be something beyond it. There may be an
U||   object in keeping with the principle—an object unattainable by the
U||   means ordinarily possessed by individuals, yet which, if attained,
U||   would lend a charm to the landscape-garden far surpassing that which a
U||   sense of merely human interest could bestow. A poet, having very
U||   unusual pecuniary resources, might, while retaining the necessary idea
U||   of art or culture, or, as our author expresses it, of interest, so
U||   imbue his designs at once with extent and novelty of beauty, as to
U||   convey the sentiment of spiritual interference. It will be seen that,
U||   in bringing about such result, he secures all the advantages of
U||   interest or design, while relieving his work of the harshness or
U||   technicality of the worldly art. In the most rugged of wildernesses—in
U||   the most savage of the scenes of pure nature—there is apparent the art
U||   of a creator; yet this art is apparent to reflection only; in no
U||   respect has it the obvious force of a feeling. Now let us suppose this
U||   sense of the Almighty design to be one step depressed—to be brought
U||   into something like harmony or consistency with the sense of human
U||   art—to form an intermedium between the two:—let us imagine, for
U||   example, a landscape whose combined vastness and definitiveness—whose
U||   united beauty, magnificence, and strangeness, shall convey the idea of
U||   care, or culture, or superintendence, on the part of beings superior,
U||   yet akin to humanity—then the sentiment of interest is preserved, while
U||   the art intervolved is made to assume the air of an intermediate or
U||   secondary nature—a nature which is not God, nor an emanation from God,
U||   but which still is nature in the sense of the handiwork of the angels
U||   that hover between man and God.”
U||   It was in devoting his enormous wealth to the embodiment of a vision
U||   such as this—in the free exercise in the open air ensured by the
U||   personal superintendence of his plans—in the unceasing object which
U||   these plans afforded—in the high spirituality of the object—in the
U||   contempt of ambition which it enabled him truly to feel—in the
U||   perennial springs with which it gratified, without possibility of
U||   satiating, that one master passion of his soul, the thirst for beauty,
U||   above all, it was in the sympathy of a woman, not unwomanly, whose
U||   loveliness and love enveloped his existence in the purple atmosphere of
U||   Paradise, that Ellison thought to find, and found, exemption from the
U||   ordinary cares of humanity, with a far greater amount of positive
U||   happiness than ever glowed in the rapt day-dreams of De Staël.
U||   I despair of conveying to the reader any distinct conception of the
U||   marvels which my friend did actually accomplish. I wish to describe,
U||   but am disheartened by the difficulty of description, and hesitate
U||   between detail and generality. Perhaps the better course will be to
U||   unite the two in their extremes.
U||   Mr. Ellison’s first step regarded, of course, the choice of a locality,
U||   and scarcely had he commenced thinking on this point, when the
U||   luxuriant nature of the Pacific Islands arrested his attention. In
U||   fact, he had made up his mind for a voyage to the South Seas, when a
U||   night’s reflection induced him to abandon the idea. “Were I
U||   misanthropic,” he said, “such a locale would suit me. The thoroughness
U||   of its insulation and seclusion, and the difficulty of ingress and
U||   egress, would in such case be the charm of charms; but as yet I am not
U||   Timon. I wish the composure but not the depression of solitude. There
U||   must remain with me a certain control over the extent and duration of
U||   my repose. There will be frequent hours in which I shall need, too, the
U||   sympathy of the poetic in what I have done. Let me seek, then, a spot
U||   not far from a populous city—whose vicinity, also, will best enable me
U||   to execute my plans.”
U||   In search of a suitable place so situated, Ellison travelled for
U||   several years, and I was permitted to accompany him. A thousand spots
U||   with which I was enraptured he rejected without hesitation, for reasons
U||   which satisfied me, in the end, that he was right. We came at length to
U||   an elevated table-land of wonderful fertility and beauty, affording a
U||   panoramic prospect very little less in extent than that of Aetna, and,
U||   in Ellison’s opinion as well as my own, surpassing the far-famed view
U||   from that mountain in all the true elements of the picturesque.
U||   “I am aware,” said the traveller, as he drew a sigh of deep delight
U||   after gazing on this scene, entranced, for nearly an hour, “I know that
U||   here, in my circumstances, nine-tenths of the most fastidious of men
U||   would rest content. This panorama is indeed glorious, and I should
U||   rejoice in it but for the excess of its glory. The taste of all the
U||   architects I have ever known leads them, for the sake of ‘prospect,’ to
U||   put up buildings on hill-tops. The error is obvious. Grandeur in any of
U||   its moods, but especially in that of extent, startles, excites—and then
U||   fatigues, depresses. For the occasional scene nothing can be better—for
U||   the constant view nothing worse. And, in the constant view, the most
U||   objectionable phase of grandeur is that of extent; the worst phase of
U||   extent, that of distance. It is at war with the sentiment and with the
U||   sense of seclusion—the sentiment and sense which we seek to humor in
U||   ‘retiring to the country.’ In looking from the summit of a mountain we
U||   cannot help feeling abroad in the world. The heart-sick avoid distant
U||   prospects as a pestilence.”
U||   It was not until toward the close of the fourth year of our search that
U||   we found a locality with which Ellison professed himself satisfied. It
U||   is, of course, needless to say where was the locality. The late death
U||   of my friend, in causing his domain to be thrown open to certain
U||   classes of visitors, has given to Arnheim a species of secret and
U||   subdued if not solemn celebrity, similar in kind, although infinitely
U||   superior in degree, to that which so long distinguished Fonthill.
U||   The usual approach to Arnheim was by the river. The visitor left the
U||   city in the early morning. During the forenoon he passed between shores
U||   of a tranquil and domestic beauty, on which grazed innumerable sheep,
U||   their white fleeces spotting the vivid green of rolling meadows. By
U||   degrees the idea of cultivation subsided into that of merely pastoral
U||   care. This slowly became merged in a sense of retirement—this again in
U||   a consciousness of solitude. As the evening approached, the channel
U||   grew more narrow; the banks more and more precipitous; and these latter
U||   were clothed in rich, more profuse, and more sombre foliage. The water
U||   increased in transparency. The stream took a thousand turns, so that at
U||   no moment could its gleaming surface be seen for a greater distance
U||   than a furlong. At every instant the vessel seemed imprisoned within an
U||   enchanted circle, having insuperable and impenetrable walls of foliage,
U||   a roof of ultramarine satin, and no floor—the keel balancing itself
U||   with admirable nicety on that of a phantom bark which, by some accident
U||   having been turned upside down, floated in constant company with the
U||   substantial one, for the purpose of sustaining it. The channel now
U||   became a gorge—although the term is somewhat inapplicable, and I employ
U||   it merely because the language has no word which better represents the
U||   most striking—not the most distinctive—feature of the scene. The
U||   character of gorge was maintained only in the height and parallelism of
U||   the shores; it was lost altogether in their other traits. The walls of
U||   the ravine (through which the clear water still tranquilly flowed)
U||   arose to an elevation of a hundred and occasionally of a hundred and
U||   fifty feet, and inclined so much toward each other as, in a great
U||   measure, to shut out the light of day; while the long plume-like moss
U||   which depended densely from the intertwining shrubberies overhead, gave
U||   the whole chasm an air of funereal gloom. The windings became more
U||   frequent and intricate, and seemed often as if returning in upon
U||   themselves, so that the voyager had long lost all idea of direction. He
U||   was, moreover, enwrapt in an exquisite sense of the strange. The
U||   thought of nature still remained, but her character seemed to have
U||   undergone modification, there was a weird symmetry, a thrilling
U||   uniformity, a wizard propriety in these her works. Not a dead
U||   branch—not a withered leaf—not a stray pebble—not a patch of the brown
U||   earth was anywhere visible. The crystal water welled up against the
U||   clean granite, or the unblemished moss, with a sharpness of outline
U||   that delighted while it bewildered the eye.
U||   Having threaded the mazes of this channel for some hours, the gloom
U||   deepening every moment, a sharp and unexpected turn of the vessel
U||   brought it suddenly, as if dropped from heaven, into a circular basin
U||   of very considerable extent when compared with the width of the gorge.
U||   It was about two hundred yards in diameter, and girt in at all points
U||   but one—that immediately fronting the vessel as it entered—by hills
U||   equal in general height to the walls of the chasm, although of a
U||   thoroughly different character. Their sides sloped from the water’s
U||   edge at an angle of some forty-five degrees, and they were clothed from
U||   base to summit—not a perceptible point escaping—in a drapery of the
U||   most gorgeous flower-blossoms; scarcely a green leaf being visible
U||   among the sea of odorous and fluctuating color. This basin was of great
U||   depth, but so transparent was the water that the bottom, which seemed
U||   to consist of a thick mass of small round alabaster pebbles, was
U||   distinctly visible by glimpses—that is to say, whenever the eye could
U||   permit itself not to see, far down in the inverted heaven, the
U||   duplicate blooming of the hills. On these latter there were no trees,
U||   nor even shrubs of any size. The impressions wrought on the observer
U||   were those of richness, warmth, color, quietude, uniformity, softness,
U||   delicacy, daintiness, voluptuousness, and a miraculous extremeness of
U||   culture that suggested dreams of a new race of fairies, laborious,
U||   tasteful, magnificent, and fastidious; but as the eye traced upward the
U||   myriad-tinted slope, from its sharp junction with the water to its
U||   vague termination amid the folds of overhanging cloud, it became,
U||   indeed, difficult not to fancy a panoramic cataract of rubies,
U||   sapphires, opals, and golden onyxes, rolling silently out of the sky.
U||   The visitor, shooting suddenly into this bay from out the gloom of the
U||   ravine, is delighted but astounded by the full orb of the declining
U||   sun, which he had supposed to be already far below the horizon, but
U||   which now confronts him, and forms the sole termination of an otherwise
U||   limitless vista seen through another chasm-like rift in the hills.
U||   But here the voyager quits the vessel which has borne him so far, and
U||   descends into a light canoe of ivory, stained with arabesque devices in
U||   vivid scarlet, both within and without. The poop and beak of this boat
U||   arise high above the water, with sharp points, so that the general form
U||   is that of an irregular crescent. It lies on the surface of the bay
U||   with the proud grace of a swan. On its ermined floor reposes a single
U||   feathery paddle of satin-wood; but no oarsmen or attendant is to be
U||   seen. The guest is bidden to be of good cheer—that the fates will take
U||   care of him. The larger vessel disappears, and he is left alone in the
U||   canoe, which lies apparently motionless in the middle of the lake.
U||   While he considers what course to pursue, however, he becomes aware of
U||   a gentle movement in the fairy bark. It slowly swings itself around
U||   until its prow points toward the sun. It advances with a gentle but
U||   gradually accelerated velocity, while the slight ripples it creates
U||   seem to break about the ivory side in divinest melody—seem to offer the
U||   only possible explanation of the soothing yet melancholy music for
U||   whose unseen origin the bewildered voyager looks around him in vain.
U||   The canoe steadily proceeds, and the rocky gate of the vista is
U||   approached, so that its depths can be more distinctly seen. To the
U||   right arise a chain of lofty hills rudely and luxuriantly wooded. It is
U||   observed, however, that the trait of exquisite cleanness where the bank
U||   dips into the water, still prevails. There is not one token of the
U||   usual river débris. To the left the character of the scene is softer
U||   and more obviously artificial. Here the bank slopes upward from the
U||   stream in a very gentle ascent, forming a broad sward of grass of a
U||   texture resembling nothing so much as velvet, and of a brilliancy of
U||   green which would bear comparison with the tint of the purest emerald.
U||   This plateau varies in width from ten to three hundred yards; reaching
U||   from the river-bank to a wall, fifty feet high, which extends, in an
U||   infinity of curves, but following the general direction of the river,
U||   until lost in the distance to the westward. This wall is of one
U||   continuous rock, and has been formed by cutting perpendicularly the
U||   once rugged precipice of the stream’s southern bank, but no trace of
U||   the labor has been suffered to remain. The chiselled stone has the hue
U||   of ages, and is profusely overhung and overspread with the ivy, the
U||   coral honeysuckle, the eglantine, and the clematis. The uniformity of
U||   the top and bottom lines of the wall is fully relieved by occasional
U||   trees of gigantic height, growing singly or in small groups, both along
U||   the plateau and in the domain behind the wall, but in close proximity
U||   to it; so that frequent limbs (of the black walnut especially) reach
U||   over and dip their pendent extremities into the water. Farther back
U||   within the domain, the vision is impeded by an impenetrable screen of
U||   foliage.
U||   These things are observed during the canoe’s gradual approach to what I
U||   have called the gate of the vista. On drawing nearer to this, however,
U||   its chasm-like appearance vanishes; a new outlet from the bay is
U||   discovered to the left—in which direction the wall is also seen to
U||   sweep, still following the general course of the stream. Down this new
U||   opening the eye cannot penetrate very far; for the stream, accompanied
U||   by the wall, still bends to the left, until both are swallowed up by
U||   the leaves.
U||   The boat, nevertheless, glides magically into the winding channel; and
U||   here the shore opposite the wall is found to resemble that opposite the
U||   wall in the straight vista. Lofty hills, rising occasionally into
U||   mountains, and covered with vegetation in wild luxuriance, still shut
U||   in the scene.
U||   Floating gently onward, but with a velocity slightly augmented, the
U||   voyager, after many short turns, finds his progress apparently barred
U||   by a gigantic gate or rather door of burnished gold, elaborately carved
U||   and fretted, and reflecting the direct rays of the now fast-sinking sun
U||   with an effulgence that seems to wreath the whole surrounding forest in
U||   flames. This gate is inserted in the lofty wall; which here appears to
