U||   A Pendant to “The Domain of Arnheim”
U||   During A pedestrian trip last summer, through one or two of the river
U||   counties of New York, I found myself, as the day declined, somewhat
U||   embarrassed about the road I was pursuing. The land undulated very
U||   remarkably; and my path, for the last hour, had wound about and about
U||   so confusedly, in its effort to keep in the valleys, that I no longer
U||   knew in what direction lay the sweet village of B——, where I had
U||   determined to stop for the night. The sun had scarcely shone—strictly
U||   speaking—during the day, which nevertheless, had been unpleasantly
U||   warm. A smoky mist, resembling that of the Indian summer, enveloped all
U||   things, and of course, added to my uncertainty. Not that I cared much
U||   about the matter. If I did not hit upon the village before sunset, or
U||   even before dark, it was more than possible that a little Dutch
U||   farmhouse, or something of that kind, would soon make its
U||   appearance—although, in fact, the neighborhood (perhaps on account of
U||   being more picturesque than fertile) was very sparsely inhabited. At
U||   all events, with my knapsack for a pillow, and my hound as a sentry, a
U||   bivouac in the open air was just the thing which would have amused me.
U||   I sauntered on, therefore, quite at ease—Ponto taking charge of my
U||   gun—until at length, just as I had begun to consider whether the
U||   numerous little glades that led hither and thither, were intended to be
U||   paths at all, I was conducted by one of them into an unquestionable
U||   carriage track. There could be no mistaking it. The traces of light
U||   wheels were evident; and although the tall shrubberies and overgrown
U||   undergrowth met overhead, there was no obstruction whatever below, even
U||   to the passage of a Virginian mountain wagon—the most aspiring vehicle,
U||   I take it, of its kind. The road, however, except in being open through
U||   the wood—if wood be not too weighty a name for such an assemblage of
U||   light trees—and except in the particulars of evident wheel-tracks—bore
U||   no resemblance to any road I had before seen. The tracks of which I
U||   speak were but faintly perceptible—having been impressed upon the firm,
U||   yet pleasantly moist surface of—what looked more like green Genoese
U||   velvet than any thing else. It was grass, clearly—but grass such as we
U||   seldom see out of England—so short, so thick, so even, and so vivid in
U||   color. Not a single impediment lay in the wheel-route—not even a chip
U||   or dead twig. The stones that once obstructed the way had been
U||   carefully placed—not thrown—along the sides of the lane, so as to
U||   define its boundaries at bottom with a kind of half-precise,
U||   half-negligent, and wholly picturesque definition. Clumps of wild
U||   flowers grew everywhere, luxuriantly, in the interspaces.
U||   What to make of all this, of course I knew not. Here was art
U||   undoubtedly—that did not surprise me—all roads, in the ordinary sense,
U||   are works of art; nor can I say that there was much to wonder at in the
U||   mere excess of art manifested; all that seemed to have been done, might
U||   have been done here—with such natural “capabilities” (as they have it
U||   in the books on Landscape Gardening)—with very little labor and
U||   expense. No; it was not the amount but the character of the art which
U||   caused me to take a seat on one of the blossomy stones and gaze up and
U||   down this fairy-like avenue for half an hour or more in bewildered
U||   admiration. One thing became more and more evident the longer I gazed:
U||   an artist, and one with a most scrupulous eye for form, had
U||   superintended all these arrangements. The greatest care had been taken
U||   to preserve a due medium between the neat and graceful on the one hand,
U||   and the pittoresque, in the true sense of the Italian term, on the
U||   other. There were few straight, and no long uninterrupted lines. The
U||   same effect of curvature or of color appeared twice, usually, but not
U||   oftener, at any one point of view. Everywhere was variety in
U||   uniformity. It was a piece of “composition,” in which the most
U||   fastidiously critical taste could scarcely have suggested an
U||   emendation.
U||   I had turned to the right as I entered this road, and now, arising, I
U||   continued in the same direction. The path was so serpentine, that at no
U||   moment could I trace its course for more than two or three paces in
U||   advance. Its character did not undergo any material change.
U||   Presently the murmur of water fell gently upon my ear—and in a few
U||   moments afterward, as I turned with the road somewhat more abruptly
U||   than hitherto, I became aware that a building of some kind lay at the
U||   foot of a gentle declivity just before me. I could see nothing
U||   distinctly on account of the mist which occupied all the little valley
U||   below. A gentle breeze, however, now arose, as the sun was about
U||   descending; and while I remained standing on the brow of the slope, the
U||   fog gradually became dissipated into wreaths, and so floated over the
U||   scene.
U||   As it came fully into view—thus gradually as I describe it—piece by
U||   piece, here a tree, there a glimpse of water, and here again the summit
U||   of a chimney, I could scarcely help fancying that the whole was one of
U||   the ingenious illusions sometimes exhibited under the name of
U||   “vanishing pictures.”
U||   By the time, however, that the fog had thoroughly disappeared, the sun
U||   had made its way down behind the gentle hills, and thence, as if with a
U||   slight chassez to the south, had come again fully into sight, glaring
U||   with a purplish lustre through a chasm that entered the valley from the
U||   west. Suddenly, therefore—and as if by the hand of magic—this whole
U||   valley and every thing in it became brilliantly visible.
U||   The first coup d’œil, as the sun slid into the position described,
U||   impressed me very much as I have been impressed, when a boy, by the
U||   concluding scene of some well-arranged theatrical spectacle or
U||   melodrama. Not even the monstrosity of color was wanting; for the
U||   sunlight came out through the chasm, tinted all orange and purple;
U||   while the vivid green of the grass in the valley was reflected more or
U||   less upon all objects from the curtain of vapor that still hung
U||   overhead, as if loth to take its total departure from a scene so
U||   enchantingly beautiful.
U||   The little vale into which I thus peered down from under the fog canopy
U||   could not have been more than four hundred yards long; while in breadth
U||   it varied from fifty to one hundred and fifty or perhaps two hundred.
U||   It was most narrow at its northern extremity, opening out as it tended
U||   southwardly, but with no very precise regularity. The widest portion
U||   was within eighty yards of the southern extreme. The slopes which
U||   encompassed the vale could not fairly be called hills, unless at their
U||   northern face. Here a precipitous ledge of granite arose to a height of
U||   some ninety feet; and, as I have mentioned, the valley at this point
U||   was not more than fifty feet wide; but as the visitor proceeded
U||   southwardly from the cliff, he found on his right hand and on his left,
U||   declivities at once less high, less precipitous, and less rocky. All,
U||   in a word, sloped and softened to the south; and yet the whole vale was
U||   engirdled by eminences, more or less high, except at two points. One of
U||   these I have already spoken of. It lay considerably to the north of
U||   west, and was where the setting sun made its way, as I have before
U||   described, into the amphitheatre, through a cleanly cut natural cleft
U||   in the granite embankment; this fissure might have been ten yards wide
U||   at its widest point, so far as the eye could trace it. It seemed to
U||   lead up, up like a natural causeway, into the recesses of unexplored
U||   mountains and forests. The other opening was directly at the southern
U||   end of the vale. Here, generally, the slopes were nothing more than
U||   gentle inclinations, extending from east to west about one hundred and
U||   fifty yards. In the middle of this extent was a depression, level with
U||   the ordinary floor of the valley. As regards vegetation, as well as in
U||   respect to every thing else, the scene softened and sloped to the
U||   south. To the north—on the craggy precipice—a few paces from the
U||   verge—up sprang the magnificent trunks of numerous hickories, black
U||   walnuts, and chestnuts, interspersed with occasional oak; and the
U||   strong lateral branches thrown out by the walnuts especially, spread
U||   far over the edge of the cliff. Proceeding southwardly, the explorer
U||   saw, at first, the same class of trees, but less and less lofty and
U||   Salvatorish in character; then he saw the gentler elm, succeeded by the
U||   sassafras and locust—these again by the softer linden, red-bud,
U||   catalpa, and maple—these yet again by still more graceful and more
U||   modest varieties. The whole face of the southern declivity was covered
U||   with wild shrubbery alone—an occasional silver willow or white poplar
U||   excepted. In the bottom of the valley itself—(for it must be borne in
U||   mind that the vegetation hitherto mentioned grew only on the cliffs or
U||   hillsides)—were to be seen three insulated trees. One was an elm of
U||   fine size and exquisite form: it stood guard over the southern gate of
U||   the vale. Another was a hickory, much larger than the elm, and
U||   altogether a much finer tree, although both were exceedingly beautiful:
U||   it seemed to have taken charge of the northwestern entrance, springing
U||   from a group of rocks in the very jaws of the ravine, and throwing its
U||   graceful body, at an angle of nearly forty-five degrees, far out into
U||   the sunshine of the amphitheatre. About thirty yards east of this tree
U||   stood, however, the pride of the valley, and beyond all question the
U||   most magnificent tree I have ever seen, unless, perhaps, among the
U||   cypresses of the Itchiatuckanee. It was a triple-stemmed tulip-tree—the
U||   Liriodendron Tulipiferum—one of the natural order of magnolias. Its
U||   three trunks separated from the parent at about three feet from the
U||   soil, and diverging very slightly and gradually, were not more than
U||   four feet apart at the point where the largest stem shot out into
U||   foliage: this was at an elevation of about eighty feet. The whole
U||   height of the principal division was one hundred and twenty feet.
U||   Nothing can surpass in beauty the form, or the glossy, vivid green of
U||   the leaves of the tulip-tree. In the present instance they were fully
U||   eight inches wide; but their glory was altogether eclipsed by the
U||   gorgeous splendor of the profuse blossoms. Conceive, closely
U||   congregated, a million of the largest and most resplendent tulips! Only
U||   thus can the reader get any idea of the picture I would convey. And
U||   then the stately grace of the clean, delicately-granulated columnar
U||   stems, the largest four feet in diameter, at twenty from the ground.
U||   The innumerable blossoms, mingling with those of other trees scarcely
U||   less beautiful, although infinitely less majestic, filled the valley
U||   with more than Arabian perfumes.
U||   The general floor of the amphitheatre was grass of the same character
U||   as that I had found in the road; if anything, more deliciously soft,
U||   thick, velvety, and miraculously green. It was hard to conceive how all
U||   this beauty had been attained.
U||   I have spoken of two openings into the vale. From the one to the
U||   northwest issued a rivulet, which came, gently murmuring and slightly
U||   foaming, down the ravine, until it dashed against the group of rocks
U||   out of which sprang the insulated hickory. Here, after encircling the
U||   tree, it passed on a little to the north of east, leaving the tulip
U||   tree some twenty feet to the south, and making no decided alteration in
U||   its course until it came near the midway between the eastern and
U||   western boundaries of the valley. At this point, after a series of
U||   sweeps, it turned off at right angles and pursued a generally southern
U||   direction meandering as it went—until it became lost in a small lake of
U||   irregular figure (although roughly oval), that lay gleaming near the
U||   lower extremity of the vale. This lakelet was, perhaps, a hundred yards
U||   in diameter at its widest part. No crystal could be clearer than its
U||   waters. Its bottom, which could be distinctly seen, consisted
U||   altogether, of pebbles brilliantly white. Its banks, of the emerald
U||   grass already described, rounded, rather than sloped, off into the
U||   clear heaven below; and so clear was this heaven, so perfectly, at
U||   times, did it reflect all objects above it, that where the true bank
U||   ended and where the mimic one commenced, it was a point of no little
U||   difficulty to determine. The trout, and some other varieties of fish,
U||   with which this pond seemed to be almost inconveniently crowded, had
U||   all the appearance of veritable flying-fish. It was almost impossible
U||   to believe that they were not absolutely suspended in the air. A light
U||   birch canoe that lay placidly on the water, was reflected in its
U||   minutest fibres with a fidelity unsurpassed by the most exquisitely
U||   polished mirror. A small island, fairly laughing with flowers in full
U||   bloom, and affording little more space than just enough for a
U||   picturesque little building, seemingly a fowl-house—arose from the lake
U||   not far from its northern shore—to which it was connected by means of
U||   an inconceivably light-looking and yet very primitive bridge. It was
U||   formed of a single, broad and thick plank of the tulip wood. This was
U||   forty feet long, and spanned the interval between shore and shore with
U||   a slight but very perceptible arch, preventing all oscillation. From
U||   the southern extreme of the lake issued a continuation of the rivulet,
U||   which, after meandering for, perhaps, thirty yards, finally passed
U||   through the “depression” (already described) in the middle of the
U||   southern declivity, and tumbling down a sheer precipice of a hundred
U||   feet, made its devious and unnoticed way to the Hudson.
U||   The lake was deep—at some points thirty feet—but the rivulet seldom
U||   exceeded three, while its greatest width was about eight. Its bottom
U||   and banks were as those of the pond—if a defect could have been
U||   attributed, in point of picturesqueness, it was that of excessive
U||   neatness.
U||   The expanse of the green turf was relieved, here and there, by an
U||   occasional showy shrub, such as the hydrangea, or the common snowball,
U||   or the aromatic seringa; or, more frequently, by a clump of geraniums
U||   blossoming gorgeously in great varieties. These latter grew in pots
U||   which were carefully buried in the soil, so as to give the plants the
U||   appearance of being indigenous. Besides all this, the lawn’s velvet was
U||   exquisitely spotted with sheep—a considerable flock of which roamed
U||   about the vale, in company with three tamed deer, and a vast number of
U||   brilliantly-plumed ducks. A very large mastiff seemed to be in vigilant
U||   attendance upon these animals, each and all.
U||   Along the eastern and western cliffs—where, toward the upper portion of
U||   the amphitheatre, the boundaries were more or less precipitous—grew ivy
U||   in great profusion—so that only here and there could even a glimpse of
U||   the naked rock be obtained. The northern precipice, in like manner, was
U||   almost entirely clothed by grape-vines of rare luxuriance; some
U||   springing from the soil at the base of the cliff, and others from
U||   ledges on its face.
U||   The slight elevation which formed the lower boundary of this little
U||   domain, was crowned by a neat stone wall, of sufficient height to
U||   prevent the escape of the deer. Nothing of the fence kind was
U||   observable elsewhere; for nowhere else was an artificial enclosure
U||   needed:—any stray sheep, for example, which should attempt to make its
U||   way out of the vale by means of the ravine, would find its progress
U||   arrested, after a few yards’ advance, by the precipitous ledge of rock
U||   over which tumbled the cascade that had arrested my attention as I
U||   first drew near the domain. In short, the only ingress or egress was
U||   through a gate occupying a rocky pass in the road, a few paces below
U||   the point at which I stopped to reconnoitre the scene.
U||   I have described the brook as meandering very irregularly through the
U||   whole of its course. Its two general directions, as I have said, were
U||   first from west to east, and then from north to south. At the turn, the
U||   stream, sweeping backward, made an almost circular loop, so as to form
U||   a peninsula which was very nearly an island, and which included about
U||   the sixteenth of an acre. On this peninsula stood a dwelling-house—and
U||   when I say that this house, like the infernal terrace seen by Vathek,
U||   “etait d’une architecture inconnue dans les annales de la terre,” I
U||   mean, merely, that its tout ensemble struck me with the keenest sense
U||   of combined novelty and propriety—in a word, of poetry—(for, than in
U||   the words just employed, I could scarcely give, of poetry in the
U||   abstract, a more rigorous definition)—and I do not mean that merely
U||   outre was perceptible in any respect.
U||   In fact nothing could well be more simple—more utterly unpretending
U||   than this cottage. Its marvellous effect lay altogether in its artistic
U||   arrangement as a picture. I could have fancied, while I looked at it,
U||   that some eminent landscape-painter had built it with his brush.
U||   The point of view from which I first saw the valley, was not
U||   altogether, although it was nearly, the best point from which to survey
U||   the house. I will therefore describe it as I afterwards saw it—from a
U||   position on the stone wall at the southern extreme of the amphitheatre.
U||   The main building was about twenty-four feet long and sixteen
U||   broad—certainly not more. Its total height, from the ground to the apex
U||   of the roof, could not have exceeded eighteen feet. To the west end of
U||   this structure was attached one about a third smaller in all its
U||   proportions:—the line of its front standing back about two yards from
U||   that of the larger house, and the line of its roof, of course, being
U||   considerably depressed below that of the roof adjoining. At right
U||   angles to these buildings, and from the rear of the main one—not
U||   exactly in the middle—extended a third compartment, very small—being,
U||   in general, one-third less than the western wing. The roofs of the two
U||   larger were very steep—sweeping down from the ridge-beam with a long
U||   concave curve, and extending at least four feet beyond the walls in
U||   front, so as to form the roofs of two piazzas. These latter roofs, of
U||   course, needed no support; but as they had the air of needing it,
U||   slight and perfectly plain pillars were inserted at the corners alone.
U||   The roof of the northern wing was merely an extension of a portion of
U||   the main roof. Between the chief building and western wing arose a very
U||   tall and rather slender square chimney of hard Dutch bricks,
U||   alternately black and red:—a slight cornice of projecting bricks at the
U||   top. Over the gables the roofs also projected very much:—in the main
U||   building about four feet to the east and two to the west. The principal
U||   door was not exactly in the main division, being a little to the
U||   east—while the two windows were to the west. These latter did not
U||   extend to the floor, but were much longer and narrower than usual—they
U||   had single shutters like doors—the panes were of lozenge form, but
U||   quite large. The door itself had its upper half of glass, also in
U||   lozenge panes—a movable shutter secured it at night. The door to the
U||   west wing was in its gable, and quite simple—a single window looked out
U||   to the south. There was no external door to the north wing, and it also
U||   had only one window to the east.
U||   The blank wall of the eastern gable was relieved by stairs (with a
U||   balustrade) running diagonally across it—the ascent being from the
U||   south. Under cover of the widely projecting eave these steps gave
U||   access to a door leading to the garret, or rather loft—for it was
U||   lighted only by a single window to the north, and seemed to have been
U||   intended as a store-room.
U||   The piazzas of the main building and western wing had no floors, as is
U||   usual; but at the doors and at each window, large, flat irregular slabs
U||   of granite lay imbedded in the delicious turf, affording comfortable
U||   footing in all weather. Excellent paths of the same material—not nicely
U||   adapted, but with the velvety sod filling frequent intervals between
U||   the stones, led hither and thither from the house, to a crystal spring
U||   about five paces off, to the road, or to one or two out-houses that lay
U||   to the north, beyond the brook, and were thoroughly concealed by a few
U||   locusts and catalpas.
U||   Not more than six steps from the main door of the cottage stood the
U||   dead trunk of a fantastic pear-tree, so clothed from head to foot in
U||   the gorgeous bignonia blossoms that one required no little scrutiny to
U||   determine what manner of sweet thing it could be. From various arms of
U||   this tree hung cages of different kinds. In one, a large wicker
U||   cylinder with a ring at top, revelled a mocking bird; in another an
U||   oriole; in a third the impudent bobolink—while three or four more
U||   delicate prisons were loudly vocal with canaries.
U||   The pillars of the piazza were enwreathed in jasmine and sweet
U||   honeysuckle; while from the angle formed by the main structure and its
U||   west wing, in front, sprang a grape-vine of unexampled luxuriance.
U||   Scorning all restraint, it had clambered first to the lower roof—then
U||   to the higher; and along the ridge of this latter it continued to
U||   writhe on, throwing out tendrils to the right and left, until at length
U||   it fairly attained the east gable, and fell trailing over the stairs.
U||   The whole house, with its wings, was constructed of the old-fashioned
U||   Dutch shingles—broad, and with unrounded corners. It is a peculiarity
U||   of this material to give houses built of it the appearance of being
U||   wider at bottom than at top—after the manner of Egyptian architecture;
U||   and in the present instance, this exceedingly picturesque effect was
U||   aided by numerous pots of gorgeous flowers that almost encompassed the
U||   base of the buildings.
U||   The shingles were painted a dull gray; and the happiness with which
U||   this neutral tint melted into the vivid green of the tulip tree leaves
U||   that partially overshadowed the cottage, can readily be conceived by an
U||   artist.
U||   From the position near the stone wall, as described, the buildings were
U||   seen at great advantage—for the southeastern angle was thrown
U||   forward—so that the eye took in at once the whole of the two fronts,
U||   with the picturesque eastern gable, and at the same time obtained just
U||   a sufficient glimpse of the northern wing, with parts of a pretty roof
U||   to the spring-house, and nearly half of a light bridge that spanned the
U||   brook in the near vicinity of the main buildings.
U||   I did not remain very long on the brow of the hill, although long
U||   enough to make a thorough survey of the scene at my feet. It was clear
U||   that I had wandered from the road to the village, and I had thus good
U||   traveller’s excuse to open the gate before me, and inquire my way, at
U||   all events; so, without more ado, I proceeded.
U||   The road, after passing the gate, seemed to lie upon a natural ledge,
U||   sloping gradually down along the face of the north-eastern cliffs. It
U||   led me on to the foot of the northern precipice, and thence over the
U||   bridge, round by the eastern gable to the front door. In this progress,
U||   I took notice that no sight of the out-houses could be obtained.
U||   As I turned the corner of the gable, the mastiff bounded towards me in
U||   stern silence, but with the eye and the whole air of a tiger. I held
U||   him out my hand, however, in token of amity—and I never yet knew the
U||   dog who was proof against such an appeal to his courtesy. He not only
U||   shut his mouth and wagged his tail, but absolutely offered me his
U||   paw—afterward extending his civilities to Ponto.
U||   As no bell was discernible, I rapped with my stick against the door,
U||   which stood half open. Instantly a figure advanced to the
U||   threshold—that of a young woman about twenty-eight years of
U||   age—slender, or rather slight, and somewhat above the medium height. As
U||   she approached, with a certain modest decision of step altogether
U||   indescribable. I said to myself, “Surely here I have found the
U||   perfection of natural, in contradistinction from artificial grace.” The
U||   second impression which she made on me, but by far the more vivid of
U||   the two, was that of enthusiasm. So intense an expression of romance,
U||   perhaps I should call it, or of unworldliness, as that which gleamed
U||   from her deep-set eyes, had never so sunk into my heart of hearts
U||   before. I know not how it is, but this peculiar expression of the eye,
U||   wreathing itself occasionally into the lips, is the most powerful, if
U||   not absolutely the sole spell, which rivets my interest in woman.
U||   “Romance,” provided my readers fully comprehended what I would here
U||   imply by the word—“romance” and “womanliness” seem to me convertible
U||   terms: and, after all, what man truly loves in woman, is simply her
U||   womanhood. The eyes of Annie (I heard some one from the interior call
U||   her “Annie, darling!”) were “spiritual grey;” her hair, a light
U||   chestnut: this is all I had time to observe of her.
U||   At her most courteous of invitations, I entered—passing first into a
U||   tolerably wide vestibule. Having come mainly to observe, I took notice
U||   that to my right as I stepped in, was a window, such as those in front
U||   of the house; to the left, a door leading into the principal room;
U||   while, opposite me, an open door enabled me to see a small apartment,
U||   just the size of the vestibule, arranged as a study, and having a large
U||   bow window looking out to the north.
U||   Passing into the parlor, I found myself with Mr. Landor—for this, I
U||   afterwards found, was his name. He was civil, even cordial in his
U||   manner, but just then, I was more intent on observing the arrangements
U||   of the dwelling which had so much interested me, than the personal
U||   appearance of the tenant.
U||   The north wing, I now saw, was a bed-chamber, its door opened into the
U||   parlor. West of this door was a single window, looking toward the
U||   brook. At the west end of the parlor, were a fireplace, and a door
U||   leading into the west wing—probably a kitchen.
U||   Nothing could be more rigorously simple than the furniture of the
U||   parlor. On the floor was an ingrain carpet, of excellent texture—a
U||   white ground, spotted with small circular green figures. At the windows
U||   were curtains of snowy white jaconet muslin: they were tolerably full,
U||   and hung decisively, perhaps rather formally in sharp, parallel plaits
U||   to the floor—just to the floor. The walls were prepared with a French
U||   paper of great delicacy, a silver ground, with a faint green cord
U||   running zig-zag throughout. Its expanse was relieved merely by three of
U||   Julien’s exquisite lithographs a trois crayons, fastened to the wall
U||   without frames. One of these drawings was a scene of Oriental luxury,
U||   or rather voluptuousness; another was a “carnival piece,” spirited
U||   beyond compare; the third was a Greek female head—a face so divinely
U||   beautiful, and yet of an expression so provokingly indeterminate, never
U||   before arrested my attention.
U||   The more substantial furniture consisted of a round table, a few chairs
U||   (including a large rocking-chair), and a sofa, or rather “settee;” its
U||   material was plain maple painted a creamy white, slightly interstriped
U||   with green; the seat of cane. The chairs and table were “to match,” but
U||   the forms of all had evidently been designed by the same brain which
U||   planned “the grounds;” it is impossible to conceive anything more
U||   graceful.
U||   On the table were a few books; a large, square, crystal bottle of some
U||   novel perfume; a plain ground glass astral (not solar) lamp with an
U||   Italian shade; and a large vase of resplendently-blooming flowers.
U||   Flowers, indeed, of gorgeous colours and delicate odour formed the sole
U||   mere decoration of the apartment. The fire-place was nearly filled with
U||   a vase of brilliant geranium. On a triangular shelf in each angle of
U||   the room stood also a similar vase, varied only as to its lovely
U||   contents. One or two smaller bouquets adorned the mantel, and late
U||   violets clustered about the open windows.
U||   It is not the purpose of this work to do more than give in detail, a
U||   picture of Mr. Landor’s residence—as I found it. How he made it what it
U||   was—and why—with some particulars of Mr. Landor himself—may, possibly
U||   form the subject of another article.
U||WILLIAM WILSON
U||   What say of it? what say of CONSCIENCE grim,
U||   That spectre in my path?
U||                       —Chamberlayne’s Pharronida.
U||   Let me call myself, for the present, William Wilson. The fair page now
U||   lying before me need not be sullied with my real appellation. This has
U||   been already too much an object for the scorn—for the horror—for the
U||   detestation of my race. To the uttermost regions of the globe have not
U||   the indignant winds bruited its unparalleled infamy? Oh, outcast of all
U||   outcasts most abandoned!—to the earth art thou not forever dead? to its
U||   honors, to its flowers, to its golden aspirations?—and a cloud, dense,
U||   dismal, and limitless, does it not hang eternally between thy hopes and
U||   heaven?
U||   I would not, if I could, here or to-day, embody a record of my later
U||   years of unspeakable misery, and unpardonable crime. This epoch—these
U||   later years—took unto themselves a sudden elevation in turpitude, whose
U||   origin alone it is my present purpose to assign. Men usually grow base
U||   by degrees. From me, in an instant, all virtue dropped bodily as a
U||   mantle. From comparatively trivial wickedness I passed, with the stride
U||   of a giant, into more than the enormities of an Elah-Gabalus. What
U||   chance—what one event brought this evil thing to pass, bear with me
U||   while I relate. Death approaches; and the shadow which foreruns him has
U||   thrown a softening influence over my spirit. I long, in passing through
U||   the dim valley, for the sympathy—I had nearly said for the pity—of my
U||   fellow men. I would fain have them believe that I have been, in some
U||   measure, the slave of circumstances beyond human control. I would wish
U||   them to seek out for me, in the details I am about to give, some little
U||   oasis of fatality amid a wilderness of error. I would have them
U||   allow—what they cannot refrain from allowing—that, although temptation
U||   may have erewhile existed as great, man was never thus, at least,
U||   tempted before—certainly, never thus fell. And is it therefore that he
U||   has never thus suffered? Have I not indeed been living in a dream? And
U||   am I not now dying a victim to the horror and the mystery of the
U||   wildest of all sublunary visions?
U||   I am the descendant of a race whose imaginative and easily excitable
U||   temperament has at all times rendered them remarkable; and, in my
U||   earliest infancy, I gave evidence of having fully inherited the family
U||   character. As I advanced in years it was more strongly developed;
U||   becoming, for many reasons, a cause of serious disquietude to my
U||   friends, and of positive injury to myself. I grew self-willed, addicted
U||   to the wildest caprices, and a prey to the most ungovernable passions.
U||   Weak-minded, and beset with constitutional infirmities akin to my own,
U||   my parents could do but little to check the evil propensities which
U||   distinguished me. Some feeble and ill-directed efforts resulted in
U||   complete failure on their part, and, of course, in total triumph on
U||   mine. Thenceforward my voice was a household law; and at an age when
U||   few children have abandoned their leading-strings, I was left to the
U||   guidance of my own will, and became, in all but name, the master of my
U||   own actions.
U||   My earliest recollections of a school-life, are connected with a large,
U||   rambling, Elizabethan house, in a misty-looking village of England,
U||   where were a vast number of gigantic and gnarled trees, and where all
U||   the houses were excessively ancient. In truth, it was a dream-like and
U||   spirit-soothing place, that venerable old town. At this moment, in
U||   fancy, I feel the refreshing chilliness of its deeply-shadowed avenues,
U||   inhale the fragrance of its thousand shrubberies, and thrill anew with
U||   undefinable delight, at the deep hollow note of the church-bell,
U||   breaking, each hour, with sullen and sudden roar, upon the stillness of
U||   the dusky atmosphere in which the fretted Gothic steeple lay imbedded
U||   and asleep.
U||   It gives me, perhaps, as much of pleasure as I can now in any manner
U||   experience, to dwell upon minute recollections of the school and its
U||   concerns. Steeped in misery as I am—misery, alas! only too real—I shall
U||   be pardoned for seeking relief, however slight and temporary, in the
U||   weakness of a few rambling details. These, moreover, utterly trivial,
U||   and even ridiculous in themselves, assume, to my fancy, adventitious
U||   importance, as connected with a period and a locality when and where I
U||   recognise the first ambiguous monitions of the destiny which afterwards
U||   so fully overshadowed me. Let me then remember.
U||   The house, I have said, was old and irregular. The grounds were
U||   extensive, and a high and solid brick wall, topped with a bed of mortar
U||   and broken glass, encompassed the whole. This prison-like rampart
U||   formed the limit of our domain; beyond it we saw but thrice a week—once
U||   every Saturday afternoon, when, attended by two ushers, we were
U||   permitted to take brief walks in a body through some of the
U||   neighbouring fields—and twice during Sunday, when we were paraded in
U||   the same formal manner to the morning and evening service in the one
U||   church of the village. Of this church the principal of our school was
U||   pastor. With how deep a spirit of wonder and perplexity was I wont to
U||   regard him from our remote pew in the gallery, as, with step solemn and
U||   slow, he ascended the pulpit! This reverend man, with countenance so
U||   demurely benign, with robes so glossy and so clerically flowing, with
U||   wig so minutely powdered, so rigid and so vast,—-could this be he who,
U||   of late, with sour visage, and in snuffy habiliments, administered,
U||   ferule in hand, the Draconian laws of the academy? Oh, gigantic
U||   paradox, too utterly monstrous for solution!
U||   At an angle of the ponderous wall frowned a more ponderous gate. It was
U||   riveted and studded with iron bolts, and surmounted with jagged iron
U||   spikes. What impressions of deep awe did it inspire! It was never
U||   opened save for the three periodical egressions and ingressions already
U||   mentioned; then, in every creak of its mighty hinges, we found a
U||   plenitude of mystery—a world of matter for solemn remark, or for more
U||   solemn meditation.
U||   The extensive enclosure was irregular in form, having many capacious
U||   recesses. Of these, three or four of the largest constituted the
U||   play-ground. It was level, and covered with fine hard gravel. I well
U||   remember it had no trees, nor benches, nor anything similar within it.
U||   Of course it was in the rear of the house. In front lay a small
U||   parterre, planted with box and other shrubs, but through this sacred
U||   division we passed only upon rare occasions indeed—such as a first
U||   advent to school or final departure thence, or perhaps, when a parent
U||   or friend having called for us, we joyfully took our way home for the
U||   Christmas or Midsummer holidays.
U||   But the house!—how quaint an old building was this!—to me how veritably
U||   a palace of enchantment! There was really no end to its windings—to its
U||   incomprehensible subdivisions. It was difficult, at any given time, to
U||   say with certainty upon which of its two stories one happened to be.
U||   From each room to every other there were sure to be found three or four
U||   steps either in ascent or descent. Then the lateral branches were
U||   innumerable—inconceivable—and so returning in upon themselves, that our
U||   most exact ideas in regard to the whole mansion were not very far
U||   different from those with which we pondered upon infinity. During the
U||   five years of my residence here, I was never able to ascertain with
U||   precision, in what remote locality lay the little sleeping apartment
U||   assigned to myself and some eighteen or twenty other scholars.
U||   The school-room was the largest in the house—I could not help thinking,
U||   in the world. It was very long, narrow, and dismally low, with pointed
U||   Gothic windows and a ceiling of oak. In a remote and terror-inspiring
U||   angle was a square enclosure of eight or ten feet, comprising the
U||   sanctum, “during hours,” of our principal, the Reverend Dr. Bransby. It
U||   was a solid structure, with massy door, sooner than open which in the
U||   absence of the “Dominie,” we would all have willingly perished by the
U||   peine forte et dure. In other angles were two other similar boxes, far
U||   less reverenced, indeed, but still greatly matters of awe. One of these
U||   was the pulpit of the “classical” usher, one of the “English and
U||   mathematical.” Interspersed about the room, crossing and recrossing in
U||   endless irregularity, were innumerable benches and desks, black,
U||   ancient, and time-worn, piled desperately with much-bethumbed books,
U||   and so beseamed with initial letters, names at full length, grotesque
U||   figures, and other multiplied efforts of the knife, as to have entirely
U||   lost what little of original form might have been their portion in days
U||   long departed. A huge bucket with water stood at one extremity of the
U||   room, and a clock of stupendous dimensions at the other.
U||   Encompassed by the massy walls of this venerable academy, I passed, yet
U||   not in tedium or disgust, the years of the third lustrum of my life.
U||   The teeming brain of childhood requires no external world of incident
U||   to occupy or amuse it; and the apparently dismal monotony of a school
U||   was replete with more intense excitement than my riper youth has
U||   derived from luxury, or my full manhood from crime. Yet I must believe
U||   that my first mental development had in it much of the uncommon—even
U||   much of the outré. Upon mankind at large the events of very early
U||   existence rarely leave in mature age any definite impression. All is
U||   gray shadow—a weak and irregular remembrance—an indistinct regathering
U||   of feeble pleasures and phantasmagoric pains. With me this is not so.
U||   In childhood I must have felt with the energy of a man what I now find
U||   stamped upon memory in lines as vivid, as deep, and as durable as the
U||   exergues of the Carthaginian medals.
U||   Yet in fact—in the fact of the world’s view—how little was there to
U||   remember! The morning’s awakening, the nightly summons to bed; the
U||   connings, the recitations; the periodical half-holidays, and
U||   perambulations; the play-ground, with its broils, its pastimes, its
U||   intrigues;—these, by a mental sorcery long forgotten, were made to
U||   involve a wilderness of sensation, a world of rich incident, an
U||   universe of varied emotion, of excitement the most passionate and
U||   spirit-stirring. “Oh, le bon temps, que ce siècle de fer!”
U||   In truth, the ardor, the enthusiasm, and the imperiousness of my
U||   disposition, soon rendered me a marked character among my schoolmates,
U||   and by slow, but natural gradations, gave me an ascendancy over all not
U||   greatly older than myself;—over all with a single exception. This
U||   exception was found in the person of a scholar, who, although no
U||   relation, bore the same Christian and surname as myself;—a
U||   circumstance, in fact, little remarkable; for, notwithstanding a noble
U||   descent, mine was one of those everyday appellations which seem, by
U||   prescriptive right, to have been, time out of mind, the common property
U||   of the mob. In this narrative I have therefore designated myself as
U||   William Wilson,—a fictitious title not very dissimilar to the real. My
U||   namesake alone, of those who in school phraseology constituted “our
U||   set,” presumed to compete with me in the studies of the class—in the
U||   sports and broils of the play-ground—to refuse implicit belief in my
U||   assertions, and submission to my will—indeed, to interfere with my
U||   arbitrary dictation in any respect whatsoever. If there is on earth a
U||   supreme and unqualified despotism, it is the despotism of a master-mind
U||   in boyhood over the less energetic spirits of its companions.
U||   Wilson’s rebellion was to me a source of the greatest embarrassment;
U||   the more so as, in spite of the bravado with which in public I made a
U||   point of treating him and his pretensions, I secretly felt that I
U||   feared him, and could not help thinking the equality which he
U||   maintained so easily with myself, a proof of his true superiority;
U||   since not to be overcome cost me a perpetual struggle. Yet this
U||   superiority—even this equality—was in truth acknowledged by no one but
U||   myself; our associates, by some unaccountable blindness, seemed not
U||   even to suspect it. Indeed, his competition, his resistance, and
U||   especially his impertinent and dogged interference with my purposes,
U||   were not more pointed than private. He appeared to be destitute alike
U||   of the ambition which urged, and of the passionate energy of mind which
U||   enabled me to excel. In his rivalry he might have been supposed
U||   actuated solely by a whimsical desire to thwart, astonish, or mortify
U||   myself; although there were times when I could not help observing, with
U||   a feeling made up of wonder, abasement, and pique, that he mingled with
U||   his injuries, his insults, or his contradictions, a certain most
U||   inappropriate, and assuredly most unwelcome affectionateness of manner.
U||   I could only conceive this singular behavior to arise from a consummate
U||   self-conceit assuming the vulgar airs of patronage and protection.
U||   Perhaps it was this latter trait in Wilson’s conduct, conjoined with
U||   our identity of name, and the mere accident of our having entered the
U||   school upon the same day, which set afloat the notion that we were
U||   brothers, among the senior classes in the academy. These do not usually
U||   inquire with much strictness into the affairs of their juniors. I have
U||   before said, or should have said, that Wilson was not, in the most
U||   remote degree, connected with my family. But assuredly if we had been
U||   brothers we must have been twins; for, after leaving Dr. Bransby’s, I
U||   casually learned that my namesake was born on the nineteenth of
U||   January, 1813—and this is a somewhat remarkable coincidence; for the
U||   day is precisely that of my own nativity.
U||   It may seem strange that in spite of the continual anxiety occasioned
U||   me by the rivalry of Wilson, and his intolerable spirit of
U||   contradiction, I could not bring myself to hate him altogether. We had,
U||   to be sure, nearly every day a quarrel in which, yielding me publicly
U||   the palm of victory, he, in some manner, contrived to make me feel that
U||   it was he who had deserved it; yet a sense of pride on my part, and a
U||   veritable dignity on his own, kept us always upon what are called
U||   “speaking terms,” while there were many points of strong congeniality
U||   in our tempers, operating to awake me in a sentiment which our position
U||   alone, perhaps, prevented from ripening into friendship. It is
U||   difficult, indeed, to define, or even to describe, my real feelings
U||   towards him. They formed a motley and heterogeneous admixture;—some
U||   petulant animosity, which was not yet hatred, some esteem, more
U||   respect, much fear, with a world of uneasy curiosity. To the moralist
U||   it will be unnecessary to say, in addition, that Wilson and myself were
U||   the most inseparable of companions.
U||   It was no doubt the anomalous state of affairs existing between us,
U||   which turned all my attacks upon him, (and they were many, either open
U||   or covert) into the channel of banter or practical joke (giving pain
U||   while assuming the aspect of mere fun) rather than into a more serious
U||   and determined hostility. But my endeavours on this head were by no
U||   means uniformly successful, even when my plans were the most wittily
U||   concocted; for my namesake had much about him, in character, of that
U||   unassuming and quiet austerity which, while enjoying the poignancy of
U||   its own jokes, has no heel of Achilles in itself, and absolutely
U||   refuses to be laughed at. I could find, indeed, but one vulnerable
U||   point, and that, lying in a personal peculiarity, arising, perhaps,
U||   from constitutional disease, would have been spared by any antagonist
U||   less at his wit’s end than myself;—my rival had a weakness in the
U||   faucal or guttural organs, which precluded him from raising his voice
U||   at any time above a very low whisper. Of this defect I did not fail to
U||   take what poor advantage lay in my power.
U||   Wilson’s retaliations in kind were many; and there was one form of his
U||   practical wit that disturbed me beyond measure. How his sagacity first
U||   discovered at all that so petty a thing would vex me, is a question I
U||   never could solve; but, having discovered, he habitually practised the
U||   annoyance. I had always felt aversion to my uncourtly patronymic, and
U||   its very common, if not plebeian praenomen. The words were venom in my
U||   ears; and when, upon the day of my arrival, a second William Wilson
U||   came also to the academy, I felt angry with him for bearing the name,
U||   and doubly disgusted with the name because a stranger bore it, who
U||   would be the cause of its twofold repetition, who would be constantly
U||   in my presence, and whose concerns, in the ordinary routine of the
U||   school business, must inevitably, on account of the detestable
U||   coincidence, be often confounded with my own.
U||   The feeling of vexation thus engendered grew stronger with every
U||   circumstance tending to show resemblance, moral or physical, between my
U||   rival and myself. I had not then discovered the remarkable fact that we
U||   were of the same age; but I saw that we were of the same height, and I
U||   perceived that we were even singularly alike in general contour of
U||   person and outline of feature. I was galled, too, by the rumor touching
U||   a relationship, which had grown current in the upper forms. In a word,
U||   nothing could more seriously disturb me, (although I scrupulously
U||   concealed such disturbance,) than any allusion to a similarity of mind,
U||   person, or condition existing between us. But, in truth, I had no
U||   reason to believe that (with the exception of the matter of
U||   relationship, and in the case of Wilson himself,) this similarity had
U||   ever been made a subject of comment, or even observed at all by our
U||   schoolfellows. That he observed it in all its bearings, and as fixedly
U||   as I, was apparent; but that he could discover in such circumstances so
U||   fruitful a field of annoyance, can only be attributed, as I said
U||   before, to his more than ordinary penetration.
U||   His cue, which was to perfect an imitation of myself, lay both in words
U||   and in actions; and most admirably did he play his part. My dress it
U||   was an easy matter to copy; my gait and general manner were, without
U||   difficulty, appropriated; in spite of his constitutional defect, even
U||   my voice did not escape him. My louder tones were, of course,
U||   unattempted, but then the key—it was identical; and his singular
U||   whisper, it grew the very echo of my own.
U||   How greatly this most exquisite portraiture harassed me, (for it could
U||   not justly be termed a caricature,) I will not now venture to describe.
U||   I had but one consolation—in the fact that the imitation, apparently,
U||   was noticed by myself alone, and that I had to endure only the knowing
U||   and strangely sarcastic smiles of my namesake himself. Satisfied with
U||   having produced in my bosom the intended effect, he seemed to chuckle
U||   in secret over the sting he had inflicted, and was characteristically
U||   disregardful of the public applause which the success of his witty
U||   endeavours might have so easily elicited. That the school, indeed, did
U||   not feel his design, perceive its accomplishment, and participate in
U||   his sneer, was, for many anxious months, a riddle I could not resolve.
U||   Perhaps the gradation of his copy rendered it not so readily
U||   perceptible; or, more possibly, I owed my security to the master air of
U||   the copyist, who, disdaining the letter, (which in a painting is all
U||   the obtuse can see,) gave but the full spirit of his original for my
U||   individual contemplation and chagrin.
U||   I have already more than once spoken of the disgusting air of patronage
U||   which he assumed toward me, and of his frequent officious interference
U||   with my will. This interference often took the ungracious character of
U||   advice; advice not openly given, but hinted or insinuated. I received
U||   it with a repugnance which gained strength as I grew in years. Yet, at
U||   this distant day, let me do him the simple justice to acknowledge that
U||   I can recall no occasion when the suggestions of my rival were on the
U||   side of those errors or follies so usual to his immature age and
U||   seeming inexperience; that his moral sense, at least, if not his
U||   general talents and worldly wisdom, was far keener than my own; and
U||   that I might, to-day, have been a better, and thus a happier man, had I
U||   less frequently rejected the counsels embodied in those meaning
U||   whispers which I then but too cordially hated and too bitterly
U||   despised.
U||   As it was, I at length grew restive in the extreme under his
U||   distasteful supervision, and daily resented more and more openly what I
U||   considered his intolerable arrogance. I have said that, in the first
U||   years of our connexion as schoolmates, my feelings in regard to him
U||   might have been easily ripened into friendship; but, in the latter
U||   months of my residence at the academy, although the intrusion of his
U||   ordinary manner had, beyond doubt, in some measure, abated, my
U||   sentiments, in nearly similar proportion, partook very much of positive
U||   hatred. Upon one occasion he saw this, I think, and afterwards avoided,
U||   or made a show of avoiding me.
U||   It was about the same period, if I remember aright, that, in an
U||   altercation of violence with him, in which he was more than usually
U||   thrown off his guard, and spoke and acted with an openness of demeanor
U||   rather foreign to his nature, I discovered, or fancied I discovered, in
U||   his accent, his air, and general appearance, a something which first
U||   startled, and then deeply interested me, by bringing to mind dim
U||   visions of my earliest infancy—wild, confused and thronging memories of
U||   a time when memory herself was yet unborn. I cannot better describe the
U||   sensation which oppressed me than by saying that I could with
U||   difficulty shake off the belief of my having been acquainted with the
U||   being who stood before me, at some epoch very long ago—some point of
U||   the past even infinitely remote. The delusion, however, faded rapidly
U||   as it came; and I mention it at all but to define the day of the last
U||   conversation I there held with my singular namesake.
U||   The huge old house, with its countless subdivisions, had several large
U||   chambers communicating with each other, where slept the greater number
U||   of the students. There were, however, (as must necessarily happen in a
U||   building so awkwardly planned,) many little nooks or recesses, the odds
U||   and ends of the structure; and these the economic ingenuity of Dr.
U||   Bransby had also fitted up as dormitories; although, being the merest
U||   closets, they were capable of accommodating but a single individual.
U||   One of these small apartments was occupied by Wilson.
U||   One night, about the close of my fifth year at the school, and
U||   immediately after the altercation just mentioned, finding every one
U||   wrapped in sleep, I arose from bed, and, lamp in hand, stole through a
U||   wilderness of narrow passages from my own bedroom to that of my rival.
U||   I had long been plotting one of those ill-natured pieces of practical
U||   wit at his expense in which I had hitherto been so uniformly
U||   unsuccessful. It was my intention, now, to put my scheme in operation,
U||   and I resolved to make him feel the whole extent of the malice with
U||   which I was imbued. Having reached his closet, I noiselessly entered,
U||   leaving the lamp, with a shade over it, on the outside. I advanced a
U||   step, and listened to the sound of his tranquil breathing. Assured of
U||   his being asleep, I returned, took the light, and with it again
U||   approached the bed. Close curtains were around it, which, in the
U||   prosecution of my plan, I slowly and quietly withdrew, when the bright
U||   rays fell vividly upon the sleeper, and my eyes, at the same moment,
U||   upon his countenance. I looked;—and a numbness, an iciness of feeling
U||   instantly pervaded my frame. My breast heaved, my knees tottered, my
U||   whole spirit became possessed with an objectless yet intolerable
U||   horror. Gasping for breath, I lowered the lamp in still nearer
U||   proximity to the face. Were these—these the lineaments of William
U||   Wilson? I saw, indeed, that they were his, but I shook as if with a fit
U||   of the ague in fancying they were not. What was there about them to
U||   confound me in this manner? I gazed;—while my brain reeled with a
U||   multitude of incoherent thoughts. Not thus he appeared—assuredly not
U||   thus—in the vivacity of his waking hours. The same name! the same
U||   contour of person! the same day of arrival at the academy! And then his
U||   dogged and meaningless imitation of my gait, my voice, my habits, and
U||   my manner! Was it, in truth, within the bounds of human possibility,
U||   that what I now saw was the result, merely, of the habitual practice of
U||   this sarcastic imitation? Awe-stricken, and with a creeping shudder, I
U||   extinguished the lamp, passed silently from the chamber, and left, at
U||   once, the halls of that old academy, never to enter them again.
U||   After a lapse of some months, spent at home in mere idleness, I found
U||   myself a student at Eton. The brief interval had been sufficient to
U||   enfeeble my remembrance of the events at Dr. Bransby’s, or at least to
U||   effect a material change in the nature of the feelings with which I
U||   remembered them. The truth—the tragedy—of the drama was no more. I
U||   could now find room to doubt the evidence of my senses; and seldom
U||   called up the subject at all but with wonder at extent of human
U||   credulity, and a smile at the vivid force of the imagination which I
U||   hereditarily possessed. Neither was this species of scepticism likely
U||   to be diminished by the character of the life I led at Eton. The vortex
U||   of thoughtless folly into which I there so immediately and so
U||   recklessly plunged, washed away all but the froth of my past hours,
U||   engulfed at once every solid or serious impression, and left to memory
U||   only the veriest levities of a former existence.
U||   I do not wish, however, to trace the course of my miserable profligacy
U||   here—a profligacy which set at defiance the laws, while it eluded the
U||   vigilance of the institution. Three years of folly, passed without
U||   profit, had but given me rooted habits of vice, and added, in a
U||   somewhat unusual degree, to my bodily stature, when, after a week of
U||   soulless dissipation, I invited a small party of the most dissolute
U||   students to a secret carousal in my chambers. We met at a late hour of
U||   the night; for our debaucheries were to be faithfully protracted until
U||   morning. The wine flowed freely, and there were not wanting other and
U||   perhaps more dangerous seductions; so that the gray dawn had already
U||   faintly appeared in the east, while our delirious extravagance was at
U||   its height. Madly flushed with cards and intoxication, I was in the act
U||   of insisting upon a toast of more than wonted profanity, when my
U||   attention was suddenly diverted by the violent, although partial
U||   unclosing of the door of the apartment, and by the eager voice of a
U||   servant from without. He said that some person, apparently in great
U||   haste, demanded to speak with me in the hall.
U||   Wildly excited with wine, the unexpected interruption rather delighted
U||   than surprised me. I staggered forward at once, and a few steps brought
U||   me to the vestibule of the building. In this low and small room there
U||   hung no lamp; and now no light at all was admitted, save that of the
U||   exceedingly feeble dawn which made its way through the semi-circular
U||   window. As I put my foot over the threshold, I became aware of the
U||   figure of a youth about my own height, and habited in a white
U||   kerseymere morning frock, cut in the novel fashion of the one I myself
U||   wore at the moment. This the faint light enabled me to perceive; but
U||   the features of his face I could not distinguish. Upon my entering he
U||   strode hurriedly up to me, and, seizing me by the arm with a gesture of
U||   petulant impatience, whispered the words “William Wilson!” in my ear.
U||   I grew perfectly sober in an instant.
