U||THE TELL-TALE HEART.
U||   True!—nervous—very, very dreadfully nervous I had been and am; but why
U||   will you say that I am mad? The disease had sharpened my senses—not
U||   destroyed—not dulled them. Above all was the sense of hearing acute. I
U||   heard all things in the heaven and in the earth. I heard many things in
U||   hell. How, then, am I mad? Hearken! and observe how healthily—how
U||   calmly I can tell you the whole story.
U||   It is impossible to say how first the idea entered my brain; but once
U||   conceived, it haunted me day and night. Object there was none. Passion
U||   there was none. I loved the old man. He had never wronged me. He had
U||   never given me insult. For his gold I had no desire. I think it was his
U||   eye! yes, it was this! He had the eye of a vulture—a pale blue eye,
U||   with a film over it. Whenever it fell upon me, my blood ran cold; and
U||   so by degrees—very gradually—I made up my mind to take the life of the
U||   old man, and thus rid myself of the eye forever.
U||   Now this is the point. You fancy me mad. Madmen know nothing. But you
U||   should have seen me. You should have seen how wisely I proceeded—with
U||   what caution—with what foresight—with what dissimulation I went to
U||   work! I was never kinder to the old man than during the whole week
U||   before I killed him. And every night, about midnight, I turned the
U||   latch of his door and opened it—oh, so gently! And then, when I had
U||   made an opening sufficient for my head, I put in a dark lantern, all
U||   closed, closed, that no light shone out, and then I thrust in my head.
U||   Oh, you would have laughed to see how cunningly I thrust it in! I moved
U||   it slowly—very, very slowly, so that I might not disturb the old man’s
U||   sleep. It took me an hour to place my whole head within the opening so
U||   far that I could see him as he lay upon his bed. Ha!—would a madman
U||   have been so wise as this? And then, when my head was well in the room,
U||   I undid the lantern cautiously—oh, so cautiously—cautiously (for the
U||   hinges creaked)—I undid it just so much that a single thin ray fell
U||   upon the vulture eye. And this I did for seven long nights—every night
U||   just at midnight—but I found the eye always closed; and so it was
U||   impossible to do the work; for it was not the old man who vexed me, but
U||   his Evil Eye. And every morning, when the day broke, I went boldly into
U||   the chamber, and spoke courageously to him, calling him by name in a
U||   hearty tone, and inquiring how he has passed the night. So you see he
U||   would have been a very profound old man, indeed, to suspect that every
U||   night, just at twelve, I looked in upon him while he slept.
U||   Upon the eighth night I was more than usually cautious in opening the
U||   door. A watch’s minute hand moves more quickly than did mine. Never
U||   before that night had I felt the extent of my own powers—of my
U||   sagacity. I could scarcely contain my feelings of triumph. To think
U||   that there I was, opening the door, little by little, and he not even
U||   to dream of my secret deeds or thoughts. I fairly chuckled at the idea;
U||   and perhaps he heard me; for he moved on the bed suddenly, as if
U||   startled. Now you may think that I drew back—but no. His room was as
U||   black as pitch with the thick darkness, (for the shutters were close
U||   fastened, through fear of robbers,) and so I knew that he could not see
U||   the opening of the door, and I kept pushing it on steadily, steadily.
U||   I had my head in, and was about to open the lantern, when my thumb
U||   slipped upon the tin fastening, and the old man sprang up in bed,
U||   crying out—“Who’s there?”
U||   I kept quite still and said nothing. For a whole hour I did not move a
U||   muscle, and in the meantime I did not hear him lie down. He was still
U||   sitting up in the bed listening;—just as I have done, night after
U||   night, hearkening to the death watches in the wall.
U||   Presently I heard a slight groan, and I knew it was the groan of mortal
U||   terror. It was not a groan of pain or of grief—oh, no!—it was the low
U||   stifled sound that arises from the bottom of the soul when overcharged
U||   with awe. I knew the sound well. Many a night, just at midnight, when
U||   all the world slept, it has welled up from my own bosom, deepening,
U||   with its dreadful echo, the terrors that distracted me. I say I knew it
U||   well. I knew what the old man felt, and pitied him, although I chuckled
U||   at heart. I knew that he had been lying awake ever since the first
U||   slight noise, when he had turned in the bed. His fears had been ever
U||   since growing upon him. He had been trying to fancy them causeless, but
U||   could not. He had been saying to himself—“It is nothing but the wind in
U||   the chimney—it is only a mouse crossing the floor,” or “It is merely a
U||   cricket which has made a single chirp.” Yes, he had been trying to
U||   comfort himself with these suppositions: but he had found all in vain.
U||   All in vain; because Death, in approaching him had stalked with his
U||   black shadow before him, and enveloped the victim. And it was the
U||   mournful influence of the unperceived shadow that caused him to
U||   feel—although he neither saw nor heard—to feel the presence of my head
U||   within the room.
U||   When I had waited a long time, very patiently, without hearing him lie
U||   down, I resolved to open a little—a very, very little crevice in the
U||   lantern. So I opened it—you cannot imagine how stealthily,
U||   stealthily—until, at length a simple dim ray, like the thread of the
U||   spider, shot from out the crevice and fell full upon the vulture eye.
U||   It was open—wide, wide open—and I grew furious as I gazed upon it. I
U||   saw it with perfect distinctness—all a dull blue, with a hideous veil
U||   over it that chilled the very marrow in my bones; but I could see
U||   nothing else of the old man’s face or person: for I had directed the
U||   ray as if by instinct, precisely upon the damned spot.
U||   And have I not told you that what you mistake for madness is but
U||   over-acuteness of the sense?—now, I say, there came to my ears a low,
U||   dull, quick sound, such as a watch makes when enveloped in cotton. I
U||   knew that sound well, too. It was the beating of the old man’s heart.
U||   It increased my fury, as the beating of a drum stimulates the soldier
U||   into courage.
U||   But even yet I refrained and kept still. I scarcely breathed. I held
U||   the lantern motionless. I tried how steadily I could maintain the ray
U||   upon the eye. Meantime the hellish tattoo of the heart increased. It
U||   grew quicker and quicker, and louder and louder every instant. The old
U||   man’s terror must have been extreme! It grew louder, I say, louder
U||   every moment!—do you mark me well? I have told you that I am nervous:
U||   so I am. And now at the dead hour of the night, amid the dreadful
U||   silence of that old house, so strange a noise as this excited me to
U||   uncontrollable terror. Yet, for some minutes longer I refrained and
U||   stood still. But the beating grew louder, louder! I thought the heart
U||   must burst. And now a new anxiety seized me—the sound would be heard by
U||   a neighbour! The old man’s hour had come! With a loud yell, I threw
U||   open the lantern and leaped into the room. He shrieked once—once only.
U||   In an instant I dragged him to the floor, and pulled the heavy bed over
U||   him. I then smiled gaily, to find the deed so far done. But, for many
U||   minutes, the heart beat on with a muffled sound. This, however, did not
U||   vex me; it would not be heard through the wall. At length it ceased.
U||   The old man was dead. I removed the bed and examined the corpse. Yes,
U||   he was stone, stone dead. I placed my hand upon the heart and held it
U||   there many minutes. There was no pulsation. He was stone dead. His eye
U||   would trouble me no more.
U||   If still you think me mad, you will think so no longer when I describe
U||   the wise precautions I took for the concealment of the body. The night
U||   waned, and I worked hastily, but in silence. First of all I dismembered
U||   the corpse. I cut off the head and the arms and the legs.
U||   I then took up three planks from the flooring of the chamber, and
U||   deposited all between the scantlings. I then replaced the boards so
U||   cleverly, so cunningly, that no human eye—not even his—could have
U||   detected any thing wrong. There was nothing to wash out—no stain of any
U||   kind—no blood-spot whatever. I had been too wary for that. A tub had
U||   caught all—ha! ha!
U||   When I had made an end of these labors, it was four o’clock—still dark
U||   as midnight. As the bell sounded the hour, there came a knocking at the
U||   street door. I went down to open it with a light heart,—for what had I
U||   now to fear? There entered three men, who introduced themselves, with
U||   perfect suavity, as officers of the police. A shriek had been heard by
U||   a neighbour during the night; suspicion of foul play had been aroused;
U||   information had been lodged at the police office, and they (the
U||   officers) had been deputed to search the premises.
U||   I smiled,—for what had I to fear? I bade the gentlemen welcome. The
U||   shriek, I said, was my own in a dream. The old man, I mentioned, was
U||   absent in the country. I took my visitors all over the house. I bade
U||   them search—search well. I led them, at length, to his chamber. I
U||   showed them his treasures, secure, undisturbed. In the enthusiasm of my
U||   confidence, I brought chairs into the room, and desired them here to
U||   rest from their fatigues, while I myself, in the wild audacity of my
U||   perfect triumph, placed my own seat upon the very spot beneath which
U||   reposed the corpse of the victim.
U||   The officers were satisfied. My manner had convinced them. I was
U||   singularly at ease. They sat, and while I answered cheerily, they
U||   chatted of familiar things. But, ere long, I felt myself getting pale
U||   and wished them gone. My head ached, and I fancied a ringing in my
U||   ears: but still they sat and still chatted. The ringing became more
U||   distinct:—it continued and became more distinct: I talked more freely
U||   to get rid of the feeling: but it continued and gained
U||   definiteness—until, at length, I found that the noise was not within my
U||   ears.
U||   No doubt I now grew very pale;—but I talked more fluently, and with a
U||   heightened voice. Yet the sound increased—and what could I do? It was a
U||   low, dull, quick sound—much such a sound as a watch makes when
U||   enveloped in cotton. I gasped for breath—and yet the officers heard it
U||   not. I talked more quickly—more vehemently; but the noise steadily
U||   increased. I arose and argued about trifles, in a high key and with
U||   violent gesticulations; but the noise steadily increased. Why would
U||   they not be gone? I paced the floor to and fro with heavy strides, as
U||   if excited to fury by the observations of the men—but the noise
U||   steadily increased. Oh God! what could I do? I foamed—I raved—I swore!
U||   I swung the chair upon which I had been sitting, and grated it upon the
U||   boards, but the noise arose over all and continually increased. It grew
U||   louder—louder—louder! And still the men chatted pleasantly, and smiled.
U||   Was it possible they heard not? Almighty God!—no, no! They heard!—they
U||   suspected!—they knew!—they were making a mockery of my horror!—this I
U||   thought, and this I think. But anything was better than this agony!
U||   Anything was more tolerable than this derision! I could bear those
U||   hypocritical smiles no longer! I felt that I must scream or die! and
U||   now—again!—hark! louder! louder! louder! louder!
U||   “Villains!” I shrieked, “dissemble no more! I admit the deed!—tear up
U||   the planks!—here, here!—It is the beating of his hideous heart!”
U||BERENICE
U||   Dicebant mihi sodales, si sepulchrum amicae visitarem, curas meas
U||   aliquar tulum fore levatas.—Ebn Zaiat.
U||   Misery is manifold. The wretchedness of earth is multiform.
U||   Overreaching the wide horizon as the rainbow, its hues are as various
U||   as the hues of that arch—as distinct too, yet as intimately blended.
U||   Overreaching the wide horizon as the rainbow! How is it that from
U||   beauty I have derived a type of unloveliness?—from the covenant of
U||   peace, a simile of sorrow? But as, in ethics, evil is a consequence of
U||   good, so, in fact, out of joy is sorrow born. Either the memory of past
U||   bliss is the anguish of to-day, or the agonies which are, have their
U||   origin in the ecstasies which might have been.
U||   My baptismal name is Egaeus; that of my family I will not mention. Yet
U||   there are no towers in the land more time-honored than my gloomy, gray,
U||   hereditary halls. Our line has been called a race of visionaries; and
U||   in many striking particulars—in the character of the family mansion—in
U||   the frescos of the chief saloon—in the tapestries of the dormitories—in
U||   the chiselling of some buttresses in the armory—but more especially in
U||   the gallery of antique paintings—in the fashion of the library
U||   chamber—and, lastly, in the very peculiar nature of the library’s
U||   contents—there is more than sufficient evidence to warrant the belief.
U||   The recollections of my earliest years are connected with that chamber,
U||   and with its volumes—of which latter I will say no more. Here died my
U||   mother. Herein was I born. But it is mere idleness to say that I had
U||   not lived before—that the soul has no previous existence. You deny
U||   it?—let us not argue the matter. Convinced myself, I seek not to
U||   convince. There is, however, a remembrance of aerial forms—of spiritual
U||   and meaning eyes—of sounds, musical yet sad—a remembrance which will
U||   not be excluded; a memory like a shadow—vague, variable, indefinite,
U||   unsteady; and like a shadow, too, in the impossibility of my getting
U||   rid of it while the sunlight of my reason shall exist.
U||   In that chamber was I born. Thus awaking from the long night of what
U||   seemed, but was not, nonentity, at once into the very regions of fairy
U||   land—into a palace of imagination—into the wild dominions of monastic
U||   thought and erudition—it is not singular that I gazed around me with a
U||   startled and ardent eye—that I loitered away my boyhood in books, and
U||   dissipated my youth in reverie; but it is singular that as years rolled
U||   away, and the noon of manhood found me still in the mansion of my
U||   fathers—it is wonderful what stagnation there fell upon the springs of
U||   my life—wonderful how total an inversion took place in the character of
U||   my commonest thought. The realities of the world affected me as
U||   visions, and as visions only, while the wild ideas of the land of
U||   dreams became, in turn, not the material of my every-day existence, but
U||   in very deed that existence utterly and solely in itself.
U||     __________________________________________________________________
U||   Berenice and I were cousins, and we grew up together in my paternal
U||   halls. Yet differently we grew—I, ill of health, and buried in
U||   gloom—she, agile, graceful, and overflowing with energy; hers, the
U||   ramble on the hill-side—mine the studies of the cloister; I, living
U||   within my own heart, and addicted, body and soul, to the most intense
U||   and painful meditation—she, roaming carelessly through life, with no
U||   thought of the shadows in her path, or the silent flight of the
U||   raven-winged hours. Berenice!—I call upon her name—Berenice!—and from
U||   the gray ruins of memory a thousand tumultuous recollections are
U||   startled at the sound! Ah, vividly is her image before me now, as in
U||   the early days of her light-heartedness and joy! Oh, gorgeous yet
U||   fantastic beauty! Oh, sylph amid the shrubberies of Arnheim! Oh, Naiad
U||   among its fountains! And then—then all is mystery and terror, and a
U||   tale which should not be told. Disease—a fatal disease, fell like the
U||   simoon upon her frame; and, even while I gazed upon her, the spirit of
U||   change swept over her, pervading her mind, her habits, and her
U||   character, and, in a manner the most subtle and terrible, disturbing
U||   even the identity of her person! Alas! the destroyer came and went!—and
U||   the victim—where is she? I knew her not—or knew her no longer as
U||   Berenice.
U||   Among the numerous train of maladies superinduced by that fatal and
U||   primary one which effected a revolution of so horrible a kind in the
U||   moral and physical being of my cousin, may be mentioned as the most
U||   distressing and obstinate in its nature, a species of epilepsy not
U||   unfrequently terminating in trance itself—trance very nearly resembling
U||   positive dissolution, and from which her manner of recovery was in most
U||   instances, startlingly abrupt. In the mean time my own disease—for I
U||   have been told that I should call it by no other appellation—my own
U||   disease, then, grew rapidly upon me, and assumed finally a monomaniac
U||   character of a novel and extraordinary form—hourly and momently gaining
U||   vigor—and at length obtaining over me the most incomprehensible
U||   ascendancy. This monomania, if I must so term it, consisted in a morbid
U||   irritability of those properties of the mind in metaphysical science
U||   termed the attentive. It is more than probable that I am not
U||   understood; but I fear, indeed, that it is in no manner possible to
U||   convey to the mind of the merely general reader, an adequate idea of
U||   that nervous intensity of interest with which, in my case, the powers
U||   of meditation (not to speak technically) busied and buried themselves,
U||   in the contemplation of even the most ordinary objects of the universe.
U||   To muse for long unwearied hours, with my attention riveted to some
U||   frivolous device on the margin, or in the typography of a book; to
U||   become absorbed, for the better part of a summer’s day, in a quaint
U||   shadow falling aslant upon the tapestry or upon the floor; to lose
U||   myself, for an entire night, in watching the steady flame of a lamp, or
U||   the embers of a fire; to dream away whole days over the perfume of a
U||   flower; to repeat, monotonously, some common word, until the sound, by
U||   dint of frequent repetition, ceased to convey any idea whatever to the
U||   mind; to lose all sense of motion or physical existence, by means of
U||   absolute bodily quiescence long and obstinately persevered in: such
U||   were a few of the most common and least pernicious vagaries induced by
U||   a condition of the mental faculties, not, indeed, altogether
U||   unparalleled, but certainly bidding defiance to anything like analysis
U||   or explanation.
U||   Yet let me not be misapprehended. The undue, earnest, and morbid
U||   attention thus excited by objects in their own nature frivolous, must
U||   not be confounded in character with that ruminating propensity common
U||   to all mankind, and more especially indulged in by persons of ardent
U||   imagination. It was not even, as might be at first supposed, an extreme
U||   condition, or exaggeration of such propensity, but primarily and
U||   essentially distinct and different. In the one instance, the dreamer,
U||   or enthusiast, being interested by an object usually not frivolous,
U||   imperceptibly loses sight of this object in a wilderness of deductions
U||   and suggestions issuing therefrom, until, at the conclusion of a
U||   day-dream often replete with luxury, he finds the incitamentum, or
U||   first cause of his musings, entirely vanished and forgotten. In my
U||   case, the primary object was invariably frivolous, although assuming,
U||   through the medium of my distempered vision, a refracted and unreal
U||   importance. Few deductions, if any, were made; and those few
U||   pertinaciously returning in upon the original object as a centre. The
U||   meditations were never pleasurable; and, at the termination of the
U||   reverie, the first cause, so far from being out of sight, had attained
U||   that supernaturally exaggerated interest which was the prevailing
U||   feature of the disease. In a word, the powers of mind more particularly
U||   exercised were, with me, as I have said before, the attentive, and are,
U||   with the day-dreamer, the speculative.
U||   My books, at this epoch, if they did not actually serve to irritate the
U||   disorder, partook, it will be perceived, largely, in their imaginative
U||   and inconsequential nature, of the characteristic qualities of the
U||   disorder itself. I well remember, among others, the treatise of the
U||   noble Italian, Coelius Secundus Curio, “De Amplitudine Beati Regni
U||   Dei;” St. Austin’s great work, the “City of God;” and Tertullian’s “De
U||   Carne Christi,” in which the paradoxical sentence “Mortuus est Dei
U||   filius; credible est quia ineptum est: et sepultus resurrexit; certum
U||   est quia impossibile est,” occupied my undivided time, for many weeks
U||   of laborious and fruitless investigation.
U||   Thus it will appear that, shaken from its balance only by trivial
U||   things, my reason bore resemblance to that ocean-crag spoken of by
U||   Ptolemy Hephestion, which steadily resisting the attacks of human
U||   violence, and the fiercer fury of the waters and the winds, trembled
U||   only to the touch of the flower called Asphodel. And although, to a
U||   careless thinker, it might appear a matter beyond doubt, that the
U||   alteration produced by her unhappy malady, in the moral condition of
U||   Berenice, would afford me many objects for the exercise of that intense
U||   and abnormal meditation whose nature I have been at some trouble in
U||   explaining, yet such was not in any degree the case. In the lucid
U||   intervals of my infirmity, her calamity, indeed, gave me pain, and,
U||   taking deeply to heart that total wreck of her fair and gentle life, I
U||   did not fail to ponder, frequently and bitterly, upon the
U||   wonder-working means by which so strange a revolution had been so
U||   suddenly brought to pass. But these reflections partook not of the
U||   idiosyncrasy of my disease, and were such as would have occurred, under
U||   similar circumstances, to the ordinary mass of mankind. True to its own
U||   character, my disorder revelled in the less important but more
U||   startling changes wrought in the physical frame of Berenice—in the
U||   singular and most appalling distortion of her personal identity.
U||   During the brightest days of her unparalleled beauty, most surely I had
U||   never loved her. In the strange anomaly of my existence, feelings with
U||   me, had never been of the heart, and my passions always were of the
U||   mind. Through the gray of the early morning—among the trellised shadows
U||   of the forest at noonday—and in the silence of my library at night—she
U||   had flitted by my eyes, and I had seen her—not as the living and
U||   breathing Berenice, but as the Berenice of a dream; not as a being of
U||   the earth, earthy, but as the abstraction of such a being; not as a
U||   thing to admire, but to analyze; not as an object of love, but as the
U||   theme of the most abstruse although desultory speculation. And now—now
U||   I shuddered in her presence, and grew pale at her approach; yet,
U||   bitterly lamenting her fallen and desolate condition, I called to mind
U||   that she had loved me long, and, in an evil moment, I spoke to her of
U||   marriage.
U||   And at length the period of our nuptials was approaching, when, upon an
U||   afternoon in the winter of the year—one of those unseasonably warm,
U||   calm, and misty days which are the nurse of the beautiful Halcyon
U||   (*1),—I sat, (and sat, as I thought, alone,) in the inner apartment of
U||   the library. But, uplifting my eyes, I saw that Berenice stood before
U||   me.
U||   Was it my own excited imagination—or the misty influence of the
U||   atmosphere—or the uncertain twilight of the chamber—or the gray
U||   draperies which fell around her figure—that caused in it so vacillating
U||   and indistinct an outline? I could not tell. She spoke no word; and
U||   I—not for worlds could I have uttered a syllable. An icy chill ran
U||   through my frame; a sense of insufferable anxiety oppressed me; a
U||   consuming curiosity pervaded my soul; and sinking back upon the chair,
U||   I remained for some time breathless and motionless, with my eyes
U||   riveted upon her person. Alas! its emaciation was excessive, and not
U||   one vestige of the former being lurked in any single line of the
U||   contour. My burning glances at length fell upon the face.
U||   The forehead was high, and very pale, and singularly placid; and the
U||   once jetty hair fell partially over it, and overshadowed the hollow
U||   temples with innumerable ringlets, now of a vivid yellow, and jarring
U||   discordantly, in their fantastic character, with the reigning
U||   melancholy of the countenance. The eyes were lifeless, and lustreless,
U||   and seemingly pupilless, and I shrank involuntarily from their glassy
U||   stare to the contemplation of the thin and shrunken lips. They parted;
U||   and in a smile of peculiar meaning, the teeth of the changed Berenice
U||   disclosed themselves slowly to my view. Would to God that I had never
U||   beheld them, or that, having done so, I had died!
U||     __________________________________________________________________
U||   The shutting of a door disturbed me, and, looking up, I found that my
U||   cousin had departed from the chamber. But from the disordered chamber
U||   of my brain, had not, alas! departed, and would not be driven away, the
U||   white and ghastly spectrum of the teeth. Not a speck on their
U||   surface—not a shade on their enamel—not an indenture in their edges—but
U||   what that period of her smile had sufficed to brand in upon my memory.
U||   I saw them now even more unequivocally than I beheld them then. The
U||   teeth!—the teeth!—they were here, and there, and everywhere, and
U||   visibly and palpably before me; long, narrow, and excessively white,
U||   with the pale lips writhing about them, as in the very moment of their
U||   first terrible development. Then came the full fury of my monomania,
U||   and I struggled in vain against its strange and irresistible influence.
U||   In the multiplied objects of the external world I had no thoughts but
U||   for the teeth. For these I longed with a phrenzied desire. All other
U||   matters and all different interests became absorbed in their single
U||   contemplation. They—they alone were present to the mental eye, and
U||   they, in their sole individuality, became the essence of my mental
U||   life. I held them in every light. I turned them in every attitude. I
U||   surveyed their characteristics. I dwelt upon their peculiarities. I
U||   pondered upon their conformation. I mused upon the alteration in their
U||   nature. I shuddered as I assigned to them in imagination a sensitive
U||   and sentient power, and even when unassisted by the lips, a capability
U||   of moral expression. Of Mademoiselle Salle it has been well said, “Que
U||   tous ses pas etaient des sentiments,” and of Berenice I more seriously
U||   believed que toutes ses dents etaient des idées. Des idées!—ah here was
U||   the idiotic thought that destroyed me! Des idées!—ah, therefore it was
U||   that I coveted them so madly! I felt that their possession could alone
U||   ever restore me to peace, in giving me back to reason.
U||   And the evening closed in upon me thus—and then the darkness came, and
U||   tarried, and went—and the day again dawned—and the mists of a second
U||   night were now gathering around—and still I sat motionless in that
U||   solitary room—and still I sat buried in meditation—and still the
U||   phantasma of the teeth maintained its terrible ascendancy, as, with the
U||   most vivid hideous distinctness, it floated about amid the changing
U||   lights and shadows of the chamber. At length there broke in upon my
U||   dreams a cry as of horror and dismay; and thereunto, after a pause,
U||   succeeded the sound of troubled voices, intermingled with many low
U||   moanings of sorrow or of pain. I arose from my seat, and throwing open
U||   one of the doors of the library, saw standing out in the ante-chamber a
U||   servant maiden, all in tears, who told me that Berenice was—no more!
U||   She had been seized with epilepsy in the early morning, and now, at the
U||   closing in of the night, the grave was ready for its tenant, and all
U||   the preparations for the burial were completed.
U||     __________________________________________________________________
U||   I found myself sitting in the library, and again sitting there alone.
U||   It seemed that I had newly awakened from a confused and exciting dream.
U||   I knew that it was now midnight, and I was well aware, that since the
U||   setting of the sun, Berenice had been interred. But of that dreary
U||   period which intervened I had no positive, at least no definite
U||   comprehension. Yet its memory was replete with horror—horror more
U||   horrible from being vague, and terror more terrible from ambiguity. It
U||   was a fearful page in the record my existence, written all over with
U||   dim, and hideous, and unintelligible recollections. I strived to
U||   decypher them, but in vain; while ever and anon, like the spirit of a
U||   departed sound, the shrill and piercing shriek of a female voice seemed
U||   to be ringing in my ears. I had done a deed—what was it? I asked myself
U||   the question aloud, and the whispering echoes of the chamber answered
U||   me,—“What was it?”
U||   On the table beside me burned a lamp, and near it lay a little box. It
U||   was of no remarkable character, and I had seen it frequently before,
U||   for it was the property of the family physician; but how came it there,
U||   upon my table, and why did I shudder in regarding it? These things were
U||   in no manner to be accounted for, and my eyes at length dropped to the
U||   open pages of a book, and to a sentence underscored therein. The words
U||   were the singular but simple ones of the poet Ebn Zaiat:—“Dicebant mihi
U||   sodales si sepulchrum amicae visitarem, curas meas aliquantulum fore
U||   levatas.” Why then, as I perused them, did the hairs of my head erect
U||   themselves on end, and the blood of my body become congealed within my
U||   veins?
U||   There came a light tap at the library door—and, pale as the tenant of a
U||   tomb, a menial entered upon tiptoe. His looks were wild with terror,
U||   and he spoke to me in a voice tremulous, husky, and very low. What said
U||   he?—some broken sentences I heard. He told of a wild cry disturbing the
U||   silence of the night—of the gathering together of the household—of a
U||   search in the direction of the sound; and then his tones grew
U||   thrillingly distinct as he whispered me of a violated grave—of a
U||   disfigured body enshrouded, yet still breathing—still palpitating—still
U||   alive!
U||   He pointed to garments;—they were muddy and clotted with gore. I spoke
U||   not, and he took me gently by the hand: it was indented with the
U||   impress of human nails. He directed my attention to some object against
U||   the wall. I looked at it for some minutes: it was a spade. With a
U||   shriek I bounded to the table, and grasped the box that lay upon it.
U||   But I could not force it open; and in my tremor, it slipped from my
U||   hands, and fell heavily, and burst into pieces; and from it, with a
U||   rattling sound, there rolled out some instruments of dental surgery,
U||   intermingled with thirty-two small, white and ivory-looking substances
U||   that were scattered to and fro about the floor.
U||ELEONORA
U||   Sub conservatione formæ specificæ salva anima.
U||                       —Raymond Lully.
U||   I am come of a race noted for vigor of fancy and ardor of passion. Men
U||   have called me mad; but the question is not yet settled, whether
U||   madness is or is not the loftiest intelligence—whether much that is
U||   glorious—whether all that is profound—does not spring from disease of
U||   thought—from moods of mind exalted at the expense of the general
U||   intellect. They who dream by day are cognizant of many things which
U||   escape those who dream only by night. In their gray visions they obtain
U||   glimpses of eternity, and thrill, in awakening, to find that they have
U||   been upon the verge of the great secret. In snatches, they learn
U||   something of the wisdom which is of good, and more of the mere
U||   knowledge which is of evil. They penetrate, however, rudderless or
U||   compassless into the vast ocean of the “light ineffable,” and again,
U||   like the adventures of the Nubian geographer, “agressi sunt mare
U||   tenebrarum, quid in eo esset exploraturi.”
U||   We will say, then, that I am mad. I grant, at least, that there are two
U||   distinct conditions of my mental existence—the condition of a lucid
U||   reason, not to be disputed, and belonging to the memory of events
U||   forming the first epoch of my life—and a condition of shadow and doubt,
U||   appertaining to the present, and to the recollection of what
U||   constitutes the second great era of my being. Therefore, what I shall
U||   tell of the earlier period, believe; and to what I may relate of the
U||   later time, give only such credit as may seem due, or doubt it
U||   altogether, or, if doubt it ye cannot, then play unto its riddle the
U||   Oedipus.
U||   She whom I loved in youth, and of whom I now pen calmly and distinctly
U||   these remembrances, was the sole daughter of the only sister of my
U||   mother long departed. Eleonora was the name of my cousin. We had always
U||   dwelled together, beneath a tropical sun, in the Valley of the
U||   Many-Colored Grass. No unguided footstep ever came upon that vale; for
U||   it lay away up among a range of giant hills that hung beetling around
U||   about it, shutting out the sunlight from its sweetest recesses. No path
U||   was trodden in its vicinity; and, to reach our happy home, there was
U||   need of putting back, with force, the foliage of many thousands of
U||   forest trees, and of crushing to death the glories of many millions of
U||   fragrant flowers. Thus it was that we lived all alone, knowing nothing
U||   of the world without the valley—I, and my cousin, and her mother.
U||   From the dim regions beyond the mountains at the upper end of our
U||   encircled domain, there crept out a narrow and deep river, brighter
U||   than all save the eyes of Eleonora; and, winding stealthily about in
U||   mazy courses, it passed away, at length, through a shadowy gorge, among
U||   hills still dimmer than those whence it had issued. We called it the
U||   “River of Silence”; for there seemed to be a hushing influence in its
U||   flow. No murmur arose from its bed, and so gently it wandered along,
U||   that the pearly pebbles upon which we loved to gaze, far down within
U||   its bosom, stirred not at all, but lay in a motionless content, each in
U||   its own old station, shining on gloriously forever.
U||   The margin of the river, and of the many dazzling rivulets that glided
U||   through devious ways into its channel, as well as the spaces that
U||   extended from the margins away down into the depths of the streams
U||   until they reached the bed of pebbles at the bottom,—these spots, not
U||   less than the whole surface of the valley, from the river to the
U||   mountains that girdled it in, were carpeted all by a soft green grass,
U||   thick, short, perfectly even, and vanilla-perfumed, but so besprinkled
U||   throughout with the yellow buttercup, the white daisy, the purple
U||   violet, and the ruby-red asphodel, that its exceeding beauty spoke to
U||   our hearts in loud tones, of the love and of the glory of God.
U||   And, here and there, in groves about this grass, like wildernesses of
U||   dreams, sprang up fantastic trees, whose tall slender stems stood not
U||   upright, but slanted gracefully toward the light that peered at
U||   noon-day into the centre of the valley. Their mark was speckled with
U||   the vivid alternate splendor of ebony and silver, and was smoother than
U||   all save the cheeks of Eleonora; so that, but for the brilliant green
U||   of the huge leaves that spread from their summits in long, tremulous
U||   lines, dallying with the Zephyrs, one might have fancied them giant
U||   serpents of Syria doing homage to their sovereign the Sun.
U||   Hand in hand about this valley, for fifteen years, roamed I with
U||   Eleonora before Love entered within our hearts. It was one evening at
U||   the close of the third lustrum of her life, and of the fourth of my
U||   own, that we sat, locked in each other’s embrace, beneath the
U||   serpent-like trees, and looked down within the water of the River of
U||   Silence at our images therein. We spoke no words during the rest of
U||   that sweet day, and our words even upon the morrow were tremulous and
U||   few. We had drawn the God Eros from that wave, and now we felt that he
U||   had enkindled within us the fiery souls of our forefathers. The
U||   passions which had for centuries distinguished our race, came thronging
U||   with the fancies for which they had been equally noted, and together
U||   breathed a delirious bliss over the Valley of the Many-Colored Grass. A
U||   change fell upon all things. Strange, brilliant flowers, star-shaped,
U||   burn out upon the trees where no flowers had been known before. The
U||   tints of the green carpet deepened; and when, one by one, the white
U||   daisies shrank away, there sprang up in place of them, ten by ten of
U||   the ruby-red asphodel. And life arose in our paths; for the tall
U||   flamingo, hitherto unseen, with all gay glowing birds, flaunted his
U||   scarlet plumage before us. The golden and silver fish haunted the
U||   river, out of the bosom of which issued, little by little, a murmur
U||   that swelled, at length, into a lulling melody more divine than that of
U||   the harp of Æolus—sweeter than all save the voice of Eleonora. And now,
U||   too, a voluminous cloud, which we had long watched in the regions of
U||   Hesper, floated out thence, all gorgeous in crimson and gold, and
U||   settling in peace above us, sank, day by day, lower and lower, until
U||   its edges rested upon the tops of the mountains, turning all their
U||   dimness into magnificence, and shutting us up, as if forever, within a
U||   magic prison-house of grandeur and of glory.
U||   The loveliness of Eleonora was that of the Seraphim; but she was a
U||   maiden artless and innocent as the brief life she had led among the
U||   flowers. No guile disguised the fervor of love which animated her
U||   heart, and she examined with me its inmost recesses as we walked
U||   together in the Valley of the Many-Colored Grass, and discoursed of the
U||   mighty changes which had lately taken place therein.
U||   At length, having spoken one day, in tears, of the last sad change
U||   which must befall Humanity, she thenceforward dwelt only upon this one
U||   sorrowful theme, interweaving it into all our converse, as, in the
U||   songs of the bard of Schiraz, the same images are found occurring,
U||   again and again, in every impressive variation of phrase.
U||   She had seen that the finger of Death was upon her bosom—that, like the
U||   ephemeron, she had been made perfect in loveliness only to die; but the
U||   terrors of the grave to her lay solely in a consideration which she
U||   revealed to me, one evening at twilight, by the banks of the River of
U||   Silence. She grieved to think that, having entombed her in the Valley
U||   of the Many-Colored Grass, I would quit forever its happy recesses,
U||   transferring the love which now was so passionately her own to some
U||   maiden of the outer and everyday world. And, then and there, I threw
U||   myself hurriedly at the feet of Eleonora, and offered up a vow, to
U||   herself and to Heaven, that I would never bind myself in marriage to
U||   any daughter of Earth—that I would in no manner prove recreant to her
U||   dear memory, or to the memory of the devout affection with which she
U||   had blessed me. And I called the Mighty Ruler of the Universe to
U||   witness the pious solemnity of my vow. And the curse which I invoked of
U||   Him and of her, a saint in Helusion should I prove traitorous to that
U||   promise, involved a penalty the exceeding great horror of which will
U||   not permit me to make record of it here. And the bright eyes of
U||   Eleonora grew brighter at my words; and she sighed as if a deadly
U||   burthen had been taken from her breast; and she trembled and very
U||   bitterly wept; but she made acceptance of the vow, (for what was she
U||   but a child?) and it made easy to her the bed of her death. And she
U||   said to me, not many days afterward, tranquilly dying, that, because of
U||   what I had done for the comfort of her spirit she would watch over me
U||   in that spirit when departed, and, if so it were permitted her return
U||   to me visibly in the watches of the night; but, if this thing were,
U||   indeed, beyond the power of the souls in Paradise, that she would, at
U||   least, give me frequent indications of her presence, sighing upon me in
U||   the evening winds, or filling the air which I breathed with perfume
U||   from the censers of the angels. And, with these words upon her lips,
U||   she yielded up her innocent life, putting an end to the first epoch of
U||   my own.
U||   Thus far I have faithfully said. But as I pass the barrier in Time’s
U||   path, formed by the death of my beloved, and proceed with the second
U||   era of my existence, I feel that a shadow gathers over my brain, and I
U||   mistrust the perfect sanity of the record. But let me on.—Years dragged
U||   themselves along heavily, and still I dwelled within the Valley of the
U||   Many-Colored Grass; but a second change had come upon all things. The
U||   star-shaped flowers shrank into the stems of the trees, and appeared no
U||   more. The tints of the green carpet faded; and, one by one, the
U||   ruby-red asphodels withered away; and there sprang up, in place of
U||   them, ten by ten, dark, eye-like violets, that writhed uneasily and
U||   were ever encumbered with dew. And Life departed from our paths; for
U||   the tall flamingo flaunted no longer his scarlet plumage before us, but
U||   flew sadly from the vale into the hills, with all the gay glowing birds
U||   that had arrived in his company. And the golden and silver fish swam
U||   down through the gorge at the lower end of our domain and bedecked the
U||   sweet river never again. And the lulling melody that had been softer
U||   than the wind-harp of Æolus, and more divine than all save the voice of
U||   Eleonora, it died little by little away, in murmurs growing lower and
U||   lower, until the stream returned, at length, utterly, into the
U||   solemnity of its original silence. And then, lastly, the voluminous
U||   cloud uprose, and, abandoning the tops of the mountains to the dimness
U||   of old, fell back into the regions of Hesper, and took away all its
U||   manifold golden and gorgeous glories from the Valley of the
U||   Many-Colored Grass.
U||   Yet the promises of Eleonora were not forgotten; for I heard the sounds
U||   of the swinging of the censers of the angels; and streams of a holy
U||   perfume floated ever and ever about the valley; and at lone hours, when
U||   my heart beat heavily, the winds that bathed my brow came unto me laden
U||   with soft sighs; and indistinct murmurs filled often the night air, and
U||   once—oh, but once only! I was awakened from a slumber, like the slumber
U||   of death, by the pressing of spiritual lips upon my own.
U||   But the void within my heart refused, even thus, to be filled. I longed
U||   for the love which had before filled it to overflowing. At length the
U||   valley pained me through its memories of Eleonora, and I left it for
U||   ever for the vanities and the turbulent triumphs of the world.
U||   I found myself within a strange city, where all things might have
U||   served to blot from recollection the sweet dreams I had dreamed so long
U||   in the Valley of the Many-Colored Grass. The pomps and pageantries of a
U||   stately court, and the mad clangor of arms, and the radiant loveliness
U||   of women, bewildered and intoxicated my brain. But as yet my soul had
U||   proved true to its vows, and the indications of the presence of
U||   Eleonora were still given me in the silent hours of the night. Suddenly
U||   these manifestations they ceased, and the world grew dark before mine
U||   eyes, and I stood aghast at the burning thoughts which possessed, at
U||   the terrible temptations which beset me; for there came from some far,
U||   far distant and unknown land, into the gay court of the king I served,
U||   a maiden to whose beauty my whole recreant heart yielded at once—at
U||   whose footstool I bowed down without a struggle, in the most ardent, in
U||   the most abject worship of love. What, indeed, was my passion for the
U||   young girl of the valley in comparison with the fervor, and the
U||   delirium, and the spirit-lifting ecstasy of adoration with which I
U||   poured out my whole soul in tears at the feet of the ethereal
U||   Ermengarde?—Oh, bright was the seraph Ermengarde! and in that knowledge
U||   I had room for none other. Oh, divine was the angel Ermengarde! and as
U||   I looked down into the depths of her memorial eyes, I thought only of
U||   them—and of her.
U||   I wedded—nor dreaded the curse I had invoked; and its bitterness was
U||   not visited upon me. And once—but once again in the silence of the
U||   night; there came through my lattice the soft sighs which had forsaken
U||   me; and they modelled themselves into familiar and sweet voice, saying:
U||   “Sleep in peace! for the Spirit of Love reigneth and ruleth, and, in
U||   taking to thy passionate heart her who is Ermengarde, thou art
U||   absolved, for reasons which shall be made known to thee in Heaven, of
U||   thy vows unto Eleonora.”
